<SLUG> BC-UTILITIES-ACQUIRE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COLUMBIA EERGY SETS DEADLINE FOR RESPONSE TO BID FOR CONSOLIDATED
NATURAL GAS  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Va.)   By DANA CANEDY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times Nws Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Seeking to force the Consolidated Natural Gas Co. to respond to
its $6.7 billion hostile bid, Columbia Energy Group said Friday
that it would send Consolidated's board a merger proposal with a
deadline of 5 p.m. on Monday
</P>
<P>
   Consolidated, which two-and-a-half months ago agreed to be
acquired by Dominion Resources Inc., based in Richmond, Va., for
$6.3 billion, stressed Friday that it still had a merger agreement
with Dominion. As for Columbia's offer, so far Consolidated has
only said that it is reviewing it.
</P>
<P>
   Columbia described its proposal Friday as good for the
shareholders of both companies. Oliver G. Richard III, chairman,
president and chief executive of Columbia, said, ``We believe the
CNG board will find it compelling.'' Columbia also said it had
provided additional requested information to Consolidated.
</P>
<P>
   A person involved in the negotiations on Columbia's behalf said
that Consolidated now had to act on the merger agreement. Between
now and the Monday deadline, ``the Consolidated board is absolutely
going to have to respond,'' this person said.
</P>
<P>
   ``They can't drag it out any longer,'' the person added.
</P>
<P>
   Columbia, based in Herndon, Va., first made its cash-and-stock
bid to Consolidated, based in Pittsburgh, last month.
</P>
<P>
   Chet Wade, a spokesman for Consolidated, said its board ``had a
process in place regarding the Columbia Energy Group's proposal and
will respond in due course.''
</P>
<P>
   He declined to say if the company would meet Columbia's
deadline.
</P>
<P>
   As the utility industry is deregulating, companies have sought
to strengthen their competitive positions by taking over natural
gas companies like Consolidated so they can offer a package of
electricity and natural gas.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts had been critical of Dominion's offer because it would
not contribute to earnings for at least two years. Dominion had
said that it would not sweeten its offer to Consolidated. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
