<SLUG> BC-BBA-RANGERS-LITES-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW RANGERS PRESIDENT WON'T SHAPE TEAM
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By T.R. SULLIVAN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas _ Jim Lites said he's a fan, not a baseball
guy. But by going to 10 games a year, the Rangers' new president
has had no trouble figuring out his new team's biggest need.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know this team can hit, run and field,'' Lites said. ``I
think it needs pitching. Obviously, we have to do a better job
keeping the other team off the scoreboard.''
</P>
<P>
   But Lites, who was announced yesterday as the Rangers' president
in addition to remaining the Stars' president, said finding more
pitching is general manager Doug Melvin's job and ``it will
continue to be so.''
</P>
<P>
   Owner Tom Hicks agreed.
</P>
<P>
   Lites is the boss, Hicks said, ``but both these two teams will
be run by professional sports people. Doug Melvin will run the
baseball team; Bob Gainey will run the hockey team.''
</P>
<P>
   That means Melvin will report directly to Hicks as much as he
does to Lites.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think this will have much of an impact,'' Melvin said.
``I feel confident it's something that will work out. We'll
continue to do the things we've always done, and that's put the
best product we can on the field.''
</P>
<P>
   Lites replaces Tom Schieffer, who spent eight years as the
Rangers' president before stepping down last week to concentrate on
the real estate development around The Ballpark in Arlington. The
change takes place immediately. Schieffer was serving as president
until a successor was hired.
</P>
<P>
   Lites, who spent the past six years as Stars president, grew up
a baseball fan in Michigan and played the sport through high
school. But he has spent the past 17 years working for the Stars
and Detroit Red Wings. He has never worked in baseball. He also
boasts of no expertise on the subject.
</P>
<P>
   ``In all the years I've been in sports, the one thing I've
learned is don't try to do the things you're not capable of
doing,'' Lites said. ``I'm not capable of making baseball player
evaluations, and I won't be. I can't tell you if a guy is a good
baseball player. Those decisions have to be made by the people
responsible.''
</P>
<P>
   Lites said he will not directly involve himself in player
contract negotiations or the pursuit of free agents. Schieffer took
an active role in both. Lites said he'll tell Melvin how much money
he can spend, but it's up to the general manager to decide how to
spend it.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been doing that successfully the last three years with
the Stars, and it will hold true with Doug,'' Hicks said. ``He'll
make the recommendations, Jim will be his sounding board and make
the final recommendation, and I'll have the final say, yes or no.
</P>
<P>
   ``But the recommendations have to come from the bottom up, not
the top down.''
</P>
<P>
   For the Stars, there is a clear line between the hockey
operations department and the executive department. People under
Lites' immediate management handle marketing, sales, event
presentation, finance, communications, arena development and more.
</P>
<P>
   People under general manager Bob Gainey handle the on-ice
product, player contract negotiations, team travel and scouting.
Lites has been an intermediary for Hicks in matters such as
free-agent acquisitions and trades, but more to inform the owner
rather than inject opinion.
</P>
<P>
   ``We haven't really talked about how we're going to handle
things, but I don't expect any changes,'' Gainey said. ``We know
where our departments intersect, and we know how to intersect well
with each other. We know what's in each of our departments, and we
know what is combined for both departments. We've had a very good
relationship in those matters, so I don't see why anything should
change.''
</P>
<P>
   Lites did say the Rangers' emphasis on scouting and player
development will continue.
</P>
<P>
   ``Your scouting and development through the minor leagues has to
be effective because you don't have enough money to buy free agents
for every position,'' Lites said. ``The emphasis has to be on
scouting and player development.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Melvin: ``The one thing he's familiar with is a farm
system. Hockey has a farm system as well, even though it's not the
magnitude of baseball.''  &LR; taptop:Staff writer Mike Heika
contributed to this report. T.R. Sullivan, (817) 390-7760
</P>
</TEXT>
