<SLUG> BC-NY-BROOKLYN-DEVELOP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEVELOPER PURSUES PLANS FOR COMPLEX ALONG BROOKLYN'S WATERFRONT 
</HEADLINE>
  (bl) 
 By HERBERT MUSCHAMP   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ One of Europe's most celebrated architects has been
hired to design a controversial shopping and entertainment complex
in Brooklyn that could transform the waterfront area north of
Brooklyn Heights.
</P>
<P>
   The site for the project lies between the Brooklyn and Manhattan
Bridges, in the area called Dumbo, for Down Under the Manhattan
Bridge Overpass. In recent years, the manufacturing district has
been transformed into a popular residential neighborhood, and the
developer of the new project, David Walentas, wants to make it a
commercial and artistic center as well. His plans include a
redesigned park at the foot of the Brooklyn Bridge, a hotel and a
sizable exhibition space for art in the historic brick warehouses.
</P>
<P>
   The architect, Jean Nouvel, a 53-year-old Frenchman, has created
a number of important buildings abroad. For the Brooklyn
development, he will work in association with the New York
architectural firm Beyer Blinder Belle, whose projects include the
renovation of Grand Central Terminal.
</P>
<P>
   But Walentas' plans have faced fierce opposition in nearby
Brooklyn Heights, where community leaders say the complex will
worsen the traffic congestion in downtown Brooklyn and undermine
efforts to open up waterfront land to the public.
</P>
<P>
   Neighborhood leaders have vowed to fight the plan on several
levels, and a draft land-use plan by Community Board 2, which
covers Dumbo, differs from Walentas' plan in various ways. It calls
for maintaining a mix of industrial and residential buildings in
Dumbo and seeks to preserve parkland along the waterfront by
restricting commercial development around Empire-Fulton Ferry State
Park.
</P>
<P>
   But Walentas' hiring of Nouvel signals that the developer is
serious about proceeding with his vision for the neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   The project would be Nouvel's first building in the United
States. He was the architect of the Arab World Institute, one of
the ``grand projets'' of Paris commissioned during the 1980s by
President Francois Mitterrand. Nouvel also designed the Cartier
Foundation for Contemporary Art on the city's Left Bank, the
Galleries Lafayette department store in Berlin and a concert hall
in Lucerne, Switzerland. His most recent building is a Museum of
Advertising that will open in the fall as part of the Louvre.
</P>
<P>
   Nouvel's work features an inventive use of technology. For the
Arab World Institute, he designed a wall of photosensitive camera
eyes that control the natural light entering the structure. The
Cartier Foundation commands an imposing prospect on the Boulevard
Raspail with a free-standing wall of glass. For a building housing
the CLM BBDO advertising agency on the Seine River just north of
Paris, Nouvel devised a hydraulically operated roof that rises like
the wings of a butterfly.
</P>
<P>
   Although the Dumbo area offers considerable advantages to a
developer, not the least of which is the spectacular view of the
lower Manhattan skyline, the project still faces several hurdles.
</P>
<P>
   Walentas has been designated by New York state as the
conditional developer of the public property between the two
bridges, but community members have said that if he does not scale
back his designs and expand the state park, they will fight his
proposal.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you have a choice between a park at that spectacular
location and a shopping mall which could go anywhere, it doesn't
seem much of a choice,'' said Paul DiLeo, a member of Community
Board 2 who helped draft the board's plan. ``Even if a mall were a
good use of the property, which it's not, can anyone get there
without going insane?''
</P>
<P>
   Although community groups have been notified about the selection
of Nouvel and invited to preview Walentas' plans for the area, some
of these organizations have already objected to the choice of
architect. They expect him to propose a starkly modern structure
that would be inappropriate in an area notable for its cobblestone
streets and historic warehouses.
</P>
<P>
   ``Walentas has told us he wants to construct a Sydney Opera
House,'' said Marianna Koval, deputy director of the Brooklyn
Bridge Park Coalition, a community group that supports building a
greatly expanded park along the waterfront, stretching from just
southwest of the Brooklyn Heights Promenade to the Brooklyn Navy
Yard. ``I think there is community consensus that it is a totally
inappropriate structure for that site. To place a huge modern
edifice right next to Civil War-era warehouses and in this
turn-of-the-century manufacturing area seems ill-conceived.''
</P>
<P>
   The Walentas project is one of several projects by prominent
architects under way in New York. Others include the Austrian
Cultural Institute on East 52nd Street, designed by Raimund
Abraham; a commercial building on East 57th Street, designed by
Christian de Portzamparc; the expansion of the Museum of Modern
Art, a project designed by Yoshio Taniguchi; a hotel on 42nd Street
and Eighth Avenue, designed by Arquitectonica; and the remodeling
of 350 Madison Ave. by Skidmore, Owings and Merrill. The new Second
Stage Theater, at 307 W. 43rd St., a project by Richard Gluckman in
association with the Dutch architect Rem Koolhaas, is also a
notable addition to the New York cityscape.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
