<HEADER>
A9174 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-SCION-SUICIDE-2TAK     05-08 1008
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-SCION-SUICIDE-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A MAN HAUNTED BY HIS RICH FAMILY'S HISTORY OF TRAGEDY 
</HEADLINE>
  (bl) 
 By JIM YARDLEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ William Woodward III was born to a family with few
peers in New York society. The Woodwards had old money and blue
blood, but they also had a penchant for self-destruction that
landed them in the novels of Truman Capote and Dominick Dunne, as
well as in the headlines of newspapers around the world.
</P>
<P>
   William was only 11 years old in 1955 when his mother shot and
killed his father, mistaking him for a prowler at their weekend
estate. The crack of the shotgun did not wake young Woody, but the
shooting echoed throughout his life: His mother, Ann, was
exonerated, but she committed suicide in 1975 after Capote depicted
her as a murderous vamp.
</P>
<P>
   His younger brother, Jimmy, dabbled in drugs and spent time in
mental institutions before he jumped to his death from a hotel
window.
</P>
<P>
   But William Woodward III persevered, eager to become more than
another poor little rich boy. He became a journalist in the late
1960s and later ran for public office. He served as New York's
deputy superintendent of banks. Later, he got married and had a
daughter and lived, for a time, a quiet life. And then last Sunday,
at age 54, he jumped through the kitchen window of his East Side
apartment and fell 14 stories to his death. Police called it an
apparent suicide.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a terrible tragedy,'' said Lionel Larner, a friend who
attended Woodward's funeral Thursday. ``His desire was to give
something back, to try to do good. But there was always a shadow of
sadness. It seemed to emanate from him. He wanted very much to be
happy.''
</P>
<P>
   The shadows in Woodward's life had become darker in recent
years. Friends say he suffered periods of severe depression and had
been under psychiatric care. He and his wife, Lisa, had been waging
a divorce and custody fight since 1996. His wife's lawyer, Jerome
Tarnoff, said Woodward experienced dramatic mood swings, veering
from euphoria to despair. In his eulogy at the funeral, Parkman
Shaw, a longtime friend, said Woodward called him two weeks ago,
fearful that he had fallen into a depression without bottom.
</P>
<P>
   Tarnoff said: ``The man couldn't help himself. He had demons, so
to speak.''
</P>
<P>
   His closest friends, a few of whom regularly telephoned him in
recent years to ``check up,'' gathered at a small, private
reception after the funeral. In later interviews, several friends
described a man of vivid contrasts: He was charming and bright, a
patrician with liberal politics, a doting father, someone
determined to make his mark. He was also very private, sometimes
guarded and subject to increasingly unpredictable behavior.
</P>
<P>
   His death, a close friend said, was ``on one level shocking, but
on another level it was not.'' He added: ``I think mental illness
is so terrible and insidious.''
</P>
<P>
   The skyline of wealth in New York City is ever changing, with
new families rising and old ones falling, but the Woodwards ranked
at the summit for much of the century.
</P>
<P>
   William Woodward was a chairman of Central-Hanover Bank and a
sportsman who purchased the famous Belair Stud, the Maryland
thoroughbred farm that produced three Kentucky Derby winners. His
wife, Elsie, became a grande dame of high society and a leading
philanthropist. Their son, William ``Billy'' Woodward Jr., was an
international sportsmen, most famous for his thoroughbred, Nashua,
winner of two-thirds of racing's triple crown. He married Ann
Crowell, a woman of ordinary lineage but of extraordinary beauty.
She was a Powers model, and became a radio personality known,
somewhat oddly, as ``the most beautiful girl in radio.''
</P>
<P>
   They had two sons, William III and James, and if they were born
as princes of the realm, they ultimately became victims in a chain
of family destruction that seems almost Gothic.
</P>
<P>
   On the night of Oct. 30, 1955, Billy and Ann Woodward had
returned to their weekend estate in Oyster Bay on Long Island,
after attending a dinner party honoring the Duchess of Windsor.
There had been reports of a prowler, and the couple retired to
separate bedrooms armed with loaded weapons. Awakened by what she
later described as the sound of an intruder, Mrs. Woodward grabbed
her gun and fired at a shadow in her doorway. It was her husband,
and she had killed him. The two boys, asleep elsewhere in the
house, did not wake up.
</P>
<P>
   The shooting electrified the nation. Life magazine dubbed it
``The Shooting of the Century.'' Distraught and visibly anguished,
Mrs. Woodward was hospitalized for days but she eventually appeared
before a Nassau County grand jury, which deemed the shooting an
accident. But the family would never recover. Mrs. Woodward was
ostracized socially and hounded by whispers questioning her
innocence. The whispers eventually landed in the ears of Truman
Capote, whose unfinished, but published, novel, ``Answered
Prayers,'' included a thinly veiled fictional account of the
Woodward shooting. He depicted Mrs. Woodward as Ann Cutler, a
harlot and a gold digger who killed her husband because he had
discovered she was a bigamist.
</P>
<P>
   In 1975, Esquire published an excerpt from the novel, and Ann
Woodward was soon found dead in her Fifth Avenue apartment from
suicide. Susan Braudy, whose 1992 book, ``This Crazy Thing Called
Love,'' documented the shooting, said New York society quickly
accepted Capote's fictional account as fact.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, that's that,'' Elsie Woodward, then in her 90s, said six
weeks after Ann's death, according to Ms. Braudy's book. ``She shot
my son, and Truman just murdered her, and so now I suppose we don't
have to worry about that anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   But after eight years of research, Ms. Braudy concluded that the
shooting, in fact, had been an accident. Police had arrested a
prowler who admitted to being at the Woodward estate. Ms. Braudy
also discovered that Capote's story about her background was pure
fabrication, despite the whispers to the contrary.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   ``There was an awful lot of gossip about it among their friends
taking sides and wondering if it was an accident,'' said Ann
Slater, a friend of the Woodward family. ``The boys were at an age
where they couldn't miss it.''
</P>
<P>
   The youngest, Jimmy, died first. A handsome Vietnam veteran, he
quickly fell into the drug culture of the early 1970s, according to
Ms. Braudy. He bent heirloom silver spoons to heat heroin, and one
night in 1972, high on drugs, he jumped out of a fourth floor
window but survived. Released from a mental institution, Jimmy
befriended Xaviera Hollander, the self-proclaimed madam and author
of ``The Happy Hooker'' series. In one of her later books, she had
a chapter, ``Jimmy, Don't Jump Again.''
</P>
<P>
   He did. Less than a year after his mother's suicide, Jimmy
jumped out of a window of a hotel on Central Park South and died.
</P>
<P>
   Woody Woodward was the last of his family, and for years he
struggled to make a name for himself. He had attended an exclusive
Swiss boarding school and graduated from Harvard College. In 1968,
he became a reporter at The New York Post, and if newspapering
seemed an unlikely career for a multimillionaire, he embraced it.
He paid his own way to cover the Vietnam War, riding around the war
on a motorcycle. In New York, he represented the Newspaper Guild in
contract negotiations with management, another unlikely role for
the heir to a banking fortune.
</P>
<P>
   In 1971, two journalists, Richard Pollak and J. Anthony Lukas,
were searching for investors to underwrite a new magazine of media
criticism called More. They knew about Woodward's role in The
Post's contract negotiations, and they later met him at the Harvard
Club. ``Suddenly, Bill said, `Well, I might be willing to put up
money,''' Pollak recalled. He spent $5,000 to bankroll a trial
issue, and when it succeeded, More was born.
</P>
<P>
   He became the publisher, and More became acclaimed as an
influential, liberal critical voice.
</P>
<P>
   Woodward eventually left the magazine to attend Harvard Business
School and ultimately he turned to politics. He served in the
administrations of Gov. Hugh Carey and Mayor Ed Koch. In 1978, he
ran for the state Senate in the East Side's ``silk stocking
district'' but lost to the Republican incumbent, Roy Goodman.
</P>
<P>
   In 1981, he ran for an at-large seat in the City Council, but
the courts abolished those seats before the election. And then
Woodward essentially dropped out of the public eye.
</P>
<P>
   The family saga resurfaced when another fictional account of the
shooting, ``The Two Mrs. Grenvilles'' by Dunne, was published in
1985 and later produced as a television movie. Dunne said this week
that Woodward had called him before publication to ask that he not
mention the Woodward name while publicizing the book. Dunne said he
obliged.
</P>
<P>
   As ``The Two Mrs. Grenvilles'' reached the best-seller lists,
Woodward and Lisa Dawn Woodward were married Sept. 28, 1985 in
Paris. They had each attended the same Swiss private school, Le
Rosey, then reconnected later in life. Friends and Tarnoff, the
lawyer, say that for several years the couple lived a life of
comfort, sailing their boat in the Mediterranean and spending time
in apartments in London, Paris and New York.
</P>
<P>
   But Tarnoff said the marriage began to unravel in 1994. He said
Woodward spent much of the year traveling the world, calling from
train stations in Europe. In 1996, Mrs. Woodward filed for divorce,
and the couple began a contentious custody battle over their
daughter, now 7 years old.
</P>
<P>
   Woodward's lawyer, Steven E. Lewis, did not return telephone
calls left at his office, but Tarnoff said Mrs. Woodward had
temporary custody during the divorce proceedings. He said Woodward
was allowed to see their daughter ``40 percent of the time,'' and
that he took her on trips to Colorado and Rhode Island.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was a very good father,'' Tarnoff said. ``He loved that
child more than life.''
</P>
<P>
   But friends said Woodward slid into another depression late last
year. Pollak, who had not spoken to Woodward since they worked
together at More, said they exchanged letters last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a very unhappy letter,'' Pollak said of the note from
Woodward. ``He talked about how his marriage was breaking up, and
how he was not getting to see his child as much as he liked.''
</P>
<P>
   For Woodward's friends, this final image of a despondent man is
not how they wish to remember him. Instead, friends recalled his
sensitive nature and his unique style.
</P>
<P>
   ``He wore clothes differently,'' said Ms. Braudy, who became
friends with Woodward during the '70s, before she wrote her book.
``He had the manners of a European prince. He was a very attractive
personality, but he was vulnerability transcended in a way.''
</P>
<P>
   Another friend said simply, almost wishfully, upon receiving a
call from a reporter, ``Everybody is tired of this story, right?
It's tragic and awful and it's over, I hope.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
