<SLUG> BC-BKN-HEAT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HEAT'S PLAN IS TO MAKE A RUN FOR IT AGAINST EWING
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By CHARLIE NOBLES   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ P.J. Brown will wear basketball shoes when the Miami
Heat opens the playoffs on Saturday afternoon against the Knicks,
but the power forward will be thinking like a runner.
</P>
<P>
   Brown, a one-time brawler in this contentious series, is quite
aware that Knicks center Patrick Ewing, 36, and hampered by an
Achilles' tendon problem, is expected to defend him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I can run a little bit better than he does,'' Brown
said Friday at practice. ``If I get up and down and try to get him
tired, hopefully around the third or fourth quarter he won't be as
effective in the post. He's hurting and I'm going to try to take
advantage of it.''
</P>
<P>
   There is another reason Brown plans to sprint as this
best-of-5-game series begins: the former Net believes several
fast-break layups will be pivotal.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's going to be the big key to this series: who can get the
most easy baskets,'' he said. ``Our defenses are so compact and
there's going to be some ugly basketball, like there always is.''
</P>
<P>
   After a long study session and a short practice today at La
Salle High School in Coconut Grove, Heat players again faced
questions about the animosity between the teams. Most of their
answers were distilled for family consumption, but occasionally a
verbal spark or two would fly.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if the teams hate each other, Brown said: ``I don't know
about hate. There's definitely a big dislike. There's no doubt
about that.''
</P>
<P>
   Center Alonzo Mourning, apparently tired of hearing how
difficult the Knicks have been for Miami to defeat in recent years,
said: ``I look at it this way. If we can't match up and play well
against anybody in the eighth spot, then we don't need to be in the
playoffs at all.''
</P>
<P>
   In another corner of the gym, forward Dan Majerle said:
``There's not a lot of love between these teams. We know they want
to play us. We're just going to go out and play our game and let
our game talk.''
</P>
<P>
   Brown even took exception to the notion that the Knicks take
more delight in beating Miami than other teams, and seem to save
their best basketball for the Heat.
</P>
<P>
   Pat Riley, the Heat coach, said Friday that Ewing is averaging
10 more points a game against Miami than he is against the rest of
the league, and forward Larry Johnson is averaging six more.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what type of team just points out one team and
wants them,'' Brown said. ``I look at the total picture. But if
they want us, they got us. They'll get a chance to prove
themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   Point guard Tim Hardaway also commented on how much better the
Knicks have played against Miami than they have against other
teams.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look at the paper,'' Hardaway said. ``Against other teams,
they really don't produce. For some reason, they make it their
season when they play us. We have to start making it our season
when we play them. We have to show them that we are No. 1 and we
earned it and deserved it, and we have to come out and play like we
are the No. 1 seed in the East.''
</P>
<P>
   One factor that may hurt the Heat is that Hardaway, Miami's most
effective player against the Knicks over the last three seasons,
has been dragging a damaged left knee around since a Feb. 26
collision with Grant Hill of the Detroit Pistons. While Hardaway
only missed one game and has not called attention to the injury, it
has limited his explosiveness and penetrating ability.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been out there trying to be a threat,'' he said. ``Your
legs are everything to you in basketball. I can get back to that,
but I don't know if it will be until the off season.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Hardaway's competitiveness is bubbling over right now.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like the pressure, I like the challenges, I like whatever it
brings,'' he said. ``It's got to bring out the best in you. As a
team, our window of opportunity is wide open. It's mainly a matter
of just going out and doing what we know we can do.''  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
