<SLUG> BC-SOC-METROSTARS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HURTADO STATUS DOUBTFUL AS METROSTARS HIT ROAD 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By STEVE POPPER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The MetroStars have had many problems on offense this season,
from their own lack of scoring to the fruitless search for a
forward to fill the vacant foreigner slot on their roster. As if
those struggles were not enough, the MetroStars are expected to be
without Eduardo Hurtado when they travel to Washington to face D.C.
United Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Hurtado, the team's leading scorer this season with three goals,
is listed as doubtful with a right hamstring strain and did not
practice this week.
</P>
<P>
   Since joining the MetroStars in a trade from Los Angeles last
season, Hurtado has been the key to the MetroStars' offensive
success; the team has a 9-2 record in games in which he has scored
a goal and is 15-2 in games in which he has registered a point.
</P>
<P>
   But perhaps the trip to Washington is just what the MetroStars
(3-3) need to right themselves. The MetroStars have struggled
offensively at home, currently enduring a stretch of 280 minutes
without a goal.
</P>
<P>
   In the MetroStars' latest loss _ in a shootout to the Galaxy _
at least Mark Chung and Roy Myers were able to convert in the
shootout. Since scoring two goals in their first game, the
MetroStars have scored only two goals in the last five games and
rank 10th in Major League Soccer with 0.67 goals a game.
</P>
<P>
   D.C. United (3-3) is in a three-game losing streak, the longest
slide since the team lost its first four games in 1996, its
inaugural season, and has yet to win in two home games this season.
United is also struggling with injury problems, with defender Eddie
Pope out for four to six weeks with a broken foot and midfielder
Marco Etcheverry out with a groin strain.
</P>
<P>
   Still, D.C. United does have forward Roy Lassiter, who has six
goals this season and has scored 14 times in 16 games against the
MetroStars, the most by any opponent. Since joining United, he has
scored four goals in five matches against the MetroStars, including
the game-winning goal in the 47th minute of a 1-0 victory on April
9.
</P>
<P>
   The MetroStars may rely on an unlikely source to try to lift
them from their offensive doldrums, inserting Nansha Kalonji into
Hurtado's spot beside Myers at forward.
</P>
<P>
   Kalonji, 26, is from the Democratic Republic of Congo and played
at Ramapo College. He was selected in the supplemental draft in
February. Believed to be the fastest player in the league, he
played 20 minutes in Hurtado's place last week.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
