<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-MAYOR-CHANCELLOR-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GIULIANI: ``I STIR THINGS UP'' 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By DAN BARRY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The public breakdown of the professional, if not
private, relationship between Mayor Rudolph Giuliani and Schools
Chancellor Rudy Crew continued Friday, as the mayor asserted that
he was primarily responsible for whatever reform was being planned
for the city's school system.
</P>
<P>
   The reason, he said, is that ``I stir things up.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The whole reason why the chancellor is talking about ending
social promotion is because I stir things up,'' he said at a news
conference. ``The whole reason why there is a discussion of ending
principal tenure is because I stir things up.''
</P>
<P>
   The mayor went on to say that discussions about school vouchers,
in which public money would pay for the private-school tuition of
disadvantaged children, were taking place ``because I stir things
up.'' He also said that discussions about abolishing the Board of
Education were occurring ``because I stir things up.''
</P>
<P>
   Crew and his aides chose Friday not to comment directly on the
mayor's comments. ``Situations like this are very volatile and
we've always tried to suppress volatility,'' said Chiara Coletti, a
spokeswoman for Crew.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, Giuliani's remarks seemed to suggest that he
believed Crew had had little impact on the agenda for the city's
schools, and came just days after a power play by the mayor and his
aides seemed to undercut Crew's influence over the school board.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, a four-member majority of the school board,
including two of the mayor's appointees, rejected Crew's five-year
school construction plan and replaced it with one supported by the
mayor. It marked the chancellor's first defeat since assuming the
job in 1995, and left him complaining about politics polluting the
educational process.
</P>
<P>
   The mayor's remarks Friday also suggested a continuing shift
away from the enthusiastic support he has expressed for Crew's
leadership in the past.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly after the school board hired Crew in late 1995 _ with
the prodding of Giuliani _ he and the mayor developed what aides
say was a close personal relationship. Late at night, often after
delivering speeches or attending functions, they would meet for
dinner to talk about matters both professional and personal.
</P>
<P>
   But this year, the public has witnessed the gradual
deterioration of that relationship, often played out through
emotionally charged debates over school policy. Crew's aides say
that it began with the mayor's push earlier this year to begin a
pilot voucher program, which one school official suggested had more
to do with the mayor's political aspirations than anything else.
</P>
<P>
   Harry Spence, the deputy schools chancellor for operations, said
on a news program Thursday night that the mayor told Crew in
January not to worry about his promotion of vouchers, which the
chancellor vehemently opposes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not doing this to hurt you,'' Spence said the mayor
effectively told Crew at a time when Giuliani was traveling the
country and the state as a potential candidate for the Senate.
``It's not something I expect to be driving home. It's something I
need to be talking about.''
</P>
<P>
   Spence previously enjoyed the support of Giuliani, but his
television appearance seemed to have damaged his reputation in City
Hall. ``Harry's performance is not inconsistent with our past
experiences with him in not being able to tell the truth,'' Deputy
Mayor Joseph Lhota said. ``He's bringing dissembling to a lower
level, and it's disgusting.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
