A9184 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-LEBRETON-COLUMN-T     05-08 0740
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-LEBRETON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HICKS SMACKS HOME RUN WITH NEW RANGERS PRESIDENT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GIL LEBRETON 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Hicks with a kick save!
</P>
<P>
   Gee. That could have been a lot worse.
</P>
<P>
   But just when it looked as if multi-owner Tom Hicks had let his
first baseball blunder whiz under his cuff links, he rallied
yesterday in classic, Eddie Belfour-like fashion.
</P>
<P>
   In rawest baseball terms, Jim Lites is no Tom Schieffer. But he
could be. And if you listened real closely, that sound you heard
yesterday at The Ballpark in Arlington was Rangers fans, sighing
with relief.
</P>
<P>
   Club president. Don't dare shrug at yesterday's announcement.
</P>
<P>
   If you think that on the new millennium's organizational chart,
the club president can't affect a team's on-field performance, let
me remind you of two words: Frank and Zaccanelli.
</P>
<P>
   Lites is neither of them. He arrives with neither a hidden
agenda nor riding a power trip. Nor is the new Rangers president
some young bean counter that Bud Selig's office sent over.
</P>
<P>
   If you're apprehensive about Lites' baseball resume, remember
this: the hockey team he helped build has had the best record in
the NHL for the past two seasons. Lites' roll call of prior diamond
experience is, in fact, at least a couple of paragraphs beyond what
Schieffer's was when he first assumed the big chair.
</P>
<P>
   Just a few seasons ago, this would have seemed like folly, this
notion of one man guiding the business operations of two local
sports teams.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a lot more conventional now because of the size of the
investments that have occurred,'' Lites said on his first day on
the new job. ``There is a need to run these businesses as
businesses and not like owners' playthings.
</P>
<P>
   ``Given the level of investment that Mr. Hicks has made in these
two teams, and the importance of making them make business sense,
they treat them very seriously now.
</P>
<P>
   ``Before, I guess, owners would go in and put a guy in charge
who ran one of his other businesses _ and then look out.''
</P>
<P>
   Look out below, he means. We only have to look at the rudderless
few weeks before Don Nelson joined the Mavericks for an example.
</P>
<P>
   So why shouldn't this work? Lites' new job isn't about finding a
new starting pitcher any more than his old job was scouring for a
new left winger. As Bob Gainey has been allowed to flex his general
manager elbows, so will Doug Melvin.
</P>
<P>
   As Lites said, ``When I talked with him today, I told him,
`Doug, I've worked with Bob Gainey, and I intend to have the same
relationship with you and hopefully that will evolve over time. I
won't bother you. I won't do your job, and I don't expect you to do
mine.' ''
</P>
<P>
   There are billboards to sell and seats to fill _ same as with
the NHL Stars. There is a physical plant to run and operational
details to tidy _ same as with the Stars.
</P>
<P>
   Lites plans to maintain an office both at the Dr Pepper
StarCenter and at The Ballpark. But until further notice, he says,
he will be spending ``about 80 percent'' of his time at the
baseball park.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got a lot of learning to do,'' Lites said.
</P>
<P>
   He grew up a Detroit Tigers fan. Twice a season, Lites' father
would pack up his son and drive the 250 miles to Tiger Stadium for
what amounted to a five-game weekend. Yes, he skipped school to
watch Al Kaline, Norm Cash and Don Wert play.
</P>
<P>
   When Lites was a young vice president with the Detroit Red
Wings, his former father-in-law, Mike Ilitch, purchased the Tigers,
and Lites was given some additional baseball duties.
</P>
<P>
   ``In certain regards,'' Lites said, comparing the business ends
of baseball and hockey, ``they are exactly the same.''
</P>
<P>
   Hell truly does occasionally freeze over. How outrageous would
it have sounded to Texans, say, 10 years ago to hear that a hockey
guy was taking over as president of the Rangers?
</P>
<P>
   If it frightens you, you haven't been paying attention to the
Stars enough. While Owner Jones has been juggling the salary cap
plates at Valley Ranch, the local NHL team has stamped itself as
the area's model organization.
</P>
<P>
   Rome is done. Jones is old news. Hicks is the big sports man in
town now, and Lites has been a worthy lieutenant.
</P>
<P>
   Schieffer will be missed, as quality baseball people always are.
But replacing him could have been much worse.
</P>
<P>
   Save, Hicks. All you need to know about the new president is
that in his ``other job,'' he wins.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-08-99 0024EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
