<SLUG> BC-EDITORIAL-KOSOVO-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OUTLINE FOR PEACE IN KOSOVO 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The diplomatic endgame has begun. That is the meaning of the
peace plan for Kosovo drafted by the Group of Seven countries _ the
United States, Great Britain, Germany, France, Italy, Canada, and
Japan _ plus Russia. Shrewdly, the drafters left crucial matters
vague enough to accommodate the compromises that will be needed for
a workable peace agreement.
</P>
<P>
   The most evident issue left unresolved in the G-7 statement is
what provoked the war in the first place: the Clinton
administration's insistence that an armed NATO force protect
civilians and keep the peace in Kosovo. The text authored by the
G-7 foreign ministers in Bonn backs away from that adamant demand,
calling instead for the deployment in Kosovo ``of effective
international civil and security presences endorsed by the United
Nations.''
</P>
<P>
   This is a formulation that leaves room for peacekeeping
contingents of varying kinds. One peacekeeping force that could
protect repatriated refugees and also be acceptable to all parties
would be an asymmetrical mixed contingent, with NATO troops
protecting Albanian Kosovars and Russian, Belorussian, and
Ukrainian soldiers stationed in areas populated by Serbs.
</P>
<P>
   Some may object that such a division of labor among peacekeepers
would anticipate a partition of Kosovo into Serbian and Albanian
regions.
</P>
<P>
   Since the safety of returning refugees must be the world's
paramount consideration, however, a security formula that
foreshadows the de facto partition of Kosovo may be better suited
to protect Albanians and Serbs alike than an arrangement intended
to validate American conceptions of pluralism and diversity.
</P>
<P>
   What is certain is that any peacekeeping force that enters
Kosovo must be sufficiently well armed not only to protect itself
but to guarantee the safety of 1.5 million traumatized Albanian
Kosovars who have already seen their kinfolk slaughtered and their
houses burned to the ground.
</P>
<P>
   This newspaper has grave doubts about the bombing war, but it
would be a mistake now to halt it unless Slobodan Milosevic
demonstrates that he is willing to withdraw his troops and accept
the return of all the people he expelled from Kosovo.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-08-99 0040EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990508.0013 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-08 00:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9190 &Cx1f; tth-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-POLICE-FORCE-SPI &LR;      05-08 1232
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POLICE-FORCE-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FORMER SEATTLE OFFICER'S SUIT ALLEGES BRUTALITY, COVER-UP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By VANESSA HO  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ In 1996, Seattle Police Officer Paul Vang was writing
reports when a scuffle broke out in a nearby holding cell. Vang
says he ran over and saw three fellow officers punching and kicking
a 17-year-old boy who was bleeding, motionless and on the ground.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what you get for (expletive) with the police,'' one
officer said before cleaning blood from his clothes, Vang recounts.
</P>
<P>
   The boy complained of excessive force to the Seattle Police
Department's Internal Investigations unit, and Vang made a similar
complaint. But Vang says that when he tried to give his statement,
the unit's captain intimidated him and told him to go home and
reconsider his account. The boy's complaint was not sustained, even
though Vang was never interviewed by the investigators.
</P>
<P>
   Vang's allegations of brutality and cover-up have come to light
because of a lawsuit he filed against the department for emotional
distress. A few months after the scuffle, Vang quit the Seattle
police force. He said other officers were hostile to him at the
department, after trying to bury his allegations, and retaliated
against him. The lawsuit is scheduled for trial in November.
</P>
<P>
   His allegations are the latest to hit a police department
already smarting from criticism over its two-year failure to
investigate a homicide detective's alleged theft of $10,000 from a
crime scene.
</P>
<P>
   The revelations that at least eight officers, including a
sergeant in the internal investigations unit, knew of the alleged
1996 theft and did nothing has raised doubts about the integrity of
the department and its internal investigations unit. The case,
which resulted in a criminal charge against the detective last
week, also prompted the mayor to appoint an independent board to
review the entire department.
</P>
<P>
   Vang's account also illuminates one of hundreds of
excessive-force complaints filed against the department. From 1992
to 1998, 737 such complaints were made, with internal investigators
finding only 10 were valid, according to reports by an IIS civilian
auditor.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no doubt in my mind whatsoever what I saw then and
what I know now, as far as acceptable use of force,'' said Vang,
now 35 and a police officer in Wisconsin. ``He clearly wasn't
resisting, and (the officers) were still punching and kicking.''
</P>
<P>
   Police spokeswoman Carmen Best said the department can't comment
on the case because of Vang's pending lawsuit, but did say: ``We
don't believe Mr. Vang's characterizations of the facts are
accurate.''
</P>
<P>
   The incident Vang says he witnessed did result in criminal
charges _ against Demetrius Fisher, now 20, the man involved in the
scuffle. The officers said Fisher threw a punch, resisted being
handcuffed and fought them, forcing them to wrestle him to the
floor. He was convicted of three counts of assaulting the officers.
</P>
<P>
   The officers suffered injuries that required no medical
attention: One had a minor black eye and a lump on the head, and
the others had sore knees, wrists and hands.
</P>
<P>
   Fisher, who was being questioned about an alleged drug deal at
the time of the incident but was never charged in it, fared worse:
His ears and face were bruised, his nose was swollen, bloody and
bent; and his head had a small cut that needed sutures.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was clear from Demetrius' appearance on the day following
the incident that the officers used excessive force in this case,''
said George Yeannakis, Fisher's public defender.
</P>
<P>
   During his assault trial, Yeannakis said Fisher was flailing his
arms in self-defense. Vang's testimony might have helped Fisher's
case, but Yeannakis said he never interviewed him and didn't know
his account.
</P>
<P>
   Dan Satterberg, chief of staff for the King County Prosecutor's
Office, said police documents on the incident didn't name Vang.
</P>
<P>
   ``(The deputy prosecutor) was unaware that he was any type of
witness at all,'' Satterberg said. Fisher is in jail on an
unrelated weapons charge at the Regional Justice Center in Kent,
Wash. He declined comment.
</P>
<P>
   Terry Carroll, the internal investigations unit civilian
auditor, said he could not discuss the Fisher case, but said the
low rate of sustained excessive-force complaints (those ruled
supportable) is a concern.
</P>
<P>
   But he quickly added that many police departments have similar
low rates of sustaining such complaints.
</P>
<P>
   He said he doesn't believe Seattle has a ``systemic'' problem
with excessive force. The number of such complaints is low compared
with the large number of contacts between officers and citizens, he
notes. Also, the number of such complaints has steadily declined
over the years.
</P>
<P>
   He said it's difficult to sustain excessive force complaints
because it often boils down to ``he says-she says'' situations. He
said he has made suggestions to the department on how to improve
the sustaining rate, including doing more face-to-face interviews
with officers. The department now sometimes accepts written
statements or telephone interviews with witnesses and officers.
</P>
<P>
   But others say the internal investigations unit exonerates
officers even when confronted with physical evidence.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, Charles Tomaras says, police officers wrenched his arm
behind his back after responding to what they thought was a
domestic-violence call. Arriving officers saw a Leatherman tool on
Tomaras' belt and asked Tomaras what it was.
</P>
<P>
   Tomaras said he moved to show them the tool when two officers
grabbed him, twisted his arm behind his back, slammed him against a
wall and threw him over a counter. His arm was broken, he said.
</P>
<P>
   He filed a complaint, but Internal Investigations ruled the
confrontation was justified, even though Tomaras never resisted. An
arbitrator recently ruled that he was entitled to about $17,000 in
compensation for his injury, but the city disagreed and requested a
trial now scheduled for July.
</P>
<P>
   ``They overreacted,'' said Tomaras, a 39-year-old sound mixer.
``They broke my arm, which was horribly bruised afterward.''
</P>
<P>
   Vang said Fisher also suffered, and describes the young man's
blood pooling on the floor after the officers punched and kicked
him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I couldn't believe what I'm seeing. I thought you only saw
those things on TV,'' he said. ``I felt shameful, on behalf of what
the officers were doing. I feel terrible, sick to my stomach.''
</P>
<P>
   Two months later, after an investigator for Fisher's attorney
called Vang about the incident, Vang talked with Internal
Investigations.
</P>
<P>
   Vang said he was telling then-Capt. Clark Kimerer about the
incident when Kimerer interrupted and began grilling him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Capt. Kimerer intimidated and insulted me,'' Vang recalled.
``He tried to minimize what I saw with my very own eyes.'' Kimerer,
now an assistant chief, did not respond to a request for comment.
</P>
<P>
   Kimerer later asked him for a statement, but his request came
eight days after the excessive force complaint was dismissed and
the day after Fisher was convicted of assault.
</P>
<P>
   While Vang was drafting his statement, his sergeant told him to
consider self-preservation over personal integrity at that state of
his career, Vang said.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, Vang never gave a statement. Vang quit in January
1997.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
