<SLUG> BC-BBA-RANGERS-JAYS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLARK FUMBLES LEAD IN RANGERS' DEFEAT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHNNY PAUL 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   TORONTO _ The Rangers play smash-mouth baseball.
</P>
<P>
   Their powerful lineup _ despite its inconsistencies this season
_ mashes and grinds opponents for nearly 5 1/2 runs per game.
</P>
<P>
   Their rotation plays a similar brand of football.
</P>
<P>
   Too often it provides three innings and a cloud of dust.
</P>
<P>
   That unstable combination produced another implosion with last
night's 9-6 defeat to the Toronto Blue Jays at SkyDome.
</P>
<P>
   Four home runs _ two by right fielder Juan Gonzalez and
unexpected ones from center fielder Tom Goodwin and second baseman
Mark McLemore _ accounted for the Rangers' six runs.
</P>
<P>
   It would not be nearly enough.
</P>
<P>
   Right-hander Mark Clark (2-3) produced the sixth start this
season in which a member of the rotation failed to pitch at least
four innings, and the Rangers completed only their 29th game of
this young, yet-growing-old-fast season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we've had three 1-2-3 innings this road trip,''
manager Johnny Oates said afterward. ``You can't play that way.''
</P>
<P>
   Seattle manager Lou Piniella shared a similar experience.
</P>
<P>
   Right-hander Ken Cloude survived the entire 1998 season in the
Mariners' rotation despite his 6.37 earned-run average _ the worst
since 1940 for a pitcher with a minimum of 154 innings pitched _
and 5.18 innings pitched per start.
</P>
<P>
   Cloude, though, was only one member of the Mariners' rotation.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers' rotation appears full of Cloudes. It will enter
this afternoon's game at SkyDome with a 6.35 ERA and averaging 5.08
innings per start.
</P>
<P>
   Clark, who retired only 11 batters before his premature shower,
received two runs in support before Blue Jays right-hander Pat
Hentgen (2-1) threw his ninth pitch.
</P>
<P>
   Goodwin pulled Hentgen's fifth pitch down the right-field line
for only the 10th home run of a major-league career that spans
2,293 at-bats. McLemore followed suit with his first home run of
the season three pitches later.
</P>
<P>
   Clark, though, surrendered four runs during the bottom half of
the inning, which included Carlos Delgado's two-run homer and Mike
Matheny's two-out, run-scoring double.
</P>
<P>
   Thus, the first leadoff home run of Goodwin's career became only
a novelty.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's just his command right now,'' Oates said of
Clark. ``He'll make two good pitches and then make a bad one. The
consistency just isn't there yet, but it will be. It's not like
we're talking about a 20-year-old kid.''
</P>
<P>
   Gonzalez's second homer _ a three-run, seventh-inning blast off
left-hander Dan Plesac _ pulled the Rangers within a run. The Blue
Jays, though, strengthened their 7-6 lead with two runs during the
eighth.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a chance to win this ballgame,'' Gonzalez said.
</P>
<P>
   The bullpen, though, also failed despite a scoreless seventh
inning from right-hander Danny Patterson.
</P>
<P>
   ``Juan's three-run homer made it respectable for half an
inning,'' Oates said. ``Goodwin's and McLemore's home runs made it
respectable for half an inning there.''
</P>
<P>
   Oates does not blame the rotation entirely.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not just the pitching,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Left fielder Rusty Greer agreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``It goes back to getting all three parts _ pitching, hitting
and defense _ on a consistent basis,'' Greer said. ``It's not about
hitting when you don't pitch or pitching when you don't hit or not
playing well defensively.''
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, the Rangers should be scoring enough runs.
</P>
<P>
   The rotation's failures, though, likely will become more
magnified tomorrow.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers will part with a reliever to make room on the roster
for right-hander John Burkett, tomorrow's scheduled starter. The
Rangers likely will expose left-hander Eric Gunderson to outright
waivers by designating him for assignment or option right-hander
Danny Patterson or left-hander Mike Venafro to Triple-A Oklahoma.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't go with three extra guys'' on the bench, Oates said.
``What would I do with the 13 pitchers? I don't need more
pitchers.''
</P>
<P>
   The manager needs outs _ preferably in 1-2-3 fashion _ from the
existing staff.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
