<SLUG> BC-HKN-BLUES-NOTES-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BELFOUR LIKELY TO SEE AGGRESSIVE FOE IN GAME 2
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JENNIFER FLOYD 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ Insiders say Colorado has a chance to unseat defending
Stanley Cup champ Detroit because goalie Patrick Roy has an ability
to steal a series.
</P>
<P>
   Toronto's Curtis Joseph and Buffalo's Dominik Hasek were
credited for doing just that in Round 1. Boston's Byron Dafoe
supposedly has been playing his best hockey.
</P>
<P>
   Every goalie, it seemed, was being talked about as a
series-influencing type of player, except for Stars goalie Ed
Belfour.
</P>
<P>
   Until now.
</P>
<P>
   The St. Louis Blues couldn't stop talking about him after Game
1, a 3-0 Stars victory. Belfour finished with 23 saves and extended
his shutout streak to 130 minutes and one second.
</P>
<P>
   The Blues were suddenly buzzing about how to beat him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we need more traffic in front of him,'' St. Louis
coach Joel Quenneville said. ``I think we need to be hungrier in
front of the net.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Blues winger Geoff Courtnall: ``I think most of the
opportunities we had last night were from the outside. I think we
just have to get a little bit hungrier around the net and get
better opportunities. Their defense does such a good job of not
only blocking shots but clearing the pucks in front of them.''
Welcome back
</P>
<P>
   Blues winger Scott Pellerin skated yesterday, but he said not to
expect him back in the lineup for Game 2.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have to say I'm still a little ways away,'' Pellerin said.
</P>
<P>
   He sprained his groin in St. Louis' opening series against
Phoenix and missed Games 6 and 7. He had an empty-net goal in Game
1.
</P>
<P>
   Pellerin said he planned to be back by Game 4, and maybe, Game 3
in St. Louis.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's day-to-day,'' Quenneville said. ``Maybe, he needs a
little more rest, but we'll see him in this series.''
OK, maybe a little
</P>
<P>
   Blues players were quick to downplay fatigue as a factor to
losing Game 1.
</P>
<P>
   Physical fatigue? No.
</P>
<P>
   Emotional fatigue? Yes.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't play with the same enthusiasm that we just finished
the last series with,'' Quenneville said. ``It's just the way it
is. You play three games with all-out emotion, with life and death,
and maybe you let your guard down a bit.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I think we need to get back and get energized, get
enthused in getting back in the series.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
