<SLUG> BC-BUFFALO-MUSEUM-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESSMAN OPENS MUSEUM TO HOUSE HIS PASSION FOR BUFFALO 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BARBARA YOST  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SCOTTSDALE, Ariz. _ Buffalo roam at Gemmie Baker's insurance
office.
</P>
<P>
   For more than 40 years, Baker has collected buffalo memorabilia.
You name it, he has it: ceramics, pelts, movie posters, china,
silver spoons, miniatures, taxidermy.
</P>
<P>
   He has a stuffed buffalo that children can ride.
</P>
<P>
   He has a theater where he screens the movie ``Dances With
Wolves.''``
</P>
<P>
   He has documents written by ``Buffalo Bill'' Cody.
</P>
<P>
   He has wood carvings, bronzes, hood ornaments, plates and
platters.
</P>
<P>
   Insurance is his business, but buffaloes are his passion.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is my hobby,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   That's an understatement. How many people open up a museum just
to house a hobby?
</P>
<P>
   Eight years ago, Baker founded the Buffalo Museum of America in
a strip center at Scottsdale Road and Shea Boulevard. His insurance
office takes up one corner of the first floor. The museum sprawls
across the rest of the two-story rented space, divided into such
areas as the Dances With Wolves room, the Buffalo Bill room and the
Wounded Knee room.
</P>
<P>
   He can't even estimate how many items he owns. Thousands. A
whole herd of stuff.
</P>
<P>
   The Buffalo Museum is one of more than 30 Valley institutions
that will offer free admission in May during Museum Month. The
event is sponsored by the Central Arizona Museum Association and
Robinsons-May department stores.
</P>
<P>
   Participants can pick up a Museum Passport and Museum Brochure
at Robinsons-May checkout counters. The pass allows one-time free
admission at each institution.
</P>
<P>
   Museum Month gives people a chance to visit not only such
well-known destinations as the Phoenix Art Museum and the Heard
Museum but also lesser-known Scottsdale venues, such as the
Hoo-Hoogam Ki Museum, the Sylvia Plotkin Judaica Museum and the
Buffalo Museum.
</P>
<P>
   Baker says his place is something of a well-kept secret, but he
believes it's the only one of its kind in the country. Despite the
popularity of the American icon, scientifically known as the bison,
his objects are rare.
</P>
<P>
   ``Buffalo items are hard to find today,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Although Baker had been a collector since he was a boy, amassing
stores of coins, antiques and iron works, he decided to concentrate
on buffalo 10 years ago. He and his wife moved to Arizona in 1972
and brought everything along, planning to open a museum someday to
show off the collection.
</P>
<P>
   It became a family project for Baker, married 43 years, father
of two children, grandfather of two.
</P>
<P>
   ``People wanted to see it, so I set it up,'' he says. Shaking
his head, he adds, ``It was so much work I would never do it
again.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet with the museum bursting its seams, Baker is determined to
expand into a larger facility. He's now cataloging every item, a
tedious task with no end in sight.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're just trying to tie the history together,'' he says,
``for historians and museum buffs to look at.''
</P>
<P>
   It's the ``heritage part of it'' that attracts American
visitors, but European tourists also enjoy the place, he says.
</P>
<P>
   It's a favorite of schoolchildren, who eagerly climb aboard the
stuffed and saddled buffalo downstairs and delight in the animated,
talking buffalo family upstairs. Mom, Dad and calf croon a bison
version of ``Home on the Range'' while a prairie dog pops out of
its hole.
</P>
<P>
   In the Dances With Wolves room, a ``dead'' rubber buffalo lies
mortally wounded. Covered in fake fur and sporting a bloody gash,
it was one of the props used in the 1990 Kevin Costner film. Back
home in South Dakota, Baker and his brother, a truck driver, once
delivered buffalo to the ranch where the movie was filmed.
</P>
<P>
   The featured attraction in the Buffalo Bill room is a scrapbook,
event posters and a rifle owned by the Western showman.
</P>
<P>
   A collection of silver teaspoons, all bearing buffalo motifs,
includes one spoon commemorating the 1803 Louisiana Purchase
Exposition.
</P>
<P>
   Bronze sculptures have been collected from France, England,
Siberia and Czechoslovakia.
</P>
<P>
   ``People shake their heads. They don't have any idea how many
items there were that were buffalo,'' Baker says.
</P>
<P>
   Museum Month brings in more visitors.
</P>
<P>
   ``We get quite a few people who come out every year for that,''
Baker says, promising, ``they'll see things they haven't seen
before.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-08-99 0049EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
