u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HOLOCAUST-SURVIVOR-SP     05-08 0972
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOLOCAUST-SURVIVOR-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ONE WHO SURVIVED URGES STUDENTS TO BE TOLERANT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JUDI HUNT  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ KENT, Wash. _ Teenager Sara Wilson leaned against a
wall in the school auditorium, unable to take her eyes off
Holocaust survivor Bronka Serebrin: ``I'll remember her and this
day forever.''
</P>
<P>
   Sara won't be the only one, judging from the reactions Friday of
other Sequoia Junior High School students who heard Serebrin
describe the horrors she endured as a teenager at the Auschwitz and
Mauthausen concentration camps during World War II.
</P>
<P>
   The 350 teenagers hung on to Serebrin's every word, so still and
silent not even a chair squeaked at Kent-Meridian High School's
performing arts center. They rushed to the stage to hug her when
she was through.
</P>
<P>
   During her speech, Serebrin implored the students to be nice to
each other and speculated that the Columbine High School massacre
in Littleton, Colo., was caused by two boys who had been treated
badly for years. She also urged them not to stand by and let others
suffer in any way.
</P>
<P>
   ``Help each other, love each other and don't ever hate. It's
hate that leads to bad things happening like the Holocaust or the
ethnic cleansing _ I hate those words _ in Kosovo.''
</P>
<P>
   What impressed Sara most were the vivid images Serebrin's words
evoked.
</P>
<P>
   ``And the power of her words!'' the 14-year-old said. ``This is
real. She's living proof that what we've been studying actually
happened, just the way we've heard.''
</P>
<P>
   The students were awestruck by the diminutive Serebrin, who told
her story bluntly and calmly.
</P>
<P>
   She described how her entire family, except for her sister,
perished in the Holocaust. She talked about working as a slave in a
munitions and airplane parts factory, with only a piece of bread
and soup to eat once a week. ``And the cold, we were always
freezing with the cold.''
</P>
<P>
   The teenagers, who have been studying the Holocaust for more
than a month, didn't even squirm when Serebrin finished her story
and started lecturing them about how to behave toward people who
are different.
</P>
<P>
   She warned against mistreating people of different races,
religions and ethnicities _ or who simply don't fit in.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what Hitler did, he went after the gypsies, gay people,
the mentally ill, the Jews, Jehovah's Witnesses, ethnic people,''
said Serebrin, who spent six years in concentration camps. ``Don't
pick on each other. That's what Hitler did to the Jews and I know
how very painful, very hurtful it can be.
</P>
<P>
   ``And you don't realize what it might do to someone. Look at
those two boys in Colorado. They were picked on and picked on until
something cracked.''
</P>
<P>
   Serebrin also advised her young audience to cherish their
families.
</P>
<P>
   ``My sister, who was in the same camps as I was, is the only
other survivor of a large family that numbered 65 with aunts,
uncles and cousins. I watched my mother die in the Jewish Ghetto in
Poland.
</P>
<P>
   ``My father is in that big pile of ashes they've saved as a
memorial at Auschwitz. He was put in the line that went to the gas
ovens so I know he's dead, too.''
</P>
<P>
   As for the Ku Klux Klan and other white supremacist groups, she
admonished: Stay away.
</P>
<P>
   ``Be against what they stand for. Don't listen to them,
especially that man (Louis) Farrakhan, who is teaching you to hate
me (the Jews). You don't want to hate me, you love me.''
</P>
<P>
   Serebrin was joined Friday by Leo Hymas, a World War II veteran
and a member of Gen. George Patton's 97th Infantry Division. Hymas,
who was at Sequoia Junior High to give another dimension to the
Holocaust, shared his memories of liberating the Buchenwald
concentration camp in Germany.
</P>
<P>
   When their turn came to question Serebrin and Hymas, the
students most often turned to Serebrin, who used to own Bronka, a
trendy Seattle clothing shop that's now closed.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the students prefaced their questions with ``I'm sorry
you had to suffer like that,'' and ``I'm glad you survived.''
</P>
<P>
   They wanted to know everything: what a day was like in the
camps, how she got through the beatings, what she did to survive
starvation (``we'd find a piece of raw potato skin and eat that'')
and what she did to keep from freezing to death.
</P>
<P>
   ``I survived because of my faith,'' Serebrin replied. ``And
never losing my spirit, like my father did when we were in the
ghetto before being sent to the concentration camps.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was so spirited I would have gone and gotten Hitler out of
his bunker, if I could have escaped. But there was no escape, they
watched us all the time while we worked and when we slept.
</P>
<P>
   ``So instead, I sabotaged some of the small parts I made for the
German war planes, the ones called Messerschmitts. I would have
been killed instantly if they had caught me, but it was my way of
fighting back.''
</P>
<P>
   Serebrin was liberated from Mauthausen in 1945 by U.S. troops.
</P>
<P>
   When the question session finally ended, students were still
lined up at the microphones. That is, until they saw classmates
crowding around Serebrin. Suddenly everyone was down in front,
trying to get close to her.
</P>
<P>
   They all had something to say to her and were delighted when she
listened, then gave them big hugs and kisses. Even the most macho
male students looked pleased at the mushiness. And Serebrin? ``I
feel like a movie star.''
</P>
<P>
   But she still took the time to remind them, ``Don't forget,
don't ever forget.'' That's why she's telling her story publicly,
so people will remember the Holocaust.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they don't, it will happen again, it is already
happening,'' she said. ``Soon all the survivors will be gone and
there will be no one to tell with their own lips how it really was.
I think it's important that we do that now, while there is time.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-08-99 0053EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
