<DOCNO> NYT19990508.0019 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-08 00:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9199 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  CELL-PHONEUSERS:LETUSOFF     05-08 0685
</HEADER>
<BODY>
 CELL-PHONE USERS: LET US OFF THE HOOK  
 (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID LEIBOWITZ  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   There we were Thursday morning, in mid-workout, each of us
sweating on a Stairmaster. Well, actually, I was on the
Stairmaster. One machine over, Blondie was on her cellular phone.
</P>
<P>
   ``I . . . erf . . . like . . . hof . . . can . . . uff . . . not
. . . hif . . . be . . . awg . . . lieve . . . her,'' she said.
``That's . . . ooof . . . lame.''
</P>
<P>
   Yours truly, like, couldn't have agreed more. Especially after
13 painful minutes (during which I, like, burned exactly 207.7
calories!).
</P>
<P>
   The good news: I am nothing if not a man of action.
</P>
<P>
   Me: ``Tell . . . erf . . . him . . . ooof . . . to . . . hold .
. . on!''
</P>
<P>
   Blondie: ``Huff?''
</P>
<P>
   Me: ``You're . . . hof . . . hif . . . rude.''
</P>
<P>
   Blondie: ``Whatever!''
</P>
<P>
   What followed was a hotly contested debate _ four minutes (63.3
calories!) _ on the subject of cell-phone etiquette. She made her
points, I made mine, and while I regret suggesting certain
anatomically-specific uses for a Motorola StarTac tele phone, I
don't regret the outcome.
</P>
<P>
   Blondie: ``I'll . . . erf . . . call . . . hof . . . you . . .
back.''
</P>
<P>
   Score one for right-thinking Americans everywhere. And welcome
to the new millennium, where we, citizens who de mand chitchat-free
personal space, will take back our restaurants, ballgames, pro duce
aisles, theaters and Stairmasters.
</P>
<P>
   OK, fine. They can have the Stairmas ters. Anywhere else, the
cellular plague has to stop. &QL; 
Forced etiquette
</P>
<P>
   A few weeks ago, I was watching The Matrix when a man one row
ahead of me took a call during the previews. I ex plained to him
that I like the previews, and that, compared to the acting of Keanu
Reeves, these previews might win an Academy Award. He explained
that he thought the previews ``didn't count as part of the movie.''
A large man two rows over then told Cellular Man he'd ``better have
911 on his speed dial.''
</P>
<P>
   End, happily, of debate.
</P>
<P>
   The debate is ending in other places as well. On Wednesday, the
New York Times reported on the latest Manhattan restau rant trend:
Cell-phone-free dining rooms.
</P>
<P>
   They've been outlawed for the beauti ful people eating at Tabla
and for the downscale types who frequent the Old Town Bar on East
18th Street.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a cellular-free zone. People have to go outside,'' Old
Town manager Gerard Meagher told the Times. ``We try to maintain
the spirit of a tavern, a place of good feeling and fellowship.
Talking on a cell phone is self-indulgent.''
</P>
<P>
   That self-indulgence sits at the heart of cellular sickness.
These phones have be come pocket Porsches, handheld status symbols,
the '90s equivalent of designer jeans. Every publicly uttered
syllable shouts, ``Here I am, and I'm important, too important to
be out of touch.'' &QL; 
A time for everything
</P>
<P>
   My own rule of thumb, as a longtime cell-phone owner and private
cell-phone user: If you feel compelled to reach out and touch
someone, do it where you can not be heard. Alone is the key. Coat
clos ets work fine, as do dark alleys and J.D. Hayworth press
conferences.
</P>
<P>
   Even a moving vehicle is an acceptable alternative: At least a
crash might mean once less cell-phone user in the world. Besides,
given the number of chitchatting drivers, chances are you'd merely
hit an other Cellular Person.
</P>
<P>
   Yeah, I know that's harsh. But this is war. We can take no
prisoners.
</P>
<P>
   Which isn't to say we can't make ex ceptions. A perfect example:
</P>
<P>
   ALTA, Utah (Associated Press) _ A skier buried chest-high in an
avalanche found his cell phone in a jacket pocket and managed to
dial for help.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Ron Clark, his two sons and 12 other skiers and snowboarders
were swept up by a slide that roared down Lone Peak Ridge on
Wednesday. Clark said his jacket was twisted over his head by the
force of the slide, placing his cell phone in a pocket in front of
his face.
</P>
<P>
   To me, that scenario sounds frigid, frightening and really
painful.
</P>
<P>
   The moral: If it's a cold day in hell, then you can use the cell
phone. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-08-99 0055EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990508.0020 </DOCNO>
