   NA895607-TNS-WIR BC-LEWIS-COLUMN-NYT 719 5/07,21:51 U K
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY: WHEN LEADERSHIP FAILS
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-08-99 0117EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990508.0023 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-08 01:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9216 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SOC-GALAXY-LADN-(SLAN     05-08 0484
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-GALAXY-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GALAXY REGROUPS IN KANSAS CITY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By FRED J. ROBLEDO  
 c.1999 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PASADENA, Calif. _ When defensive midfielder Danny Pena joined
the Galaxy in 1997, he brought much more than his reckless style of
play. He brought a hockey, drop-your-gloves-and-fight fierceness.
It's an attitude he carries off the field as well.
</P>
<P>
   That's why he has no problem explaining the Galaxy's poor 4-3
start, with only one of those victories coming in regulation.
</P>
<P>
   Los Angeles has scored only four goals in seven games as it
prepares to meet winless Kansas City (0-7) at Arrowhead Stadium
today at 5:30 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   As Pena explained, the Galaxy has been relying on Clint Mathis
and Cobi Jones to be the strikers because Welton is injured and
Carlos Hermosillo remains in Mexico. To make matters worse, Mathis
is unavailable this afternoon because of a red-card suspension and
Jones is questionable after injuring his toe last week.
</P>
<P>
   ``People have to understand that we have a couple of forwards up
top that are not natural forwards,'' Pena said. ``Cobi has always
been more effective out on the flanks and Clint has always been
more effective in the middle of the field.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just a matter of getting our forwards healthy and letting
our guys move to their natural positions.''
</P>
<P>
   When people suggest the Galaxy's record is only a preview of
what lies ahead, Pena just shrugs and shakes his head.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no worry or panic with this team at all,'' said Pena.
``That's nonsense. The confidence on this team keeps rising,
whether it's a shootout win or not.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know it's just a matter of time before we start breaking
through and creating more opportunities for ourselves.''
</P>
<P>
   Like many other players have stated before, one of the reasons
for Pena's optimism is coach Sigi Schmid.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we go into a game, we feel like we're going in with a
game plan,'' Pena said. ``Not only offensively but defensively.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we defend, we're defending as a team as opposed to five
or six guys defending and the offensive players just sitting up
front and waiting for counter attacks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now, the defending starts up front and moves all the way down.
It won't take long before the wins start piling up. We know we're
headed in the right direction.''
</P>
<P>
   Just as the Galaxy rewarded the newly hired Schmid with a
victory in his first game two weeks ago, the Wizards will be trying
to do the same for newly hired coach Bob Gansler, who replaced Ron
Newman on April 28.
</P>
<P>
   ``When Sigi came in here, San Jose was afraid to play us because
they knew Sigi would inject some new energy into us,'' said Pena.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's why we expect them (Kansas City) to come out flying.
But if we do the things Sigi says he wants out of us, I don't think
we're going to have any problems with Kansas City.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
