<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-CHINA-U.N.-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.N. SECURITY COUNCIL MEETS AS CHINA VOICES ANGER 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS _ The U.N. Security Council met in an emergency
session early Saturday morning to consider the NATO bombing of the
Chinese Embassy in Belgrade.
</P>
<P>
   The Chinese mission issued a statement condemning the bombing.
``NATO's barbarian act is a gross violation of the U.N. Charter,
international law and norms covering international relations,'' the
statement said. ``It is also a violation of the Geneva Convention.
NATO should be responsible for all the consequences. We call on
NATO to stop immediately its military actions.''
</P>
<P>
   The Russian representative, Sergei V. Lavrov, said early on
Saturday: ``I don't think it's a proper time for comment on the
diplomatic process. It means a lot for the Chinese Embassy.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   As delegates filed into the Security Council chamber near
midnight, Peter Burleigh, the acting U.S. representative at the
United Nations, struck a tone that was both cautious and resolute.
``In case it was a NATO bomb, it is obviously something we deeply
regret, and we apologize for it. We never target civilians and we
would never target an embassy,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Burleigh added: ``I also feel, and will say to the council, that
it's very important, despite this, to keep our eye on the big
picture, and the big picture is that Slobodan Milosevic is
responsible for what's going on in Yugoslavia now.''
</P>
<P>
   In Beijing, the Chinese government, in a statement read on
television news, called the attack a ``brutal encroachment on the
sovereignty of China.''
</P>
<P>
   The television report, on the main national news program at noon
Saturday, was the first notice to the public in Beijing of the
embassy bombing, which seems certain to evoke wide public outrage
and damage Chinese-American relations. Officials in Beijing said
the attack would create intense pressures on the government to more
forcefully oppose the American-led intervention in Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
