<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-08 01:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9220 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JENNY-ASSESS-AZR &LR;      05-08 0861
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JENNY-ASSESS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DROP REMOTE, TAKE CONTROL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVE WALKER  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   One suggestion to fix our culture in the wake of the Littleton,
Colo., killings is to teach media literacy to our citizens. The
idea: Had the coldblooded killers understood that TV shows and
music and computer games aren't real _ had they been intellectually
equipped to passionlessly process the messages they got from their
entertainment choices _ perhaps there would now be no grieving.
</P>
<P>
   Though it likely wouldn't have averted what happened at
Columbine High, media-literacy education for all is an excellent
idea. In the wake of Friday's verdict in the ``Jenny Jones'' case,
let's move right along to Lesson One: You, and only you, are
accountable for your actions.
</P>
<P>
   The news and entertainment industries aren't. They can't be,
because you really don't want them to be. Hollywood, the news and
entertainment media and all those creepy video games are made
possible by the brand of rapacious capitalism that we've agreed, as
a society, to worship.
</P>
<P>
   Network officials and movie moguls have no social agenda, no
conscience, no obligation to make the world a better place. They
are accountable only to profitability.
</P>
<P>
   When you consume their products, you vote for the system. The
operative criterion here, just to repeat, is bucks. All of the
other media-literacy lessons you'll get are secondary. I know it
sounds a lot like Ned Beatty's big speech in ``Network,'' but it's
pure truth.
</P>
<P>
   Granted, Friday's jury in Pontiac, Mich., would seem to
disagree, holding Jenny Jones' show accountable for the violent
actions of one of its guests. The jury was wrong, and its decision
will be negated by an appellate court. But what those jurors
attempted to articulate is worth talking about for a few more
minutes, or at least until the news cycle turns to another tragedy.
</P>
<P>
   The jury said, in the interpretation of Scott Amedure's family's
attorney Geoffrey Fieger, ``You can't abuse other people for
profit.''
</P>
<P>
   It's a humane concept, utterly holistic, quaint, nostalgic even.
It demonstrates a vague sense of civic anger at big-media
companies, and distaste for the daytime-TV muckbath enjoyed by a
significant percentage of the jury's neighbors.
</P>
<P>
   Bringing suit and hoping for such a jury is one way of bucking
the system that produces shows like Jenny Jones'. Because this $25
million verdict is certain to be voided on appeal, the Amedure
family's victory _ and the jury's statement _ is rhetorical at
best. Besides, $25 million isn't very much to a company like Time
Warner, the ``Jenny Jones'' parent company whose executives likely
spend that much each year in airport newsstands.
</P>
<P>
   Another way _ the only way, really _ to buck the system is
taking yourself and your family off the pop-culture grid. Sounds
simple, right? If you believe that TV, pop music, computers,
computer games and the Internet played some part, however small, in
inspiring the Littleton rampage, don't call your congressman. He is
likely having lunch with a National Association of Broadcasters
lobbyist, anyway.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, quickly call your mutual-fund manager to ensure you're
not currently profiting from soaring digital-industry stocks.
</P>
<P>
   Also, forget about seeing ``The Wild Wild West'' this summer,
which is positioned as Warner Bros.' big popcorn movie of the
season. And while you're at it, black-out the ``TV Week'' listings
for ``The Drew Carey Show, Friends'' and ``ER.'' All are Warner
Bros. products. ``Buffy, the Vampire Slayer, Felicity, Dawson's
Creek'' _ all airing on the Warner Bros. television network _ get
crossed off, too.
</P>
<P>
   And, sorry, junior, no more Poke mon, either.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jenny Jones'' was all over CNN on Friday because we have
agreed, as a society, to let the marketplace run our lives. If you
do not approve of ``Jenny Jones,'' don't watch it. If it really
makes you angry, don't watch its local carrier, Fox affiliate
Channel 10 (KSAZ), at all. No more ``The X-Files.'' No more NFC
football. See ya, Homer Simpson.
</P>
<P>
   It's not going to be easy.
</P>
<P>
   But the only other option is government intervention, and based
on the vast numbers of people who call talk radio to gripe about
Big Brother, that's not going to happen.
</P>
<P>
   The point that Jones herself made on the stand in this case is
accurate. I'll restate it here: The people you see on daytime talk
shows are not conscripts. They're volunteers. They get what they
deserve. No, that doesn't include death, but consumers of the
``Jenny Jones'' show are as accountable as its producers. After
all, who holds the clicker?
</P>
<P>
   Arming yourself and your loved ones with media-literacy
knowledge and strategies is nice, but, as a consumer in this
culture, you're most powerful at the point of purchase.
</P>
<P>
   The best thing about absorbing live and late-breaking news on
one of the cable-news networks is how they keep you posted on the
true state of the Union by carrying the day's running financial box
scores. No matter how bad the real news might seem, the economy
rocks on.
</P>
<P>
   Friday, the Dow finished up a perky 84.77. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-08-99 0120EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
