<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-CHINA-REACT-2NDLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EMBASSY BOMBING MAY WIDEN CHINA OPPOSITION TO NATO  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (SUBS lede to update with Chinese condemnation of embassy bombing;
3rd graf to delete outdated material; 5th graf to update New China
News Agency casualty report to 2 DEAD, 4 WOUNDED)  By ERIK ECKHOLM   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIJING _ China strongly condemned the bombing of its embassy in
Belgrade, the official New China News Agency reported today, as
Chinese diplomats at the United Nations in New York called for an
emergency meeting of the Security Council. Foreign policy experts
and officials here said the attack would create intense pressures
on the government to oppose forcefully the U.S.-led air attacks in
Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   Late Saturday morning, news of the embassy bombing had not yet
been reported on television, and much of the public remained
unaware of the attack. But at the United Nations in New York, the
Chinese delegate, Qin Huasun, said, ``NATO's barbarian act is a
violation of the U.N. charter,'' and he repeated Chinese calls for
an immediate end to the air campaign.
</P>
<P>
   As news of the bombing and casualties becomes more widely known
here, it is certain to inflame the already passionate sense that
NATO's bombing raids in Yugoslavia constitute illegal aggression _
a view deeply held by much of the public as well as by officials.
</P>
<P>
   The New China News Agency said Saturday morning that two people
were confirmed dead and four were wounded.
</P>
<P>
   But if current diplomatic initiatives fail to stop the campaign,
it is not clear what direct measures China could take to counter
NATO.
</P>
<P>
   ``The government has already been under increasing pressure to
take stronger action against the NATO bombing,'' said a military
officer who spoke on the condition of anonymity, and did not know
about the embassy incident until he was told.
</P>
<P>
   The officer said that even before the attack, there was a
consensus among senior military officers that China should more
strongly counter the NATO raids, which China views as an illegal
intervention in a sovereign country.
</P>
<P>
   Jia Qingguo, a professor of international studies at Beijing
University, said, ``This strengthens the hand of those who have
argued for closer Chinese-Russian cooperation in aiding Serbia
against NATO.''
</P>
<P>
   ``In the past, China opposed the bombing but Yugoslavia was far
away,'' Jia said. ``Now the war is brought closer to home.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-08-99 0125EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
