<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LITTON-DEAL-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEAL SKIRTS RIVAL'S WOES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY GREGORY J. WILCOX  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- Litton Industries Inc.'s $2.4 billion bid to
become the nation's biggest military shipbuilder might not
encounter the same turbulence that scuttled a similar maneuver by
rival General Dynamics Corp., analysts said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Litton's separate offers late Thursday for Newport News
Shipbuilding and Avondale Industries Inc. came about two weeks
after the Department of Defense blocked General Dynamics' attempt
to buy Newport News. Antitrust regulators sunk that deal because of
its anti-competitive nature.
</P>
<P>
   Combining Litton's Pascagoula, Miss.,-based Ingalls Shipbuilding
with Newport News and Avondale would still give the Defense
Department a choice of two contractors for nuclear-powered ships
and submarines.
</P>
<P>
   Combined, the three companies would have revenue of about $7.4
billion and more than 58,000 employees.
</P>
<P>
   ``My feeling is that the Litton-Newport-Avondale merger has a
much greater chance of passing muster with the Pentagon,'' said
Robert Friedman, the aerospace and defense industry analyst at
Standard &AMP; Poors Equity Group in New York City. ``At least you have
two different companies making nuclear vessels, not just one.''
</P>
<P>
   General Dynamics' $1.4 billion unsolicited offer for Newport
News would have created a company that received about 90 percent of
the U.S. Navy's research and development money and 70 percent of
the construction funds.
</P>
<P>
   ``That did not go over well with the Department of Defense,''
said Brian Madonick, an analyst at Bear Stearns &AMP; Co.
</P>
<P>
   Under a bigger Litton, the research and development money would
be split evenly with General Dynamics; the construction funds would
be tipped about 60-40 in Litton's favor.
</P>
<P>
   Madonick does not believe there would be any major obstacles to
Litton acquiring either Newport News or Avondale.
</P>
<P>
   ``To acquire both is a little tougher but I think it has a
better chance than not of going through,'' he said. ``It's more
balanced this way in terms of the construction budget and
engineering plus you're better matching the teams, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Newport News, based in Newport News, Va., is the only U.S. maker
of nuclear-powered aircraft carriers. Avondale, based in Avondale,
La., manufactures amphibious assault vehicles and other military
ships.
</P>
<P>
   Buying these two companies would give Litton shipyards on the
East, West and Gulf coasts. The West Coast operations are at the
former Continental Marine site in San Diego, where maintenance,
repair and renovation work is done on Navy vessels.
</P>
<P>
   So far there is no timetable for the federal review process.
Litton's offer still must be evaluated by the boards of directors
at Newport News and Avondale.
</P>
<P>
   But the federal officials were made aware of Litton's intention
before the bid was made public.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had preliminary discussions with the Department of Defense
about our proposals and we are well aware of the considerations
that led to the rejection of the proposed combination between
General Dynamics and Newport News Shipbuilding,'' Michael R. Brown,
Litton chairman and chief executive officer, said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
   Newport News and Avondale had already agreed to merge and that
deal won Department of Justice approval.
</P>
<P>
   Defense Department spokesman Glenn Flood said that the review of
Litton will still focus on competitive measures but it is not
likely to take very long once it starts in light of the General
Dynamics situation. That evaluation took about a month.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think it should go faster since we've done a lot of the
homework already. But it's still early in the game,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The deal appeared to pick up support from two powerful
legislators on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``The teaming of Avondale and Newport News would create the
world's most competitive shipbuilding force,'' Senate Majority
Leader Trent Lott and Sen. Thad Cochran said in a joint statement.
Both are Republicans from Mississippi.
</P>
<P>
   They said the new shipbuilding team would save taxpayers
millions of dollars because of efficiencies gained in design and
construction.
</P>
<P>
   But Sen. John Warner, the Virginia Republican who chairs the
Senate Armed Services Committee, was more cautious.
</P>
<P>
   ``There will have to be a complete evaluation of this from a
national security standpoint and from the perspective of the
employees of the yards,'' Warner said. He holds some critical sway
because he had strong reservations about General Dynamics bid for
Newport News, which is headquartered in his state.
</P>
<P>
   X X X &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
