 SOX-ANGELS-BOS 
FENWAY FANS FAITHFUL TO FORMER FAVORITE &HT;    (For use by New York Times News Service clients) 
 &HT;     By DAN SHAUGHNESSY 
 &HT;     c.1999 The Boston Globe 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   There was a playoff atmosphere at Fenway Friday afternoon and
evening. Thanks to Pedro Martinez. Thanks to Mo Vaughn.
Unfortunately, it won't be like this again around the old yard
until the All-Star Game or until Roger Clemens pitches here for the
Yankees _ whichever comes first.
</P>
<P>
   Mo's Comeback Concert filled Fenway and the Mo bashers had their
way as the Hit Dog fanned twice and went 0 for 4 as the Angels
succumbed to the 15-strikeout mastery of Boston's new best player,
King Pedro.
</P>
<P>
   Vaughn got a rousing ovation when he came to the plate in the
first inning, but as the evening wore on, fans hooted him as they
would any other rival star.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was already the enemy,'' Mo said with a grin after the game.
``But that's expected. The fans are gonna get behind their team.
It's really no big deal. I'm sure they'll be all over me
tomorrow.''
</P>
<P>
   It was an eventful day for Vaughn. He visited his youth
foundation in Dorchester, then arrived at Fenway, via limo, at
around 2 p.m. and took some early hitting in the cages under the
center field bleachers. He swapped greetings with Jim Rice and
Flash Gordon, and was surprised when Red Sox CEO John Harrington
stopped by the visitor's clubhouse to wish him well (apparently Shy
John is finally listening to those high-priced consultants he keeps
hiring).
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a good exchange between two men,'' said Vaughn. ``We
put things aside and it was nice. He didn't have to do that.''
</P>
<P>
   Two hours before the first pitch, an overview of the field
provided a funny sight. From high above the diamond, it looked as
if somebody had tilted Fenway to the left, forcing all reporters to
roll toward the visitor's dugout.
</P>
<P>
   Pointing to the first base bench, Sox publicist Kevin ``Dean
Wormer'' Shea said, ``Ah, guys, the Red Sox dugout is over there.''
</P>
<P>
   True. The Sox dugout is on the first base side. But the story
was on the other side. The pregame story was the return of Mo.
</P>
<P>
   When Vaughn came out to stretch with his teammates, he said
hello to Jimy Williams, Mike Stanley, and best pal John Valentin.
Stanley and Vaughn inspected a first baseman's mitt. Mo has become
Stanley's glove supplier.
</P>
<P>
   The gates opened at 5:30 and Mo was an obvious target as he
stood on the field.
</P>
<P>
   ``We love you, Mo.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You're always welcome here, Mo.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Put two or three off the wall tonight. Put it right back in
Duquette's face.''
</P>
<P>
   And . . .
</P>
<P>
   ``You suck. Go home, Mo!''
</P>
<P>
   Red Sox general manager Dan Duquette did not make his customary
rounds behind the batting cage during the pregame drills. Just as
well. We were spared a phony handshake between enemies.
</P>
<P>
   There had been a report in a Boston paper that a group of
performers from the Foxy Lady might make the trek from Providence
to cheer for Mo. Your intrepid servant attempted to find said
representatives in the stands, but uncovered nothing. I spotted
three possible suspects, but let's face it: There is no way to
politely ask, ``Excuse me, are you a stripper?''
</P>
<P>
   At game time, Mo stood on the dugout step, bat in hand, as Darin
Erstad stepped in to face Pedro. When Erstad doubled off the glove
of Stanley (thousands quipped ``Mo would have had it''), Vaughn
walked to the on-deck circle. At 7:13 p.m., after Matt Walbeck
grounded to third, Mo stepped to the Fenway plate for the first
time.
</P>
<P>
   The initial reaction was a chorus of boos _ as if Antoine Walker
had just missed a pair of free throws. Then the groundswell
started. Fans stood and applauded. You may get arguments from
others who were there, but from an open air seat in the press box,
the first-inning boos were submerged by a wave of good will.
</P>
<P>
   As the applause mounted, Mo turned on his heels and saluted Red
Sox Nation.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was definitely nice,'' he said. ``I'll appreciate that as
long as I play this game. But it was really hard facing these guys.
It's tough facing guys you played with a long time. I did a lot of
good here, but to get your feet in that batter's box brings back a
lot of memories.''
</P>
<P>
   Pedro's first pitch to Mo was a called strike. On the next
pitch, Vaughn ripped a drive to the foul side of Pesky's Pole. He
fouled an 0-2 pitch, took ball one, then swung wildly and missed
Pedro's 1-2 offspeed offering.
</P>
<P>
   Mighty Mo had struck out and there was joy in Mudville, not to
mention smirks all around in Executive Box F.
</P>
<P>
   The booing was decidedly stronger in subsequent at-bats. Vaughn
grounded to first on a 3-0 pitch his second time up, then fanned
(swinging) on a 3-2 pitch in the sixth. By this time, he was
getting the Bob Stanley treatment.
</P>
<P>
   In the top of the eighth, with Pedro leading, 6-0, and the game
no longer in doubt, Vaughn came up for the last time. A hail of
boos. Ulf Samuelsson stuff. Pedro had taken over the game. Mo flied
to center on a 1-0 pitch.
</P>
<P>
   The crowd stood and cheered.
</P>
<P>
   For Pedro.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
