<HEADLINE>
HENDERSON ON DISABLED LIST 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX _ When Steve Phillips, the Mets' general manager, signed
Rickey Henderson and acquired Bobby Bonilla during the off season,
there was speculation about whether the 40-year-old Henderson and
the 36-year-old Bonilla would be able to coax their bodies through
another season.
</P>
<P>
   One month into the season the answer is a resounding no.
</P>
<P>
   Phillips placed Henderson on the 15-day disabled list,
retroactive to May 3, after Friday night's 14-7 loss to the Arizona
Diamondbacks. Henderson, who sprained his right knee last Sunday,
will not be eligible to come off the list until May 18. But
Phillips insisted that he would not place Bonilla, who has been
bothered by a partial ligament tear in his right knee since spring
training, on the disabled list. Bonilla was 1 for 4 Friday night
and is batting .159.
</P>
<P>
   ``Release is not in the plans, nor is a trade in the plans,''
Phillips said. ``We have no plans to release, trade or disable him
at this point.''
</P>
</TEXT>
