<SLUG> BC-BBN-METS-DIAMONDBACKS-GAME-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HERSHISER FLOP DOOMS METS TO 3RD STRAIGHT LOSS 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By JASON DIAMOS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX _ No matter how many times the Mets tried to bail him
out Friday night, Orel Hershiser did not deserve to win. But the
Mets' 14-7 loss to the Arizona Diamondbacks _ the most runs New
York has allowed this season _ had to leave more than a few people
in the crowd wondering how Todd Stottlemyre, who fully deserved to
lose, picked up the victory instead.
</P>
<P>
   Stottlemyre (4-1) threw 111 pitches in just five innings and
allowed a 5-1 lead to disappear. But even after the Mets had
rallied for a short-lived 6-5 lead in the top of the fifth,
Hershiser (2-3) could not hold it in the bottom of the inning, and
the Mets (17-12) lost their third in a row.
</P>
<P>
   As poorly as Stottlemyre pitched _ allowing nine hits and six
runs (five earned) in his five innings _ Hershiser pitched even
worse. The 40-year-old right-hander allowed nine runs on nine hits
in four and a third innings, the first time in nearly three years
that he had allowed that many runs.
</P>
<P>
   In six starts this season, Hershiser has allowed 22 earned runs
in 291/3 innings for an earned run average of 6.75.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets scored once in the first on Robin Ventura's run-scoring
single but left the bases loaded when Bobby Bonilla grounded out to
first.
</P>
<P>
   And then it took Hershiser five batters just to record an out.
Tony Womack _ who would later establish a club record with two
triples _ walked on four pitches to open the Arizona first, and Jay
Bell singled. Luis Gonzalez, who later homered off Josias
Manzanillo to extend his major league-best hitting streak to 20
games, walked on five pitches to load the bases. And that brought
out the pitching coach Bob Apodaca.
</P>
<P>
   The bases were not loaded for very long. On a 1-0 pitch to Matt
Williams, the National League player of the month, Williams cracked
a bases-clearing double through the power alley in right-center
field and then took third when Brian McRae robbed Steve Finley with
a sliding catch in center. Tony Batista followed with a first-pitch
single to right to score Williams. And the Mets were down by 4-1.
</P>
<P>
   After each team scored, Alfonzo drilled a three-run homer off
Stottlemyre with two outs in the fourth to tie the game at 5-5. And
when Mike Piazza ripped an opposite-field double leading off the
Mets' fifth, took third on a Ventura fly to right and scored on a
McRae single, Hershiser and the Mets had a 6-5 lead.
</P>
<P>
   After the second inning, Hershiser had settled down, and when he
got the first out in the fifth he had retired 10 of the last 11
batters. But then Williams belted a double to center, Finley
walked, and Batista singled to load the bases with his ninth hit in
18 career at-bats versus Hershiser.
</P>
<P>
   That brought out Bobby Valentine, asking his starter whether he
thought he could escape the bases-loaded jam. Hershiser convinced
the manager to leave him in.
</P>
<P>
   One pitch later, however, Travis Lee's hit dropped just inside
the left-field line for a bases-clearing double, the Mets were down
by 8-6 and Hershiser was leaving the game.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
