<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-CONTEMPT-1STLD-WRITETHRU-500&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
17.) 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (SUBS 12th graf (`They asked for...') to correct Jan. 18 to JAN. (ATTN: Texas)  
 JONES LAWYERS WANT $496,000 FROM CLINTON  
(Eds: See also STARR-STEELE) 
(mk) 
 By NEIL A. LEWIS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Lawyers for Paula Jones told a federal judge in
Arkansas Friday that President Clinton owed them more than $496,000
as a result of extra work they say they were forced to perform
because of his dishonest testimony in her sexual misconduct case.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Bennett, Clinton's lawyer, immediately denounced the
request as ``unreasonable, greedy and contrary to law,'' and said
he would challenge the amount before the judge, Susan Webber
Wright.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, Bennett said in a letter to Ms. Wright that
the president would not challenge her order of April 12 holding him
in civil contempt. Ms. Wright ruled then that the president lied in
a deposition in the Jones case when, on Jan. 17, 1998, he denied
having engaged in sex with Monica Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   It was this ruling that led to the filing by the Jones lawyers
Friday. In holding Clinton in civil contempt _ the first time a
president had ever been held in contempt of court _ Ms. Wright
ordered that he pay the Jones lawyers ``any reasonable expenses,''
including legal fees, incurred because of his false testimony. In
addition, she ordered him to reimburse the court $1,202, her
expenses for traveling from Little Rock, Ark., to Washington on
Jan. 17 to preside over the deposition.
</P>
<P>
   The size of the Jones lawyers' request for reimbursement and the
swift reaction of the president's chief personal lawyer insures
that the remnants of a case that vexed the Clinton White House for
years and ultimately led to a presidential impeachment drama will
not be put to rest soon.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Wright dismissed Mrs. Jones' lawsuit in April 1998, saying
that even if there was truth in her accusation _ that Clinton
propositioned her in a Little Rock hotel room when he was governor
of Arkansas and she a state clerical employee _ his act did not
amount to sexual harassment or a violation of her constitutional
rights.
</P>
<P>
   In their appeal of that dismissal, Mrs. Jones' lawyers argued
that Clinton had lied in denying a sexual relationship with Ms.
Lewinsky. They cited his admission of last August that in fact he
had had a relationship with her that he described as
``inappropriate.''
</P>
<P>
   Before the appeals court could rule, the president settled the
case by giving Mrs. Jones $850,000, of which she received about
$200,000, with the rest going to her various lawyers.
</P>
<P>
   In filings Friday, the Dallas law firm of Rader, Campbell,
Fisher &AMP; Pyke, which represented Mrs. Jones, submitted fees and
expenses totaling $437,825, while the Rutherford Institute of
Charlottesville, Va., which also provided representation, said it
was owed $58,533.
</P>
<P>
   The Dallas firm said in its submission that Clinton's denial of
an intimate relationship with Ms. Lewinsky ``became one of the most
important aspects'' of its case and involved the work of six
lawyers and two paralegals over many hours.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clinton's lies at his deposition as well as the lies in his
earlier answers to written interrogatories affected our work in
every step of the case from that point forward,'' the Dallas
lawyers asserted.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   They asked for more than $97,000 in fees and expenses that
accrued even before the Jan. 17 deposition, saying the president's
dishonesty began on Dec. 23, 1997, when he answered ``none'' to a
written question asking whether there were any female employees of
the federal government with whom he had had sexual relations.
</P>
<P>
   The expense claim also appears to demand that Clinton pay the
Dallas lawyers for their time spent with Linda Tripp, Ms.
Lewinsky's onetime friend, who became an informer for both the
Jones lawyers and Kenneth Starr, the independent counsel. The claim
includes a charge of $1,500 for 10 hours of work by one of the
Dallas lawyers, T. Wesley Holmes, on Jan. 16, 1998. That appears to
be a meeting with Mrs. Tripp, who was secretly interviewed the
night before the Clinton deposition.
</P>
<P>
   On the day of the deposition, Clinton was so stunned by the
detailed knowledge implicit in the Jones lawyers' questions that he
canceled evening plans and summoned his personal secretary, Betty
Currie, to see him the next day, when he discussed with her his
relationship with Ms. Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   In their filing Friday, the Dallas lawyers said the task of
selecting which of their expenses were attributable to Clinton's
false answers about Ms. Lewinsky had been extremely onerous. In
fact, included in their claim is a bill for more than $12,000 to
pay the costs of trying to figure out how much they were owed.
</P>
<P>
   The expenses range from a $12 claim, for a $60-an-hour paralegal
to read The New York Times and The Washington Post for articles
about Ms. Lewinsky, to lawyers' fees of $150 to $225 an hour for
preparation of legal documents. The Dallas lawyers said their fees
were especially reasonable in comparison with the hourly rate
charged by Bennett, which they estimated at $450.
</P>
<P>
   As for the president's decision not to challenge the contempt
order, some legal scholars had said they thought he would have
strong grounds to fight it. But White House officials said the main
reason for not doing so was to be rid of the case as quickly as
possible.
</P>
<P>
   They also said they had expected that the Jones legal fees in
connection with the contempt order would be about $100,000.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
