<HEADER>
A9232 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-FISHER-LADN     05-08 1102
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-FISHER-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POINTING THE WAY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   INGLEWOOD, Calif. _ Tracking Derek Fisher's NBA career is a
little like watching a seismograph track earthquake aftershocks.
The lines are steady for a while, then jump wildly across the
screen before settling into a calm rhythm again. At least until the
next jolt.
</P>
<P>
   And so far, Fisher's three-year stint with the Lakers has been
less predictable than the shift of tectonic plates.
</P>
<P>
   A quick review of '98: He's the backup point guard, then he's
the starter. Then he's the starter, but he's playing less minutes
than the backup.
</P>
<P>
   New season: He's the starter again. But then he's told he won't
play in crunch time. Then he's starting games but not finishing,
again playing second-string minutes.
</P>
<P>
   A couple of weeks later, he's the backup again. Two months
later, he's the starter again. But, as always, with no guarantees
about what the next game, or even the next quarter, holds for him.
</P>
<P>
   If it's a bit dizzying, it should give you a feel for what the
24-year-old from Arkansas-Little Rock has been through in his short
pro career. Even now, after starting the last 11 games of the
season, anointed the starter for the playoffs that begin Sunday,
Fisher says it's hard to say he feels like the Lakers' starter.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been too crazy. It's been way too crazy,'' he said. ``I'm
starting basically by default. It's not really a feeling of I'm
starting because I'm clearly the best guy for the position or
anything like that. I just feel like I'm starting because I'm
playing well right now, and that could change. That's what's kind
of tough. You really don't know how long it's gonna last, so you
just have to go out and just play.''
</P>
<P>
   And that's where Fisher's rough-and-tumble attitude has
benefited him and the Lakers the most. Since re-inheriting the
starting job from Derek Harper on April 13, Fisher has gradually
regained his confidence and has played at his highest level in the
last week.
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers won their last four games of the regular season, and
Fisher finished with a flurry as well _ averaging 8.0 points and
7.3 assists in the last three games.
</P>
<P>
   When coach Kurt Rambis handed Fisher the reins a few weeks back,
it was because he wanted to rest the 37-year-old Harper. But by the
time the season ended, Fisher had fended off a challenge from
hyperactive rookie Tyronn Lue and won the three-way battle for the
starting job.
</P>
<P>
   His steady play bodes well for the Lakers, who figure Fisher and
Kobe Bryant should give them an edge over the Houston Rockets'
all-rookie backcourt.
</P>
<P>
   ``The way he's been distributing the basketball, Fisher's been
in control,'' Rambis said. ``He's making the right plays at the
right time, getting the ball to the right people. His defense has
always been good, his heart's always been huge, he's just been
playing with more confidence. And I think it shows in all of his
decision making.''
</P>
<P>
   That hasn't always been the case. If there's anything
predictable, in fact, about Fisher's performance, it's that his
slumps usually coincide with a blow to his confidence.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Fisher impressed everyone when he stepped in for the
injured Nick Van Exel in mid-February and played the best month of
his career. But when Van Exel returned and chose to come off the
bench, coach Del Harris eventually started giving Van Exel, an
All-Star, the majority of minutes. Fisher's confidence sagged, he
became more hesitant on the court and his play suffered.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Fisher had shown management he was capable of starting for a
championship contender, and that made the decision easier to ship
Van Exel to Denver last June.
</P>
<P>
   Fisher came to camp as the incumbent starter, with Harper
brought in as backup and tutor. But the day before the season
opener, Harris told Fisher that Harper would finish games. The
unspoken message seemed to be: We trust you, just not during crunch
time.
</P>
<P>
   That, Fisher said, was ``the low point'' of his season. Here he
was in a contract year, trying to prove himself worthy of a
long-term deal from the Lakers, and he'd just had the rug yanked
out from under him.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's really where the mentally exhausting part started,''
Fisher said. ``It put me in the hole from the beginning. Here we
are, we haven't even played a game yet, and he's telling me I
probably won't be playing in the fourth quarter. It was hard for me
to comprehend. And it affected me physically, because mentally I
was all messed up.''
</P>
<P>
   So much so that he stumbled out of the gate, playing a hesitant
and ineffective game for the first two weeks. Harper, meanwhile,
was playing like a 25-year-old again, and Harris eventually
promoted him over Fisher.
</P>
<P>
   It hurt Fisher, who probably worked as hard as anyone during the
offseason, playing daily at UCLA and coming to camp in prime shape.
</P>
<P>
   ``At times I really didn't feel like I was contributing what I
knew I could. I knew how hard I had worked for seven months during
the lockout, and I wasn't even close to playing at the good level I
was capable of playing.''
</P>
<P>
   But after days of second-guessing himself, trying to change his
playing style to fit someone else's expectations and regular calls
to Germany to seek moral support from his brother, Duane
Washington, Fisher just went back to playing without thinking.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been really tough mentally dealing with my own individual
situation, but I think what made it harder for me is we weren't
playing well as a team,'' he said. ``The team was struggling and
that really was hard, trying to tell myself to stay positive every
day, always having to figure out some new trick to stay positive
and stay confident.''
</P>
<P>
   No tricks are needed now. Although Fisher thought his latest
stint as starter would be temporary, he's made it easy for Rambis
to decide against tinkering again. The vote of confidence, however
soft, has made Fisher an effective starter again.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm playing more relaxed and more confident, and that's
because I know I'm gonna be out on the floor,'' he said. ``Before I
tried to play not to come out, trying not to make a mistake or
feeling like I had to make every shot to stay in the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now I feel confident enough where if I miss two or three shots
in a row or I turn the basketball over a couple times, I still know
that I'm gonna be out there on the floor contributing in other ways
and just giving it all that I have. That's done tremendous things
for me mentally.''
</P>
<P>
   A little predictability, in other words, can be comforting.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-08-99 0236EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
