<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-08 02:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9233 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-ANGELS-LADN     05-08 0712
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGELS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARTINEZ STEALS ALL THE MO-MENTUM
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 c.1999 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Anaheim Angels pitcher Shigetoshi Hasegawa noticed the
horde of television reporters and cameramen surrounding somebody
just outside the Angels dugout before Friday's game against the
Boston Red Sox and couldn't resist.
</P>
<P>
   ``Who are they talking to? Madonna? Michael Jackson?'' Hasegawa
asked.
</P>
<P>
   It was none other than Mo Vaughn, whose return to Fenway Park in
an Angels uniform ended without the drama and excitement that was
evident before the game.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels could blame Red Sox starter Pedro Martinez for
spoiling Vaughn's homecoming. Martinez struck out a career-high 15
while throwing eight shutout innings in the Red Sox's 6-0 victory
before a sellout crowd of 32,220.
</P>
<P>
   Vaughn got a standing ovation from the crowd as he walked toward
the plate for his first-inning at-bat, but also heard a smattering
of boos. The crowd cheered even louder when Martinez struck him out
with a changeup for the second out of the inning.
</P>
<P>
   Vaughn finished the game 0-for-4, striking out twice, reaching
on a fielder's choice and flying out to center. A night that
started with Vaughn in the spotlight ended with Martinez taking
bows.
</P>
<P>
   ``Great pitchers can do that,'' Angels manager Terry Collins
said. ``A lot of times great pitchers can make a game like that
with all the hype and take the steam out of it. And it did for
us.''
</P>
<P>
   For Vaughn, the game gave him cause for reflection.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was out there looking at the guys I came up with, guys I won
games with, that was the sad part,'' he said. ``But I had to move
on. I'm glad I got through this. I'm glad it's over. It wasn't
something I marked on my calendar when the season started. I've
played a lot of games, and I just wanted to make this another
one.''
</P>
<P>
   Martinez (6-1) gave up six hits and did not walk a batter in
making 126 pitches. And while he was hard on the Angels hitters, he
still has a soft spot for Vaughn.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said hi to him,'' Martinez said. ``He looked at me like he
always looked at me when he used to play first base, to let me know
that he still loves me and respects me.''
</P>
<P>
   It was a strange atmosphere for the Angels before the game with
so much media attention.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a distraction, but it's fun,'' Collins said during all
the hoopla. ``It's part of the game. You guys have been to the
World Series, the All-Star game. It's what the game is all about.
It's still entertainment, it's still a business. And one of the
biggest entertainers came back.''
</P>
<P>
   Collins said he saw Friday's game as a test for his players. How
would they perform under such scrutiny?
</P>
<P>
   ``When you have this kind of attention you find out who can play
under this scenario,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels didn't show their manager much, although they had
chances against Martinez.
</P>
<P>
   In the first inning, Darin Erstad led off with a double and was
stranded. In the fourth, they had runners at first and second with
one out when Troy Glaus singled to center.
</P>
<P>
   However, Matt Walbeck initially broke back towards second. He
managed to beat center fielder Damon Buford's throw home, but
catcher Jason Varitek blocked the plate and forced Walbeck to slide
past the plate without touching it. Varitek then tagged him out.
</P>
<P>
   Later in the game, Walbeck was run over at the plate by Troy
O'Leary, who tried to score from first on a double by Mike Stanley.
Walbeck hung onto the ball for the out, but had to come out of the
game and had an icepack on his neck and right shoulder after the
game.
</P>
<P>
   ``He got me pretty good, he got me on the chin,'' Walbeck said.
``He could have slid, I gave him half the plate.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked why he didn't run over Varitek when he had the chance,
Walbeck said: ``I don't do that because you can (mess) yourself up.
I'm not going to knock the ball out of his hand, I'm 5-10.... I've
made that (hook slide) a thousand times. It was the right play. He
just rode my foot off the plate. It was a good play on his part.''
</P>
<P>
   Angels starter Omar Olivares didn't pitch poorly, but he was no
match for Martinez. Olivares (3-3) gave up four runs (three earned)
and seven hits in five-plus innings.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
