<HEADLINE>
IT'S NOT GRAND NIGHT FOR DODGERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ As Alan Mills disappeared down the runway of the
Los Angeles Dodgers dugout Friday night, Darren Dreifort made a
point to pat him on the behind and tell him things were OK.
</P>
<P>
   Things obviously were not OK, not after Mills allowed a
pinch-hit grand slam to Bruce Aven in the seventh inning that gave
the lowly Florida Marlins a 6-3 victory in front of a sellout crowd
of 54,009 at Dodger Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   But Mills, who replaced Dreifort with one out in the seventh,
has been the Dodgers' best setup man. He had nine consecutive
scoreless appearances and batters were 1 for 19 with runners in
scoring position.
</P>
<P>
   Against the Marlins, who were opening a nine-game trip after a
2-11 homestand, that usually would have been enough.
</P>
<P>
   Dreifort, who was eight outs from his fifth victory in six
decisions, also knew he was to blame. He did not walk a batter
until the seventh, which would have been a story in itself. He had
walked 22 in 21 innings in April, but just one in his first May
start.
</P>
<P>
   But suddenly in the seventh, Mark Kotsay singled with one out
and Derrek Lee walked. Pitching coach Charlie Hough came to the
mound and the bullpen got busy. Todd Dunwoody followed with an RBI
double to left to cut the Dodgers lead to 3-2.
</P>
<P>
   Jorge Fabregas was intentionally walked and Mills entered the
game. Aven, batting for Marlins starter Dennis Springer (1-4),
worked the count to 2-2 before driving a fastball into the
left-field bleachers.
</P>
<P>
   It was the first pinch grand slam in Marlins history. It also
led to the first save for Marlins hard-throwing closer Matt Mantei,
who had made 12 appearances this season without even a save
opportunity.
</P>
<P>
   Mantei allowed a leadoff double to Todd Hundley to open the
ninth, Hundley's second double of the game. But Eric Karros struck
out. Adrian Beltre, who gave the Dodgers a 1-0 lead in the third
with his second home run, blooped a single to right that moved a
cautious Hundley to third.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Grudzielanek, who does not have a hit this season with
runners in scoring position, popped to short for the second out.
Pinch-hitter Todd Hollandsworth represented the tying run at the
plate, but he struck out on a fastball over his head.
</P>
<P>
   The loss ruined a chance for the Dodgers to keep pace with the
San Francisco Giants, who won and now lead the Dodgers by 1{ games
in the NL West.
</P>
<P>
   It is a little early for pennant talk, but the Giants have been
struggling and the Dodgers were coming off a 7-2 road trip.
</P>
<P>
   Beltre gave the Dodgers a 1-0 lead in the third and the club
added two more in the fourth on an RBI single by Raul Mondesi and
an RBI by Karros on a fielder's choice.
</P>
<P>
   But that play hurt the Dodgers, too. Mondesi took off from
second on the grounder to short and was thrown out trying to take
third. The Dodgers didn't score again.
</P>
<P>
   Springer, who spent seven seasons in the Dodgers organization,
pitched out of trouble in the second when Mondesi was cut down at
the plate on a two-out grounder to short by Karros.
</P>
<P>
   Mondesi collided with Fabregas at the plate and the two
exchanged words.
</P>
<P>
   Beltre, who batted .417 (10 for 24) on the trip, opened the
third with his second home run of the season, a drive that just
cleared the fence in right-center. It was his second of the year
and raised his average against right-handers to .409 (26 for 66).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
