<HEADER>
A9235 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-CHINA-REACT-3R     05-08 0630
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-CHINA-REACT-3RDLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHINA ASSAILS `GROSS VIOLATION OF SOVEREIGNTY'  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (SUBS for writethru: subs lede and grafs 2-6 to update with Chinese
government statement broadcast on Chinese television; grafs 10-11
to add info from military officer; grafs 12-14 to add info from
professor; adds last 2 grafs to provide background on China's
stance in NATO-Yugoslav conflict; outdated infor deleted
throughout.)  By ERIK ECKHOLM   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIJING _ The Chinese government called the attack on its
embassy in Belgrade a ``gross violation of Chinese sovereignty'' in
a statement read on television news Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   The report, on the main national news program at noon Saturday,
was the first notice to the public here of the embassy bombing,
which seems certain to evoke public outrage and to damage
Chinese-American relations.
</P>
<P>
   Foreign policy experts and officials said the attack would
create intense pressures on the government to oppose forcefully the
U.S.-led air attacks in Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   The news program on China Central Television included images of
the burning embassy and rescue operations, with commentary by
telephone from a reporter on the scene who said the embassy had
been directly struck by two missiles and had been damaged by a
third that exploded close by.
</P>
<P>
   The program said that two Chinese had been killed in the attack,
including a journalist from the New China News Agency, Shao
Yunhuan. It said 20 had been injured and two others were still
missing .
</P>
<P>
   The Beijing announcer read an unusually harsh government
statement that condemned ``U.S.-led NATO'' for violating Chinese
sovereignty.
</P>
<P>
   As news of the bombing and casualties becomes more widely known
here, it is certain to inflame the already passionate sense that
NATO's bombing raids in Yugoslavia constitute illegal aggression _
a view deeply held by much of the public as well as by officials.
</P>
<P>
   ``The government has already been under increasing pressure to
take stronger action against the NATO bombing,'' said a military
officer who spoke on the condition of anonymity, and did not know
about the embassy incident until he was told.
</P>
<P>
   The officer said that even before the attack, there was a
consensus among senior military officers that China should more
strongly counter the NATO raids, which China views as an illegal
intervention in a sovereign country.
</P>
<P>
   On hearing of a Yugoslav news agency report that the embassy had
been hit by more than one bomb, the officer said this would
indicate that the attack on China's embassy might have been
deliberate.
</P>
<P>
   If current diplomatic initiatives fail to stop the campaign, it
is not clear what direct measures China can take to counter NATO.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview Saturday morning, Jia Qingguo, a professor of
international studies at Beijing University, said, ``This
strengthens the hand of those who have argued for closer
Chinese-Russian cooperation in aiding Serbia against NATO.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Those who have heard this news are very angry,'' Jia said.
``This is an act of aggression against China.''
</P>
<P>
   ``In the past, China opposed the bombing but Yugoslavia was far
away,'' Jia said. ``Now the war is brought closer to home.''
</P>
<P>
   From the start, China has virulently opposed the American-led
bombing of Yugoslavia. The state-run media attacked the NATO
operations as barbarism, part of a plot to extend NATO control over
eastern Europe. It has been consistently one-sided in its coverage
of the conflict and has virtually ignored evidence of Serb
brutality in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Until Saturday, the official Chinese reaction has been
rhetorical. China has appeared eager to preserve good ties with the
United States even as it violently objects to American policy over
Kosovo.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
