<SLUG> BC-BKN-VECSEY-COLUMN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KARL CALLINGS IN HELP FOR BUCKS PLAYOFF RUN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By LAURA VECSEY  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Now that George Karl has led the Bucks to the
playoffs, he's really getting serious.
</P>
<P>
   The former Sonics coach/leakmeister has signed Del Harris _ who
guided Milwaukee into the playoffs in '92, the last time they made
it _ to lend a hand with scouting. Karl also called Kevin Johnson
to see if the Suns' retired point guard might be available for the
postseason.
</P>
<P>
   Let's just assume that Karl's aggressive playoff preparations
have just a little to do with the ex-Sonics coach's desire to stay
alive in May while his former team is already on a long,
uncomfortable summer vacation.
</P>
<P>
   George may leak to Sonics fans, but Wally Walker is the one
``taking full responsibility and making no excuses.''
</P>
<P>
   For anyone familiar with Karl, what's the over-under on Karl
shortening his rotation to eight players against the heavily
favored Pacers and benching Ervin Johnson?
</P>
<P>
   A JET ALL THE WAY: It is sad news about Leon Hess. The oil
tycoon and owner of the Jets died Friday at the age of 85. That
means after suffering through Bruce Coslet and Rich Kotite, Hess
did not live to see his team in another Super Bowl, though Lord
knows Bill Parcells busted his Tuna gills to make it happen.
</P>
<P>
   THREE-TO-ONE: Odds that Seahawks owner Paul Allen gets a Super
Bowl ring in his lifetime.
</P>
<P>
   SUZUKI VS. IRABU: Sushi series in New York, just like the old
times.
</P>
<P>
   TRADE (DE)BAIT: Why all the ruckus about the Mariners needing to
make a blockbuster trade right now for a starter? Has anyone looked
at the AL West standings? Do you really want to give up David Segui
or Russ Davis _ or, heaven forbid, A-Rod this far before his
contract is up _ if 79 wins could swipe this under-.500 division?
Let the not-so-mighty M's muck it out.
</P>
<P>
   DROP AND GIVE US 25: Summer diet suggestions for Vin Baker, who
loves to cook. Oatmeal, not omelets, for breakfast. Rice cakes,
carrot sticks, orange roughy, cod or broiled scrod _ if you're back
in New England. No sour cream on the baked potato, no alfredo sauce
on the pasta or scampi butter on the shrimp. Water instead of fruit
juice (high carbs and calories). Lots of green, leafy vegetables
and for a rare treat, may we suggest Ben &AMP; Jerry's Cherry Garcia
low-fat frozen yogurt.
</P>
<P>
   A SIGN THAT THE APOCALYPSE IS UPON US?: The NHL has filed a
claim in federal bankruptcy court to dismantle the cash-strapped
Penguins, which could spell the end for the 1991 and '92 Stanley
Cup champs.
</P>
<P>
   Baseball is not far behind. In Kansas City, the in-limbo Royals
could be next. Or Montreal, where the Expos just finished a 2-8
homestand and the average attendance (11,489) is the lowest in
baseball, which begs the question:
</P>
<P>
   Why can't baseball adopt the socialist revenue-sharing policies
of the very healthy National Football League, which is now helping
Massachusetts pay to build a stadium to keep the Patriots?
</P>
<P>
   PAYTON'S PLACE: One thing came out of the Sonics' finale in
L.A., and that was Detlef Schrempf's level of discontent. What do
you think drove the disenchanted Schrempf to publicly question
whether the Sonics had the right ``attitude, commitment, work
ethic'' to entice him back?
</P>
<P>
   After trying for years to squelch feelings that the Sonics'
premier point guard can do as much damage to the team as good,
Schrempf's frustration with Gary Payton became obvious this bust of
a season. If Schrempf signs with another team, it will be because
he, like other Sonics, feels Payton is out of control. Payton truly
holds the keys to this franchise and needs to take care.
</P>
<P>
   THE QUESTION: What disparaging comments will Charles Barkley
have for Allen Iverson now that the Sixers star has earned his
first scoring title _ and gotten Sir Charles' old, old team into
the playoffs? For a guy who spits on fans and pushes fellow bar
patrons through windows, maybe Barkley should lay off the Philly
kid.
</P>
<P>
   DEATH WISH: Scottish soccer referee Hugh Davis needed four
stitches in his head after he was struck by a coin during last
Sunday's match between Celtic and Rangers, presumably by Celtic
fans angry over calls during their team's 3-0 loss. Davis' reward?
He gets to referee the rematch when the same teams meet in the
Scottish Cup final May 29.
</P>
<P>
   And baseball umpires think they have it bad?
</P>
<P>
   NBA UPSET SPECIALS: Or first-round playoff results we could root
for but that aren't likely. Suns shoot down Blazers. C. Webb and
White Chocolate out-run and out-gun Stockton and Malone.
</P>
<P>
   Bucks topple Pacers. Sixers (Iverson) and Magic (Penny Hardaway)
play triple-overtime in Game 5.
</P>
<P>
   JERRY SPRINGER SERIES: Knicks def. Heat by TKO.
</P>
<P>
   NOTE TO NBC: Lakers-Rockets isn't the only series we want to
see.
</P>
<P>
   BASEBALL DIPLOMACY: After seeing how poorly the Orioles play the
game, of course the Cuban baseball players decided they would
rather go home.
</P>
<P>
   Laura Vecsey is a P-I columnist.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-08-99 0253EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
