<SLUG> BC-BBA-MARINERS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MISMATCH IN BRONX AS YANKS BEAT UP ON MARINER ROOKIES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By TYLER KEPNER  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ If it seems confidence must be low among Mariner
relievers after another stinging loss Friday night, consider the
confidence of their instructor.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think they have to start talking to me to keep my confidence
up, because it's getting a little tiresome seeing that many runs
every night,'' said pitching coach Stan Williams, after Seattle's
10-1 loss to the New York Yankees. ``We're sitting on a 6.50 ERA as
a team. That's incredible. I keep waiting for this thing to get
better, we're trying, we're really working on things, but we
haven't been getting what we're going to have to get, period.''
</P>
<P>
   All four pitchers who worked for the Mariners Friday are
rookies. Another, Freddy Garcia, starts Saturday, and a sixth,
Brett Hinchliffe, could start Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   There were strong indications Friday that Hinchliffe could join
the team Saturday, and Sunday's starter, John Halama, was forced
into mop-up duty Friday night. Halama said he didn't know if his
arm could bounce back for a start Sunday because he has so little
experience as a reliever.
</P>
<P>
   Starter Mac Suzuki shut out the Yankees for four innings Friday,
but unraveled in the fifth, allowing a three-run homer to Derek
Jeter. Suzuki and Eric Weaver allowed four runs in the sixth, and
two runs scored off Sean Spencer in the seventh.
</P>
<P>
   Weaver and Spencer have 14 major league games between them, and
combined with Ken Cloude to allow four runs in a loss to Cleveland
on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Believe me, if we can get some experienced (relief) pitching
in here, we're going to have to, if we can,'' said manager Lou
Piniella. ``(The media) and the fans are going to lose their
patience before I do, I can tell you that.''
</P>
<P>
   Suzuki appeared in control with two outs and a runner on first
in the fifth. But he hit Chad Curtis, who was batting .163, to
bring up Jeter, the American League's leading hitter. Suzuki had
his mind on the hit-by-pitch when he hung a split-finger that Jeter
crushed over the center field wall.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess I was disappointed before, when I hit Curtis,'' Suzuki
said. ``That (pitch) was hanging, but still, I was thinking about
Curtis.''
</P>
<P>
   Suzuki left trailing 4-0 with one out and the bases loaded.
Weaver induced a soft chopper by Luis Sojo, picked it up, whirled
and threw off-balance to home for the force. The throw bounced wide
of the plate, and by the time catcher Dan Wilson recovered it and
lunged back toward home, two Yankees had scored.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm ready for it to start turning my way,'' said Weaver, who
lost Thursday's game. ``It's a tough situation I'm in, but that's
what I want, and obviously that's the way they're using me. I'll
take a line drive right at somebody right now, just for something
positive.''
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees' biggest positive Friday was the pitching of Hideki
Irabu (1-0), who held the M's to a Russ Davis solo homer and three
other hits over seven innings as New York improved to 11-1 at home.
</P>
<P>
   The matchup of Irabu and Suzuki was the first in major league
history of two Japanese starters. But it was more coincidence than
a sign of any increasing influence of Japanese pitchers on the
majors. The trailblazer, 1995 National League Rookie of the Year
Hideo Nomo, recently signed with his third team this season, and
neither Irabu nor Suzuki had a decision before Friday night.
</P>
<P>
   The game did not attract the widespread Japanese media attention
some had predicted. Although the game was televised in Japan, only
about 15 Japanese media members attended, which the Yankees said
was no greater than the turnout for an average Irabu start.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not such a big deal,'' Shoko Mizutsugi, of Japan's
Baseball Magazine, said of Friday's game. ``People are used to
Japanese pitchers in the major leagues. A lot of people were crazy
about Nomo a few years ago, but now a lot of Japanese are settled
down about watching pitchers pitch for major league teams. ... This
season, (Masato) Yoshii of the Mets is the only Japanese starter
pitching well. So this (matchup) is a rare case this season.''
</P>
<P>
   Suzuki, who was making just his seventh career start, is largely
a curiosity in Japan. Not much is known about him, Mizutsugi said,
because he signed with the Mariners at age 18 and never played
professionally in Japan.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody knows him, but he is not as popular (as others),''
Mizutsugi said. ``He hasn't proved himself yet in baseball, so
people don't know how good he is.''
</P>
<P>
   Piniella said he will keep Suzuki in the rotation, though he was
hoping his pitcher would last longer than 107 pitches Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a big, strong kid,'' Piniella said. ``He should be able
to give us seven innings. This is his second start. There's no
reason why after a couple of starts, he can't throw 115-120 pitches
a game.''
</P>
<P>
   Only once in the past 10 games has a Mariner starter worked
seven innings, and that was in a loss. Only three times this year
has a Mariners starter worked seven innings in a game the M's won.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-08-99 0257EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
