u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-CHINA-U.N.-1ST     05-08 0377
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-CHINA-U.N.-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.N. SECURITY COUNCIL MEETS AS CHINA VOICES ANGER 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (SUBS last 3 grafs to add background on China's stance in
NATO-Yugoslav conflict and to add comment by Chinese ambassador in
Belgrade.) (js) 
 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS _ The U.N. Security Council met in an emergency
session early Saturday morning to consider the NATO bombing of the
Chinese Embassy in Belgrade.
</P>
<P>
   The Chinese mission led by Qin Huasun issued a statement
condemning the bombing. ``NATO's barbarian act is a gross violation
of the U.N. Charter, international law and norms covering
international relations,'' the statement said. ``It is also a
violation of the Geneva Convention. NATO should be responsible for
all the consequences. We call on NATO to stop immediately its
military actions.''
</P>
<P>
   The Russian representative, Sergei V. Lavrov, said early on
Saturday: ``I don't think it's a proper time for comment on the
diplomatic process. It means a lot for the Chinese Embassy.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   As delegates filed into the Security Council chamber near
midnight, Peter Burleigh, the acting U.S. representative at the
United Nations, struck a tone that was both cautious and resolute.
``In case it was a NATO bomb, it is obviously something we deeply
regret, and we apologize for it. We never target civilians and we
would never target an embassy,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Burleigh added: ``I also feel, and will say to the council, that
it's very important, despite this, to keep our eye on the big
picture, and the big picture is that Slobodan Milosevic is
responsible for what's going on in Yugoslavia now.''
</P>
<P>
   China, a permanent member of the Security Council, with veto
rights, has strongly opposed the NATO bombing, saying the entire
operation violated the ``territorial integrity'' of a sovereign
country.
</P>
<P>
   Beijing has represented Yugoslav interests in the United States
since Belgrade broke diplomatic ties with Washington after the air
strikes began March 24.
</P>
<P>
   In Belgrade, the Chinese ambassador, Pan Zhanlien, standing
before the shattered embassy in the capital's New Belgrade
district, said, ``the People's Republic has been attacked.'' Fire
trucks converged on the building, which was engulfed in smoke.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
