<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-08 03:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9242 &Cx1f; taf-z
u v &Cx13;  &Cx11;  PM-BUDGET-NYT     05-08 1633
</HEADER>
<BODY>
 PM-BUDGET-NYT 
 (js) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; For SATURDAY PMs &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are the top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for PMs of Saturday, May 8.
</P>
<P>
   The PMs news desk, 212-556-1927, opens at 7 a.m. Eastern Time.
To get story repeats before this hour call 212-621-1595 for reruns
on AP DataFeatures or 214-980-8305 or 8367 for repeats on UPI
DataNews.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL _ (Moved in ``i'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-MILITARY (Washington) _ NATO forces that were pounding
the center of Belgrade struck and badly damaged the Chinese embassy
Friday night, only hours after knocking out electrical power across
much of the country. Yugoslav authorities immediately reported
numerous injuries, both inside and outside the embassy, which they
said held 26 people at the time. China said two of its citizens
were killed and two more were missing. By Steven Lee Meyers. With
photos and graphic.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-CHINA-REACT (Beijing) _ The Chinese government called the
attack on its embassy in Belgrade a ``gross violation of Chinese
sovereignty'' in a statement read on television news Saturday. The
report, on the main national news program at noon Saturday, was the
first notice to the public here of the embassy bombing, which seems
certain to evoke public outrage and to damage Chinese-American
relations. By Eric Eckholm.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-CHINA-U.N. (United Nations) _ The U.N. Security Council
met in an emergency session early Saturday morning to consider the
NATO bombing of the Chinese Embassy in Belgrade. The Chinese
mission issued a statement condemning the bombing. ``NATO's
barbarian act is a gross violation of the U.N. Charter,
international law and norms covering international relations,'' the
statement said.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-DIPLO (Washington) _ President Clinton Friday described
the peacekeeping operation in Bosnia, which includes American
soldiers working under the direction of NATO and with U.N.
approval, as a model for the military force that is envisioned to
return and protect ethnic Albanian refugees to Kosovo. By Jane
Perlez.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-REFUGEES (Tirana, Albania) _ After nearly 25,000 Kosovo
refugees flooded into Macedonia earlier this week, the border fell
eerily silent Friday and refugee officials said they feared that
Yugoslav forces were expelling ethnic Albanians from their homes
but barring them from fleeing. By David Rohde. With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   POPE-ROMANIA (Bucharest, Romania) _ Fulfilling a dream long
denied, John Paul II arrived in Romania Friday for the first visit
of a pope to a predominantly Orthodox country. By Alessandra
Stanley.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-NUKE (Washington) _ Wen Ho Lee, the scientist accused of
passing nuclear secrets to China, issued a statement through his
lawyer defending himself. By James Risen.
</P>
<P>
   SCOTLAND-ELECT (Edinburgh) _ In voting for the first Scottish
Parliament in 300 years, Labor finished first with 39 percent, the
Nationalists second with 29 percent. Labor is expected to form a
coalition with the Liberal Democrats. By Warren Hoge.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-TV (Hong Kong) _ In a move that may reflect China's
jitters during a year of politically charged milestones, the
Chinese government has begun to clamp down on illegal reception of
foreign television channels. By Mark Landler.
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL-FLYING-VOTERS (New York) _ In a transcontinental
incarnation of one of America's most time-honored political
practices _ getting out the vote _ supporters of the two major
candidates for prime minister are arranging for thousands of
Israelis living in the United States to fly home at cut-rate fares
for the upcoming national elections. By Adam Nagourney. With photo.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL _ GENERAL (Moved in ``a'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   JENNY-JONES-SUIT (Pontiac, Mich.) _ n a case that has focused
attention on confrontational talk shows, a jury here on Friday
ordered ``The Jenny Jones Show'' to pay $25 million to the family
of a gay man who was shot to death after revealing that he was
sexually attracted to another man on the show.
</P>
<P>
   By Keith Bradsher.
</P>
<P>
   STARR-STEELE (Alexandria, Va.) _ After jury members twice
described themselves as ``hopelessly deadlocked,'' a federal judge
declared a mistrial Friday in the obstruction of justice trial of
Julie Hiatt Steele, the Richmond, Va., woman who played a
peripheral role in Kenneth Starr's investigation of President
Clinton. By Don Van Natta Jr.
</P>
<P>
   BUSH-FINANCES (Austin, Texas) _ With George W. Bush emerging as
an early front-runner for the Republican nomination in 2000, his
business dealings illuminate an essential question of his
biography: whether his success is primarily inherited or achieved.
It is a question that has dogged Bush, as a son of former President
George Bush, throughout his business career, as throughout his
political life. By Kevin Sack. With photos.
</P>
<P>
   NJ-KOSOVO-REFUGEES (Fort Dix, N.J.) _ An additional 407 ethnic
Albanians, among the hundreds of thousands pushed out of their
homes in Kosovo by Yugoslav forces, arrived at this training camp
turned immigration center Friday. By Diana Jean Schemo. With photo.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON _ (Moved in ``w'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   LOTT-FUNDRAISING (Washington) _ WASHINGTON _ An academic center
being built at the University of Mississippi and named for Senate
Majority Leader Trent Lott is being endowed with million-dollar
donations from companies with huge stakes in pending congressional
legislation. By Frank Bruni. With photo.
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-CONTEMPT (Washington) _ Lawyers for Paula Jones told a
federal judge in Arkansas Friday that President Clinton owed them
more than $496,000 as a result of extra work they say they were
forced to perform because of his dishonest testimony in her sexual
misconduct case. By Neil A. Lewis.
</P>
<P>
   TIPPER-DEPRESSION (Washington) _ Tipper Gore, the wife of the
vice president, disclosed in a newspaper article published Friday
that she was treated for depression after their 6-year-old son was
severely injured in an automobile accident in 1989.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BUSINESS DAY _ (Moved in ``f'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ECON-REPORT (Undated) _ The economy resumed its torrid pace of
job creation last month after an interruption in March, generating
234,000 jobs without putting pressure on companies to raise
employees' wages. The jobless rate crept up to 4.3 percent in April
from 4.2 percent in March. While the gain in new jobs was somewhat
larger than forecasts, hourly wages rose less than expected, easing
concern that interest rates are headed higher. By Sylvia Nasar.
With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   BARCLAYS-INVEST (London) _ The market has delivered a clear
message about Barclays PLC: This is a great bank, but it needs a
lot of outside help. By Alan Cowell. With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   COLUMBIA-FLOWERS (Guaymaral, Colombia) _ The Acuarela flower
farm here grows nothing but roses of every hue, and on a recent
morning workers were rushing to fill the last Mother's Day orders
from American clients. Exploiting advances in transportation and
refrigeration and its proximity to the world's largest consumer
market, Colombia has surpassed California as the principal supplier
of roses, carnations, chrysanthemums and other popular blooms to
the United States. By Larry Rohter.
</P>
<P>
   BRITAIN-GOLD (London) _ Britain surprised world financial
markets Friday by announcing that it would sell more than half the
country's bullion reserves, a move that further eroded the value of
what was once the safest and strongest measure of wealth. By Alan
Cowell.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COMMENTARY (Moved in ``k'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; LEWIS-COLUMN (Boston) _ At the end of this terrible century,
why was another murderous tyrant in Europe able to carry out mass
killings and expulsions? Weakness of leadership is the reason. By
Anthony Lewis.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ENTERTAINMENT (Moved in ``e'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   TRAUMA-STUDIES (Undated) _ From the punishing cycle of violence
in the Balkans to the string of teenage killing sprees at high
schools, trauma has become nearly as commonplace as the weather on
the evening news. It has rippled through boardrooms and bedrooms,
emergency rooms and courtrooms across the United States. Nearly
everywhere, it seems, except the university classroom. Many
specialists say that American universities have been slow to
respond to the recent flood of advances in the study and treatment
of trauma. By Patricia Cohen.
</P>
<P>
   INDEPENDENT-SCHOLARS (Undated) _ A look at the advantages, and
disadvantages, of making ones way as a scholar outside the
protection of the academy. By Janny Scott. With photo.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-IVAN (Undated) _ ``Domostroi,'' a 16th-century guide to
living written by the spiritual mentor of Ivan the Terrible, is
enjoying a resurgence in Russia. By John Varoli.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SPORTS (Moved in ``s'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   FBN-ANDERSON-COLUMN (Undated) _ Sports of The Times column on
Leon Hess, the long-time owner of the New York Jets who died on
Friday morning at the age of 85. By Dave Anderson.
</P>
<P>
   FBN-OBIT-HESS-REACT (Undated) _ Reaction to the death of Leon
Hess, from the Jets and from people in and around the NFL. By Bill
Pennington.
</P>
<P>
   TEN-ITALY (Rome) _ In the Italian Open, Martina Hingis extracts
revenge on Serena Williams, beating her in straight sets. Next for
Hingis: probably Venus Williams, in the semifinals.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; OBITUARIES (Moved in ``a'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   OBIT-HESS (New York) _ Leon Hess, who took over his family's
bankrupt fuel-oil business during the Depression and built it into
one of the world's largest petroleum companies, but was perhaps
best known as the steadfast owner of the long-floundering New York
Jets football team, died Friday in New York. He was 85. By Gerald
Eskenazi. With photos.
</P>
