<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-08 11:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9272 &Cx1f; taf-z
u v &Cx13;  &Cx11;  AM-NYT-BUDGET &LR;      05-08 1569
</HEADER>
<BODY>
 AM-NYT-BUDGET  
(nk) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; FOR SUNDAY AMs &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are today's top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for AMs of Sunday, May 9:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Questions or reruns: (888) 346-9867. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   The day supervisor is Ned Kilkelly.
</P>
<P>
   The late supervisor is Lynn Hoogenboom.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Technical problems: &LR;  Peter Trigg.
</P>
<P>
   Phone: (212) 499-3332.
</P>
<P>
   Pager: (800) 946-4645 (PIN 599-4539).
</P>
<P>
   E-mail: triggp(at)nytimes.com.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; KOSOVO  &LR; (Coded i)
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-CHINA (Beijing) _ Massive angry and sometimes violent
protests erupted on the streets surrounding the American Embassy
here, as Chinese learned on the noon news Saturday that NATO bombs
had hit their Embassy in Belgrade. By Elisabeth Rosenthal.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-CHINA-EMBASSY (Belgrade) _ Chinese embassy personnel were
packing up, loading up their cars and dragging suitcases across the
forecourt of their bombed out embassy, still dazed and shaken after
Saturday night's missile attack. By Carlotta Gall.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-U.N.-CHINA (United Nations) _ China convened a rare
overnight session of the Security Council early Saturday and
condemned the the NATO bombing of its embassy in Belgrade as a
``flagrant attack'' that constituted a ``crime of war and should be
punished.'' By Jacques Steinberg.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-SERBIA (Velika Dobranja, Yugoslavia) _ The Llugiqi
family, like the rest of this ethnic Albanian village of about
2,500 people, has not left their homes. Nor has anyone here been
asked or ordered to go. ``You hear different stories, and what is
true you never know,'' said Mehmet Llugiqi, 36. ``No one has
bothered us here. But we don't know what will happen tomorrow. If
someone comes and says to leave, I guess we would have to do it.''
By Steven Erlanger.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-EUROPE (Brussels) _ NATO's 45-day-old bombing campaign
against Yugoslavia has made America's European allies painfully
aware of a growing gap between their own defense capabilities and
the vastly more mobile, numerous and powerful forces the United
States has brought here. By Craig R. Whitney.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-MONTENEGRO (Cetinje, Montenegro) _ It was a beguiling
promise, ``To Live Better,'' that helped Montenegro's governing
coalition win power last year. But few people in this ancient city
would say their lives are better now than before. By Anthony
DePalma.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; OTHER INTERNATIONAL  &LR; (Coded i)
</P>
<P>
   LEMBA-JEWISH-GENES (Undated) _ The Lemba, a Bantu-speaking
people of southern Africa, practive Judaic rites and claim that
they were led out of Judea by a man named Buba. Although there is
no Buba in the records of Jewish history, the remarkable thing
about the Lemba tradition is that it may be exactly right. A team
of geneticists has found that many Lemba men carry in their male
chromosome a set of DNA sequences that is distinctive of the
cohanim, the Jewish priests believed to be the descendants of
Aaron. By Nicholas Wade.
</P>
<P>
   POPE-ROMANIA (Bucharest, Romania) _ Pooling their moral
authority, John Paul II and Patriarch Teoctist of Romania on
Saturday jointly requested an immediate end to the fighting in
Kosovo. It was the first communal appeal for peace between leaders
of the long estranged Roman Catholic and Orthodox churches since
the war began. By Alessandra Stanley.
</P>
<P>
   INDIA-NUCLEAR-BAN (New Delhi) _ A year after India and Pakistan
sent tremors of anxiety around the world by conducting nuclear
tests, the once-strong likelihood that India would soon sign the
nuclear test ban treaty faded this week to a very faint
possibility. By Celia Dugger.
</P>
<P>
   COLOMBIA-DRUGS (Bolivia) _ Senior U.S. officials say they are
beginning to believe President Hugo Banzer might fulfill his pledge
to eradicate all of Bolivia's illegal coca crop by the end of his
term in late 2002. ``Bolivia is making history,'' said Donna
Hrinak, the American Ambassador in La Paz. By Clifford Krauss.
</P>
<P>
   SYRIA-ASSAD (Damascus) _ With the Clinton administration having
vowed to try again in the months ahead to promote peace between
Syria and Israel, President Assad's fixation on succession has left
some diplomats here concerned. They say they worry that he might be
less willing to make concessions out of concern that any domestic
criticism would rebound against his son. By Douglas Jehl.
</P>
<P>
   AFRICA-REFUGEES (Kaputa, Zambia) _ International aid officials
say all refugees are treated equally, but there is no doubt that
the world's attention is on the hundreds of thousands of people
displaced in the Balkans, and refugees and aid workers in Africa
worry that attention to the plight of refugees here may fade even
further. By Ian Fisher.
</P>
<P>
   INDONESIA-U.S.-POLICE (Washington) _ The Clinton administration
has decided to offer riot-control training to the Indonesian police
in preparation for next month's national elections despite concerns
from human rights groups over the abysmal human rights record of
the police there, administration officials say. By Philip Shenon.
</P>
<P>
   BRITAIN-POLITICS-ASSESS (London) _ With elections now completed
for new legislatures in Northern Ireland, Scotland and Wales, Prime
Minister Tony Blair has won the battle for a Britain with its
politics radically reconfigured to his own design. But he has also
given power and legitimacy to forces in the three parts of the
United Kingdom of Great Britain and Northern Ireland that are
restive over their continuing relationship with the fourth,
England, and dream of full independence from London. By Warren
Hoge.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON &LR;  (Coded w)
</P>
<P>
   UNINSURED-CHILDREN (Washington) _ States are using less than 20
percent of the money that Congress made available, with much
fanfare, for a big new program to subsidize health insurance for
children in low-income families. Some states say they can't find
enough eligible uninsured kids to use their full allotments of
federal money. The accumulation of unspent cash is tempting
Republicans in Congress to take some back and use it for other
purposes. By Robert Pear.
</P>
<P>
   UTAH-JUDGE (Washington) _ Ted Stewart, chief of staff to Utah's
Republican governor, would not seem a likely candidate for
President Clinton to nominate as a federal judge. Stewart, a GOP
political operative, is widely disliked by environmental groups.
But Clinton is about to name Stewart, who is being pushed by Sen.
Orrin Hatch, R-Utah, chairman of the Senate Judiciary Committee who
has blocked all other nominees until he gets his man. That could
mean trouble for Al Gore, who has been asked to block the
nomination by environmental groups. By Neil Lewis.
</P>
<P>
   DEA-MUSEUM (Washington) _ The Drug Enforcement Administration
opens a museum in Washington. By Christopher Wren.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL  &LR; (Coded a)
</P>
<P>
   OKLA-STORMS-CLINTON (Oklahoma City) _ As he prepared to tour
communities devastated by Monday's tornadoes, President Clinton
announced in his weekly radio address Saturday that he had
instructed the Labor Department to hire thousands of Oklahomans who
lost their jobs in businesses destroyed by the storms and that he
would ask Congress for more money for disaster relief. By David E.
Rosenbaum.
</P>
<P>
   ASSISTED-LIVING (Framingham, Mass.) _ A look at one of the most
dramatic changes in the way the old live, the assisted living
movement. Ten years ago, assisted living facilities, which provide
private apartments plus daily assistance, were barely known. There
was no step between independence and helplessness. Today, some 1.2
million people live in assisted living facilities, and towns across
the country are asking developers to build more so that their aging
residents can stay close to home. By Sarah Rimer.
</P>
<P>
   MEDIA-YOUTH-VIOLENCE (Undated) _ As the White House prepares to
talk to education and entertainment industry officials about the
possible connections between entertainment and youth violence,
experts are wondering what the fuss is all about. For years, they
say, studies have shown that there is a connection. By Lawrie
Mifflin.
</P>
<P>
   SUICIDE-BRIDGE (Tampa, Fla.) _ At the crest of the massive
Sunshine Skyway Bridge, a dizzying 200 feet above the jade-colored
water of Tampa Bay, state Patrolmen Gary Schluter and James Covert
periodically have to persuade people poised on the edge of their
own destruction to step slowly back, and live. By Rick Bragg.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COLUMNS &LR;  (Coded k)
</P>
<P>
   HERBERT-COLUMN (Undated) _ Commentary by Bob Herbert: Al Gore is
hardly a sure thing. But he's a sitting vice president in
exceptionally good economic times. Whatever the early polls are
saying, the presidency is his to lose.
</P>
<P>
   DOWD-COLUMN (Washington) _ Commentary by Maureen Dowd: When I
went out to buy a gun one night, I had no idea it would be easier
and less expensive than buying a pink cashmere sweater set.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Moving later: &LR;
</P>
<P>
   AM-FRONTPAGE-NYT -- A description of the front page layout of
the first edition of The New York Times; will move at approximately
1 p.m. ET.
</P>
