<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HERBERT-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: LONG SHOTS AND SHADOWS 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By BOB HERBERT    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   I keep running into people who tell me that Al Gore can't or
won't win the presidency. These are ordinary voters, not
politicians or people in the media. Most are right in step with
Gore philosophically. But they are saying the same things everybody
seems to be saying about the vice president. He's a cardboard
figure. Doesn't connect with people. Gives lousy speeches. Al Bore.
</P>
<P>
   So I ask who they think will be the next president, and they say
Bush. I ask why and I get silence. I ask if they know Bush's full
name and most say George Bush Jr. I ask if they know what he's done
as governor of Texas and they haven't a clue. I ask if they know
what his position is on guns, or abortion, or the war in the
Balkans, and the reply is usually something like: ``Hey, I'm not
saying I'm for him or anything. I'm just saying Gore can't win and
Bush probably can.''
</P>
<P>
   A number have also said Bill Bradley is looking pretty good.
</P>
<P>
   Listen up. We know that anything can happen between now and
November of next year. The economy could fall into a sinkhole. We
could find out that George W. Bush, in his first crack at national
office, has campaign skills that a Ronald Reagan or a John Kennedy
would envy. Bill Bradley, somewhat vague to date, may turn his big
themes into specific policies so irresistible he steals the
Democratic nomination from Gore, demolishes whatever candidate the
Republicans run against him, and becomes our tallest president.
</P>
<P>
   Any of those things could happen. But don't bet a lot of money
on it. Bush, for example, has already stumbled a couple of times in
his early attempts to master the finer points of foreign policy. He
recently referred to the Greeks as Grecians and the Kosovars as
Kosovoians.
</P>
<P>
   Al Gore may be a little stiff in front of the cameras, but he's
smart, he's got tons of campaign cash and, most significantly, he's
got an incredibly strong economy going for him.
</P>
<P>
   The early polls? Return with us for a moment to that thrilling
year, 1987. Vice President George Bush was gearing up for his run
for the presidency. E.J. Dionne Jr., then a reporter for The New
York Times (he's now a columnist for The Washington Post), did a
story about a Times poll and interviews with Republican Party
leaders. He wrote:
</P>
<P>
   ``The poll and the party leaders suggested that Bush was seen by
many Americans, even Republicans who like him, as somewhat boring,
too loyal to President Reagan to be true to himself. He is
respected for honesty but not for strength. He is viewed as a man
who stirs feelings of trust but not passion.''
</P>
<P>
   That summer Bush trailed Michael Dukakis by some 18 points. That
fall, John Harwood of The St. Petersburg Times wrote: ``Bush's
much-discussed image problem had gotten around. Several
participants observed that Bush is `weak' or `doesn't have the
charisma' that Reagan had displayed.'''
</P>
<P>
   It's the price you pay for standing in the shadow of the
presidency. The price is even higher if the president is
particularly popular or possesses extraordinary political skills.
Emerging from the shadow can be tough.
</P>
<P>
   Al Gore is not a charismatic or entertaining figure, and he has
been hurt by Bill Clinton's reckless behavior.
</P>
<P>
   ``He seems tarnished somehow, I guess because he's been so loyal
to Clinton,'' a woman told me last week. ``It may not be fair, but
that's the way I feel.''
</P>
<P>
   That same woman added, however, ``I think he would be a good
president.''
</P>
<P>
   The voters who are ambivalent about Al Gore are concerned
largely with superficial matters, about whether he is stiff or
boring or comforting or entertaining. Working in the vice
president's favor is the fact that most of those voters already
believe he is capable of being a decent president, of leading the
country in an era of breathtaking economic and technological
change. And very few of those voters will be anxious to tinker with
the economic escalator the country has been riding the last few
years.
</P>
<P>
   Al Gore is hardly a sure thing. But he's a sitting vice
president in exceptionally good economic times. Whatever the early
polls are saying, the presidency is his to lose. Bill Bradley,
George W. Bush, Elizabeth Dole and all the rest are long shots by
comparison.  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
