<HEADER>
A9277 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-KNICKS-ALONZO-ART     05-08 1426
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-KNICKS-ALONZO-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IMPOSING, YET IN TOUCH WITH HIS CEREBRAL SIDE 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(jt) 
 By MIKE WISE    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Inside the visitors' locker room at Madison Square
Garden on Wednesday, some Miami Heat players were watching a
videotape of their horrendous loss to the Knicks on April 25.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the most striking image during the Knicks' improbable
20-point comeback victory was the imposing figure walking upcourt,
biceps bulging, face contorted in a scowl.
</P>
<P>
   Alonzo Mourning looked ornery, as if his 6-foot-10-inch,
265-pound frame would erupt at the slightest sound of a referee's
whistle. But it did not. Instead, he continued walking.
</P>
<P>
   ``That box over there, you know, people pass judgment on
players, athletes and people in general by what they see on TV,''
Mourning said, sitting in front of his cubicle and pointing at the
television. ``That's my job right there. That's what I do.''
</P>
<P>
   This season Mourning is doing his job better than he has done in
his seven years in the National Basketball Association. Once an
ejection-prone center, Mourning is a candidate for most valuable
player. He led the league in blocked shots (3.9), ranked fourth in
shooting percentage (.511), sixth in rebounding (11.0) and 14th in
scoring (20.1). And Miami is the No. 1-seeded team in the Eastern
Conference playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   The image of ``Zo Ready to Blow'' is unavoidable. Who can forget
his last-second altercation with Larry Johnson in the playoffs last
season that led to his suspension for Game 5, a Heat loss. This
season his technical fouls are down, his tolerance is up and no one
is crawling under his skin and planting fiendish ideas in his head.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a human being,'' Mourning said. ``People don't look at me
like that when they sit in front of the TV and watch me. So they
pass judgment on a person they don't even know. And they think I'm
some psycho, maniac, hard-to-get-along-with emotional guy. But
again, that's my job.''
</P>
<P>
   It remains to be seen whether he can maintain his equilibrium in
the crucible of Knicks-Heat III, a first-round, three-of-five
series that begins Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   This time, Mourning said, he will not blow. ``It was an
unfortunate situation and I regret that even happening,'' Mourning
said. ``Bottom line is, I made a bad decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``Emotion is something that is part of my game. But in some
cases, it has affected me in a negative way. That's part of going
through the maturity process. Every player goes through a
maturation period where they develop and improve.''
</P>
<P>
   Clearly, the aftermath of last year's fight changed his outlook.
</P>
<P>
   ``Competition is going to bring out the very best and the worst
in everybody over their careers,'' Heat Coach Pat Riley said. ``And
I think Zo has already had his worst times there. He's had a great,
great year. And I think a lot of it is born out of the fact that he
was very disappointed last year. He came back strong.''
</P>
<P>
   Mourning's wife, Tracy Wilson-Mourning, said: ``He thought about
the incident with Larry all summer, and how much it cost the team.
I think, more than anything, he made it a learning experience.''
</P>
<P>
   Tim Hardaway was approached by Mourning soon after the fight.
The two have been good friends and teammates the past three
seasons.
</P>
<P>
   ``He asked me if he was right,'' Hardaway said of exchanging
punches with Johnson. ``I said: `Yeah, you right. You did the right
thing.' I would have done the same thing, too. If the referee's not
going to take care of it, you got to take care of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Jack Ramsay, the Heat broadcaster and ESPN analyst, said: ``He's
no longer predictable. He would always drive to his right. Even if
all five defenders were there, he would say, `You're not going to
stop me.' He would try and bull his way in there.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now, the range of his offensive game _ the jump shot, driving
in either direction, the jump hook with either hand _ they all make
him better.''
</P>
<P>
   Mourning said: ``I've diversified, but the only statistical
difference is that my techs are lower. I'm staying in ball games.
It's extremely important for me to be on the court. That's my main
concern.''
</P>
<P>
   His agent, David Falk, said: ``It's not a kinder, gentler Alonzo
on the court. He's just more cerebral.''
</P>
<P>
   The transformation comes seven years after NBA scouts wondered
what position Mourning would play coming out of Georgetown: center
or power forward.
</P>
<P>
   ``When he interviewed with us, he asked us who the highest-paid
forward and center in the league were,'' Falk said. ``At the time,
I think Danny Ferry was the highest-paid forward at about $4
million a season and Patrick Ewing was making $11 million as the
highest-paid center. After that, I told him, `I never again want to
hear you say you're a power forward.'''
</P>
<P>
   Mourning signed a $100 million deal with the Heat in 1996, but
his playoff misadventures have given rise to criticism at home and
on the road, where he is a 6-10 villain.
</P>
<P>
   The intimidating presence who leads the league in death stares
is a private man who speaks in a raspy baritone, the kind you would
hear in a blues club at four in the morning.
</P>
<P>
   The scowling persona may not play well in visiting arenas _ he
is one of the most despised players by opposing fans _ but he has
another side: as the doting father of 2-year-old Alonzo 3d.
Mourning gave his wife a surprise birthday party last spring,
arranging for her close friends to fly into Miami. He also hates to
lose to her at Scrabble, and his generosity has few bounds.
</P>
<P>
   Last February he donated an estimated $70,000 worth of expensive
clothing and shoes to a 6-10 man who lost all his possessions in a
house fire. A friend of the man, Martin Williams, e-mailed Tim
Donovan, the Heat's director for sports media relations, asking for
Mourning's help.
</P>
<P>
   Donovan showed up at Mourning's house with three boxes and
stuffed them. Williams, a former college player at Hawaii Loa, had
played against Mourning in the two players' first collegiate game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know how hard it was for my parents to find clothes for me
growing up,'' Mourning said. ``Fortunately enough, he still had his
little girls and his family. I just cleaned out my closet and took
care of him.''
</P>
<P>
   During the lockout, Mourning let his teammate Mark Strickland
borrow his Mercedes-Benz convertible.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was waiting to sign his new deal and he needed something to
drive, so I took care of him,'' Mourning said. Laughing, he added,
``I told him before he brought it back to clean and service it.''
</P>
<P>
   For the last three years, Mourning, a foster child, has also
been host of a charity banquet, concert and celebrity game to
benefit the Children's Home Society and 100 Black Men of South
Florida.
</P>
<P>
   ``People sort of take his on-court demeanor and they transfer it
to his personal life,'' Riley said. ``It's easy to put a label on
him because he's a ferocious competitor. But he's an open, caring,
affable person.''
</P>
<P>
   Mourning often gives away several inches to his big-man
counterparts. Through will and the weight room, he has made himself
an elite center. Out of respect for Patrick Ewing, his good friend,
he will not compare their talents. But this season Mourning has
unofficially surpassed his former Georgetown mentor as one of the
game's dominant pivots.
</P>
<P>
   ``To so many players, practice to them is like a pause between
their cell-phone conversations,'' Marty Conlon, the Heat's reserve
forward, said. ``But Alonzo stays late working on his body, lifting
and shooting. It's refreshing to see.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes he takes the game so seriously and takes himself so
seriously. Well, I don't know if it's detrimental. But I think this
year he's a little more level-headed and grounded.''
</P>
<P>
   Mourning was thrown out of one game this season, on March 20 at
Indiana. The Heat lost that game and five of the next six. The
blow-up was another parable for what happens when the franchise
center does not have the mental discipline to stay on the court.
</P>
<P>
   It could be said that Mourning already learned his lesson by the
next game. Addressing his teammates in the locker room, he said,
``OK, guys, we got to keep our cool tonight.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody looked at him like, `Oh, you're telling us to keep
our cool?' '' Terry Porter, the veteran Heat guard, said.
``Everybody just busted up laughing. We were like: `We're fine. You
have to deal with that issue by yourself.'''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
