<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-08 11:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9278 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-ANDERSON-COLUMN-N     05-08 0859
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-ANDERSON-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: HESS EXPLORED THE JETS' RETURN TO NEW YORK 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By DAVE ANDERSON    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In early January, Leon Hess attended a National
Football League owners meeting in Commissioner Paul Tagliabue's
office. The subject: how the NFL should coexist with the Internet
in the 21st century. But when the owners broke for lunch, Hess put
on his overcoat.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sorry I can't stay,'' the Jets' owner told the
commissioner, ``but I've got a meeting with the mayor.''
</P>
<P>
   At that meeting, Mayor Rudolph Giuliani informed Hess of a
proposed West Side football stadium with a retractable dome. The
mayor hoped such a stadium would lure the Jets, after their Giants
Stadium lease expires in 2008, to a proposed complex that would
include a relocated Madison Square Garden and the Javits Convention
Center.
</P>
<P>
   Several days later, the mayor disclosed plans for the proposed
football stadium in his ``State of the City'' address.
</P>
<P>
   ``After the meeting with the mayor,'' Tagliabue was saying
Friday, ``Leon called to tell me this will take some serious
discussion, that the mayor and his staff had done a lot of work on
this. But here was a man almost 85 years old at the end of a
century who was looking ahead to the NFL being on the Internet and
to the possibility of a new football stadium in New York.''
</P>
<P>
   Leon Hess, who died Friday from complications of a blood
disease, always looked ahead, never back.
</P>
<P>
   ``Leon was not what he liked to call a `dweller,' '' Steve
Gutman, the Jets' president, recalled. ``He would tell me `Don't
dwell on mistakes. Just think about how to do things better the
next time. Don't be a dweller.' ''
</P>
<P>
   And if a West Side football stadium materializes, part of Hess'
legacy will be having initially explored the possibility of the
Jets' return to New York more than two decades after leaving Shea
Stadium following the 1983 season.
</P>
<P>
   Hess, according to league sources, has mandated that the Jets be
sold after his death, so a new owner would be even more involved in
a West Side football-only stadium that presumably would mean that
the Yankees will stay in the Bronx.
</P>
<P>
   And if the mayor's plan for that West Side stadium progresses,
it surely would enhance the franchise's price beyond the estimates
of $500 million. That new Jets' owner will need to prove deep, deep
pockets.
</P>
<P>
   Although Leon Hess' only son, John, has often attended Jets
games with his father, he has never indicated any interest in
operating the team.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1995 John Hess, who has never been part of the Jets'
hierarchy, has been the chairman of the Amerada Hess oil company
that his father built into worldwide stature from one $24
oil-delivery truck in the Depression years of the 1930s. According
to Forbes magazine, Leon Hess' worth is listed at $730 million.
</P>
<P>
   According to other NFL owners, Hess had been approached over the
years by several prospective buyers who coveted the Jets, but he
never acknowledged it publicly. He didn't want to endure any
disruptive speculation. Even with all the Jets' frustrating
seasons, he enjoyed being a clubowner too much to consider selling.
</P>
<P>
   He particularly enjoyed hiring Bill Parcells, whose nickname is
Tuna, as the Jets' major domo in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was born and brought up in Asbury Park, N.J.,'' Hess said
that day in a rare appearance at a news conference. ``Bill Parcells
is in love with Sea Girt, N.J. They're eight miles apart. Seventy
years ago, as kids in the Summertime, at low tide we used to have a
little shovel and we'd go and dig up clams and sell them.
</P>
<P>
   ``The big ones would go for clam chowder at the restaurants, the
little ones went to clam bars. We were lucky to make 50 or 75 cents
a day. Little did I think that 70 years later, eight miles away in
Sean Girt would be a Tuna. It's all the same ocean. Little did I
think the good Lord would favor me and I could marry that Tuna.''
</P>
<P>
   But when discussing the Jets, Leon Hess seldom laughed.
</P>
<P>
   In 1991 the Jets' game in Chicago coincided with that year's
Monday night opening of the Metropolitan Opera at Lincoln Center,
which Hess always attended with his wife Norma and several friends,
including Tagliabue and his wife Chan.
</P>
<P>
   While one of Hess' ears listened to Luciano Pavarotti, his other
ear was plugged to a portable radio describing the Jets game. After
the performance ended, Hess moved to a reception, but one ear was
still plugged to the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``There he was,'' Tagliabue recalled, ``sitting at a table in
his tuxedo with Pavarotti, Beverly Sills and several others
standing around listening to Leon give them a play-by-play of this
Monday night game that went into overtime.''
</P>
<P>
   That night the Jets lost, of course _ 19-13, in overtime.
</P>
<P>
   Then again, when Hess was the Jets' owner, they lost more often
than not, but he never dwelled on those losses. Rather, he kept
trying to make the Jets better. By hiring Bill Parcells, he finally
did.
</P>
<P>
   And even as Leon Hess approached his 85th birthday, he was
exploring the idea of a new stadium that, if it materializes, would
bring the Jets back to New York.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-08-99 1150EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
