 The Week in Review  
 (NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For international clients' use by
special arrangement only. Asian and European points: contact Karl
Horwitz in Paris for details and prices (Phone: 47 42 17 11; FAX:
47-42-80-44). Latin American points: contact Olivia Vasquez in Los
Angeles (Phone: 310-996-0075; FAX: 310-996-0089)  
 (bl)  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   No Joy in Baltimore &QL;
</P>
<P>
   If there is any stage on which Fidel Castro has always delighted
in mixing competition with politics, it is sports. And if there is
any sport that Cubans, including Castro, love, it is baseball.
</P>
<P>
   So Cuba's humiliation of a U.S. major league team last week _ a
12-6 romp over the Baltimore Orioles in a rain-swept Camden Yards _
felt doubly sweet for the visiting Cubans. On March 28, in Havana,
the Orioles had barely eked out a victory over the Cuban national
team in 11 innings, and this time they appeared to be no
competition at all for the Cubans. The Orioles pitched poorly,
fielded sloppily and hit badly, getting 6 hits to the Cubans' 18.
</P>
<P>
   In Cuba, according to third baseman Omar Linares, the victory
was occasion for ``a national party.''
</P>
<P>
   Mercifully for the Orioles, no third game was planned. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   One Less TV Home to Improve &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Here are a few of the things the mirror of television has shown
Americans about the American family: Dad is the master and always
wears a comforting cardigan (``Father Knows Best''); Dad is full of
right-wing bluster and hates his son-in-law (``All in the
Family''); Dad is a clueless shoe salesman with an oversexed wife
and daughter and he bickers constantly (``Married . . . With
Children'').
</P>
<P>
   The most enduring situation around which television comedies
have been built is the family unit, in one form or another. That's
what the families sitting in front of their tubes identified with
for decades.
</P>
<P>
   Until now, it seems. With the demise of the long-running ABC
series, ``Home Improvement,'' America is all but losing its last
network sitcom built around a thriving family unit. Shows now
either take place in the workplace or focus on the self-absorbed
lives of singles _ searching, it often happens, for the family life
they grew up watching on television, but find out of reach.
</P>
<P>
   _ By JAMES STERNGOLD
</P>
<P>
   A Deadline Passes With No Palestinian State
</P>
<P>
   In the West Bank and Gaza, May 4, which was to have been a
triumphal date, came and went without a declaration of Palestinian
statehood. It also came and went without much notice, aside from a
handful of small protests.
</P>
<P>
   In Israel, however, Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu, who is
running behind in the polls as the May 17 elections approach, tried
to turn the day into a moment: his moment.
</P>
<P>
   He proclaimed a victory for standing so tough that Yasser
Arafat, the Palestinian leader, had been forced to defer a
statehood declaration for fear of Israel's retaliation.
</P>
<P>
   Arafat, however, faced nearly universal pressure, including from
Arab states, to recommit himself to the peace effort.
</P>
<P>
   While May 4 was the day the interim period set up by the Oslo
peace accord expired, both Israel and the Palestinians have agreed
to extend the agreement.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Arafat awaits the outcome of the Israeli elections to see
who will be his new partner _ or adversary _ at the negotiating
table.
</P>
<P>
   _ By DEBORAH SONTAG
</P>
<P>
   Beware the Scarf in Parliament  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   At its first meeting, Turkey's newly elected Parliament turned
not to pressing problems like inflation, human rights or
educational reform, but to the question of the Muslim head scarf.
The chamber erupted in pandemonium as Merve Kavakci, an
American-educated deputy from Istanbul, sought unsuccessfully to
take her oath of office while wearing a scarf.
</P>
<P>
   She was harshly denounced by the president, the prime minister
and many others, and the press began a campaign portraying her as a
militant fundamentalist bent on subverting the secular Republic.
</P>
<P>
   The debate reflected conflict between Turkey's desire for fuller
democracy and its fear of religious influence in politics.
</P>
<P>
   _ By STEPHEN KINZER
</P>
<P>
   Another Record For the Dow. (Ho Hum).
</P>
<P>
   Another month, another milestone. The Dow Jones industrial
average topped 11,000 on Monday, just 24 trading days after
barreling past 10,000.
</P>
<P>
   But the old bull market had a new look.
</P>
<P>
   While a small group of glamour stocks _ including Merck, General
Electric and Wal-Mart _ had fueled the market's rally for months,
April's push came from industrial companies like Goodyear Tire &AMP;
Rubber and Allied-Signal that investors had left for dead.
</P>
<P>
   While the dogs of the Dow had their day, the former favorites
fell, and investors wondered if the market's dominance by
high-flying growth stocks was drawing to an end.
</P>
<P>
   _ By GRETCHEN MORGENSON
</P>
<P>
   Over Iraq, Another Air War Continues
</P>
<P>
   Even as the Pentagon stepped up its air campaigns in the
Balkans, another U.S. military campaign continued apace against
Iraq, with almost daily skirmishes reported over the last two
weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Pentagon planners say that President Saddam Hussein appears to
believe that the United States is distracted by the Kosovo crisis,
and is trying to capitalize on it by making trouble for U.S. pilots
flying patrols over northern and southern Iraq.
</P>
<P>
   His provocations have come at a cost: the destruction of Iraqi
air-defense sites and reports of the deaths of dozens of Iraqi
civilians.
</P>
<P>
   _ By PHILIP SHENON
</P>
<P>
   Motion for a Nomination, But No Progress  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The long story of Richard Holbrooke's long-stalled nomination as
the top U.S. diplomat to the United Nations has overtones of the
Perils of Pauline. Only days after a State Department ethics
investigation found there was no reason to block the nomination
over lecture fees he had taken, Republicans on the Senate Foreign
Relations Committee tussled over whether the panel can schedule a
confirmation hearing.
</P>
<P>
   Two Republicans called for a hearing quickly.
</P>
<P>
   But a spokesman for the panel's powerful chairman, Sen. Jesse
Helms, R-N.C., said it would be ``insane'' to do anything until the
Justice Department handed over documents from an earlier
investigation, this one involving lobbying by Holbrooke.
</P>
<P>
   _ By PHILIP SHENON
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
