<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-08 12:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9291 &Cx1f; var-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COLO-SHOOTING-ODDS-RE     05-08 0975
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COLO-SHOOTING-ODDS-REVIEW-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BY THE NUMBERS: SCIENCE LOOKS AT LITTLETON, AND SHRUGS 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Week in Review)  
 (NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For international clients' use by
special arrangement only. Asian and European points: contact Karl
Horwitz in Paris for details and prices (Phone: 47 42 17 11; FAX:
47-42-80-44). Latin American points: contact Olivia Vasquez in Los
Angeles (Phone: 310-996-0075; FAX: 310-996-0089)  
 (bl)  
 By SHERYL GAY STOLBERG   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The bullets were still ricocheting off the lockers
at Columbine High School when the accusations began to fly. Clues
were ignored: Gothic music, black trench coats, video games
spelling combat with a K. The sheriffs missed the Web site ravings.
The psychiatrist missed the hidden rage. The parents missed the
pipe bombs. If only somebody had spotted the warning signs, a
terrible tragedy might have been averted.
</P>
<P>
   That is a comforting thought for a nation scarred and grieving.
But viewed through the prism of science, it isn't necessarily true.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, if there is anything left to be said about the recent
tragedy in Littleton, Colo., it may be this: the cold, hard reality
of the deadliest school massacre in American history is that it was
the statistical equivalent of a needle in a haystack.
</P>
<P>
   Because such events are so rare, and because it is impossible to
eliminate risk from life, there may be no larger lessons to draw,
and no way to prevent another one.
</P>
<P>
   Consider the numbers. Homicide is the second-leading cause of
death among youngsters. But according to the Centers for Disease
Control and Prevention, fewer than 1 percent of child homicides
occur in or around schools. While the number of school shootings
with multiple victims _ the kind that attract intense media
attention _ has risen recently, from an average of 2 to an average
of 5 a year, the annual total has declined.
</P>
<P>
   ``The reality is that schools are very safe environments for our
kids,'' said Dr. Jim Mercy, associate director for science in the
division of violence prevention at the Centers for Disease Control
and Prevention.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be very hard to predict or identify ahead of time the
kinds of kids and the constellation of factors that are likely to
lead to this kind of event,'' he added. ``They are so rare, and
there are so many school kids, and our understanding of what
motivates people to be violent is so imprecise, that this would be
a very difficult task.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, there is the impulse to analyze, to understand, to
prevent. In the wake of disasters like Littleton, where two
teen-age gunmen killed 13 people and then themselves, sociologists,
psychologists and criminal justice experts are interrogated by the
media in a collective search for societal failures, in much the
same way that aviation investigators look for jammed rudders or
ruptured fuel lines after an airplane crash.
</P>
<P>
   But risk cannot be eliminated. Fine surgeons still kill
patients. Tornados still wipe out towns. ``There is a lot of
randomness in the world,'' said Dr. John D. Graham, director of the
Center for Risk Analysis at the Harvard University School of Public
Health. ``Part of understanding risk is understanding that things
are not fully explainable and not reducible to zero.''
</P>
<P>
   That is true of air crashes, and it is true of school shootings.
Last week, when state attorneys general gathered in Jackson, Miss.,
for a two-day conference on youth violence, officials from
Littleton delivered a sobering message: They had long been in a
good position to prevent the Columbine massacre. Their county
already had one of the few juvenile assessment centers in the
country. Its population is affluent and well educated. Children get
a good education and health care. And one of the gunmen, Eric
Harris, was already seeing a psychiatrist.
</P>
<P>
   Still, 15 people died. Most took that as disturbing evidence
that a good system had failed. Dr. Arnold Barnett, professor of
statistics at the Massachusetts Institute of Technology, says it
may mean the opposite: a good system worked.
</P>
<P>
   ``This might represent one aberrant case,'' Barnett said. ``Even
measures that are highly successful, that 99.9 percent of the time
will defuse potential tragedies, will every now and then break
down. People seek higher meanings and seek major failures to
produce major tragedies like this. But it doesn't always work that
way.''
</P>
<P>
   Given the vast number of schoolchildren who report carrying
guns, it is surprising that such shootings do not occur more often.
According to the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention, 5.9
percent of the 15 million high school students said they carried a
gun in the 30 days prior to a recent survey. ``And yet,'' said Dr.
Jeffrey Fagan, director of the Center for Violence Research and
Prevention at Columbia University in New York, ``they don't
shoot.''
</P>
<P>
   ``When you start thinking about risk,'' Fagan said, ``it changes
the conversation from the culture war that is going on now about
video games, parental supervision and the alienation of the
suburbs. It changes it to a much more hard-headed approach that
says, `Sometimes bad things happen and we can't always explain
it.'''
</P>
<P>
   When public health experts look at risks to young people,
homicides, which account for 14 percent of all deaths among
children, come in second. The biggest threat is accidents,
primarily car crashes, which are responsible for 42 percent of
childhood deaths. Graham says there is a danger to the ``emotional
gush'' over Littleton: ``It diverts energies from the big risks
that adolescents face, which are binge drinking, traffic crashes,
unprotected sex.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet people yearn for explanations, and it is disturbing to
entertain the possibility that not everything is within their
control.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-08-99 1207EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990508.0066 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-08 12:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6939 &Cx1f; var-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COLO-SHOOTING-ODDS-RE     05-08 0975
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COLO-SHOOTING-ODDS-REVIEW-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BY THE NUMBERS: SCIENCE LOOKS AT LITTLETON, AND SHRUGS 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Week in Review)  
 (NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For international clients' use by
special arrangement only. Asian and European points: contact Karl
Horwitz in Paris for details and prices (Phone: 47 42 17 11; FAX:
47-42-80-44). Latin American points: contact Olivia Vasquez in Los
Angeles (Phone: 310-996-0075; FAX: 310-996-0089)  
 (bl)  
 By SHERYL GAY STOLBERG   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The bullets were still ricocheting off the lockers
at Columbine High School when the accusations began to fly. Clues
were ignored: Gothic music, black trench coats, video games
spelling combat with a K. The sheriffs missed the Web site ravings.
The psychiatrist missed the hidden rage. The parents missed the
pipe bombs. If only somebody had spotted the warning signs, a
terrible tragedy might have been averted.
</P>
<P>
   That is a comforting thought for a nation scarred and grieving.
But viewed through the prism of science, it isn't necessarily true.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, if there is anything left to be said about the recent
tragedy in Littleton, Colo., it may be this: the cold, hard reality
of the deadliest school massacre in American history is that it was
the statistical equivalent of a needle in a haystack.
</P>
<P>
   Because such events are so rare, and because it is impossible to
eliminate risk from life, there may be no larger lessons to draw,
and no way to prevent another one.
</P>
<P>
   Consider the numbers. Homicide is the second-leading cause of
death among youngsters. But according to the Centers for Disease
Control and Prevention, fewer than 1 percent of child homicides
occur in or around schools. While the number of school shootings
with multiple victims _ the kind that attract intense media
attention _ has risen recently, from an average of 2 to an average
of 5 a year, the annual total has declined.
</P>
<P>
   ``The reality is that schools are very safe environments for our
kids,'' said Dr. Jim Mercy, associate director for science in the
division of violence prevention at the Centers for Disease Control
and Prevention.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be very hard to predict or identify ahead of time the
kinds of kids and the constellation of factors that are likely to
lead to this kind of event,'' he added. ``They are so rare, and
there are so many school kids, and our understanding of what
motivates people to be violent is so imprecise, that this would be
a very difficult task.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, there is the impulse to analyze, to understand, to
prevent. In the wake of disasters like Littleton, where two
teen-age gunmen killed 13 people and then themselves, sociologists,
psychologists and criminal justice experts are interrogated by the
media in a collective search for societal failures, in much the
same way that aviation investigators look for jammed rudders or
ruptured fuel lines after an airplane crash.
</P>
<P>
   But risk cannot be eliminated. Fine surgeons still kill
patients. Tornados still wipe out towns. ``There is a lot of
randomness in the world,'' said Dr. John D. Graham, director of the
Center for Risk Analysis at the Harvard University School of Public
Health. ``Part of understanding risk is understanding that things
are not fully explainable and not reducible to zero.''
</P>
<P>
   That is true of air crashes, and it is true of school shootings.
Last week, when state attorneys general gathered in Jackson, Miss.,
for a two-day conference on youth violence, officials from
Littleton delivered a sobering message: They had long been in a
good position to prevent the Columbine massacre. Their county
already had one of the few juvenile assessment centers in the
country. Its population is affluent and well educated. Children get
a good education and health care. And one of the gunmen, Eric
Harris, was already seeing a psychiatrist.
</P>
<P>
   Still, 15 people died. Most took that as disturbing evidence
that a good system had failed. Dr. Arnold Barnett, professor of
statistics at the Massachusetts Institute of Technology, says it
may mean the opposite: a good system worked.
</P>
<P>
   ``This might represent one aberrant case,'' Barnett said. ``Even
measures that are highly successful, that 99.9 percent of the time
will defuse potential tragedies, will every now and then break
down. People seek higher meanings and seek major failures to
produce major tragedies like this. But it doesn't always work that
way.''
</P>
<P>
   Given the vast number of schoolchildren who report carrying
guns, it is surprising that such shootings do not occur more often.
According to the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention, 5.9
percent of the 15 million high school students said they carried a
gun in the 30 days prior to a recent survey. ``And yet,'' said Dr.
Jeffrey Fagan, director of the Center for Violence Research and
Prevention at Columbia University in New York, ``they don't
shoot.''
</P>
<P>
   ``When you start thinking about risk,'' Fagan said, ``it changes
the conversation from the culture war that is going on now about
video games, parental supervision and the alienation of the
suburbs. It changes it to a much more hard-headed approach that
says, `Sometimes bad things happen and we can't always explain
it.'''
</P>
<P>
   When public health experts look at risks to young people,
homicides, which account for 14 percent of all deaths among
children, come in second. The biggest threat is accidents,
primarily car crashes, which are responsible for 42 percent of
childhood deaths. Graham says there is a danger to the ``emotional
gush'' over Littleton: ``It diverts energies from the big risks
that adolescents face, which are binge drinking, traffic crashes,
unprotected sex.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet people yearn for explanations, and it is disturbing to
entertain the possibility that not everything is within their
control.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   ``People need to believe that they live in a just world, for
their own sake and sanity,'' said Dr. Melvin Lerner, a retired
professor of psychology at the University of Waterloo in Ontario.
``When faced with obvious horrible things, we go out looking for
people to blame.''
</P>
<P>
   They also look for patterns. The Columbine massacre was the
sixth multiple-victim school shooting in the past 18 months. If
there are common threads, said Fagan, it is that each involved
firearms, undiagnosed mental illness and longstanding grievances on
the part of the gunmen. ``Any one of these three risks separately
does not produce a violent event,'' he said. ``It's their
convergence and interaction that produces an event.''
</P>
<P>
   Over the past decade, the CDC has devoted considerable attention
to investigating violence as a public health threat, trying to
examine the trends. But its research has only scratched the
surface, providing information about the who, what, where and when
of school shootings, but little insight as to why.
</P>
<P>
   Scientists now know that between July 1, 1992, and June 30,
1994, two-thirds of school shooting victims were students; of the
children killed, 83 percent were boys. The deaths occurred in 25
states, in communities of all sizes. But fewer than one-third of
the shootings, 28 percent, occurred inside school. ``What we were
not able to do,'' said Mercy, ``was a psychological profile of the
offenders, to look at the commonalities.''
</P>
<P>
   There is a well-known story about the London doctor John Snow,
who traced an outbreak of cholera to one pump spouting tainted
water. He removed the pump handle. It didn't clean up the water,
but it ended the epidemic. In the same way, said Dr. Alfred
Blumstein, director of the National Consortium on Violence Research
at Carnegie Mellon University in Pittsburgh, there is a simple way
to address school shootings: eliminate access to guns. ``Guns,'' he
said, ``transform what is widespread teen-age behavior into
disasters.''
</P>
<P>
   One might also eliminate video games, or the Internet, or shut
down schools or institutionalize troubled children. But that would
simply create other risks, Graham said, like unsupervised or truant
children. Yet even in the absence of solutions, said Lerner, the
search may still be useful. ``One could make a good case,'' he
said, ``that it is the only rational response.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
