Angeles (Phone: 310-996-0075; FAX: 310-996-0089)  
 (bl)  
 By DAVID FIRESTONE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Between the roar of an Amtrak train crash in March and
the rampage of tornadoes last Monday, there was a terribly quiet
moment in Arkansas last weekend.
</P>
<P>
   An amphibious boat filled with 21 tourists began taking on water
on Lake Hamilton, just outside Hot Springs. Thirty seconds later it
disappeared below the surface.
</P>
<P>
   The accident killed 13 people, two more than died in the Amtrak
crash outside of Chicago on March 15. But unlike those victims, or
the 15 who died in the massacre at Columbine High School in
Littleton, Colo., or the more than 40 who died in the tornadoes in
Oklahoma and Kansas, the people who drowned spent only an instant
in a national consciousness ever restless for greater grief and
higher drama. Like the boat itself, news of the accident sank
without a trace.
</P>
<P>
   The national television networks, including CNN and MSNBC, ran
reports of only a few minutes, deep into their broadcasts. Regional
newspapers in Dallas, Memphis, ran front-page articles, but none of
the national newspapers did. Although The New York Times ran the
train accident on its front page, the boat accident ran inside.
</P>
<P>
   There were, of course, a few other things going on in the world
that Saturday afternoon. The Rev. Jesse Jackson was leading three
U.S. prisoners of war out of Yugoslavia. The bombing was continuing
in Kosovo, and the national meditation over Littleton went on.
</P>
<P>
   But the Arkansas boating accident serves as a reminder that
while people may be created equal, they do not necessarily die that
way. On the swiftly calculated sliding scale of death, accidents
are assigned a news value based not on how many lives were lost,
but on how and where they happened to die.
</P>
<P>
   ``None of us make any bones about this _ pictures really
matter,'' said Erik Sorenson, vice president and general manager of
MSNBC. ``In this case, the boat vanished. And we had a rather
tranquil-looking water top. In the train wreck, we had a very
large, quite mangled Amtrak train lying on its side, and that's a
much more compelling photograph, whether for a newspaper or an
Internet site or a television program.''
</P>
<P>
   But visuals aren't everything. For journalists, a disaster is
more interesting if people can imagine themselves within it. Just
as a school-bus crash in Kentucky will get far more U.S. coverage
than a deadly monsoon in Bangladesh that kills hundreds, so too
will a death during a commonplace activity take precedence over a
more obscure one, like boating.
</P>
<P>
   ``To a large degree, coverage is determined by editors asking
themselves, how likely is it that this accident could happen to me
or my readers?'' said James Kelly, the deputy managing editor of
Time, which did not cover the boating accident. ``And there are a
lot of people who take trains, and not that many who take tour
boats.''
</P>
<P>
   The news media have never pretended to a mathematical
consistency in what they cover. The longest-lasting stories require
a mystery or a forceful narrative, which is why the Littleton
shootings have prompted so much examination than any of the 12
deaths attributed to youth violence that occur, on average, every
day. But even by that standard, the silence in Arkansas seemed
eerie. None of the amphibious boats has ever had a fatality in
nearly 40 years of use. When death did occur _ possibly because of
a leaky rubber seal on the hull _ it seemed as if the victims were
cheated of their rightful national ritual in which their families'
grief would be displayed.
</P>
<P>
   As it happened, James Patton, whose parents and sister died on
the boat, paid tribute to them in a very personal way at their
funeral Wednesday in Ames, Okla. Accompanying a recording of Lynyrd
Skynyrd's ``Free Bird,'' the 15-year-old boy played his drum set at
the gravesite. The Associated Press was the only national news
organization to send a reporter. The cameras were 50 miles away,
filming storm rubble.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-08-99 1208EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
