<HEADER>
A9298 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-UNINSURED-CHILDREN-50     05-08 1376
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-UNINSURED-CHILDREN-500&AMP;add-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MANY STATES SLOW TO USE CHILD HEALTH PLAN 
</HEADLINE>
   (Attn: Va., W.Va, N.Y., Vt., Mn., Wash., Colo.)  
(jt) 
 By ROBERT PEAR    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON, May 8 _ States are using less than 20 percent of the
federal money that Congress made available, with much fanfare, for
a big new program to subsidize health insurance for children in
low-income families.
</P>
<P>
   Some states say they cannot find enough eligible uninsured
children to use all the money they are entitled to receive. Critics
say many states have been slow to reach out to eligible children
and sign them up.
</P>
<P>
   The program's slow start and the accumulation of unspent money
are tempting Republicans in Congress to take back some of the money
and use it for other purposes _ an idea vehemently opposed by
Democrats, by advocates for children and by governors of both
parties.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. John D. Rockefeller IV, the West Virginia Democrat who
helped create the Children's Health Insurance Program in 1997,
said, ``The Appropriations Committee is looking at the unused money
for other projects.'' He objects to such a shift.
</P>
<P>
   Elaina J. Fox, a spokeswoman for West Virginia's new child
health program, said, ``A majority of states will probably not be
able to utilize their full allotments'' of federal money.
</P>
<P>
   Governors are enthusiastic about the program, and tens of
thousands of children have clearly benefited. But Rep. Diana
DeGette, D-Colo., said some states, including her own, had ``an
abysmal record'' of finding uninsured children and enrolling them
in the new program.
</P>
<P>
   Congress provided $39 billion for the program over 10 years,
including $4.2 billion a year in 1998 and 1999. Federal officials
said states had used $260 million through December 1998 and $115
million in the first three months of this year. The Congressional
Budget Office estimates that states will use a total of $800
million this year.
</P>
<P>
   States say they have enrolled one million youngsters in the new
program. But federal officials and health policy experts say the
numbers are somewhat misleading.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly 30 percent of the million children are in New York State,
and 176,000 of the New York children were already in a
state-financed program, Child Health Plus, often described by
federal officials as a model for the nation.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, Frank C. Ullman, a health policy expert at the Urban
Institute here, said, ``The decrease in Medicaid enrollment in many
states is greater than the increase in coverage through the new
Children's Health Insurance Program.'' So it is unclear, he added,
whether there has been a net reduction in the number of uninsured
children _ one of the main goals for President Clinton and
Congress.
</P>
<P>
   The number of children without health insurance has been
creeping up in recent years and is now at least 10.7 million, the
Census Bureau says.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Under federal law, children eligible for Medicaid may not be
enrolled in the new Children's Health Insurance Program. Medicaid
is intended for families with somewhat lower incomes. States are
supposed to screen children and enroll them in Medicaid if they
qualify for it.
</P>
<P>
   But states have a strong financial incentive to put children
into the new program, rather than in Medicaid, because the federal
government pays a larger share of the costs _ 65 percent, rather
than 50 percent, in high-income states like New York, New Jersey
and Connecticut.
</P>
<P>
   The children's health plan was forged in a bipartisan agreement
between the president and Congress. When he signed the legislation
in August 1997, Clinton said it would extend insurance coverage
``to up to five million children.'' He called it ``the largest
expansion in health care for children'' in three decades.
</P>
<P>
   Bruce D. Lesley, director of congressional relations at the
National Association of Children's Hospitals, said: ``The results
to date have been mixed. Some states like South Carolina have done
an unbelievably good job of enrolling children in the new health
insurance program. Other states like Virginia are not doing so
well. In these states, parents who need to know about the new
program have no idea that it exists.''
</P>
<P>
   South Carolina simplified its enrollment process, disseminated
applications at drug stores, day care centers, schools, churches
and Indian reservations and signed up 40,400 children for the new
program. By reaching out to low-income families, the state also
found 46,000 other children who were eligible for its pre-existing
Medicaid program.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, Amy M. Atkinson, a spokeswoman for the Virginia
Department of Medical Assistance Services, said her state had
enrolled 8,599 children in the new insurance program, including
only 71 in Richmond, through May 3.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Charles S. Robb, D-Va., said, ``My state has not been as
quick off the mark as others have.''
</P>
<P>
   Edward J. Rogan, a spokesman for the New Jersey Department of
Human Services, said the state had enrolled 30,232 children in its
new health program, known as Kid Care, and expected to spend $19
million of its $88 million federal allotment this year.
</P>
<P>
   Connecticut has enrolled 8,000 children and expects to spend
$5.4 million of its $35 million federal allotment this year, said
David Dearborn, a spokesman for the Connecticut Department of
Social Services. As a side benefit, he said, in reaching out to
low-income families, the state has found several thousand children
eligible for its Medicaid program.
</P>
<P>
   Auditors in some states said some children enrolled in the new
program were probably ineligible and should have been enrolled
instead in the regular Medicaid program.
</P>
<P>
   In welfare, a separate program, states have also allowed
substantial amounts of federal money to go unspent. They say they
are keeping it for a rainy day, in case the economy sputters.
</P>
<P>
   But that concern does not explain delays in spending money on
health insurance for children. Officials in many states said they
had only recently begun to enroll children because they first had
to design new health programs, get federal approval, prepare
application forms, set up toll-free telephone lines, print posters
and run advertising to publicize the availability of the new
benefits.
</P>
<P>
   Judith A. Arnold, deputy commissioner of the New York Health
Department, said, ``Congress should be patient with states that
seem to be moving slowly.''
</P>
<P>
   The federal government has approved children's health plans for
every state except Tennessee, Washington and Wyoming.
</P>
<P>
   State officials told Congress in 1997 that they needed the
maximum latitude to design their own programs because they knew
best how to meet the health needs of uninsured children.
</P>
<P>
   But in a curious way, the law penalized states that had already
expanded Medicaid eligibility by increasing the permissible income
for families seeking coverage. Such states included Minnesota,
Vermont and Washington.
</P>
<P>
   In Washington State, for example, Medicaid covers children whose
family incomes are up to twice the official poverty level (up to
$27,760 a year for a family of three). Since those children are
eligible for Medicaid, they may not enroll in the new Children's
Health Insurance Program.
</P>
<P>
   Under federal law, Washington may use its share of the new
federal money _ $46 million a year _ for children of families with
incomes up to 2.5 times the poverty level.
</P>
<P>
   But Thomas W. Bedell, acting director of the Medicaid program in
Washington State, said: ``We won't be able to spend our full
allotment of federal money. We have only 10,000 uninsured children
with family incomes from 200 to 250 percent of the poverty level.
We estimate that we can spend only $7.5 million of our federal
money in the next year and a half.''
</P>
<P>
   Likewise, Gov. Howard Dean of Vermont, a Democrat, said the law
penalized ``states like Vermont that have served as national
leaders in expanding health care coverage.''
</P>
<P>
   Ullman of the Urban Institute said: ``In theory, there's enough
money to cover five million children a year in the initial years of
the new Children's Health Insurance Program. But only 3.2 million
uninsured children live in families with the proper income to
qualify.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-08-99 1217EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
