<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-08 12:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9299 &Cx1f; var-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLEMENCY-POLITICS-REV     05-08 0972
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLEMENCY-POLITICS-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GRANTING CLEMENCY: BEING IN THE WRONG PLACE AT THE RIGHT TIME 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif., Mo.)   (The Week in Review)  
 (NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For international clients' use by
special arrangement only. Asian and European points: contact Karl
Horwitz in Paris for details and prices (Phone: 47 42 17 11; FAX:
47-42-80-44). Latin American points: contact Olivia Vasquez in Los
Angeles (Phone: 310-996-0075; FAX: 310-996-0089)  
 (bl)  
 By EVELYN NIEVES   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ It is a bad time to be on death row.
</P>
<P>
   Politicians win points _ and votes _ by wearing the
tough-on-crime banner. In this environment, granting clemency has
become an act of courage that requires an outlay of political
capital few governors are willing to spend.
</P>
<P>
   Not that clemency has ever been a good bet: 544 inmates have
been executed and 39 granted clemency in the 23 years since the
U.S. Supreme Court reinstated the death penalty. But given the
current political climate, clemency is nearly impossible. It is no
accident, political experts say, that 14 of the 39 prisoners spared
death (including one in Alabama this year) were awarded clemency by
three governors leaving office.
</P>
<P>
   Conversely, the inmate who faces a clemency decision from a
governor in the heat of political battle, or from one who is new
and trying to prove himself, is as good as dead.
</P>
<P>
   ``For a governor new in office, especially a Democrat trying to
establish law-and-order credentials, clemency is not an option,''
said Franklin Zimring, a professor of law at the University of
California at Berkeley. ``The political pressure to deny clemency
is overwhelming.''
</P>
<P>
   Take the case of Manuel Babbitt, a Vietnam veteran with a Purple
Heart and a history of mental illness. Thousands of veterans asked
California Gov. Gray Davis to spare him, but he was executed last
week for the 1980 murder of an elderly woman.
</P>
<P>
   Davis, California's first Democratic governor in 16 years,
promised to give his fellow Vietnam veterans due respect when he
took office in January, but he also had campaigned as a supporter
of the death penalty. Babbitt was only his second clemency case.
</P>
<P>
   In his 14-page explanation denying clemency, Davis discounted or
ignored the strongest reasons for mercy, including affidavits from
two jurors who said they would have voted against the death penalty
if evidence omitted from the trial had been included. While Davis
had already rejected the first clemency plea to cross his desk,
that of a Thai Buddhist priest convicted of two murders, a single
execution was not enough for a new governor trying to establish his
law-and-order reputation.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has to have several executions under his belt to establish
his credentials,'' Zimring said. ``He could write a lengthy paper
describing why he made his decision, but in the end, the truth is
he was not going to grant clemency.''
</P>
<P>
   Recent events in Missouri underscore how even a well-timed
clemency can backfire. In January, in a much-publicized case, Gov.
Mel Carnahan commuted the sentence of an admitted triple murderer
after Pope John Paul II, who was visiting St. Louis, asked him to
do so. The governor, a moderate Democrat who is hoping to unseat
Republican incumbent Sen. John Ashcroft in 2000, had allowed more
than two dozen executions to go forward, and announced that his act
of mercy was a ``one-time event.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, the governor's opponents promptly began making political
hay. Senator Ashcroft held a victims' rights hearing in St. Louis,
inviting as star witnesses the members of the family killed by the
man Carnahan spared. Polls showed that the governor's clemency
would cost him four times as many votes for the Senate as he would
gain. All four of the clemency appeals to pass his desk since then
have been denied.
</P>
<P>
   Governors in the 38 states with a death penalty are not likely
to grant clemency except in cases of ``actual innocence,'' said
Daniel Kobil, a law professor at Capital University in Columbus,
Ohio. Clemency enables governors to commute a death sentence for
many reasons, legal experts say, including the rehabilitation of a
prisoner or extenuating circumstances that were not brought out in
trial.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, governors often deny clemency by saying they will not
second-guess the wisdom of courts and juries, Kobil said. ``I think
it's a perversion of the governor's clemency power to say this,''
he said. ``It makes clemency just another appeal, when the
executive is supposed to consider whether this punishment is fair
given all the circumstances.''
</P>
<P>
   Only when the public begins to punish politicians for not
exercising their clemency power will the pattern change, Kobil
said. In 1960, for example, when polls showed that only 50 percent
of the public favored executions, one in four cases was commuted.
But by the mid-1960s, support for the death penalty was growing.
</P>
<P>
   California Gov. Edmund G. Brown Sr. was unseated by Ronald
Reagan largely for commuting 23 death sentences from 1958 to 1966,
although he had allowed 36 executions at the same time. Brown's
son, Jerry, suffered his worst political defeat as governor in the
early 1980s after appointing three anti-death-penalty justices to
the Supreme Court. They were later ousted in an unprecedented
ballot initiative. His sister, Kathleen, lost her 1994 challenge to
then-incumbent Gov. Pete Wilson over her opposition to the death
penalty.
</P>
<P>
   Davis is likely to face more clemency pleas than any other
governor before him, or any other governor in the country.
California has more than 500 inmates on death row. At some point,
he will probably grant clemency, said Zimring. But not soon.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the pope had been in California in January,'' he said,
``his plea for mercy would have been denied.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-08-99 1222EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990508.0075 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-08 12:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6947 &Cx1f; var-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLEMENCY-POLITICS-REV     05-08 0972
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLEMENCY-POLITICS-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GRANTING CLEMENCY: BEING IN THE WRONG PLACE AT THE RIGHT TIME 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif., Mo.)   (The Week in Review)  
 (NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For international clients' use by
special arrangement only. Asian and European points: contact Karl
Horwitz in Paris for details and prices (Phone: 47 42 17 11; FAX:
47-42-80-44). Latin American points: contact Olivia Vasquez in Los
Angeles (Phone: 310-996-0075; FAX: 310-996-0089)  
 (bl)  
 By EVELYN NIEVES   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ It is a bad time to be on death row.
</P>
<P>
   Politicians win points _ and votes _ by wearing the
tough-on-crime banner. In this environment, granting clemency has
become an act of courage that requires an outlay of political
capital few governors are willing to spend.
</P>
<P>
   Not that clemency has ever been a good bet: 544 inmates have
been executed and 39 granted clemency in the 23 years since the
U.S. Supreme Court reinstated the death penalty. But given the
current political climate, clemency is nearly impossible. It is no
accident, political experts say, that 14 of the 39 prisoners spared
death (including one in Alabama this year) were awarded clemency by
three governors leaving office.
</P>
<P>
   Conversely, the inmate who faces a clemency decision from a
governor in the heat of political battle, or from one who is new
and trying to prove himself, is as good as dead.
</P>
<P>
   ``For a governor new in office, especially a Democrat trying to
establish law-and-order credentials, clemency is not an option,''
said Franklin Zimring, a professor of law at the University of
California at Berkeley. ``The political pressure to deny clemency
is overwhelming.''
</P>
<P>
   Take the case of Manuel Babbitt, a Vietnam veteran with a Purple
Heart and a history of mental illness. Thousands of veterans asked
California Gov. Gray Davis to spare him, but he was executed last
week for the 1980 murder of an elderly woman.
</P>
<P>
   Davis, California's first Democratic governor in 16 years,
promised to give his fellow Vietnam veterans due respect when he
took office in January, but he also had campaigned as a supporter
of the death penalty. Babbitt was only his second clemency case.
</P>
<P>
   In his 14-page explanation denying clemency, Davis discounted or
ignored the strongest reasons for mercy, including affidavits from
two jurors who said they would have voted against the death penalty
if evidence omitted from the trial had been included. While Davis
had already rejected the first clemency plea to cross his desk,
that of a Thai Buddhist priest convicted of two murders, a single
execution was not enough for a new governor trying to establish his
law-and-order reputation.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has to have several executions under his belt to establish
his credentials,'' Zimring said. ``He could write a lengthy paper
describing why he made his decision, but in the end, the truth is
he was not going to grant clemency.''
</P>
<P>
   Recent events in Missouri underscore how even a well-timed
clemency can backfire. In January, in a much-publicized case, Gov.
Mel Carnahan commuted the sentence of an admitted triple murderer
after Pope John Paul II, who was visiting St. Louis, asked him to
do so. The governor, a moderate Democrat who is hoping to unseat
Republican incumbent Sen. John Ashcroft in 2000, had allowed more
than two dozen executions to go forward, and announced that his act
of mercy was a ``one-time event.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, the governor's opponents promptly began making political
hay. Senator Ashcroft held a victims' rights hearing in St. Louis,
inviting as star witnesses the members of the family killed by the
man Carnahan spared. Polls showed that the governor's clemency
would cost him four times as many votes for the Senate as he would
gain. All four of the clemency appeals to pass his desk since then
have been denied.
</P>
<P>
   Governors in the 38 states with a death penalty are not likely
to grant clemency except in cases of ``actual innocence,'' said
Daniel Kobil, a law professor at Capital University in Columbus,
Ohio. Clemency enables governors to commute a death sentence for
many reasons, legal experts say, including the rehabilitation of a
prisoner or extenuating circumstances that were not brought out in
trial.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, governors often deny clemency by saying they will not
second-guess the wisdom of courts and juries, Kobil said. ``I think
it's a perversion of the governor's clemency power to say this,''
he said. ``It makes clemency just another appeal, when the
executive is supposed to consider whether this punishment is fair
given all the circumstances.''
</P>
<P>
   Only when the public begins to punish politicians for not
exercising their clemency power will the pattern change, Kobil
said. In 1960, for example, when polls showed that only 50 percent
of the public favored executions, one in four cases was commuted.
But by the mid-1960s, support for the death penalty was growing.
</P>
<P>
   California Gov. Edmund G. Brown Sr. was unseated by Ronald
Reagan largely for commuting 23 death sentences from 1958 to 1966,
although he had allowed 36 executions at the same time. Brown's
son, Jerry, suffered his worst political defeat as governor in the
early 1980s after appointing three anti-death-penalty justices to
the Supreme Court. They were later ousted in an unprecedented
ballot initiative. His sister, Kathleen, lost her 1994 challenge to
then-incumbent Gov. Pete Wilson over her opposition to the death
penalty.
</P>
<P>
   Davis is likely to face more clemency pleas than any other
governor before him, or any other governor in the country.
California has more than 500 inmates on death row. At some point,
he will probably grant clemency, said Zimring. But not soon.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the pope had been in California in January,'' he said,
``his plea for mercy would have been denied.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-08-99 1223EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990508.0076 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-08 12:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9302 &Cx1f; var-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ANIMAL-CRUELTY-REVIEW     05-08 0955
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ANIMAL-CRUELTY-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SLAPSTICK ABUSE OF ANIMALS IN MOVIES: WHY IS IT ON THE RISE? 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Week in Review)  
 (NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For international clients' use by
special arrangement only. Asian and European points: contact Karl
Horwitz in Paris for details and prices (Phone: 47 42 17 11; FAX:
47-42-80-44). Latin American points: contact Olivia Vasquez in Los
Angeles (Phone: 310-996-0075; FAX: 310-996-0089)  
 (bl)  
 By DOUGLAS MARTIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the film ``There's Something About Mary,'' a small dog flies
out a window. In ``As Good as It Gets,'' a pooch is crammed down a
trash chute. In ``EdTV,'' a love scene culminates in Matthew
McConaughey falling on a cat. In ``Men in Black,'' an alien pug
confesses after it is mercilessly shaken. Even the preview for
``Idle Hands'' shows a cat being swung around by its tail.
</P>
<P>
   For cats, dogs and other animals, life in the movies is
beginning to appear less than glamorous. Indeed, at this historical
juncture of political correctness and feeling the pain of others,
pretending to hurt animals has become an intentional laugh-getter
in movies, television and advertising.
</P>
<P>
   The ad campaign of Cyberian Outpost, an online shopping site,
features gerbils being fired from an artillery cannon into a wall.
(They were actually plastic.)
</P>
<P>
   The question arises, as President Clinton prepares to meet
Monday with experts on youth violence in the wake of the Colorado
killings, how positive an influence is all this animal abuse?
</P>
<P>
   Not very, worries Dr. Pamela Sicher, president of the Children's
Mental Health Alliance Foundation. ``Is this something that
desensitizes us to the meaning of hurting living things?'' she
said. ``At what point in children's lives can they actually discern
the meaning in this?''
</P>
<P>
   The animal bashing comes at a time when other movies like
``Babe'' depict other fauna in a sympathetic, if not adorable
manner that even the most ardent animal-rights activists applaud.
Virtually all the cinematic atrocities are, of course, staged.
Animal abuse is now a felony in 23 states. Advances in robotics and
computer imaging have made it possible to simulate just about
anything. Since 1980, after a horse was killed by a dynamite
explosion in ``Heaven's Gate,'' the Screen Actors Guild contract
has required that the American Humane Association vet any scripts
involving animals. Representatives visit film sets to insure that
even rats and spiders are not mistreated. A recent New Yorker
cartoon was on the mark: It showed a studio honcho proclaiming,
``OK. Just make sure no animals are harmed in the exploding-donkey
scene.''
</P>
<P>
   But why are there exploding donkey scenes? Mainly, it seems,
because people laugh at silly humor, and animal predicaments,
particularly painful ones, are part of that time-honored genre. Dr.
Alan Manevitz, a family psychiatrist at New York Presbyterian
Hospital, suggests that the apparent abuse represents a regression
to cartoon humor of yore. Three Stooges-style slapstick, which
relies on a dose of sadism, is no longer ``politically correct with
people,'' he says. Since people know the animals are not being hurt
_ and most filmmakers run an official disclaimer from the American
Humane Association in their credits _ animal slapstick is in.
</P>
<P>
   While the humane association ignores the film content, other
groups have focused on the message. The Ark Trust, which monitors
entertainment and media for their depictions of animals, will today
televise its Genesis Awards. Among the honorees is an episode of
``Spin City,'' in which Michael J. Fox's character refuses to kill
a fawn. It is also handing out less laudatory ``Foe-Paw'' awards,
one of which will go to Outpost for its glib depiction of gerbils.
</P>
<P>
   Gretchen Wyler, president of the trust, said such scenes are no
laughing matter. ``They sort of give legitimacy to the acts,'' Ms.
Wyler said. ``It's a potential source of destructive ideas.''
</P>
<P>
   Animal rights activists are fond of pointing to a study by the
Federal Bureau of Investigation that links many serial killers to
animal abuse. As a youth, Jeffrey L. Dahmer stole his neighbor's
pets and practiced taxidermy on them, keeping skulls in his yard.
Albert DeSalvo, the ``Boston Strangler,'' trapped dogs and cats in
orange crates and shot arrows through the boxes. Before Russell
Eugene Weston Jr. was charged with killing two policemen in the
U.S. Capitol last year, he reportedly shot 16 of his grandmother's
cats.
</P>
<P>
   ``Virtually every one of these kids who ends up shooting up the
school yard has a history of animal abuse,'' said Kenneth Shapiro,
executive director of Psychologists for the Ethical Treatment of
Animals.
</P>
<P>
   The link between pretend violence on the screen and real
behavior is fuzzier. But if Manevitz is right that the appeal of
the humor is a throwback to cartoons, there seem to be grounds for
worry: A study by George Gerbner at the University of
Pennsylvania's Annenberg School for Communication found that cruel
images of animals outnumbered positive ones 12 to 1 in Saturday
morning cartoons. As to the question whether watching a violent act
has a cathartic effect on viewers _ or is more likely to spur them
to imitate it _ research has pointed toward imitation, Shapiro
said.
</P>
<P>
   And younger children surely see the famous scene in Mel Brooks'
``Blazing Saddles,'' where Alex Karras knocks out a horse with a
single punch, differently than most adults.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you trivialize the meaning of hurting living things, you're
doing something to the pathways by which children develop
appropriate restraints and constraints on their behavior,'' said
Sicher. ``You want them to be horrified by cruelty.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-08-99 1225EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990508.0077 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
