<HEADER>
A9303 &Cx1f; var-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GAMBLING-DOSTOYEVSKY-     05-08 0898
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GAMBLING-DOSTOYEVSKY-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COME ON BABY, FYODOR NEEDS NEW SHOES! 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Week in Review)  
 (NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For international clients' use by
special arrangement only. Asian and European points: contact Karl
Horwitz in Paris for details and prices (Phone: 47 42 17 11; FAX:
47-42-80-44). Latin American points: contact Olivia Vasquez in Los
Angeles (Phone: 310-996-0075; FAX: 310-996-0089)  
 (bl)  
 By WALTER GOODMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Among the problems to be addressed or evaded in a coming report
by the National Gambling Impact Study Commission, set up by
Congress to look into the flourishing pastime, is the problem
gambler. Since any such study requires that the panelists get a
grip on the nature of the ailment, one hopes they have been
introduced to the most vivid accounts of gambling addiction in
world literature.
</P>
<P>
   They come from Fyodor Mikhailovich Dostoyevsky, who for
miserable years was an unregenerate roulette punter in the casinos
of Germany. ``Oh, the way they played yesterday,'' he wrote. ``The
excitement was tremendous! If only I had some money.''
</P>
<P>
   The reason Dostoyevsky had no money for gambling at the moment,
as every member of Gamblers Anonymous can appreciate, is that as
soon as he laid hold of a few guldens, he gambled them away. Like
so many casino clients, he had a system. ``For four days, he
studied the game and the players and very quickly he came to the
conclusion that only  &UR; he  &LR;  could master this game,'' explained Geir
Kjetsaa, a biographer. ``It was so pathetically simple: All that
was required was that one play  &UR; systematically &LR;  and keep a cool
head.'' In Dostoyevsky's novel ``The Gambler,'' the
roulette-infatuated narrator detects ``a sort of order'' in the
turn of the wheel.
</P>
<P>
   Anyone who has observed roulette players in the throes has seen
the specimens who keep track of winning numbers on little cards
(sometimes supplied by the casino), a project that may be enough to
qualify them as casino compulsives. There are at least two
difficulties with the Dostoyevskyan analysis, which has confounded
gamblers down the years: a system for playing roulette is a wishful
enterprise to begin with, and keeping a cool head is a rare talent
in the heat of play. Certainly it defied the hysteria-prone
Dostoyevsky, even as he bought books on fail-proof systems to break
the bank. In a time when even slot-machine feeders think they have
a system, the gambling panel might consider outlawing all systems
as a form of deceptive advertising.
</P>
<P>
   In a letter to his prodigiously forgiving wife, Anna,
Dostoyevsky described a progression that gamblers everywhere and in
all periods can identify with: ``To begin with I lost a little, and
then I really began to lose in earnest. I wanted to win back what I
had lost, but then I lost even more. And then I simply had to go on
playing, in order at least to get money for my homeward journey.
And then I lost everything, everything!''
</P>
<P>
   Periodically, he would assure the loyal Anna that he had
overcome a decade's passion: ``But now it is all over! This was the
 &UR; last &LR;  time!'' By the next letter, he was back at the tables.
</P>
<P>
   There, for the commission member who pays attention, is a model
of the compulsive's chronic condition.
</P>
<P>
   Kjetsaa credits Dostoyevsky's eventual ``recovery'' not to will
power but to the closing of Germany's casinos in 1872 and 1873, a
remedy that the commission, made up in part by friends of the
casino industry, is in no position to recommend. And since casinos
are not in business to produce winners, gamblers will continue,
like Dostoyevsky, to whine about losing. If the commission seeks to
stop compulsive gambling, all it need do is declare an end to
losing; winning is the cure for all gambling ailments.
</P>
<P>
   Anna saw her husband's gambling as ``an illness for which there
was no cure.'' Kjetsaa offers a more modern explanation for what he
calls a ``pathological obsession.'' He writes, ``Dostoyevsky was
possessed by an unconscious desire to lose and punish himself by
losing.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps. Anyway, the commission, under the influence of the
therapeutic community, can be counted on to treat hard-case
gambling, along with alcoholism, drug addiction and other
unwholesome habits, as an illness. But whatever the preferred
diagnosis, the difference between Dostoyevsky and an ordinary loser
is that the writer seemed to gain creative energy from every
defeat. Kjetsaa reports that ``He never worked better than when he
had lost everything and had relieved his guilt through the
merciless punishment of the roulette wheel.'' It was after a
session of torture by the wheel in Wiesbaden that Dostoyevsky
started ``Crime and Punishment.''
</P>
<P>
   Like many gamblers who cannot stop when they are ahead (too
common to be a pathology), Dostoyevsky was on intimate acquaintance
with the powerful lure of the sport and his own weakness. Even
watching someone else rake in a small fortune on improbable bets,
the narrator of ``The Gambler,'' set in the town of Roulettenberg,
becomes acutely conscious of his hands and knees shaking and the
blood beating in his brain. Unlike others of his sizable fraternity
of losers, however, Dostoyevsky was able to transmute his symptoms
into his writings. The gambling commission has to deal somehow with
all those driven players who can't count on that payback.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-08-99 1227EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990508.0079 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-08 12:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6952 &Cx1f; var-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GAMBLING-DOSTOYEVSKY-     05-08 0898
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GAMBLING-DOSTOYEVSKY-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COME ON BABY, FYODOR NEEDS NEW SHOES! 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Week in Review)  
 (NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For international clients' use by
special arrangement only. Asian and European points: contact Karl
Horwitz in Paris for details and prices (Phone: 47 42 17 11; FAX:
47-42-80-44). Latin American points: contact Olivia Vasquez in Los
Angeles (Phone: 310-996-0075; FAX: 310-996-0089)  
 (bl)  
 By WALTER GOODMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Among the problems to be addressed or evaded in a coming report
by the National Gambling Impact Study Commission, set up by
Congress to look into the flourishing pastime, is the problem
gambler. Since any such study requires that the panelists get a
grip on the nature of the ailment, one hopes they have been
introduced to the most vivid accounts of gambling addiction in
world literature.
</P>
