<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-08 13:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9315 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ASSISTED-LIVING-3TAKE     05-08 1148
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ASSISTED-LIVING-3TAKES-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPECIAL REPORT: FOR ELDERLY, `ASSISTED LIVING' CAN FILL GAP 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mass., Conn., Minn., Pa., Fla.)  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(jt) 
 By SARA RIMER    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   FRAMINGHAM, Mass. _ Susan Faessler was recently helping her
mother-in-law move into an apartment at an assisted-living center
here, Heritage at Framingham, when her cell phone rang. ``It's
Tom,'' Mrs. Faessler said, referring to her husband. ``He wants to
know how you like it.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Tell him I'm getting used to it,'' said her mother-in-law,
87-year-old Trudy Faessler.
</P>
<P>
   True, she had just been commenting on how small the studio
apartment was, after her retirement house in Sun City Center, Fla.
But Trudy Faessler knew that Tom and Susan, who live a short drive
from Heritage, were right: Now that she was a widow _ her husband,
Alfred, died recently _ she could not live on her own.
</P>
<P>
   Osteoporosis has left her too weak even to lift a tea kettle.
She needs the services available at Heritage, where her
$2,750-a-month rent includes three meals a day, housekeeping and
help with bathing and dressing.
</P>
<P>
   Ten years ago, Mrs. Faessler might have ended up spending much
more money, only to be in a nursing home. Assisted-living centers,
which provide private apartments plus daily assistance for a
monthly rent, were then barely known. There was no step between
independence and helplessness.
</P>
<P>
   Today, in one of the most sweeping changes in the way the old
live, assisted living is the focus of the industry that has grown
out of caring for the aging. About 1.2 million people live in
assisted-living facilities, and communities across the country are
asking developers to build more so that their aging residents can
stay close to home.
</P>
<P>
   But for the Faesslers and other families, as well as experts on
aging and government officials, just what ``assisted living'' is
can be confusing and even a concern. Among the nation's 30,000
assisted-living centers, the definition varies from state to state,
town to town, facility to facility, and so do the services they
provide and the fees they charge.
</P>
<P>
   Experts ask whether assisted living is a real solution for a new
stage of life or a marketing opportunity directed at two
fast-growing groups that are fearful about aging: the affluent
elderly and their adult children.
</P>
<P>
   Recalling the scandals of the nursing-home boom of the 1970s,
the experts ask what will happen to assisted-living residents who
run out of money or grow more disabled.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm concerned that they will cater to the worried rich _
`we'll cater to you in a nice setting, then when you get really
sick, you're out,''' said Rosalie A. Kane, gerontologist at the
University of Minnesota who applauds the philosophy behind assisted
living. ``I'm worried about their not being committed.''
</P>
<P>
   Tom and Susan Faessler live in a hotbed of assisted-living
competition, the suburbs of Boston. How they and Trudy Faessler
came to Heritage, and what they found there, illustrates both the
benefits and the complications of assisted living today.
</P>
<P>
   The Growth: More Older People With More Money
</P>
<P>
   Five years ago, Massachusetts had fewer than a dozen
assisted-living centers. Today it has 115 and more on the way as
national chains and local hospitals compete for a piece of the
market.
</P>
<P>
   The brief history of Heritage at Framingham suggests the ferment
within the industry, one that promises its customers stability and
support at a critical stage in their lives.
</P>
<P>
   Heritage was built in 1995 by a developer, ADS Senior Housing,
in conjunction with a local nonprofit hospital, Metrowest Medical
Center. Hospitals increasingly see assisted- living centers as
sources of patients.
</P>
<P>
   The Metrowest Medical Center then spun off a nonprofit
corporation that included Heritage. ADS Senior Housing, meanwhile,
which was managing Heritage, was bought by the Multicare Companies
Corp., which owned and managed nursing homes. Multicare was then
bought by the larger Genesis Health Ventures of Kennett Square, Pa.
A division, Genesis Elder Care, now manages Heritage.
</P>
<P>
   The founder of ADS Senior Housing, Thomas H. Grape, left to
start a new company, Benchmark Assisted Living, which has since
opened two centers, one in Massachusetts and one in Connecticut,
and has eight more being built or on which construction will start
soon in New England.
</P>
<P>
   Grape said he got into the assisted-living business in the early
1990s based on demographics.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a lot of old folks everywhere, and the numbers are
growing,'' he said. ``It was self evident that it was just going to
become a big thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Framingham had the specific demographics he wanted: lots of
people over 75 with incomes of more than $25,000 a year, and just
as important, many people with incomes of more than $75,000, to
help pay for assisted living for their parents. Indeed, one
criticism of assisted living is that Medicaid and Medicare, the
federal insurance programs, do not cover it, so it is limited to
the affluent.
</P>
<P>
   There is plenty of market research behind the design of Heritage
and other assisted-living centers.
</P>
<P>
   A three-story building with a wide front porch, Heritage, with
room for about 95 residents, was built next to an elementary
school, across from a small shopping center and near a busy
intersection.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a misperception that older people want to live off in
a serene setting by a pond,'' Grape said. ``They want to be right
smack in the middle of the action. They want to feel connected.''
</P>
<P>
   Inside, Heritage is modeled after a country inn. A grandfather
clock stands inside the entrance. The living room has a grand
piano, lace curtains and oriental rugs. There are fresh flowers in
vases and plenty of common spaces with faux antiques and
comfortable chairs.
</P>
<P>
   There are 48 apartments with kitchenettes, a feature important
to older people, who want to feel independent. There are 40 other
apartments for people with memory loss, and these do not have
kitchenettes.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the center of activity at Heritage is the dining room,
where residents gather three times a day for meals served on china
and linens. A cafeteria, Grape said, would be too institutional.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of fluorescent lights, there are lamps. And while there
are plenty of staff members, including a nurse, no one is in
uniform.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't look like a nursing home,'' said Rose Leverone, 94,
a retired Framingham tax clerk. ``Anyone can walk through and think
it's a beautiful retirement home.''
</P>
<P>
   That is a chief selling point. Americans have such a dread of
nursing homes that a recent survey found that 30 percent of people
65 and older would rather die than live in one.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Market research tells developers like Grape that they have two
customers: the older people who need a home that includes help, and
their affluent children.
</P>
<P>
   At Heritage, it is telling that the residents' rooms, which they
furnish themselves, are far simpler than the public rooms.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are people who were raised during the Depression,'' said
Ben Pearce, senior vice president for assisted living with Genesis
Elder Care. ``If it were up to them, they'd stay in their homes for
the rest of their lives, and turn all their savings over to their
kids.''
</P>
<P>
   In most cases, it is the children who make the initial contact,
and often they choose the facility.
</P>
<P>
   ``The glitz is for the kids,'' said Carol Seager, a consultant.
``They feel less guilty. They say, `Look at this beautiful place,
Mom.'''
</P>
<P>
   The cozy luxury of Heritage appealed to Tom Faessler, a dentist
who had paid for his parents' retirement house in Sun City Center,
Fla., and who was prepared to pay, after his father's death, for
assisted living for his thrifty mother if she decided that it was
too expensive.
</P>
<P>
   ``I grew up in an apartment in Kew Gardens, Queens,'' Faessler
said. ``I want the best for my parents, maybe better than they ever
had. I wanted it to be the perfect assisted-living place, with the
perfect people.''
</P>
<P>
   Alfred and Trudy Faessler had been married nearly 64 years when
he died in March, at 91, four days after a heart attack. After
retiring to Florida, they had negotiated old age as a team, without
help.
</P>
<P>
   ``What a husband I had,'' Mrs. Faessler said . ``He was well
known for how he took care of me.''
</P>
<P>
   Sun City Center, however, was built for active retirees, not the
frail elderly. It has golf courses and swimming pools, but, ``they
don't even have a taxicab, or home delivery of groceries,'' Susan
Faessler said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We knew right away she couldn't live there alone,'' Susan
Faessler said. ``The only thing we could do was bring her up
here.''
</P>
<P>
   Tom and Susan Faessler and their three daughters live in
Medfield, 15 miles from Boston. Faessler's sister, Ingrid, also
lives in Medfield. The Faesslers are typical of a growing number of
families that bring a parent back from a retirement community. They
are also typical in having the parent live near them, not with
them.
</P>
<P>
   Trudy Faessler herself says moving in with her son's family was
never an option. ``That's the last and stupidest thing anyone can
do,'' she said. ``They have a life, too. My mother didn't move in
with us when my father died, and we had a fantastic relationship.''
</P>
<P>
   The Faesslers were also typical in that most families start
thinking about assisted living only after a crisis: an aging parent
has a stroke, or has to stop driving, or suddenly cannot remember
whether she took her medication. All of a sudden they had to become
experts in the arcane world of long-term care.
</P>
<P>
   Susan Faessler, a part-time flight attendant, started looking
for a new home for her mother-in-law as soon as she returned from
her father-in-law's funeral. The fact that daughters and
daughters-in-law take on most of the responsibility is no secret to
marketers: brochures for assisted living are filled with
photographs of white-haired men and women with younger women.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Klaassen, the founder of a national chain of
assisted-living centers, Sunrise, describes the care-taking as
``doing what your daughter or daughter-in-law used to do.''
</P>
<P>
   A complication arose when Trudy Faessler, on arriving in Boston,
developed pneumonia and had to be hospitalized. The Faesslers had
already been thinking about assisted living, thanks to one of
Faessler's patients who works with the elderly. But with his mother
in a hospital, he visited a nursing home.
</P>
<P>
   Her husband learned that the nursing home would be appropriate
only if his mother needed 24-hour care. And it would be expensive:
nursing homes in Massachusetts cost, on average, $60,000 to $70,000
a year.
</P>
<P>
   With Trudy Faessler in the hospital for three weeks, her son and
daughter-in-law considered seven different assisted-living
facilities, all with studio apartments, at about $2,700 a month.
</P>
<P>
   The couple wanted a place near Medfield so everyone could visit
easily. They rejected one place because the hallways were too long,
and another because it was too far away. They put down a $500
deposit on one place but changed their minds. One place the
Faesslers liked was Sunrise at Wayland, which opened in 1997 about
seven miles from Heritage.
</P>
<P>
   The Choice: Matching Residents For Compatibility
</P>
<P>
   Sunrise is a national chain that markets its facilities as
alternatives to nursing homes, and so its residents tend to be
frailer than those at other assisted-living centers. While many
residents at the centers use walkers or wheelchairs, a Sunrise
trademark is a grand staircase in the lobby leading to the second
floor.
</P>
<P>
   ``Residents have a choice to use the staircase,'' said Cindy
Peterson, the Wayland facility's executive director, and Sunrise's
philosophy is to give residents choices.
</P>
<P>
   On a recent tour, Ms. Peterson stopped to pet Bradley, a cocker
spaniel that was tied to the concierge desk. Dogs are another
Sunrise signature. So are the ``preview windows'' just inside the
entrance, offering views into the public living room on one side,
and a cafe on the other where residents can get snacks.
</P>
<P>
   The residents, Ms. Peterson said, are of a generation not
accustomed to living communally with strangers; most, for example,
never lived in college dormitories. Preview windows allow them to
see who is in the next room _ and whether it is someone they want
to talk to.
</P>
<P>
   Another Sunrise trademark, Victorian-style architecture, is
aimed at the baby boomers, who may be familiar with the design from
trips to San Francisco, Cape May, Nantucket and Disney World, said
Paul Klaassen, the founder of Sunrise.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, Heritage just felt right. Susan Faessler clocked it
as a 26-minute drive from Medfield. It had been recommended by one
of Trudy Faessler's doctors at the hospital, who happened to be on
Heritage's board. And Faessler liked the fact that he did not see
many residents with walkers or wheelchairs. Nor did many seemed
memory impaired.
</P>
<P>
   ``At Sun City Center, all the neighbors were 15, 25 years
younger than my parents,'' he said. ``That's nice. You feel
younger. It's like when you play tennis. You play with a better
player, it brings up your game.''
</P>
<P>
   With meals served in the dining room, and his mother not needing
much more in the way of help than someone to pull on her stockings,
Faessler signed her up for the ``basic package,'' 315 minutes of
assistance a week (less than an hour a day). The next level, 840
minutes a week (two hours a day), is $500 a month more.
</P>
<P>
   One issue surrounding assisted living, according to a recent
report by the General Accounting Office, the investigative arm of
Congress, is whether families get enough information about a
facility and its services to judge whether it meets their needs _
and whether it will continue to meet their needs as a resident
declines in health.
</P>
<P>
   Just as Sunrise, for example, purposely appeals to frailer
people who might otherwise look at nursing homes, some facilities
try to attract the healthiest people they can, in part because they
cost less to care for. Extra services may be available as they are
needed, but perhaps at a cost some residents can not afford.
</P>
<P>
   If a person requires long-term nursing care around the clock,
many states prohibit them from being in an assisted living
facilities.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   At Heritage, Terese McElhaney, director of marketing, told the
Faesslers that its residents must be able to get around their
apartments without help and be able to communicate their needs. Ms.
McElhaney said many families wanted to discuss the future: How long
can their father or mother stay in assisted living? What happens if
they have to move to a nursing home? What if they run out of money?
</P>
<P>
   ``I tell them, `This is not a good answer, but this is the
answer,''' Ms. McElhaney said. `` `It's private pay. Someone has to
come up with the money. It's all a gamble. Old age is a gamble.'''
</P>
<P>
   By the end of the first week, Trudy Faessler had only praise for
Heritage: ``I must say, it's like a good hotel. The food is
absolutely delicious. I'm very lucky.''
</P>
<P>
   She was pleased, she said, to be near her family, especially her
grandchildren, who had already visited several times.
</P>
<P>
   Still, in Sun City Center, she had been surrounded by people in
their 60s and 70s. At Heritage, the average age is 83. ``I was
never in that much contact with that many old people,'' she said.
``I never realized I was old before.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. McElhaney said she had seen many old people, who had been
isolated at home, form friendships and lead richer lives in
assisted living. Still, she sympathizes with what the residents are
confronting.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't like it when adult children come in and say to me,
`Oh, I'd love to live here,''' she said. ``I say, `Oh, really,
you'd give up your spouse? You'd give up driving, and your house?'
People want to have all their independence. It's the best of a
difficult situation.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-08-99 1301EDT &QL; 
