<HEADER>
A9321 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-MILITARY-NYT &LR;      05-08 1079
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-MILITARY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NATO SAYS OUTDATED MAP A POSSIBILITY IN BOMBING OF CHINESE EMBASSY
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By MICHAEL R. GORDON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BRUSSELS, Belgium _ A NATO aircraft bombed the Chinese Embassy
in Belgrade because the military command mistakenly believed it was
a Serbian weapons depot, NATO officials said Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Allied officials said the aircraft had carried out its mission
correctly and struck the assigned building but had received faulty
target information.
</P>
<P>
   It was not clear who was responsible for the mistake. NATO
officials said the Central Intelligence Agency had picked the
target, but said that the episode was still under investigation.
One possibility, a NATO official said, is that the target was
picked using an outdated map of Belgrade, although the site of the
embassy building was well known in the Yugoslav capital.
</P>
<P>
   ``We hit what we were aiming for,'' a NATO official said. ``But
we did not mean to hit the Chinese Embassy.''
</P>
<P>
   While the alliance acknowledged its mistake, it declined to say
which aircraft was involved and what munitions were used.
</P>
<P>
   The bombing raid, which took place midnight Friday, has stirred
up a political storm for the Western alliance. But NATO officials
gave no hint of easing off their air campaign.
</P>
<P>
   NATO Secretary-General Javier Solana insisted that air strikes
would continue until Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic stopped
his attacks on ethnic Albanians and agreed to NATO's terms. ``The
attacks will continue,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, Solana met with the Chinese ambassador to
Brussels to apologize for the accident. ``NATO never has and never
will intentionally target civilians,'' he said. ``The bombing of
the Chinese Embassy was a deeply regrettable mistake.''
</P>
<P>
   The errant attack on the Chinese Embassy also revealed a glaring
limitation of high-technology warfare. Even in an age of
precision-guided bombs, an air campaign can be no better than the
intelligence it is based on.
</P>
<P>
   The incident, which killed at least three and wounded more than
20, recalled the American strike on the Al Firdos bunker in Baghdad
during the 1991 Gulf War.
</P>
<P>
   In that case, the pilot also accurately carried out his
instructions. He bombed an underground bunker used by Iraqi
intelligence officers. But as a result of an intelligence failure,
the CIA had overlooked indications that civilians were also using
the shelter.
</P>
<P>
   The uproar over the Al Firdos attack prompted Gen. Colin L.
Powell, then chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff, to restrict
attacks against targets in downtown Baghdad.
</P>
<P>
   The allied strike against the Chinese Embassy raised the
question of whether there would be a similar letup in strikes
against the Yugoslav capital. But at the Pentagon, spokesman
Kenneth Bacon seemed to dismiss that possibility Saturday. ``I see
that there will be broadening attacks,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Since NATO's air strikes began 46 days ago, allied officials
have made extensive use of laser-guided bombs and satellite-guided
munitions.
</P>
<P>
   A major aim has been to take the war home to the Yugoslav
leadership in Belgrade while avoiding civilian casualties.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The strike against the Chinese Embassy was part of a broader
series of attacks against the Yugoslav capital. Friday's strikes in
Belgrade were the heaviest so far.
</P>
<P>
   They included strikes against the Dobanovci Command Complex, a
residence of Milosevic, which includes a bunker for his high
command.
</P>
<P>
   The Hotel Jugoslavia was also pounded. Allied officials say it
houses a barracks and command center for Zeljko Raznjatovic, the
paramilitary leader knows as Arkan who has been charged with war
crimes for his attacks in Bosnia. His gang, ``Arkan's Tigers,'' has
been accused of attacking ethnic Albanians in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Other targets struck in Belgrade include various Defense
Ministry buildings, an Interior Ministry headquarters and a
building used by Yugoslav's general staff, which has a satellite
antennas for military communications.
</P>
<P>
   Electrical transformers in Belgrade and Obrenovac were also
attacked. Along with additional attacks Saturday, the strikes
disrupted the Serbs' command and control, NATO spokesman insisted.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Still, the embassy bombing was a major political setback,
particularly since China has been a sharp critic of the bombing
attacks and holds a veto on the U.N. Security Council.
</P>
<P>
   The alliance has agreed to seek the Security Council's approval
for a settlement in Kosovo and the dispatch of a security force
there to protect returning refugees.
</P>
<P>
   The attack on the embassy also comes shortly after other
mistakes, including the accidental bombing of a marketplace and a
medical clinic in Nis.
</P>
<P>
   Since NATO's air strikes began 46 days ago, NATO's air
commanders have sought not just to pummel Serbian troops. By
targeting military ministries, command posts and communications
center in and around Belgrade, they have also sought to compel the
Yugoslav president to withdraw his troops from Kosovo and meet
other allied demands.
</P>
<P>
   A key condition, however, has been that civilian casualties be
limited. It is not just a moral concern. Allied officials have been
concerned that public support in the West would be undermined if
too many civilians are killed or hurt.
</P>
<P>
   NATO officials have documented eight mistaken bombings. Until
the strike against the Chinese Embassy, the accidents stemmed from
mistakes by the pilots, technical problems with the bombs and,
sometimes, plain bad luck.
</P>
<P>
   In the recent attack on the hospital, for example, an F-16, was
trying to drop an unguided cluster bomb on an airfield a mile away.
A NATO official said it is not clear whether the pilot dropped the
bomb too soon or wind was a factor.
</P>
<P>
   The embassy case was different. In this case the pilot
successfully hit the target he was told to strike.
</P>
<P>
   Even Saturday, there was substantial confusion about the
episode. Initially, NATO spokesman Jamie P. Shea said that the
aircraft had intended to strike a nearby weapons depot, known as
the Federal Directorate for Supply and Procurement.
</P>
<P>
   ``NATO did not intentionally target the Chinese Embassy in
Belgrade last night,'' Shea said. ``The wrong building was
attacked. This was a terrible accident. NATO deeply regrets the
loss of life, and injuries to Chinese diplomatic personnel or to
any other civilians in the embassy at the time.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-08-99 1311EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990508.0087 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-08 13:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9327 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TORNADO-REBUILD-TEX     05-08 1391
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TORNADO-REBUILD-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHORTAGES MAY DELAY REBUILDING IN OKLAHOMA
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By PETE ALFANO 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOORE, Okla. _ Like many residents of Sunrise Drive and
Northwest 21st Street, a quiet neighborhood that no longer exists,
Jody Alexander is sifting through debris where his house once
stood, searching for any personal belongings that would help his
family to start life over again.
</P>
<P>
   His working-class neighborhood was leveled by a tornado Monday
evening. By midweek, homeowners were marking their turf,
spray-painting their addresses and the names of their insurance
companies on their driveways or the walls of their homes, if any
remained. A few planted American flags in the rubble, giving the
quiet streets the look of a battlefield.
</P>
<P>
   Alexander, who is 28 and delivers vending machines for
Coca-Cola, is less fortunate than many of his neighbors. He has no
homeowner's insurance.
</P>
<P>
   ``I let my homeowner's lapse, and I don't really know why,''
Alexander said. ``We were saving money to go on vacation, and I was
thinking that when we got back, I'd get insurance again.''
</P>
<P>
   It has been six days since the killer tornadoes struck, and for
those left homeless, everyday life is temporarily on hold. As the
massive cleanup begins, even those with insurance may find that
going home will take longer than they expect.
</P>
<P>
   Moore's mayor, Glenn Lewis, estimated that rebuilding could take
from six months to a year. Almost a quarter of the 15,000 houses in
the town were destroyed. Hundreds more were damaged but are
habitable, according to local police.
</P>
<P>
   But the mayor's prediction may be optimistic. A strong economy
and a construction boom have created a nationwide shortage of
building materials and construction crews. Supply cannot meet
demand, and that is driving up prices.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a sheetrock shortage and brick shortage,'' said L.O.
Harrington, a home builder and insurance agent in Moore. ``It's
frustrating to say the least.
</P>
<P>
   ``The shock is just hitting. Builders won't be able to get
subcontractors to rebuild homes, because these people can make more
money repairing homes than working on new ones. I'm not sure what
the bigger problem is,'' Harrington said, ``a lack of materials or
workers.''
</P>
<P>
   Hap Lowry of Trinity Brick, an Oklahoma City distributor, said
the tunnel kilns that produce brick are running at full capacity 24
hours a day, 365 days a year. ``They can produce only so many
bricks a day,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm also wondering whether they're going to make it a priority
for people who lost their homes to get brick first or for those who
are having homes built and have been waiting for two or three
months,'' Lowry said.
</P>
<P>
   Raymond Feuerborn, co-owner of Blanchard Building Supplies in
Blanchard, said he had used his allocation of drywall by November.
</P>
<P>
   He said insulation, lumber and roofing material are also scarce.
Also, spring is the builders' busiest season, when most housing
construction starts.
</P>
<P>
   Some tornado victims may purchase new homes that were built on
speculation in the greater Oklahoma City area. But that may require
moving to another area, which some may be unwilling to do.
</P>
<P>
   Karen Farney, a spokeswoman for the Oklahoma City mayor's
office, said there is concern that a shortage of materials and
workers will enable unscrupulous contractors to victimize impatient
homeowners.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's why we are handing out packets to people at our
shelters and command centers,'' Farney said. ``We're telling them
to get three estimates and references, even from builders or
subcontractors from out of town.''
</P>
<P>
   She said that homeowners must be particularly about roofing
repairs, because Oklahoma doesn't license roofers.
</P>
<P>
   In Moore, a bedroom community of 50,000 south of Oklahoma City,
many tornado survivors are still too busy salvaging keepsakes and
remnants of their belongings to pay attention to such issues.
</P>
<P>
   Pamela Hester, who is 26 and has three young children, is more
concerned about safety. She told her husband, Shelby, that she will
no longer live in Oklahoma without a storm shelter. All that
remains of their rented home is a 4-by-5-foot closet in the master
bedroom, where the family hid as the tornado roared over them.
</P>
<P>
   In October, a much smaller twister cut a swath a mile south of
Monday's trail of destruction. That storm damaged 150 homes.
</P>
<P>
   Carl Watson, 74, has no intention of leaving. ``I've lived all
my life in Oklahoma, and we learn to get along with this,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   After a 15-year absence, his neighbor Sheila Meadows was
welcomed home to her native Oklahoma by October's tornado. Her
husband is in the Army, stationed in Kansas. She and her three
children survived Monday's tornado in their storm shelter.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have my three children and my dog,'' she said. ``I'll
rebuild.''
</P>
<P>
   Down the street from where Jody Alexander lived, Shelly Haygood
and her teen-age daughter LaShell are sifting through the ruins of
their home.
</P>
<P>
   ``Eight years ago, I had a house burn to the ground and lost
everything,'' said Haygood, 37 and a single mother. ``I learned
that things can be replaced.''
</P>
<P>
   She hasn't thought about whether she will risk losing a third
home.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is so much to do. I've got to hold the mail; I've got to
look to rent something,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``But it will be fine. Things will work out. And I imagine that
when all is said and done, I'll have a good cry.''
</P>
<P>
   Schools in Moore will open again tomorrow. Some tornado
survivors have already returned to work. But employers are flexible
and are giving their workers an opportunity to recover from the
trauma.
</P>
<P>
   Alexander has been given a month off with pay by Coca-Cola,
which has also offered free counseling for his family. South Winds,
a nearby apartment complex, has given him an apartment rent-free
for the first three months.
</P>
<P>
   He is married and has three stepchildren. They were looking
forward to the vacation planned for June in Red River, N.M.,
celebrating his first wedding anniversary. He said it would
probably have been the last he and his wife, Donette, could afford
for a while.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Alexander tried to be optimistic. One of his relatives is
a bricklayer who promised to help him rebuild if stays at 2200
Sunrise Drive. He is counting on assistance from the Federal
Emergency Management Agency.
</P>
<P>
   His mom drove 100 miles to bring a new set of dishes.
</P>
<P>
   ``And look at this,'' Alexander said, holding up a small plastic
bag filled with loose change that was buried in the debris. ``I've
got it made.''
</P>
<P>
   At a command center at First Baptist Church in Moore, insurance
companies such as Allstate, Farmers and State Farm had catastrophe
crews on site, parked in huge trailers. They sent claims adjusters
into the tornado-ravaged neighborhoods like commando units.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're already writing checks for $5,000 for living expenses,''
said Raleigh Floyd, a spokesman for Allstate.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is where we earn our keep,'' said Kitty Miller of
Farmers.
</P>
<P>
   Bulldozers cleared some debris, although the real cleanup will
begin within three weeks under the direction of FEMA.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for the Moore Police Department said that some
debris will be sent to a landfill in Oklahoma City. Some will be
burned, because the Moore landfill has too little room.
</P>
<P>
   As the rebuilding process begins, models are available for
Oklahoma communities to study. This year marked the 20th
anniversary of a tornado that swept through Wichita Falls, killing
45 and causing $800 million in damage.
</P>
<P>
   Charles Harper, an architect considered an expert on disaster
recovery, helped formulate the rebuilding plans in Wichita Falls. A
year after ``Terrible Tuesday,'' 85 percent of residential
dwellings had been rebuilt or were being rebuilt.
</P>
<P>
   Harper also worked hand-in-hand with his alma mater, Texas Tech,
to create in-house storm shelters, steel-reinforced rooms or
closets that are likely to become increasingly popular.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps Pamela Hester will live in a house with one. Communities
can be rebuilt, but memories of last Monday will last a lifetime.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was born here and raised here,'' Hester said, ``but now I'll
be horrified whenever I hear storms come.''
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
.MDBU/ nn
</P>
