<P>
   TOXIC-PORTABLES (Sacramento) _ The Department of Health Services
has taken no action on an 8-month-old report that warns ``there is
evidence that many schools in California have serious indoor
environmental quality problems, which are causing health concerns
in students and staff, reducing teaching and learning
effectiveness, and draining resources away from the schools' core
functions.'' The team of scientists and experts said portable
classrooms _ the fastest growing type of classroom in the state _
present a particular concern because they are constructed with
toxic chemicals and are air tight. By Terri Hardy. (Will move in
the ``n'' California news file.)
</P>
<P>
   PERSONNEL-PORTABLES (Sacramento) _ Only a smattering of school
personnel in Los Angeles County have been trained through a federal
program on how to keep the bungalows safe, despite growing concerns
that toxins used in their construction pose air safety problems,
the Daily News has learned. In the county's 80 school districts,
only 260 employees have gone through a program that advises how to
keep portables free of pollutants that can sicken children and
teachers, health officials said. By Terri Hardy. (Will move in the
``n'' California news file.)
</P>
