<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-08 13:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9333 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-CHINA-1     05-08 1152
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-CHINA-1,120(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THOUSANDS GATHER IN BEIJING IN ANGRY PROTEST TO AMERICA
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By ELISABETH ROSENTHAL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIJING _ Thousands of people massed in angry and sometimes
violent protests on the streets surrounding the American Embassy
here Saturday after Chinese learned on the noon news that NATO
bombs had hit their embassy in Belgrade, reportedly killing at
least three Chinese sleeping inside.
</P>
<P>
   University students aided by ordinary Beijingers took part in
large, orderly protests as well as feverish acts of violence,
throwing rocks through the American Embassy windows, pummeling cars
belonging to embassy employees and burning American flags.
</P>
<P>
   It was the largest anti-American demonstration in Beijing since
President Nixon's groundbreaking visit to China in 1972 and the
largest political protest since the student gathering in Tiananmen
Square 10 years ago. The protests in Beijing, and smaller ones
reported in Shanghai and Guangzhou, marked an extraordinary moment
in a controlled country where such demonstrations are illegal, and
almost never occur. At least early in the day, the Beijing
demonstrations clearly had some measure of government approval.
</P>
<P>
   Late Saturday afternoon, the American Embassy ``strongly
protested'' inadequate police protection, after student
demonstrators were allowed to press up against the embassy's
street-side gates and hurl rocks through windows of an office
building still holding 15 to 20 embassy staff members, including
James Sasser, the American ambassador.
</P>
<P>
   Police reinforcements arrived, but late this evening, about
1,000 protesters, some holding candles, burst through an arm-in-arm
cordon of unarmed police that had been created two blocks from the
embassy for protection. Pushing, chanting protesters shouting
``Don't protect the Americans!'' were rebuffed at the corner of the
embassy compound by five rows of armed police, but continued to try
to push past.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now we hate America,'' said Ma Zhang Lu, a 20-year-old male
student with shoulder-length dyed hair, who had just hurled a rock
at the embassy. ``China has been especially friendly to the
American people. But we have been rebuffed and now the Americans
have broken international law.''
</P>
<P>
   Virtually all protesters said they thought the bombing was
intentional.
</P>
<P>
   The protests began in the early afternoon when angry Beijingers
started gathering on the tree-lined streets in front of the
embassy. Around 4 p.m., they were joined by thousands of angry,
chanting students, mostly Westernized youths, wearing baseball caps
and Nike sweat pants.
</P>
<P>
   The Beijing students marched in groups of several hundred behind
their university banners carrying hand-painted signs, some in
English, like ``U.S.A. Nazi Killers'' and chanting slogans like
``The blood of Chinese must be repaid.'' Each group paused in front
of the iron gate at the embassy, just 15 feet from the embassy's
front door, to chant, sing patriotic songs and deliver a variety of
petitions.
</P>
<P>
   At first, an officer from the political section came out
solemnly to accept the petitions. But the protests quickly turned
violent, as students from several universities pelted the embassy
with rocks and water bottles. Each broken light and window was
greeted with thunderous cheers.
</P>
<P>
   Although most students returned to their campuses around
nightfall, many remained in the embassy district and by 9 p.m.
raucous students and ordinary Beijingers had regrouped near the
embassy, smashing cars with American Embassy plates, identifiable
by the red character for embassy, followed by the number 224. An
American flag was burned outside Sasser's residence.
</P>
<P>
   Although police presence was heavy, the officers, generally
equipped only with cell phones, at first did little to stop the
rock throwing, even allowing furious crowds to press up ominously
against the gates. As the fever pitch increased, reinforcements
were brought in and made some serious efforts, though often with
little effect. Police stood by as hundreds of protesters burned an
American flag.
</P>
<P>
   In the afternoon march, student organizations from about a dozen
universities arranged for buses, and students said that the Beijing
Municipal government had approved the protest.
</P>
<P>
   Foreign reporters, who are generally shooed away by public
security officers from even minor car accidents, were Saturday
given freedom to interview and photograph protesters. But the anger
was deep and genuine both from the students and the thousands of
Beijingers who apparently gathered spontaneously, many with
children, after they had heard about the protest from friends or on
the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a young Chinese I've always felt a very friendly attitude
towards the U.S. and its people,'' said Wang Bin, an interpreter,
who decided in the early afternoon to stand peacefully outside the
embassy in protest. ``But now I feel a deep internal disgust and
anger.''
</P>
<P>
   Chinese public opinion has been violently opposed to the NATO
war over Kosovo since the start of the bombing, in some part
because the government-controlled press did not report on the
Serbian purge of Kosovo Albanians.
</P>
<P>
   But most also agree with their government that Kosovo's internal
ethnic conflicts should not be solved by ``a foreign bully''
wielding bombs. Thanks to the bombing, they now regard Yugoslav
President Slobodan Milosevic as a hero for standing up to NATO and
the Serbs as an oppressed people.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday, the quiet head-shaking over the bombing gave way to
violent threats and anti-American outbursts. The American Embassy
warned Americans living in Beijing to increase personal security
and to avoid any student protests.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd always thought that Kosovo should be considered an
internal affair and that NATO shouldn't be there,'' said Guo
Qionghu, a student at the National Minorities University. ``But
today this issue has fallen directly on the heads of the Chinese
people, and that's why our emotions are so aroused.''
</P>
<P>
   The evening television news carried China's official
condemnations of the attack as ``barbarian'' and a ``gross
violation of China's sovereignty'' and featured the students'
demonstrations.
</P>
<P>
   The three known Chinese killed in the Belgrade attack were
identified as Shao Yunhuan, a 40-year-old woman and reporter for
the New China News Agency; Xu Xing hu, the resident correspondent
in Belgrade for the newspaper Guangming Daily; and Xu's wife, Zhu
Yin, an employee in the advertising section of the newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   In a bitter interview on national television, the chief of the
New China News Agency praised Shao as a ``good comrade and
outstanding reporter.'' The editor of the Guangming Daily said the
dead couple had only been married a year and that Xu's final report
had appeared in Saturday's newspaper.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Before being trapped in the embassy compound, Sasser had been
called in to the Chinese Foreign Ministry.
</P>
<P>
   In a country where there is often a huge divide between official
pronouncements and public opinion, China Saturday appeared to react
as one. Even before the protests, a Chinese Internet chat room
about Kosovo that has been popular in recent weeks was deluged with
vituperative messages, including ``Tonight, let's lay siege to the
U.S. Embassy.''
</P>
<P>
   Liberal Chinese who have supported engagement with the United
States called reporters with a deep sense of disbelief and
betrayal, looking for explanations.
</P>
<P>
   The student protest, which appeared highly organized, was at
first mostly nonviolent. Student delegations from China's most
prominent universities _ Beijing University, Qinghua University and
People's University _ marched in lines, waving red flags and
banners, chanting slogans like ``Down with Imperialism'' and
singing patriotic songs.
</P>
<P>
   Some students carried hand-painted signs condemning NATO or the
United States and wore targets like those worn in protest by
civilians in Serbia.
</P>
<P>
   The crowd turned violent when the group of 200 students from
Beijing Polytechnic turned onto the road that bisects the two
grassy office compounds of the American Embassy. Piles of rocks and
cement squares lined the sidewalks, which are being re-laid as part
of the campaign to dress up Beijing for the 50th anniversary this
fall.
</P>
<P>
   The building material along the narrow street provided ample
weaponry for the students in the dense crowd, who hurled the rocks
through the windows of the American Embassy's visa office and
administrative building just behind the fence.
</P>
<P>
   The embassy is a hodgepodge of older buildings in three
different sites, all within 15 to 20 feet of the road. The street
that divides the two main office sites, home to Saturday's
protests, has been closed to nonembassy automotive traffic since
the bombings in Africa last summer.
</P>
<P>
   But the diplomatic community has long regarded the compounds as
insecure and a task force empowered to review worldwide security
has regarded the embassy here as one of its top priorities.
</P>
<P>
   Police had clearly been girding since early in the day, when
they closed a nearby popular outdoor market, Silk Alley, where
tourists flock to buy Beanie Babies, Chinese qipao dresses and fake
Prada bags.
</P>
<P>
   But they were certainly unprepared for the outpouring of anger
that gathered throughout the day and into the late evening, when
thousands of angry protesters moved from the American Embassy to
the nearby British Embassy and on to the American ambassador's
house.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
