<SLUG> BC-BBO-SCOUT-TEXT-REVIEW-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BASEBALL SCOUTING REPORTS: INTIMATIONS OF IMMORTALITY 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Week in Review)  
 (NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For international clients' use by
special arrangement only. Asian and European points: contact Karl
Horwitz in Paris for details and prices (Phone: 47 42 17 11; FAX:
47-42-80-44). Latin American points: contact Olivia Vasquez in Los
Angeles (Phone: 310-996-0075; FAX: 310-996-0089)  
 (bl)  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Spring is the beginning of the baseball season for 750 major
leaguers, but for the scouts who scour the nation trying to locate
the next generation of players, this is their pennant race.
</P>
<P>
   The Mark McGwires and Ken Griffeys of tomorrow are dotted across
America waiting to be picked in the June 2 amateur draft.
Identifying them is the hard part. Picking future superstars is far
trickier in baseball than in football or basketball because the
players are younger (half of them are 18 and under), and even the
most seasoned collegians must spend several years in the minor
leagues learning the esoteric skills of the professional game.
Prospects turn to suspects with alarming frequency.
</P>
<P>
   Many of today's major league standouts were tabbed for stardom
in high school and college. Others overcame the scouts' doubts.
Following are excerpts from scouting reports filed on players while
they were unknown amateurs.
</P>
<P>
   _ By ALAN SCHWARZ
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN ITALICS HERE) Ken Griffey Jr. had been the talk of
Cincinnati's Moeller High School for two years when Roger
Jongewaard, the Seattle Mariners' scouting director, watched him
play in 1987. The Mariners held the No. 1 pick in the draft and
Jongewaard had to persuade his bosses that Griffey, a raw
17-year-old senior, was more attractive than a polished college
pitcher who could help the team more quickly. He did so in part
with this report, which rated Griffey a 72 on baseball's standard
20-to-80 scouting scale:(END ITALICS HERE)
</P>
<P>
   Trim, well-proportioned, young face and body. . . . Immature at
times. . . .
</P>
<P>
   Rare combination of speed/power/instincts. Smooth, fluid,
natural actions. Makes game look easy. Bat speed with HR power.
Centerfield arm and overall defense. ... Will show lackadaisical
play. Doesn't utilize outstanding natural ability all of the time.
...
</P>
<P>
   Similar style but much better than Barry Bonds at same stage.
Superstar potential.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN ITALICS HERE) Greg Maddux, an uninspiring 5 feet 10 and
155 pounds as a senior at Valley High in Las Vegas, had been rated
by many organizations as a fourth- or fifth-round pick for the 1984
draft. One Chicago Cubs scout wrote that he ``lacks overall control
on all pitches,'' which seems unfathomable today considering that
Maddux, now an Atlanta Brave, controls his pitches like a
marionette. Doug Mapson, another Cubs scout, convinced the Cubs to
gamble on Maddux in the second round:(END ITALICS HERE)
</P>
<P>
   I really believe that this boy would possibly be the No. 1
player taken in the country if only he looked a bit more physical.
He throws 86-89 [m.p.h.) consistently with very good movement.
</P>
<P>
   His movement isn't a gradual tailing type but a quick explosive
bat-breaking kink. He has a big league curveball right now although
he needs to be a little more consistent with it.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN ITALICS HERE)Randy Johnson was an enigma to scouts who
watched the left-hander pitch at Livermore High School in
California in 1982. Already 6-foot-10 but just 185 pounds, the
future fireballer threw 92 mph yet was all arms and legs with
little control of his body, much less his pitches. Joe McIlvaine,
the New York Mets' scouting director, watched Johnson, now with the
Arizona Diamondbacks, and came away intrigued but hardly
raving:(END ITALICS HERE)
</P>
<P>
   Timid due to awkwardness and plenty of room to fill out. ...
</P>
<P>
   No concept yet, just a thrower. Johnson is like a box of Cracker
Jacks, there's a surprise inside. Our only problem is whether or
not we will like the surprise. He's a boom or bust. Long way to go
yet. Has no pitching mechanics. ...
</P>
<P>
   With his long arms could eventually bury all left-handed
hitters. A real gamble.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN ITALICS HERE)It's hard to find anyone who thought Mark
McGwire was a gamble coming out of the University of Southern
California in 1984. The current St. Louis Cardinals home run king
led major colleges with 32 homers and left scouts drooling. One was
Chuck McMichael of the Kansas City Royals, who after filing this
report watched helplessly while the Oakland A's grabbed McGwire at
No. 10:(END ITALICS HERE)
</P>
<P>
   Very large frame, very strong. ... Consistent average to
above-average bat speed. Dominant top hand. ...
</P>
<P>
   Occasionally takes some pretty good-looking fastballs; may be
guessing a little much. Long swing, contact ability may drop the
further he goes. Breaking pitch away hurts him. ... Chance to hit
40 HR's + .275 for me.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN ITALICS HERE)Eight years later, McMichael coveted a rangy
17-year-old shortstop from Kalamazoo, Mich., named Derek Jeter:(END
ITALICS HERE)
</P>
<P>
   Gliding runner w/ burst-type acceleration. . . . very qk. feet,
very gd. lower body control. Arm strength to spare! Excellent carry
and can throw from all angles.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN ITALICS HERE) The Yankees took Jeter at No. 6,
disappointing the Braves' Tony Steil:(END ITALICS HERE)
</P>
<P>
   Slender, agile body with long arms and legs. Large feet. . . .
Outstanding infield instincts. Soft hands and strong, accurate arm.
Bat has quickness. . . . Makes contact with gap power. Will hit
occasional long ball. Comes to play.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN ITALICS HERE)Because the Cubs slugger Sammy Sosa grew up
in the Dominican Republic, he wasn't subject to the draft and could
be signed by any organization when he turned 16 years old. Omar
