<DOCNO> NYT19990508.0099 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-08 13:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9348 &Cx1f; var-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EVEREST-REVIEW-ART-NY     05-08 0887
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EVEREST-REVIEW-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EVEREST ACCOUTERMENT, THEN AND NOW 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Week in Review)  
 (NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For international clients' use by
special arrangement only. Asian and European points: contact Karl
Horwitz in Paris for details and prices (Phone: 47 42 17 11; FAX:
47-42-80-44). Latin American points: contact Olivia Vasquez in Los
Angeles (Phone: 310-996-0075; FAX: 310-996-0089)  
(ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
 (bl)  
 By DARYL ROYSTER ALEXANDER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Mount Everest, a brutal tower of subzero temperatures, sudden
blizzards and the thinnest air, gives up its dead grudgingly. On
May 1, the remains of the legendary George Leigh Mallory were
identified by an American expedition retracing his route 75 years
later.
</P>
<P>
   It had been Mallory who answered the question, ``Why climb
Everest?'' with the deathless, ``Because it is there.'' Mallory, a
38-year-old British schoolteacher, and Andrew Irvine, a 28-year-old
Cambridge student, disappeared on the northern slope in 1924,
leaving behind a mystery that endures to this day. Did they reach
the summit?
</P>
<P>
   A pair of snow goggles, a hob-nail boot and a length of climbing
rope were found with Mallory. And though the mountaineers of the
1920s also struggled with supplies and oxygen tanks, which were
thought to be unsporting, the content of their load differed from
that of the first successful 1953 ascent by Sir Edmund Hillary and
Tenzing Norgay. The equipment for the 1999 Mallory and Irvine
Research expedition weighed 3.5 tons, excluding more than 1,500
pounds of oxygen, according to Erin Copland of International
Mountain Guides.
</P>
<P>
   Today the assault on the world's highest peak is no longer the
lofty realm of explorers but a highly commercialized enterprise
managed by professional guides, including generations of Sherpas.
For $65,000 and more, relatively inexperienced mountain climbers
can join expeditions that take with them satellite tracking
systems, computers, cellular phones, Krazy glue, espresso machines,
M&AMP;Ms and Pop Tarts, and they leave behind so much detritus that
Nepal and China charge them princely sums for what may seem to be a
license to litter. So far some 600 people have reached the summit;
more than 150 have perished in the attempt.
</P>
<P>
   For those who just want an experience that does not put them in
mortal peril, MountainZone.com, an Internet sporting retailer,
maintains a Web site (www.everest.mountainzone.com) that provides
updated dispatches from the members of the current Everest
expedition while displaying souvenir merchandise like fleece vests
and prayer flags.
</P>
<P>
   Although advancements in mountain-climbing gear have made the
trip lighter over the century, teams now carry more and store their
supplies in camps strung out along the route to the
29,028-foot-high summit.
</P>
<P>
   For those still wistfully upwardly mobile, a sobering breakdown
follows of the equipment that separates the real (overwhelmingly
male) explorers of yesteryear from the antacid-eating, CD-playing
expeditioners of today.
</P>
<P>
   1924: GEORGE MALLORY
</P>
<P>
   CLOTHING: Several sets of woolen under-garments; flannel-lined
tweed knickers; balaclava, soft elastic cashmere puttees, wool
gabardine outer garments; fur-lined gloves; Tyrolean felt hats;
fur-lined motorcycle helmet, and a huge hand-knitted muffler.
</P>
<P>
   MOUNTAIN GEAR: Canvas tents and eiderdown sleep sacks; pickaxes
and a 30-pound oxygen rig.
</P>
<P>
   FOOD: Mainly local food like dried barley and yak-based
products; sardines, bully beef (canned beef), pemmican (dried
beef), condensed milk, cookies, 60 tins of quail in foie gras and
vintage champagne.
</P>
<P>
   MISCELLANEOUS: A Kodak camera, candle grease, safety pins and
aluminum cooking pots.
</P>
<P>
   1953: EDMUND HILLARY
</P>
<P>
   CLOTHING: A hooded down jacket; woolens including short-sleeved
vest, socks, long-sleeved sweater, plaid shirt, and long underwear;
down trousers; synthetic trousers; boots (average 3 pounds, 12
ounces in weight); three pairs of gloves in silk, wool and
synthetic.
</P>
<P>
   MOUNTAIN GEAR: 2-man 15-pound tents of cotton and nylon; 2 large
dome-shaped tents (200 pounds); 3 small ``assault'' tents, 8 pounds
each; 2 sleeping bags per climber; radio sets; high-altitude
cooking stoves; oxygen equipment; thousands of feet of rope, one
30-foot metal ladder; a 2-inch mortar for dislodging avalanches.
</P>
<P>
   FOOD: Boiled yak meat, tea, cookies, soup, sardines, canned
apricots, jam, honey.
</P>
<P>
   MISCELLANEOUS: A tree branch for hoisting the Union Jack.
</P>
<P>
   1999: CONRAD ANKER, MALLORY AND IRVINE RESEARCH EXPEDITION
</P>
<P>
   CLOTHING: Jackets, pants, fleece jackets and underlayers; down
suits, mittens, gloves, plastic boots.
</P>
<P>
   MOUNTAIN GEAR: Self-inflating sleeping mats; huge domed tents;
15,000 feet of climbing rope; kerosene camp stoves; solar power
panels; satellite communications system; VHF radio; hyperbaric
chamber (for altitude adjustment).
</P>
<P>
   FOOD: Instant dinners, Power Bars, Spam, squeezable margarine,
gummy worms, spaghetti sauce, pasta, Tabasco, smoked clams,
sardines, rice, lentils, cocoa.
</P>
<P>
   MISCELLANEOUS: Metal detector; sun screen; flag pole with
Nepalese, Chinese, U.S. and British flags and sponsor banners.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-08-99 1347EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
