<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-08 13:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9349 &Cx1f; var-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MILITARY-BOOKS-REVIEW     05-08 0973
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MILITARY-BOOKS-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FIGHTING WORDS BECOME BEST-SELLERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Week in Review)  
 (NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For international clients' use by
special arrangement only. Asian and European points: contact Karl
Horwitz in Paris for details and prices (Phone: 47 42 17 11; FAX:
47-42-80-44). Latin American points: contact Olivia Vasquez in Los
Angeles (Phone: 310-996-0075; FAX: 310-996-0089)  
 (bl)  
 By DOREEN CARVAJAL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The U.S. military-literary-industrial complex is gathering might
with the surprising success of new books that portray modern
warriors as complicated heroes who confront enemies and their own
mistakes with a mixture of courage and fear.
</P>
<P>
   Two nonfiction titles with these themes have climbed onto The
New York Times best-seller list recently despite having been
rejected by top publishers because of doubts about sales prospects
and potential readership.
</P>
<P>
   ``Blind Man's Bluff,'' which recounts the exploits of Navy
submariners who spied on the Soviet Union's harbors, was canceled
by its original publisher, Simon &AMP; Schuster, which had misgivings
about the potential for a book with a Cold War theme. ``Black Hawk
Down,'' a gritty account of the 1993 battle in Mogadishu, Somalia,
that left 18 U.S. soldiers and more than 500 Somalis dead, was also
rejected by large publishers.
</P>
<P>
   Both of these unlikely best-sellers were written by authors with
no military background who offered a sympathetic view of the
20th-century warrior and had a knack for tapping them as readers.
``Blind Man's Bluff,'' by Sherry Sontag and Christopher Drew, a
reporter for The New York Times, was eventually sold to a small
publisher, Public Affairs, while ``Black Hawk Down,'' by Mark
Bowden, landed with Grove/Atlantic, an independent publisher that
paid an advance of only $35,000.
</P>
<P>
   Other current nonfiction titles with military themes include
``Immaculate Invasion'' (Viking), by the novelist Bob Shacochis,
who spent 18 months with a team of Special Forces commandos during
the 1994 U.S. intervention in Haiti, and ``Rogue Warrior: The Real
Team'' (Pocket), an account of Navy Seal missions written by
Richard Marcinko, a retired Navy commander.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the ground for this wave of true-life military tales was
already claimed by best-selling authors like Stephen E. Ambrose,
with his histories of World War II, and Tom Clancy, the
techno-thriller pioneer. But there appear to be several forces
propelling the latest surge in military titles. For one thing,
authors are racing to record the stories of aging World War II
veterans. Elizabeth M. Norman, author of ``We Band of Angels''
(Random House), scrambled to track down elderly women to interview
for her account of American nurses imprisoned by the Japanese in
the Philippines after the attack on Pearl Harbor.
</P>
<P>
   ``We knew little about our parents' war,'' Ms. Norman said. ``In
middle age, we looked at the current state of our culture and began
to appreciate the enormous obstacles and challenges our parents had
to overcome to wage and win a world war. We also faced the reality
that our parents are old and dying and if we are to extract any
lessons, any details of their experience, we have to do it now.''
</P>
<P>
   Writers are also finding inspiration in the military's
contemporary internal debate about the role of the modern soldier
in regional conflicts _ warrior, humanitarian or a mixture of both?
Unlike much of the literature that emerged after the Vietnam War,
the current books seem to portray soldiers as thoughtful and
conflicted professionals carrying out shifting U.S. policy goals.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the post-Cold War environment, the military is a bit
confused and doesn't know who it is and is aggressively sorting
that out,'' said Shacochis, whose book explores the ambiguous role
played by U.S. troops in restoring Haiti's first democratically
elected leader to power after he was ousted in a coup.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of the Special Forces don't want to do humanitarian
stuff because they signed up for the adventure,'' Shacochis said.
``The idea of baby-sitting Kosovars or Kurds is rather diminishing
to their self-image. So the military is wrangling with this in a
rather fascinating way and they are reinventing themselves. They
understand that the wars of the future are now in places like
Somalia, Iraq, Haiti and Kosovo.''
</P>
<P>
   The military, in turn, seems fascinated by books that interpret
its role and legacy. As a result, writers who have never worn a
uniform are being feted by Navy submariners, invited to sign
autographs at the PX or asked to lecture to the CIA.
</P>
<P>
   After the release of ``Blind Man's Bluff,'' Ms. Sontag and Drew
embarked on an unorthodox stealth book tour to reach the wide
network of military veterans and retirees who might be potential
readers. Ms. Sontag said she collected about 5,000 e-mail addresses
from Web sites devoted to military groups. She then sent letters
announcing the book's publication and asked the recipients to send
the notes to others.
</P>
<P>
   That strategy helped lift ``Blind Man's Bluff'' onto the Times'
best-seller list for 21 weeks, capturing the attention of readers
like George Knudtzon, a retired submarine veteran. When Knudtzon
was told by his Barnes &AMP; Noble in Silverdale, Md., that there
wasn't enough interest in a book like ``Blind Man's Bluff'' to
schedule an author lecture, he rented the local community center,
enlisted his wife and daughter to bake cookies and held an event
featuring Ms. Sontag that he said drew almost 200 people.
</P>
<P>
   ``I gave copies to all four of my kids and to other folks that
I've known throughout my life,'' said Knudtzon, 62. ``And I
included a note saying that this is something I was involved with
that I couldn't talk about. This is why I wasn't home most of the
time when you were growing up.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-08-99 1348EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990508.0102 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-08 13:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6993 &Cx1f; var-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MILITARY-BOOKS-REVIEW     05-08 0973
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MILITARY-BOOKS-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FIGHTING WORDS BECOME BEST-SELLERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Week in Review)  
 (NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For international clients' use by
special arrangement only. Asian and European points: contact Karl
Horwitz in Paris for details and prices (Phone: 47 42 17 11; FAX:
47-42-80-44). Latin American points: contact Olivia Vasquez in Los
Angeles (Phone: 310-996-0075; FAX: 310-996-0089)  
