to overcome to wage and win a world war. We also faced the reality
that our parents are old and dying and if we are to extract any
lessons, any details of their experience, we have to do it now.''
</P>
<P>
   Writers are also finding inspiration in the military's
contemporary internal debate about the role of the modern soldier
in regional conflicts _ warrior, humanitarian or a mixture of both?
Unlike much of the literature that emerged after the Vietnam War,
the current books seem to portray soldiers as thoughtful and
conflicted professionals carrying out shifting U.S. policy goals.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the post-Cold War environment, the military is a bit
confused and doesn't know who it is and is aggressively sorting
that out,'' said Shacochis, whose book explores the ambiguous role
played by U.S. troops in restoring Haiti's first democratically
elected leader to power after he was ousted in a coup.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of the Special Forces don't want to do humanitarian
stuff because they signed up for the adventure,'' Shacochis said.
``The idea of baby-sitting Kosovars or Kurds is rather diminishing
to their self-image. So the military is wrangling with this in a
rather fascinating way and they are reinventing themselves. They
understand that the wars of the future are now in places like
Somalia, Iraq, Haiti and Kosovo.''
</P>
<P>
   The military, in turn, seems fascinated by books that interpret
its role and legacy. As a result, writers who have never worn a
uniform are being feted by Navy submariners, invited to sign
autographs at the PX or asked to lecture to the CIA.
</P>
<P>
   After the release of ``Blind Man's Bluff,'' Ms. Sontag and Drew
embarked on an unorthodox stealth book tour to reach the wide
network of military veterans and retirees who might be potential
readers. Ms. Sontag said she collected about 5,000 e-mail addresses
from Web sites devoted to military groups. She then sent letters
announcing the book's publication and asked the recipients to send
the notes to others.
</P>
<P>
   That strategy helped lift ``Blind Man's Bluff'' onto the Times'
best-seller list for 21 weeks, capturing the attention of readers
like George Knudtzon, a retired submarine veteran. When Knudtzon
was told by his Barnes &AMP; Noble in Silverdale, Md., that there
wasn't enough interest in a book like ``Blind Man's Bluff'' to
schedule an author lecture, he rented the local community center,
enlisted his wife and daughter to bake cookies and held an event
featuring Ms. Sontag that he said drew almost 200 people.
</P>
<P>
   ``I gave copies to all four of my kids and to other folks that
I've known throughout my life,'' said Knudtzon, 62. ``And I
included a note saying that this is something I was involved with
that I couldn't talk about. This is why I wasn't home most of the
time when you were growing up.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
