<HEADER>
A9353 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOAT-AROUND-ALONE-WIN     05-08 0834
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOAT-AROUND-ALONE-WINNER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ITALIAN SKIPPER OUTLASTS THE COMPETITION IN AROUND ALONE RACE  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Italy, Australia, S.C.)   By BARBARA LLOYD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The slapping sound of slack sails and a fluttering rig tend to
jangle the nerves of the most fervent yachtsman. Add to that the
tension of being within 100 miles of setting a record in a
round-the-world race, and you have Giovanni Soldini, the solo
sailor from Italy.
</P>
<P>
   It was like that for days last week _ just a whisper of a breeze
_ as Soldini struggled to make landfall in Charleston, S.C. But
then, late Friday, the wind came up. Soldini's 60-foot sailboat,
Fila, reared up like a stallion at a gate. Taking off at a brisk 16
knots, the lone sailor's wide, white racing yacht crossed the
finish line in the Around Alone competition at 1:32 a.m. Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was really, really hard, no wind,'' Soldini said Saturday
afternoon about his arrival. ``The miles were not so many, but the
time I needed to reach Charleston was getting bigger and bigger. I
was really happy, and I was surprised to see so many people and so
many boats out at 2 o'clock in the morning.''
</P>
<P>
   Not only had the 32-year-old Soldini won the fourth and final
leg of the 27,000-mile event, he also was first overall, beating
the Around Alone record by more than four days. It was a first for
an Italian solo sailor, a performance that toppled the 120-day
record set in the 1990-91 race _ known then as the BOC Challenge _
by Christophe Auguin.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond that, Soldini was hailed as a hero who had saved a life.
At the dock at City Marina in the early-morning darkness, a crowd
waited to greet the ebullient Italian. Among the onlookers was
Adolfo Soldini, the sailor's father. The father knew about being
becalmed in a sailboat. It was he who taught Giovanni to sail as a
youngster along the shores of the Mediterranean Sea. But now his
son has gone where his father never dreamed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gio told me that solo sailing is the cheapest way to navigate
the oceans,'' Adolfo Soldini said in a telephone interview from
Charleston on Friday. ``He said you don't need a crew, and you
don't need much else. I envy him.''
</P>
<P>
   It was last Sept. 26 from Charleston that the Around Alone
competition first began to unwind for 16 solo sailors. It was to
become a mental ride of hardship, boredom, elation and terror. But
in the end, it was Soldini who prevailed among the nine competitors
still left.
</P>
<P>
   During the third leg, on Feb. 16, Soldini rescued Isabelle
Autissier of France, a rival in the race. After a lonely and
dangerous search across remote waters of the South Pacific Ocean,
Soldini found Autissier crouched in an overturned sailboat hull
awash with water.
</P>
<P>
   Adolfo Soldini remembers the frightening episode with a touch of
humor now. His son, frustrated at not being able to rouse Autissier
that night by shouting, tossed a hammer at the boat's hull. The
bang let Autissier know help had arrived.
</P>
<P>
   But the hammer was not Soldini's first choice of a calling card.
Earlier that evening, the younger Soldini had sent an e-mail
message to his father in Italy, asking Adolfo if he remembered
where the son's hand-operated siren had been stowed on board Fila.
Giovanni knew that he might need it later that night. Where was the
siren?
</P>
<P>
   ``I was with one of Gio's crew, and we didn't know,'' Adolfo
said. ``Other crew had different ideas _ maybe under the bunk, or
in a boat locker. Then I remembered that they had thrown it away
before Gio left. But it was too late. He had already found the
hammer _ and Isabelle _ before I could tell him.''
</P>
<P>
   Adolfo watches his son's exploits with fascination and pride. In
the 1994-95 BOC Challenge, Giovanni made his global racing debut
and placed a close second to David Adams of Australia. The pair
engaged in a furious race to the finish in Class II, a division for
the competition's smaller 50-foot boats.
</P>
<P>
   In the current race, Soldini came back with a new and innovative
60-footer. The boat faced a highly competitive French contingent.
Among them was Autissier, overall leader before her mishap, and
Marc Thiercelin, a potential winner until his yacht's mast broke
near the rounding of South America at Cape Horn.
</P>
<P>
   Soldini, despondent after coming in fifth in the 6,884-mile
first leg from Charleston to Cape Town, upped his personal pressure
gauge. By Auckland, New Zealand, the race's second stopover, he had
finished a triumphant first. Even with the rescue of Autissier, he
was given a time allowance and managed to win the third leg. Then,
he gained an even stronger foothold on first when two British
rivals, Josh Hall and Mike Golding, were halted by gear breakdowns.
</P>
<P>
   The fearless solo racer, rescuer of others in distress, was not
always Soldini's profile. His father cheerfully reveals how his son
once hid under deck cushions during a particularly nasty storm on
the Mediterranean.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was not so courageous when he was 8 or 9,'' Adolfo said.
</P>
</TEXT>
