<HEADER>
A9358 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-CASUALTIES-050     05-08 1138
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-CASUALTIES-0509-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    ANALYSIS: RISK OF 'COLLATERAL DAMAGE' UNDERMINING NATO AIR
CAMPAIGN
 &HT;    With KOSOVO-WARCRIMES-0509; KOSOVO-REFUGEES-0509.
 &HT;    Moving in both (i) International and (w) Washington categories.
 &HT;    By BOB DEANS 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SPANGDAHLEM AIR BASE, Germany _ Her name is Sydney, she's six
years old and she wore her sky blue Barbie sweater last Wednesday,
waved a pair of American flags and even skipped a bit as the
pounding strains of ``Hail to the Chief'' echoed off the corrugated
steel walls of a cavernous hangar of warplanes.
</P>
<P>
   Even after President Clinton spoke about Kosovo to the U.S.
forces and their families gathered there, little Sydney admitted
that she, like most other Americans, knew little about the
embattled province of Serbia, Yugoslavia's dominant republic.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't even know where it is,'' said Sydney, whose mother
asked that her last name be withheld for security reasons. ``But my
Dad's in Kosovo. I think he's flying an airplane.''
</P>
<P>
   Then, with clarity more common among kindergartners than
commanders in chief, she explained exactly why her father is
piloting F-16 missions over Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's saving people,'' said the child. ``Those people are
trying to hurt others.''
</P>
<P>
   Like no other major conflict in history, the NATO air war
against Yugoslavia is being fought to save lives and combat
repression.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not because your country wanted to dominate another people or
control land,'' Clinton told U.S. forces at nearby Ramstein Air
Base, ``but because we want our children and their children to live
in a decent world.''
</P>
<P>
   With humanitarian, not strategic, goals at its core, the mission
is perilously undermined every time an allied bomb kills or injures
civilians, as has happened at least eight times since the bombings
began March 24.
</P>
<P>
   The latest such incidents _ inadvertent hits on the Chinese
Embassy in Belgrade and a hospital and residential complex in the
Serbian city of Nis _ are precisely the kinds of disasters that
have the potential to galvanize and even inflame global opinion
against the air campaign.
</P>
<P>
   More than 200 civilians, including ethnic Albanian refugees,
Serb children and, now, Chinese diplomats, have been killed and at
least as many others have been seriously injured in NATO strikes
like those that hit a passenger train in early April, struck a
refugee convoy a few days later and a destroyed a bus two weeks
ago.
</P>
<P>
   Those highly-publicized accidents of war pale in scope against
the atrocities being carried out far from the eyes of the world in
Kosovo, where civilians have been the targets of a military
campaign that has left thousands dead, by NATO's reckoning, and an
estimated 1.5 million homeless inside and outside the province.
</P>
<P>
   And yet, as the civilian toll from the NATO bombing mounts,
allies fear the alliance will come to be regarded as no less
villainous than Serb leader Slobodan Milosevic, the president of
Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   ``While we see him as a war criminal, when 70 people are blown
up on a bus and a bridge, 15 children, they don't see us as people
of virtue,'' the Rev. Jesse Jackson told NBC News last Sunday after
he traveled to Belgrade and secured the release of three American
soldiers from Serb captivity. ``So there is enough demonizing to go
around.''
</P>
<P>
   Rhetorical criticism, moreover, can quickly translate into
political and diplomatic initiatives in a global village where CNN
provides the electronic campfire and the United Nations serves as a
sort of world council.
</P>
<P>
   No sooner was the Chinese Embassy in Belgrade struck late Friday
than footage of the damage was beamed worldwide. Within hours,
China was denouncing the NATO campaign, which Beijing has never
supported, at an emergency meeting of the U.N. Security Council.
</P>
<P>
   That's the very body the United States and its allies are
counting on for support this week, of sending a military
peacekeeping force into Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   The civilian casualty count is being closely watched within NATO
itself. The 19-nation alliance is deeply divided over how
aggressively to pursue the air campaign, and each fresh civilian
death lends weight to the camp advocating caution.
</P>
<P>
   ``Democracies,'' said a Pentagon official, ``won't tolerate
limited warfare with civilian casualties.''
</P>
<P>
   That dynamic has been a major restraint on the air campaign,
which has been designed and prosecuted to minimize what military
officials call ``collateral damage.''
</P>
<P>
   That approach sharply limits a wide range of combat variables,
including the types of targets that can be hit, the bombs that can
be used against them and the tactics pilots employ.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have got the clear order to avoid civilian casualties and
that order we execute,'' the outgoing chairman of NATO's military
committee, Gen. Klaus Naumann, told reporters last week in
Brussels.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is deplorable that we hit this bus,'' Naumann said,
referring to last month's incident. ``We regard it as a mistake if
one civilian has been killed.''
</P>
<P>
   To try to prevent that, the NATO air strikes have relied more
heavily than any other conflict ever on the use of precision-guided
bombs, weapons steered to their targets by laser beams, satellite
information, video cameras, infrared-sensors, radio signals or
other means.
</P>
<P>
   Pilots, moreover, and the airborne commanders who help
coordinate their strikes, are under strict orders not to drop bombs
if there are doubts about the nature of the target.
</P>
<P>
   The result would make a statistician marvel.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, before Friday's bombs went awry, the Pentagon claimed
that 99.93 percent of the 15,000 or so bombs dropped on Yugoslavia
have not hurt civilians.
</P>
<P>
   People aren't statistics, however, and civilian deaths by NATO
bombs, even 0.07 percent of them, remain a moral hazard and a
political risk to the ongoing air campaign.
</P>
<P>
   The risks are heightened, in fact, as the campaign escalates
against an increasingly desperate foe who has, from the start, seen
civilian deaths as part of its aim.
</P>
<P>
   According to NATO, Serb forces have made it standard practice to
travel, when possible, with refugee convoys, and to hide tanks,
artillery and other military assets inside homes, near mosques or
around schools. Those tactics, in violation of the Geneva
Convention, deliberately place civilians at risk in an attempt to
protect themselves from NATO search and rescue missions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Collateral damage is too kind a word for what Milosevic is
doing to (Kosovar Albanians),'' said Brian Atwood, director of the
U.S. Agency for International Development, responsible for
overseeing American foreign aid to Kosovo's refugees. ``His central
plan is to use these people as weapons of war.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
