<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-08 14:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9360 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-WARCRIMES-0509     05-08 1364
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-WARCRIMES-0509-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    INVESTIGATORS DOCUMENT WAR CRIMES IN KOSOVO, BUT WITNESSES ARE
SCATTERING
 &HT;    1000&AMP;ADD
 &HT;    With KOSOVO-DIPLOMACY-0509.
 &HT;    By MARCIA KUNSTEL 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   KUKES, Albania _ For a week refugee Filip Kolgjeraj sat every
day outside the tent that was his hospital ward, smoking cigarettes
and waiting to get back the use of hands and feet swollen like a
grotesque Popeye caricature.
</P>
<P>
   He also talked to two sets of human rights investigators,
supplying details of the beatings he said Serb police
systematically applied with a rubber wand as they questioned him
for three days outside the Kosovo city of Prizren.
</P>
<P>
   The 43-year-old Kosovar Albanian, who doctors said could not
walk when he arrived, is a candidate to become a witness for war
crimes trials already being planned for when the NATO bombing
campaign against Yugoslavia ends.
</P>
<P>
   Kolgjeraj, however, has disappeared.
</P>
<P>
   Much improved, he walked out of the field hospital of a refugee
camp on Thursday and melted into the tens of thousands of Kosovars
swamping this city and dispersing throughout Albania.
</P>
<P>
   The mobility of the refugee population _ the people who are
victims as well as eyewitnesses to what has transpired in Kosovo _
is one reason prosecutions will be so tough. The refugees tell
their stories and then they scatter, and no one is keeping track of
where they go.
</P>
<P>
   Yet scores of people are trying to document the terror that has
happened and continues to unfold within Yugoslavia's embattled
Kosovo province every day. They can only hope witnesses they
identify will rise from the massive shuffle of refugee life.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're looking for the entire story. We hope that (war crimes)
prosecution is the end result,'' said Rufus Dawkins, an
investigator with the Organization for Security and Cooperation in
Europe (OSCE).
</P>
<P>
   His team of 75 monitors is in Albania to support relief
organizations, but a primary responsibility is documenting the
myriad reports of human rights violations among the 700,000 ethnic
Albanian refugees who have been driven out of the province.
</P>
<P>
   Groups including Medecins du Monde (Doctors of the World),
Physicians for Human Rights, Human Rights Watch and Medecins Sans
Frontieres (Doctors Without Borders) are compiling dossiers.
</P>
<P>
   The latter group has not waited for legal systems to grind out
conclusions, but recently finished its own study that asserted the
Kosovars have been forcibly deported from Yugoslavia under a
systematic and pre-planned policy.
</P>
<P>
   ``The crimes committed qualify as war crimes and crimes against
humanity,'' the report charged.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators from the Hague tribunal on war crimes in the
former Yugoslavia, the body that ultimately will try any charges
brought, also have been here to assess potential cases.
</P>
<P>
   But the tribunal has been widely criticized for its wan record
in prosecuting cases that arose since Yugoslavia began its violent
splitting apart in 1991, including cases from the conflict in
Bosnia in which all sides were accused of actions that violate the
norms of civilization.
</P>
<P>
   Out of 89 persons indicted, just one has been convicted and is
serving a sentence, according to the tribunal's information
service. One other pleaded guilty and has yet to be sentenced,
while five found guilty are appealing the verdicts.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps that is why so many humanitarian groups are so intensely
trying to preserve a record while events are fresh and people are
still around.
</P>
<P>
   ``We may talk to 25 or 30 people about an incident. We don't
deal with third- or fourth-hand information,'' said Dawkins, who is
from Killeen, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   He said the OSCE monitors are law-enforcement professionals with
extensive training in witness protection and human rights.
</P>
<P>
   Patrick Brook, head of the mission here, said forcible eviction
and theft are the foremost acts reported, followed by beatings,
rapes and killings.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got to get the places, the names, dates, time and if
possible the identification of the units concerned. If possible,
who the perpetrators were,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators look for multiple, corroborating witnesses to make
an overwhelming case.
</P>
<P>
   The doctors who sit at the border to treat emergencies and who
staff refugee camp clinics are another source of evidence.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are very aware and conscious to be alert and to record as
accurately and precisely as possible what has happened,'' said Dr.
Jean Francois Viel, medical coordinator of Medecins du Monde. ``Who
is injured? Do they know the person who beat them? We try to be
very organized about this.''
</P>
<P>
   Each day the doctors' reports are sent to the group's Paris
headquarters, which ultimately will decide what to forward to the
tribunal.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes the doctors find evidence of more complicated crimes
than shootings or sexual abuse.
</P>
<P>
   This past week, for example, Viel said the doctors saw signs
that Serb authorities had systematically emptied out a major
hospital in Prizren. They got the patients as proof.
</P>
<P>
   ``We could describe the ward cleared by the people we saw coming
over the border. It was very systematic clearing of the hospital.
One day it was the psychiatric ward, another the infectious ward,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   A four-year-old girl, for example, was brought across to Albania
having received four days of antibiotic treatment for meningitis.
She should have had another eight days, but was forced to leave the
hospital and the country, Viel explained.
</P>
<P>
   Doctors, nurses and pharmacists from the hospital also were
expelled. The United Nations High Commissioner for Refugees
reported that the refugees said they were plucked from the hospital
floor, driven to the border and told to leave. They did not have a
chance to notify relatives, much less pick up personal possessions,
they said.
</P>
<P>
   Does clearing out a hospital qualify as a crime against humanity
or violation of the Geneva Convention, which are among offenses the
Hague tribunal is mandated to prosecute? The lawyers will have to
decide.
</P>
<P>
   There still remains the question of whether reports from doctors
or investigators are hard enough evidence to make a case.
</P>
<P>
   ``You need the people as witnesses. It will be very difficult to
trace them,'' said Stafaan DeWolf of Medecins Sans Frontieres.
</P>
<P>
   His group is not, for now, forwarding information to the Hague
tribunal, but has collected its documentation for a broader
historic record. It also wants to mobilize international pressure
now on the Yugoslav central government to put an end to the ethnic
cleansing of Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   ``We defined that this is repeated, systematic abuse, not
isolated cases,'' said DeWolf. ``It was an outcry of our
frustration as well.''
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   Refugees like Filip Kolgjeraj may turn up again to testify some
day. He sounded like a potentially useful witness when talking to
Cox Newspapers in two interviews, taken after he spoke to both the
OSCE and investigators from the Hague tribunal.
</P>
<P>
   He seems to be one of the rare surviving cases of torture. And
he said he can identify at least two of the people who took him
away from his home and family on April 24 _ two days before his
wife's birthday. He knows times and dates and places, can recite
the questions he said the Serbian police asked him about the Kosovo
independence movement in between battering the palms of his hands
and soles of his feet.
</P>
<P>
   So what happened to him? Perhaps he simply wandered into some
friends in town and decided to stay with them. Maybe he found his
wife and daughter of 13, for whom he had gone searching that
Thursday he disappeared, and continued on in pursuit of peace. He
might have decided suddenly to join the Kosovar guerrillas
recruiting around Kukes for fighters. Possibly Serb undercover
units tried to undo a mistake made by letting him leave Kosovo to
tell his story.
</P>
<P>
   He might come back any day. Or he might be gone for good, like
others who carry with them the puzzle pieces that could help create
a picture of responsibility for a tragedy.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
