<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Sunday, May 9, 1999, sent to computer graphics clients of The New
York Times News Service. For information call: 212-556-4204.) 
(bl) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   One more day of low clouds, spotty showers and cool weather is
expected in eastern New England on Sunday, bringing the stretch of
unpleasant conditions to nearly a week. A complex warm front will
crawl eastward through New England, but should not move offshore
until Monday. Residual moisture associated with a weakening
disturbance at 15,000 feet over Ontario, Canada will circulate
clouds southward into the eastern Ohio Valley and Appalachian
Mountains. An isolated thundershower is possible in the higher
elevations.
</P>
<P>
   High pressure stretching from the central Great Lakes to the
eastern Gulf Coast will promote dry and seasonably warm weather.
Morning fog is likely in parts of the Southeast. A few
thunderstorms will erupt mainly over central Florida as a weak
disturbance over the central Gulf drifts eastward.
</P>
<P>
   A corridor of humid air will be transported into the southern
and central Plains. By late in the day, a disturbance aloft will
move out of the Rockies triggering thunderstorms from the Texas
panhandle to western Nebraska. Conditions may favor potent
thunderstorms in Kansas and northern Oklahoma this evening.
</P>
<P>
   Wet snow in the higher elevations and cold rain in the low
elevations will dampen northern Wyoming and much of Montana on
Sunday. Showers will spread across the northern Plains. Strong
winds from the northeast will enhance the chill in this area.
</P>
<P>
   The Northwest will be unseasonably cold, but dry. Cooler, dry
air will surge into California and Nevada on gusty winds from the
north. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Focus: Northwest Chill &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Early Friday, an inch of snow coated the ground in the lowlands
just north of Seattle as unusually cold air poured into the
Northwest. Snow is relatively rare in the lower elevations of the
Pacific Northwest to the west of the Cascades. The moderating
effect of the nearby Pacific limits the average seasonal snowfall
in Seattle to about 12 inches. Snow is even more scarce during May
as the more intense sun warms the lower atmosphere. Also Friday,
the high at Seattle only reached 48, the coldest high temperature
recorded on that date. It will stay cool in the Northwest this
weekend. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
