<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-CHINA-EMBASSY-740&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHINESE EVACUATE BOMBED EMBASSY IN BELGRADE
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By CARLOTTA GALL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   BELGRADE, Yugoslavia _ Chinese Embassy personnel were packing
up, loading up their cars and dragging suitcases across the
forecourt of their bombed embassy, still dazed and shaken after a
NATO raid hit the building overnight.
</P>
<P>
   The red flag of China danced gaily at the top of its pole and
crowds of people strolled in the bright sun to look at the damage.
But inside the compound, the stress and horror were plain. At least
three people died here and about 20 were injured.
</P>
<P>
   A young couple drove out in a Mercedes, the man biting his lip,
the woman next to him holding her hand over her mouth, her face
grimacing near to tears. Behind them in the back seat, they had
tossed suitcases, jackets and belongings.
</P>
<P>
   Special rescue teams were still going through the five-story
building, a police officer said. They had found the military
attache only at 8 a.m., and brought him out, bleeding from a heavy
head wound, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The building, a modern concrete-and-glass structure, only four
years old, was hit close to midnight local time. Daylight revealed
extensive damage, the heavy blue mirrored glass of the windows was
smashed, some of the lower windows blackened by fire. The acrid
smell of burning still hung in the air.
</P>
<P>
   The main building seemed to have been hit from two sides. The
left wing was badly damaged, the facade ripped off and the ground
floor thick with rubble. The second missile hit the back of the
building just yards from the separate building of the ambassador's
residence.
</P>
<P>
   Gas canisters and plastic chairs had been scattered wildly by
the blast, which left one orange canister skewered on the spikes of
the black iron fence surrounding the compound. The glazed tiles of
the decorative roof, with open-mouthed dragons on the corners,
remained intact, as did the wires of the embassy's communications
antenna on the roof.
</P>
<P>
   Local Serbian residents brought bunches of spring flowers to lay
on the compound wall and to wind through the railings of the gate.
``We are sorry for the poor people inside, not for the buildings,
but for the people,'' said Olga Grlja, who lives nearby. ``We have
some Chinese in our apartment building. They are quiet people, kind
people.''
</P>
<P>
   A fleet of glossy embassy cars drove up in a convoy, diplomatic
personnel from the other foreign embassies in Belgrade, arriving in
a show of solidarity. ``We have just come to express solidarity and
support from all the embassies,'' said the Russian consul as he
crossed from his car toward the embassy.
</P>
<P>
   Along with him were representatives from Brazil, Australia,
Mexico, Argentina and Greece. Most other Western embassies had
evacuated their staff from Belgrade before the the NATO bombing
campaign began.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a crime, an attack on a peaceful country,'' said the
police officer on duty in front of the embassy.
</P>
<P>
   Residents said the bombing was the heaviest they had experienced
in Belgrade since the beginning of the five-week campaign. It began
not long after 9 p.m. when air raid sirens sounded and the city was
blacked out as electricity failed.
</P>
<P>
   Four strikes hit buildings in the center of town: the federal
Interior Ministry headquarters, the Defense Ministry headquarters
and, across the street, for the first time, the Serbian government
building.
</P>
<P>
   Close to midnight, missiles roared in on the district known as
New Belgrade, a spacious area of trees and wide boulevards on the
south bank of the Danube where several embassies, hotels and
government buildings lie, along with modern high-rise apartments.
</P>
<P>
   The Hotel Yugoslavia, an ugly Communist-era hotel, was hit three
times, and one wing burst into flames. Workers were sweeping up the
debris this morning and carrying out the elaborate furniture from
the hotel's casino while the man who was one of NATO's targets,
Zeljko Raznatovic, better known as the notorious paramilitary
leader and indicted war criminal Arkan, stood by the entrance
giving court to foreign journalists.
</P>
<P>
   Arkan said he was a part owner of the casino along with an
Italian partner. The casino, however, was not damaged but one wing
of the hotel and the garage behind the hotel were. Dozens of rental
cars belonging to an agency working out of the hotel were wrecked.
</P>
<P>
   Arkan poured scorn on NATO, which managed to kill an old
pensioner lodging at the hotel, but failed to hit any military or
strategic object, let alone harm Arkan himself. ``They are very
precise. They said they wanted to hit me, but I wasn't here,'' he
said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Flashing an enormous diamond ring and a diamond-encrusted gold
watch, Arkan said his paramilitary force, known as the Tigers, had
never stayed at the hotel, nor had he. ``Only my football players
have stayed here before a match,'' he said, referring to the soccer
team he owns.
</P>
<P>
   It seems that the hotel managers had known the hotel was a
target. Marija, who worked for the car rental service Yu-Team,
based in the hotel, said the receptionists had warned her two weeks
ago to evacuate the hotel as soon as she ever heard the air-raid
sirens.
</P>
<P>
   In the center of town, the damage to the military and police
buildings was heavy. ``It was so heavy I thought the ground was
going to open up,'' said one police officer, who had been on duty
in the city center.
</P>
<P>
   A great hole gaped in the police building, where the top floors
had collapsed. Another wing behind the main building had also been
hit. Already burned out from previous strikes, the building still
smoldered. Farther down Kneza Milosa, the main street, the Defense
Ministry was ravaged, seeming ready to topple from a massive
internal blast.
</P>
<P>
   Across the street, the elegant, prewar building of the Serbian
government showed a wide gap in the top floors. The statues and
elaborate decoration of the facade remained standing; the green
copper dome of the center piece was intact.
</P>
<P>
   These missiles had found their targets with obvious accuracy.
</P>
<P>
   Bystanders gazed in awe at the extent of the damage as police
swept the glass and bomb debris and washed down the streets. People
walked their dogs or rode bicycles around to look at the damage.
Other residents wearily swept up the glass from broken windows.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's astonishing,'' said Milos Peskarevic, who lived in an
adjoining street. ``This was by far the worst attack we have had. I
am not afraid anymore, just numb. We don't even know anymore if it
is dangerous for us or not.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
