<HEADER>
A9368 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-MONTENEGRO-800     05-08 1099
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-MONTENEGRO-800&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AIR WAR HURTS STABILITY OF YUGOSLAV REPUBLIC   OF MONTENEGRO
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By ANTHONY DePALMA   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   CETINJE, Montenegro _ It was a beguiling promise, ``To Live
Better,'' that helped Montenegro's governing coalition win power
last year. But few people in this ancient city would say their
lives are better now than before.
</P>
<P>
   The sprawling OBOD electronics plant here, which employs 2,500
people, has been shut down completely since NATO's bombardment of
Serbia cut off the market where 90 percent of the plant's air
conditioners, washing machines and refrigerators were sold.
</P>
<P>
   The last time workers were paid was in February, and what they
received then was December's salary. With no money circulating,
small shopkeepers like Marko Stevov Kaludjerovic have had to extend
credit to so many people that they too are in danger of going
under.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then they can count me as another casualty of the war,''
Kaludjerovic said.
</P>
<P>
   The economy of Montenegro _ which is joined with Serbia in the
Federal Republic of Yugoslavia _ was already severely weakened
before the bombardment began. And although Montenegro has never
recognized Belgrade's declaration that a state of war now exists,
it has suffered several NATO bombardments that have shocked and
angered residents who thought they would be protected because of
Montenegro's fledgling connections to the West.
</P>
<P>
   Add to that volatile mix the economic disruptions and problems
sure to be caused by the recently imposed embargo on oil for Serbia
coming through Montenegro's Adriatic ports, and the stress
fractures challenging the tiny republic's stability threaten to
break wide open.
</P>
<P>
   Government officials here acknowledge the danger. They believe
civil authority is already being undermined by aggressive moves of
the Yugoslav Army in Montenegro and the agitation of opposition
forces loyal to Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   While it struggles to check the army's moves, the government of
Montenegro's president, Milo Djukanovic, fears an economic collapse
could undermine whatever support it retains. Unemployment has
soared to as much as 50 percent, and more than 60 percent of all
635,000 residents of Montenegro may be eligible to receive some
government payment of social assistance _ if the government has the
money to pay.
</P>
<P>
   Things will only get worse. The important tourism season has
been wiped out with the NATO assaults, and the closing of the major
Adriatic seaport of Bar by the Yugoslav navy means shortages are
likely.
</P>
<P>
   The government has appealed to the West for help. The United
States provided $10 million in aid last month to help the
government meet some salary and pension obligations, and the
European Union has promised $13.86 million to cover some of the
cost of caring for the thousands of Kosovo Albanians who have
sought refuge here.
</P>
<P>
   But the government fears the West does not understand the
urgency of Montenegro's problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unless we have more help,'' Vojin Djukanovic, minister of the
economy, said in an interview in the capital, Podgorica, ``there
will be a civil war here.''
</P>
<P>
   The minister, no relation to the president , a former deputy
prime minister of the federal government in Belgrade until he was
dismissed by Milosevic last May, said that pro-Milosevic forces
were using Montenegro's economic problems to foment dissent and lay
the ground work for a coup.
</P>
<P>
   He estimates it would take $100 million in loans and credits to
enable Montenegro to survive the current crisis without forfeiting
the democratic advances it has made since Djukanovic was elected
president in 1997, and his coalition won parliamentary elections
last summer.
</P>
<P>
   ``The tragedy of our day is that the West has been opening the
port of Bar, and now the Yugoslav army is closing it,'' Vojin
Djukanovic said, referring to Montenegro's main Adriatic port.
</P>
<P>
   The government's hope is that the people of Montenegro will be
patient, and not catch war fever.
</P>
<P>
   ``People in Montenegro are not living better, that's quite
correct,'' said Bozidar Jaredic, the government's minister of
information. ``But the majority of people in Montenegro can
understand the current circumstances and they can see the
government and Parliament are doing all they can.''
</P>
<P>
   While the people of Montenegro may not yet have reached their
breaking point, they are showing strains.
</P>
<P>
   Radojica Radosevic, a jeweler in downtown Podgorica, said
business has dropped by 70 percent since the NATO attacks began and
the shop he has owned for 25 years is now empty most of the time.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one has been receiving their salaries on time so people
just don't have enough money,'' Radosevic said as workmen installed
a new folding metal security gate over the front window of his
shop. He said it was a precautionary measure, against increasingly
desperate times. ``To be honest, I don't know much longer it can go
on,'' he said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Montenegrins joke that with the port blocked, the airports
closed and border crossings often slammed shut, their country _
long known for the stunning beauty of its mountains and seaside _
has become ``the world's most beautiful prison.''
</P>
<P>
   Few places though may be under as much pressure as Cetinje,
where practically every family has suffered because of the closing
of the giant OBOD factory.
</P>
<P>
   ``Since January, I've worked only 20 days,'' said Kice Pejovic,
a mother of two sons who has been employed at the assembly plant
for 12 years. She said the family survived on the food it grows in
a small garden, and the milk it gets from a cow it keeps nearby.
They cannot remember the last time any one of them bought clothes.
``It's very hard, and every day it seems to get worse,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   No one is suggesting that the NATO assaults caused all of
Montenegro's economic problems. The OBOD plant is 45 years old and
has never been modernized. Productivity is still measured on
Communist-era scales, and the product line has not been updated for
years.
</P>
<P>
   But Branislav Basovic, the general manager, said things would
have been much better if the West had not failed to take full
account of Montenegro's democratic opening.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, he said, the sanctions imposed on Yugoslavia
earlier this decade dried up the small, but important, export
market OBOD had developed with Western Europe and the United
States. Now, he said, practically all exports _ which constitute 90
percent of the factory's output when it is operating _ go to
Serbia.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
