u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BRITAIN-POLITICS-ASSE     05-08 0959
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRITAIN-POLITICS-ASSESS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANALYSIS: WILL THE BRITISH UNION PREVAIL, OR THE CENTRIFUGAL
FORCES?  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By WARREN HOGE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ With elections now completed for new legislatures in
Northern Ireland, Scotland and Wales, Prime Minister Tony Blair has
won the battle for a Britain with its politics radically
reconfigured to his own design.
</P>
<P>
   But he has also given power and legitimacy to forces in the
three parts of the United Kingdom of Great Britain and Northern
Ireland that are restive over their continuing relationship with
the fourth, England, and dream of full independence from London one
day.
</P>
<P>
   The question facing Blair and his view of a Britain freshly
fitted out for modern times is whether the distinct new political
structures that he has thrown up in Belfast, Cardiff and Edinburgh
help to buttress and maintain the union or work to destabilize and
ultimately dissolve it.
</P>
<P>
   The results of last week's elections in Scotland and Wales and a
similar vote in Northern Ireland last June confirmed that a
majority of voters in the so-called Celtic fringe want their
regions to remain part of the United Kingdom. But they also
installed as the principal opposition in the three places political
parties that have the breakup of the union as their final goal.
</P>
<P>
   In Northern Ireland, the Social Democratic and Labor Party and
Sinn Fein, the political wing of the Irish Republican Army, embody
the largely Catholic desire to leave Britain and become part of the
Irish Republic. The Scottish Nationalists are dedicated to creating
Scotland as a separate nation, and the Welsh nationalists, Plaid
Cymru, though far less committed to full independence, reflect
feelings that their culture is under-represented while Wales
remains tightly yoked to England.
</P>
<P>
   Blair was quick to seize upon the Labor Party's success in
gaining the most seats in the Scottish and Welsh legislatures and
to play down the appeal to voters demonstrated by the Scottish
Nationalists and Plaid Cymru (pronounced plyde KUM-ree), who have
produced a new landscape with some rough footing ahead for
traditional British politics.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe and I hope that out of these elections the union of
the United Kingdom will have been strengthened rather than
weakened,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   What is looming for Blair is a clash between two proven
instincts of his party _ a bent for keeping highly centralized
authority over outlying party members and its new commitment to
letting regional leaders and not bosses in London decide what is
right for their areas.
</P>
<P>
   This need to allow diverse opinions in its own ranks has emerged
in both Scotland and Wales where Labor failed to win outright
majorities and will consequently have to compromise objectives set
in London that are at odds with those of minority parties whose
partnership local Labor leaders will need in forming coalition
governments.
</P>
<P>
   Coalition governments are themselves a new phenomenon in Britain
and will become more common because of another Blair reform, the
use of proportional representation voting that gives more say to
minority parties and reduces the dominance of the two-party system
that has prevailed in Britain for most of the century.
</P>
<P>
   Meetings began this weekend in Scotland between leaders of the
Labor Party and its most likely partner, the centrist Liberal
Democrats, and an issue has emerged that illustrates the fraught
new brand of politics that has suddenly been introduced to Britain.
</P>
<P>
   As their price for cooperation, the Liberal Democrats are
expected to demand that Labor agree to end university tuition
payments in Scotland, an innovation that Blair put into British
life at some political risk in 1997. The 1,000-pounds-a-year
payments ($1,650) were put forward as a way of marrying the
promises of Labor to increase aid for education with its pledge to
hold the line on taxes. They also fit securely into Blair's
oft-stated philosophy that individuals must join in helping finance
services that were previously the sole responsibility of the state.
</P>
<P>
   If Blair is true to his commitment to devolution, the name of
his program of ceding powers long held by London to the new
regional parliaments, he will have to free Labor leaders in
Scotland to make a decision that clashes with cherished party
policy established in 10 Downing Street.
</P>
<P>
   The problem will not end there. How will the government
reconcile a situation where Scottish students get free higher
education while students elsewhere in Britain and non-Scottish
British students studying at Scottish universities have to pay for
it?
</P>
<P>
   The Welsh elections, which drew less attention than the vote in
Scotland, illustrated another quandary for New Labor and its
devolution policy. Plaid Cymru shocked Labor by winning 17 of the
60 seats in the Welsh National Assembly and defeating Labor in
stronghold mining and valley districts that have never voted for
any other party. Analysts attributed the showing to voters
protesting heavy-handed campaign tactics by the Labor Party
headquarters in London that convinced them that the party was not
really committed to letting the Welsh have a say in their own
affairs.
</P>
<P>
   As the new bodies get up and running, the exercise of new home
rule power could satisfy people that they now have real influence
over their public affairs or it could end up emboldening
nationalists to press their case for even more authority.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think we're seeing the breakup of the United Kingdom,
but we are seeing the breakup of a unified, centralized, simple
two-party UK system,'' said Prof. Anthony King of Essex University.
``Provided people are given a degree of home rule, they will be
content to stay within the union.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
