u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-INDIA-NUCLEAR-BAN-NYT     05-08 1144
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INDIA-NUCLEAR-BAN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INDIA'S CHANCES OF SIGNING THE NUCLEAR TEST BAN APPEAR TO FADE  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By CELIA W. DUGGER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW DELHI, India _ A year after India and Pakistan sent tremors
of anxiety around the world by conducting nuclear tests, the
once-strong likelihood that India would soon sign the nuclear test
ban treaty faded this week to a very faint possibility.
</P>
<P>
   The Hindu nationalist-led government, which appeared to be
headed toward signing the treaty, narrowly lost a confidence vote
last month after only a year in office. It now faces a general
election in late September that coincides with an informal but
politically crucial deadline for adopting the treaty, which would
ban all nuclear testing.
</P>
<P>
   Leaders of the fallen government and its chief rival, the
Congress Party, said in interviews last week that they were very
pessimistic about the prospects for India signing the treaty before
the election.
</P>
<P>
   The political instability in India _ and the diminished
prospects for its signing the Comprehensive Test Ban Treaty _ may
undermine Pakistan's resolve to sign, as well. American diplomats,
who have been trying to persuade India and Pakistan to sign, say
the treaty is a crucial step to halt the spread of nuclear weapons.
</P>
<P>
   Pakistan and India have fought three wars since 1947. They
engaged in tit-for-tat nuclear tests last May, and in tit-for-tat
tests of ballistic missiles that can carry nuclear warheads last
month.
</P>
<P>
   Pakistan's Foreign Minister, Sartaj Aziz, said in a telephone
interview that if India did not sign the treaty it would become
more difficult for Pakistan to follow through on plans to sign if
the United States lifts all sanctions imposed after the nuclear
tests. ``So far, we have not changed our formal position,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   The test ban treaty faces obstacles not only in India, but in
the United States as well, where there is stiff Republican
opposition in the Senate. Neither China nor Russia has ratified the
treaty yet, either.
</P>
<P>
   The treaty ``is in big, big trouble in Washington, which also
means in Moscow and Beijing,'' said George Perkovich, director of
the Secure World Program at the W. Alton Jones Foundation in
Charlottesville, Va. ``India and Pakistan not having signed deepens
the trouble, but does not cause it.''
</P>
<P>
   Under the terms of the treaty, the United States, India and
Pakistan, along with 41 other specified countries, must sign and
ratify the treaty before it can take effect. But so far only 17
have done so. The countries that have agreed are supposed to meet
to decide how to proceed if the treaty has not won the required
signatures by Sept. 24, three years after the treaty was open for
ratification.
</P>
<P>
   Administration officials are now husbanding their political
capital to build support for the NATO campaign against Yugoslavia
and to deal with criticism of how the administration handled
accusations of nuclear espionage by China. They may have little
left over to spend on getting the test ban treaty through the
Senate, nuclear analysts say.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. officials had hoped a decision by India and Pakistan to
sign the treaty this summer would have helped to give it momentum.
</P>
<P>
   They worry that if approval is delayed into next year, the
United States will be in the midst of a presidential election
campaign, and President Clinton, a leading proponent of the treaty,
will be a lame duck without much leverage in the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   The Indians are facing a similar political problem right now.
</P>
<P>
   Prime Minister Atal Behari Vajpayee, a lame duck after only 14
months in office, said in recent interviews with news magazines
that it would be improper to sign the treaty before the election
unless he was able to build a consensus that includes the
opposition, led by the Congress Party. ``But I don't have much
hopes since we are in the midst of a do-or-die election,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   His pessimism appears well grounded. K. Natwar Singh, chief
foreign policy spokesman for the Congress Party, said Vajpayee's
government had not kept the opposition well informed about the
details of its talks with the United States on nuclear issues. He
said there was ``no chance at all'' that Congress would support
signing the treaty before elections.
</P>
<P>
   In another interview on Wednesday, Singh was a little less
categorical, but still insisted the Congress Party was unlikely to
support a decision to sign the treaty, especially if the campaign
turns ``vicious and personalized.''
</P>
<P>
   Since India conducted nuclear tests a year ago, American
officials have invested heavily in diplomatic efforts to persuade
India to sign the treaty. Deputy Secretary of State Strobe Talbott
has held eight rounds of talk with Foreign Minister Jaswant Singh.
</P>
<P>
   Karl F. Inderfurth, assistant secretary of state for South Asia,
said the United States still hoped the Vajpayee government and the
Congress Party would find common ground on the treaty before the
election.
</P>
<P>
   ``We recognize the difficulty of moving forward with the CTBT
between now and the election, but we would hope the caretaker
government and the opposition would continue to see if steps could
be taken,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   One senior State Department official said he hoped that progress
made in building closer ties between the United States and India
did not also get lost in India's political turmoil. ``Otherwise,
we're in danger of once again being ships passing in the night,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Relations between the United States and India may become more
contentious on nuclear issues if the Congress Party heads the
government.
</P>
<P>
   Singh, the Congress Party leader and a former foreign minister,
said the Congress Party was not willing to give up its demand that
the United States and the other major nuclear powers agree to take
steps toward disarmament within a defined time frame. Only then, he
said, would India agree to sign the test ban treaty.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why should we drop it?'' he said. ``They can go on having more
and more sophisticated experiments in their nuclear labs and there
are enough loopholes in the CTBT for the P-5 to do so.'' The P-5
are the five permanent members of the U.N. Security Council, all
nuclear powers: the United States, Russia, China, Britain and
France.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile Pakistan is watching the political situation in India.
If the Congress Party wins, they wonder what will happen to the
efforts to improve relations begun by Prime Minister Nawaz Sharif,
and reciprocated by Vajpayee.
</P>
<P>
   After Pakistan's foreign minister, Aziz, listened to a
description of what Singh of the Congress Party had said about the
test ban treaty, he said, ``Did he say anything about continuing
the dialogue?''
</P>
<P>
   When Aziz's question was posed to him, Singh replied: ``Most
certainly we'll talk to Pakistan. We'll want to strengthen our
relations with Pakistan.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
