<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-U.N.-CHINA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SECURITY COUNCIL MEMBERS EXPRESS SHOCK AT BOMBING OF EMBASSY
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By JACQUES STEINBERG   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS _ China convened a rare overnight session of the
Security Council early Saturday and condemned the NATO bombing of
its embassy in Belgrade as a ``flagrant attack'' that it said
constituted a ``crime of war and should be punished.''
</P>
<P>
   Members of the Security Council, as well as about a half-dozen
representatives of other countries, variously condemned the bombing
or expressed their sympathies to the Chinese. But China failed to
persuade the council to adopt a statement condemning the bombing as
a ``serious violation of international law.''
</P>
<P>
   The bombing, for which NATO took responsibility and expressed
``regret,'' left three people dead, with one person still missing,
and badly damaged the embassy building at about midnight in
Belgrade.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even in times of war,'' said the Chinese delegate here, Qin
Huasun, addressing the emergency meeting of the council at 3:45
a.m., ``it is internationally recognized that the diplomatic
institutes should not be violated and that diplomats should be
protected.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We reserve our right for taking further actions,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan, speaking to reporters briefly
in Washington later Saturday morning before addressing graduates at
the Howard University commencement, said he was ``rather shocked''
about the damage to the embassy.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a reason for continuing peace talks,'' he said. ``I
hope it will not unduly complicate our search for peace.''
</P>
<P>
   However, he added: ``Obviously it is not going to make matters
easy.''
</P>
<P>
   Overnight, the acting American representative, Peter Burleigh,
said that the causes of the bombing, which NATO said was a mistake,
were being investigated. ``NATO would never target civilians,'' he
said, ``and NATO would never target an embassy.''
</P>
<P>
   Burleigh urged the council members to keep their eyes fixed on
``the big picture'' and said that ultimate blame for the casualties
lay with Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   ``We worked for months and months and months on a negotiated
settlement with Milosevic,'' Burleigh said. ``He never agreed. And
as the world knows, he triggered a humanitarian catastrophe.''
</P>
<P>
   The delegates met for three hours behind closed doors, and then
for an 80-minute open session. But no clear consensus on the NATO
air campaign emerged from their statements.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the council president, Ambassador Denis Dangue Rewaka
of Gabon, emerged from the closed portion of the session at 3:20
a.m., rubbing his eyes, to report that the council members
``expressed their shock and concern over the casualties and
damage'' and ``expressed their sympathy and condolences to the
Chinese government and the families of the victims.''
</P>
<P>
   Several of the diplomats who spoke at the council's circular
wooden table Saturday morning took pains to alienate neither the
United States nor China, which could wield veto power to block any
peacekeeping initiative by the council, as Russia, the United
States, Japan and five other nations have reached a fragile
agreement on the need for an international force to protect Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   ``We share our colleagues' distress and concern,'' said Jeremy
Greenstock, the British ambassador. ``This is a thoroughly
unpleasant crisis.''
</P>
<P>
   But Russian Ambassador Sergei V. Lavrov did not hesitate to
bludgeon NATO, of which Russia is not a member, condemning what he
called its ``unconscionable activities'' and ``military
adventurism'' in Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every day,'' Lavrov said, ``we hear reports of further
civilian casualties.''
</P>
<P>
   The Yugoslav ambassador, Vladislav Jovanovic, who has no seat on
the council but was permitted by the council president to speak,
cast the destruction of the Chinese Embassy as the latest instance
of ``illegal and brutal aggression'' by NATO. He characterized the
NATO strategy as ``hit anything, any time, anywhere.''
</P>
<P>
   For Cuba and Iraq, two longtime rivals of the United States who
also attended the meeting overnight, the bombing offered an
opportunity to vent their own anger.
</P>
<P>
   The Iraqi ambassador, Saeed Hasan, called NATO's ``targeting''
of the Chinese Embassy a ``barbaric act which violates the charter
of the United Nations.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Who knows which of the peoples of the third world will be the
next victims,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Cuban ambassador, Bruno Rodriguez Parrilla, said he saw
little need for a NATO inquiry into the attack.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is no accident, but rather an act of aggression,'' he said.
``There is not much to investigate.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
