<HEADER>
A9373 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SYRIA-ASSAD-ART-2TAKE     05-08 1155
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SYRIA-ASSAD-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SYRIAN PRESIDENT POSITIONS SON AS HIS SUCCESSOR 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: A map is being sent. Non-subscribers can purchase by
calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(DW) 
 By DOUGLAS JEHL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAMASCUS, Syria _ As Syrians turned out by the millions in
February to re-elect their leader of 29 years to another seven-year
term, the chant reverberating through this capital was ``Assad,
Assad forever!''
</P>
<P>
   But Hafez al-Assad turns 70 this year, and he is looking frail.
At times, his manner has seemed vacant, visitors say. Twice in the
last six months, he has canceled speeches to Parliament. His focus,
diplomats here say, has turned to smoothing the way for his son,
Bashar, to succeed him.
</P>
<P>
   Asked to describe Assad's agenda, a Western diplomat said: ``One
word: succession. It has become the filter through which everything
is filtered.''
</P>
<P>
   With the Clinton administration having vowed to try again in the
months ahead to promote peace between Syria and Israel, Assad's
fixation on succession has left some diplomats here concerned. They
say they worry that he may be less willing to make concessions out
of concern that domestic criticism would rebound against his son.
Still, if Assad is indeed feeling his years, the diplomats say, it
is conceivable that he might prove eager to secure peace as his
legacy.
</P>
<P>
   Assad has suffered from heart trouble and diabetes, and he
underwent a prostate operation in 1997. He was said to have been
suffering from flu in December, when his address to Parliament was
canceled with just 30 minutes' notice, and from hoarseness in
February, when he canceled another speech.
</P>
<P>
   On the latter occasion, he traveled to the Parliament anyway to
accept members' congratulations for his election. But otherwise, he
has rarely been seen in public.
</P>
<P>
   ``You remember that image of him as a kind of sphinx, with a
chessboard in his head?'' one diplomat said. ``If you saw him now,
you wouldn't think that.''
</P>
<P>
   There have been indications that Assad was testing Bashar, 34,
as a successor for at least two years. A British-trained
ophthalmologist, Bashar al-Assad returned to Syria in 1994, after
the death of his brother, Basel, then the heir apparent, in a car
accident.
</P>
<P>
   Bashar was plunged into a military career, and by 1997, his face
began to appear on posters that hailed Basel as ``The Example'' and
Bashar as ``The Future.''
</P>
<P>
   The president moved last year to eliminate two of Bashar's
potential rivals, dismissing Assad's wayward brother, Rifaat, from
his post as one of Syria's three vice presidents, and then
dismissing the army chief of staff, Gen. Hikmat Shehabi. Neither
man was said to get along well with Bashar.
</P>
<P>
   He then promoted Bashar for the fourth time in five years,
making him a full army colonel and putting him in charge of
relations with neighboring Lebanon, where Syria is the main power
broker. That job had been the preserve of another vice president,
Abdel Halim Khaddam.
</P>
<P>
   Behind the scenes, Syrians and Western diplomats say, the Syrian
leader has begun to promote army and intelligence officers loyal to
Bashar, creating what could prove an important power base.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Assad has remained cautious. Under the 1973 Constitution,
it is the governing Baath Party that has the power to nominate a
successor, and diplomats say Assad is aware that some of its
members harbor doubts about whether Bashar is prepared to be a
national leader.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think anyone thinks he's ready,'' a Western diplomat
said of Bashar al-Assad. As long as such opposition persists,
diplomats say, the president's death could set off a struggle for
power.
</P>
<P>
   The issue of succession is a delicate one in Syria, in large
part because Assad, a former air force pilot, has maintained since
taking power in a 1970 coup that the choice of Syria's leaders is
up to the people. When asked by a French reporter last year whether
he wanted his son to succeed him, Assad answered vaguely, saying
only that his son had as much right to be active in politics as any
other Syrian.
</P>
<P>
   Bashar has been similarly coy. In an interview in February with
a Lebanese newspaper, he insisted that he was not seeking ``any
official position.'' But, he added: ``If the party command or the
rank and file call on my services to fill a certain position, I
will not say no. I am ready.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Bashar has begun to assume greater responsibilities,
traveling to Jordan in March, to meet with King Abdullah, 37, who
in February succeeded his father, the late King Hussein.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an exam or a test for Bashar to prove himself,''
Mounzer Moussly, an Assad loyalist and member of Parliament, said
of the young man's expanding portfolio. ``But I think he looks as
if he's sure of himself, and his father is sure of him.''
</P>
<P>
   The sense that a transition is under way has reached the point
that many in Damascus have predicted a show of acclamation in
support of Bashar. This would amount to an orchestrated outpouring
in which people took to the streets to demand that Bashar be given
more power and perhaps even elevated to the post left vacant when
Rifaat was dismissed.
</P>
<P>
   But some Syrians, including Riad Seif, another member of
Parliament, criticize the idea of such a spectacle. He said the
display would be seen as ``silly and old-fashioned,'' like the
weeks of staged tributes this year to celebrate the re-election of
Assad, the only candidate.
</P>
<P>
   Still, even people like Seif are careful to say the affection
for Assad and his son is genuine.
</P>
<P>
   One obstacle to Bashar al-Assad's taking power is the fact that,
under the Constitution, a president must be 40 years old, an age
Bashar will not reach until 2005. But an effort to amend the
Constitution could find support, diplomats say, particularly if
Bashar al-Assad first proved his mettle on the Baath Party's main
policy-making body, to which he is expected to be elevated sometime
this year.
</P>
<P>
   People who have met Bashar describe him as a quiet, thoughtful
bachelor who wanted to pursue a career in medicine. But his return
to Syria was followed by a rapid switch.
</P>
<P>
   By late 1994, he had graduated as a captain from the Military
Academy at Homs after a course as a tank battalion commander.
Within two months, he was a major in the Presidential Guards,
continuing his brother Basel's fight against corruption. In 1997 he
became a lieutenant colonel and commander of the Republican Guards,
and last year he was elevated to staff colonel.
</P>
<P>
   He leads Syria's computer society. His associates say that
during his time in London, he developed an affection for the West.
</P>
<P>
   In the February interview, with the Beirut newspaper Al-Kifah
Al-Arabi, however, he sounded much like his father in criticizing
the decisions by Egypt, Jordan and the Palestinians to make peace
with Israel.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Bashar was never as popular as his brother, a champion horseman
and military man whose dashing bearded figure is still seen on
posters around Damascus.
</P>
<P>
   For years, prominent Syrians have expressed doubt that he would
have the toughness to stand up to people like his uncle, Rifaat,
who led tanks into the streets in a 1984 coup attempt against his
brother and, though exiled for a time, was never stripped of his
vice presidential post.
</P>
<P>
   But the removal of Rifaat and Shehabi, who for 27 years had been
the chief of staff, may have eliminated two obstacles. At the same
time, diplomats say, Bashar has begun to cement alliances,
including one with Assef Shawket, the deputy chief of Military
Intelligence, who is married to his sister, Bushra.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
