<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-08 14:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9375 &Cx1f; tad-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COKE09-COX     05-08 1012
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COKE09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Coke debate: Fight or settle?
 &HT;    By David McNaughton
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The advice may be hard to swallow, but some crisis
managers and marketing specialists suggest Coca-Cola should settle
an employment discrimination lawsuit filed against the company.
</P>
<P>
   One former and three current employees sued April 22 in federal
court in Atlanta, charging the company discriminated against
African-Americans in pay, promotions, evaluations and terminations.
They also seek class-action status, which would raise the stakes
considerably for both sides.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the most important thing is that a company take a look
at what we call its trust bank, or how likable it is,'' said Eric
Dezenhall, a crisis manager and a founder of Nichols-Dezenhall
Communications Group in Washington. ``A company like Coca-Cola is
an extremely likable company.
</P>
<P>
   ``The general rule of thumb (for companies) with a high trust
bank is to keep it out of the news and settle it promptly,''
Dezenhall said.
</P>
<P>
   Coca-Cola, which has not filed a legal response to the suit,
says it would be premature to comment on the issues, including on
the debate whether it would be more advantageous to fight or
settle.
</P>
<P>
   But in fact, attorneys say, most employment discrimination suits
are not resolved by trial, particularly class-action ones.
</P>
<P>
   ``If class action gets certified, generally they work out some
means of trying to settle,'' said Max G. Brittain Jr., a Chicago
attorney who specializes in employment law. ``The downside of going
through with the lawsuit is that the connection between Coca-Cola
and racism gets played over and over,'' said Pam Scholder Ellen, an
associate professor of management at Georgia State University who
specializes in marketing and advertising. ``In the long run, it may
not be worth the negative publicity.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the easiest way is to settle,'' offered Asterios G.
Kefalas, a management professor at the University of Georgia and a
Coca-Cola shareholder. The benefit of doing so, he said, is that it
gets ``all the bad publicity off your back.''
</P>
<P>
   Not so fast, argued Martin R. Stoller, a professor of
organizational behavior at Northwestern University in Evanston,
Ill.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why capitulate the moral high ground unless there is clear and
compelling evidence you don't deserve it?'' asked Stoller, who has
helped defend companies in employment-related litigation. ``A
vigorous defense of your innocence is my advice.''
</P>
<P>
   Stoller added, however, it is ``rare'' for a company to mount a
proactive defense like the one put on by Johnson &AMP; Johnson during
the Tylenol poisoning scare of 1982.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, he said, ``the company will leap on its own sword
without being pushed.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The goal of good crisis management is to fight on the
territory between what you did and how deliberately you are alleged
to have done it,'' Stoller said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Settlement is the safest course of action from a legal
standpoint,'' advised Ian I. Mitroff, a professor of business
policy at the University of Southern California and founder of the
school's Center for Crisis Management.
</P>
<P>
   If a company defends itself, it needs to be ``squeaky clean, or
you're going to make the crisis worse,'' Mitroff said. If the
allegations are not true and the defendant has hard facts to prove
they aren't, ``I would come out blasting.''
</P>
<P>
   The suit alleges a companywide pattern of discrimination, a
charge Coca-Cola Chairman M. Douglas Ivester has denied to
employees. He also issued a statement saying the lawsuit is without
merit.
</P>
<P>
   ``Discrimination at the Coca-Cola Co. is not tolerated,''
Ivester said in an e-mail to employees. ``If discrimination is
alleged, we investigate it. If we find it, we act to stop it.''
</P>
<P>
   Companies that find themselves under attack have to deal with
two courts, Mitroff said. One is the actual legal system, and the
other is public opinion.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even if you are not guilty, in the court of public opinion,
the burden of proof is on you,'' Mitroff said. He added that a
company has to ask itself, ``What's going to do the least damage?''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, calculating the long-range impact of publicity goes
into formulating strategy, according to attorneys. That apparently
is not lost on Cyrus Mehri, whose Washington-based law firm filed
the suit against Coca-Cola.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there is a public dimension to (the suit), that's something
the company may have to deal with,'' Mehri said recently. ``They
are the most prominent company in Atlanta. There's an
African-American community there, and the African-American
community has a right to know what is going on in this company.''
</P>
<P>
   Even so, said Northwestern University's Stoller, the publicity
is not necessarily going to affect business.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is unlikely, in my mind, that a customer of Coca-Cola is
going to make a change based on some as-yet-unproven allegation,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   -- Gregory Allen Clark, a security officer at Coca-Cola. The
suit charges ``he has been denied promotions on the basis of race,
and has been repeatedly denied the opportunity to even apply for
promotions, because of the common practice of filling supervisory
jobs without posting the positions.''
</P>
<P>
   -- Motisola Malikha Abdallah, an administrative assistant at the
company. The suit alleges she ``has experienced discrimination in
performance evaluations and in the terms and conditions of her
employment.''
</P>
<P>
   -- Linda Ingram, an information systems analyst at Coca-Cola.
The suit alleges she ``has been consistently paid below her grade
level and thousands of dollars less than comparable Caucasian
employees.''
</P>
<P>
   -- Kimberly Gray Orton, a former employee of Coca-Cola. The suit
charges she ``was significantly underpaid compared with comparable
Caucasian employees, was compensated at the low end of her pay
grade range, and supervised Caucasian employees who were paid more
than she was.''
</P>
<P>
   McNaughton writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
