<HEADER>
A9378 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ISRAEL-ELECTIONS-NYT &LR;      05-08 1046
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL-ELECTIONS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LEFTIST DOVE IS NETANYAHU'S FAVORITE CAMPAIGN TARGET  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By DEBORAH SONTAG   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEL AVIV, Israel _ There could be no more mild-mannered
lightning rod of controversy than Yossi Beilin, a soft-spoken,
bespectacled academic who is serving as the right wing's voodoo
doll in the current election campaign in Israel.
</P>
<P>
   While he is invisible on the public stage of his own Labor
Party, Beilin, a leftist, is prominently featured as archenemy by
the conservative Likud Party and its supporters. Sometimes it seems
as if Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu is running against Beilin,
who is the fifth-ranking member of Labor's One Israel coalition,
rather than Ehud Barak, its more moderate leader.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can basically hear what Labor thinks by listening to Yossi
Beilin,'' Netanyahu said in a recent interview. ``What Yossi Beilin
says today, Barak will tomorrow.''
</P>
<P>
   In one Likud commercial for the May 17 elections, Beilin's head
pops out from behind Barak's like a jack-in-the-box. In another,
paid for by an organization apparently supporting Likud, Beilin is
nastily portrayed as a furry white, manicured lap dog with wire-rim
glasses and red _ nothing is subtle here _ ribbons. It is an
allusion to a cutting nickname that the late Yitzhak Rabin attached
to Beilin when he was a protege of Shimon Peres, the former prime
minister: ``Peres' poodle.''
</P>
<P>
   As the leading dove of his political generation and one who has
established a tight working relationship with the Palestinians,
Beilin, a political scientist, makes for a surer target and cleaner
hit than Barak, a highly decorated former general.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very flattering, really,'' Beilin said, sitting on a
black leather armchair in his sparsely decorated apartment. ``By
Netanyahu's logic, if he fails, then it's my victory. If I am the
monster Beilin who is the architect of the master plan of bad
things, and he loses, then my views win.''
</P>
<P>
   What Netanyahu most frequently refers to are Beilin's
negotiations with the Palestinian official Abu Mazen, which laid
out a blueprint including a Palestinian state with Abu Dis, a small
Arab town outside Jerusalem, as its capital. Netanyahu refers to
the Beilin-Abu Mazen agreement as if it were a secret document
unearthed by security agents, Beilin said, when it is something he
discussed openly in a recent book.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is, in a way, a promoter of my work,'' said Beilin, who
served as deputy foreign minister in the early 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   Outspoken, Beilin consciously tries to push the envelope of
political debate, introducing ideas before their time and watching
Israelis grow into them. While some mock him as a nutty radical,
others consider him prescient and the rare politician who speaks
his mind.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our politicians are seldom blessed with Beilin's dedication,
industry and guts,'' Amotz Asa-El of The Jerusalem Post said on
Friday in a column headlined ``Who Is a Poodle?'' ``Now the ease
with which Beilin's depiction as a joke is both conceived and
received speaks volumes about our political degeneration.''
</P>
<P>
   Among his ideas, aside from the Palestinian state, that have
come to seem more mainstream are calls for a unilateral withdrawal
of Israeli troops from southern Lebanon and for a cessation of
Jewish charity from abroad to the prosperous Jewish homeland.
</P>
<P>
   As minister of economy and planning in 1995 and a champion of
good government, he also became the only Cabinet minister ever to
preside over the dissolution of his own ministry at his own behest.
</P>
<P>
   Among those ideas that have not caught on yet is a recent
proposal for ``secular conversions'' to Judaism, which would train
converts to become Jewish culturally but not religiously. While
Beilin thinks that it could be a mechanism to sidestep the Israeli
chief rabbis' objections to religious conversions that are not
Orthodox, many think the idea absurd and joke that the test would
feature questions like, ``What is a bagel?''
</P>
<P>
   Barak, in a recent interview, called Beilin the ``enfant
terrible'' of the Labor Party, suggesting that it is a role that
he, at 50, should have outgrown. But then they have a complicated,
if mutually respectful, relationship.
</P>
<P>
   Beilin challenged Barak for the party leadership in 1997,
calling it the race of the ``nerd against the macho,'' and lost.
But he remains popular, having captured second place in the party
primaries held last winter, and his criticisms of Barak have not
been forgotten.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not twin brothers,'' Beilin said. ``But there is a
platform that connects us.''
</P>
<P>
   In the campaign, elections, Beilin's role, like that of Peres,
remains behind the scenes. Beilin is the avatar of the retail
politician. Charged with getting out the vote among Israeli Arabs,
he travels the country village by village, even family by family,
attending weddings, parties and town hall meetings.
</P>
<P>
   ``They ask why is our campaign so hawkish,'' Beilin said of the
Israeli Arabs. ``They want to know why Barak is portrayed as a war
hero in all the commercials and not as a peace man. I remind them
about Rabin. I remind them that they hesitated to support Rabin
since he once broke the arms and legs of their brethren but that he
turned out to be an advocate for peace.
</P>
<P>
   ``I also remind them that when I ran against Barak inside the
party, there were many Arabs who said they couldn't support me even
though they felt closer to me because he, not I, could get the
votes of Israelis.''
</P>
<P>
   While polls show Barak with a firm lead over Netanyahu, Beilin
said he did not let himself believe them.
</P>
<P>
   ``I cannot relax,'' he said. ``I told Barak this morning, `Don't
take seriously any good polls, only the bad polls.'''
</P>
<P>
   Asked about his place in a future government should Labor win,
Beilin said he knew that he is too controversial for top positions.
He said he felt that the next government should be broad-based,
moderate and ``not necessarily leftist'' in order to win consensus
for the big diplomatic decisions ahead, about the Palestinian
state, Lebanon and the Golan Heights.
</P>
<P>
   ``My influence does not necessarily have to be connected to a
job,'' he said. ``In a way, I've been more influential in
opposition than in many of my jobs in government.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
