<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OKLA-STORMS-CLINTON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON ORDERS JOB RELIEF IN AFTERMATH OF TORNADOES  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By DAVID E. ROSENBAUM   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   OKLAHOMA CITY _ As he prepared to tour communities devastated by
Monday's tornadoes, President Clinton announced in his weekly radio
address Saturday that he had instructed the Labor Department to
hire thousands of Oklahomans who lost their jobs in businesses
destroyed by the storms and that he would ask Congress for more
money for disaster relief.
</P>
<P>
   In a detour from what had been scheduled as a political trip to
Texas, the president also announced his support for a national
weather center for tornado forecasting at the University of
Oklahoma.
</P>
<P>
   Touring areas damaged by natural disasters ``is a duty I've
performed many times,'' Clinton said in the broadcast.
</P>
<P>
   ``The one thing I've learned,'' he continued, ``is that the
images we see on television can never fully convey the level of
sheer destruction or the depth of human grief. Yet I've also
learned that the worst of nature can bring out the best in
people.''
</P>
<P>
   The tornadoes killed 46 people and injured hundreds more in
Oklahoma and Kansas, with suburban areas around Oklahoma City the
hardest hit. About 12,000 homes were destroyed in the two states.
The list of the missing, which at one time numbered about 100
people, has been narrowed to three, and rescue workers said that
they may never be found.
</P>
<P>
   He said he had instructed the Labor Department to spend more
than $12 million to provide temporary jobs for 3,500 men and women
whose jobs were lost in the tornadoes. They will work at relief
centers and on construction crews.
</P>
<P>
   ``They'll be able to feed their families by rebuilding their
communities,'' the president said.
</P>
<P>
   He also said he would ask Congress for an additional $372
million for the federal Emergency Management Agency.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton alluded to the political fault line that he believes
divides Democrats from Republicans, who favor reducing the
influence of government. ``The federal government,'' the president
said, ``has the responsibility to provide individuals with the
tools they need to improve their own lives.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton flew here from Texas. After returning to Washington on
Thursday night from meetings with allies in Europe on the war in
Yugoslavia, he spent Friday at political fund-raising events in
Houston and Austin that were expected to raise $700,000 for the
Democratic Party.
</P>
<P>
   In Texas, he departed from his standard political speech to talk
about the tornadoes. At a lunch in Houston, where supporters
donated $20,000 per couple, he said:
</P>
<P>
   ``This maybe belongs more in a sermon on Sunday than a political
speech, but the lesson is, no matter how well America does, a
little humility is always in order. We are not in full control. And
we have to be sensitive about this, especially here in this part of
the country. We have to do more to try to prepare ourselves for
these storms, and we have to do more to try to minimize their
impact when they occur.''
</P>
<P>
   Then, at a poolside Mexican dinner at a supporter's home in
Austin, the president brought up the storms again. He said: ``I'm
thinking about what we can do to try to prepare better for the next
one. I'm thinking about what we can do if we know we're going to
grow and expand in areas that have been tornado alleys _ what we
ought to do to build houses that will do a better job of
withstanding them or have quicker escapes to places that will be
safer.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
