<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-RUSSIA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YELTSIN CALLS CHINA EMBASSY BOMBING AN OUTRAGE 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By CELESTINE BOHLEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ Russian President Boris Yeltsin on Saturday condemned
the bombing of the Chinese Embassy in Belgrade as ``yet another
flagrant violation of international law'' by NATO leaders and
called on them to end their military action in Yugoslavia
immediately
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a blatant outrage, and there can be no justification
for it,'' Yeltsin said in a statement released by the Kremlin.
</P>
<P>
   In his first reaction to the embassy bombing, Yeltsin ordered
Foreign Minister Igor Ivanov to put off a planned three-day visit
to Britain. Ivanov told journalists in Moscow on Saturday that
NATO's latest bombing error would ``seriously complicate the work
being done'' to negotiate an end to the war in Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   He described the strike as a provocation and a challenge to the
world community that should be taken up again at the U.N. Security
Council on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   However, Russia's special Balkan envoy, Victor Chernomyrdin,
flew to Bonn for meetings with German leaders. Ibrahim Rugova, the
moderate leader of Kosovo Albanians, who flew to Italy on
Wednesday, was also expected to meet with Chernomyrdin, German
officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Chernomyrdin is expected to go from Bonn to Belgrade on his
third mission there in three weeks.
</P>
<P>
   In a joint statement signed in Bonn the week before last, the
foreign ministers of Russia and the world's seven richest countries
agreed to pursue a peace settlement at the United Nations, where
both China and Russia have veto power on the Security Council.
</P>
<P>
   Last March, China joined Russia in condemning the NATO bombing
campaign, and Russian diplomats in Moscow said Chernomyrdin had
already been considering a trip to Beijing to negotiate the terms
of a U.N. resolution before a NATO bomb struck the Chinese Embassy.
</P>
<P>
   The embassy bombing could solidify Chinese support for a Russian
proposal to put any future peacekeeping operation in Kosovo
strictly under Security Council control. NATO leaders are insisting
that their troops be the core of such a force and that they be
under NATO command, with U.N. authorization.
</P>
<P>
   Russia, which has taken on the role of mediator between Belgrade
and the West, has pushed for a greater U.N. role, arguing that
Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic will not accept NATO troops
in Kosovo, particularly from those countries that have taken part
in the bombing campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Yeltsin's statement was one of the harshest he has made since
NATO began its attacks on Yugoslavia six weeks ago, and reflected
Moscow's concern that the conflict in Kosovo could spin still
further out of control
</P>
<P>
   It repeated warnings of ``very harsh consequences'' of continued
bombing for European security and stability, adding,
``Responsibility for those consequences fully rests with those who
masterminded this venture.''
</P>
<P>
   Ivanov went further Saturday, saying that those who were
launching military strikes ``must be punished appropriately'' and
warning that those who ``hope to escape punishment are seriously
deluding themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   As Russian diplomacy moved into high gear in recent weeks, the
stridently anti-Western tone in official statements had begun to
soften. Saturday, after the embassy bombing, a top military
official again accused the United States of pursuing global
ambitions.
</P>
<P>
   ``By attacking the Chinese Embassy, the United States
demonstrates the drive for a unilateral dictatorship of force to
meet its interests,'' the official, Leonid Ivashov, head of the
Defense Ministry's international liaison department, said. ``The
United States sent a strategic challenge to the world community
which can result in a global apocalypse.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
