<SLUG> BC-GUN-LOBBY-RIFT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN BREAK WITH NRA, TWO GUN GROUPS AGREE WITH SOME CLINTON
PROPOSALS
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Colo., Okla., Pa.)  (rk) 
 By KATHARINE Q. SEELYE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Two groups representing gun manufacturers have
agreed in principle to back some of President Clinton's proposals
to clamp down on access to guns in the wake of the school shootings
in Colorado.
</P>
<P>
   The proposals are generally opposed by the National Rifle
Association, and the other groups' support for them is the first by
manufacturers for gun-control measures. The move signals a breach
among the powerful firearms interests over tactics as the
manufacturers try to take steps to appease public officials and
avoid costly lawsuits.
</P>
<P>
   With Congress expected to begin debating gun-control legislation
this week, a split within the gun lobby could help gun opponents
portray the rifle association as an extremist organization and
begin to break the lobby's political hold on lawmakers,
particularly those from swing districts.
</P>
<P>
   The five proposals being backed by the two groups, the American
Shooting Sports Council and the National Shooting Sports Council,
include: raising the age limit for possessing a handgun to 21 from
18, while still allowing exemptions for hunting, target shooting,
employment and ranching; extending background checks to those who
buy guns at gun shows, provided that the records are eventually
expunged; banning juveniles who are convicted of violent felonies
from ever owning guns; prosecuting parents if they recklessly or
negligently allow guns to fall into the hands of children who then
use them to commit crimes, and expanding to 75 cities the
government's gun-tracing program, which is now under way in 35
cities.
</P>
<P>
   The proposals emerged from the annual meeting in January of the
U.S. Conference of Mayors. The industry has been working with
several of the mayors, notably Ed Rendell of Philadelphia, to try
to show a good-faith effort to reduce youth access to firearms.
</P>
<P>
   So far, Philadelphia has held off joining seven other cities in
filing potentially expensive lawsuits against the gun manufacturers
to try to recover the health and social costs of gun-related
violence.
</P>
<P>
   After the rampage by two students in a Littleton, Colo., high
school last month, Clinton announced a package of anti-gun
measures, many of which had been advanced by the mayors.
</P>
<P>
   In bits and pieces, spokesmen for the weapons manufacturers
publicly offered their backing for five of those measures, although
they, along with the rifle association, still oppose one that the
administration considers crucial _ restricting handgun sales to one
a month per person.
</P>
<P>
   The White House has called a seminar for Monday on youth and
violence and invited representatives of gun manufacturers. In
preparation for the seminar, Bruce Reed, Clinton's domestic policy
adviser, invited Robert A. Ricker, executive director of the
American Shooting Sports Council, and Robert Delfay, president of
the National Shooting Sports Council, to the White House, and they
met for 90 minutes on Tuesday to discuss the legislation. Also at
the meeting was Paul Jannuzzo, general counsel for Glock, a gun
manufacturer.
</P>
<P>
   The White House has spurned the high-profile members of the
rifle association, not inviting Charlton Heston, the association's
president, or Wayne LaPierre, its executive director.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, it has invited a member of the association's board,
Bill Brewster, a former Republican congressman from Oklahoma and
now a lobbyist in Washington. Reed described Brewster, who has gone
duck-hunting with Clinton, as ``an old friend of the president's.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-08-99 1609EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
