<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CITADEL-FEMALE-CADET-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FEMALE CADET GRADUATES AT THE CITADEL, A FIRST 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHARLESTON, S.C. _ She was not the first woman to gain admission
to the Citadel, but Nancy Mace on Saturday became the first female
graduate of this 156-year-old state-supported military college.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Mace, 21, became a cadet in the fall of 1996, just months
before her father, J. Emory Mace, a retired Army brigadier general,
became the Citadel's commandant of cadets.
</P>
<P>
   She has fulfilled the dashed dream of the first female cadet,
Shannon Faulkner, who was admitted in 1995 following a federal
court order that was fiercely contested by the Citadel and the
state of South Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Faulkner's victory was shortlived. She left the college
after less than a week, citing isolation and stress.
</P>
<P>
   The Citadel now has 42 women among the 1,700 cadets and expects
to have as many as 90 women next year, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Mace has remained largely aloof from the news media in her
three years at the Citadel. But she lowered her guard slightly as
graduation approached, appearing, for example, with her father and
mother on the ABC program ``Good Morning America'' on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Though she values the conservative traditions of the corps, she
sees herself as a trailblazer for women with similar ambitions.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just wanted an opportunity to join the long, gray line. I
think I am paving the way for other women,'' Ms. Mace said in an
interview with the Charleston newspaper, The Post and Courier.
</P>
<P>
   In the fall of 1996, Ms. Mace entered the Citadel with three
other women, but their integration into the harsh military culture
did not go smoothly. Two of the women, Kim Messer of Clover, S.C.,
and Jeanie Mentavlos of Charlotte, N.C., quit that winter, citing
hazing, harassment and abuse.
</P>
<P>
   Several male cadets were disciplined after an investigation of
the accusations.
</P>
<P>
   The fourth woman, Petra Lovetinska, is an upperclass cadet.
</P>
<P>
   What the institution seemed to yearn for more than anything was
a sense of normalcy, for a time when the graduation of a woman
would no longer be news. `This marks the end of the transition,''
said Brig. Gen. Roger Poole, the chief academic officer of the
college and presided over the admission of Nancy Mace and her three
classmates
</P>
<P>
   ``From the day Nancy Mace and the three others stepped onto this
campus, we were committed to seeing them graduate,'' Poole said.
``We're just sorry that only two of them will make it to
graduation.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Ms. Mace's name was only mentioned in the graduation ceremony as
she walked across the stage and received her diploma from her
father, who is also a Citadel graduate. Her brief appearance was
greeted with long and enthusiastic applause from many in the
audience and reserved smiles from her military family as she raised
her diploma in triumph.
</P>
<P>
   And her understated place in history was just as she wanted it
to be.
</P>
<P>
   Following the ceremony, she briefly met with reporters and said
she just wished that her fellow cadet, Petra Lovetinska, could have
been on the graduation list with her. Ms. Mace graduated after
three years at The Citadel because she transferred credits from a
community college.
</P>
<P>
   Asked how they had changed The Citadel, Ms. Mace and Ms.
Lovetinska smiled at each other and said as a chorus: ``for the
better.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
