<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEASTER-COLUMN-KAN </SLUG>
  
 Taking a dip into the mailbag  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY HEASTER  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The choice was to either blow off Saturday's column before
leaving on a long getaway weekend, or dip into the mailbag and
leave the writing to the readers:
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to comment on your article on `Congress, not the IRS,
is the problem.' I just spent three months working (two days a
week) at the Johnson County Library doing voluntary free tax
preparation for elderly or low-income persons. Many availed
themselves of this free service, but many did not, either because
they didn't know about it or it wasn't close to where they lived.
That means many many people...had to pay somebody else to help them
prepare their return....That enormous cost is directly related to
what you call the `tax code's complexity (and) body of
incomprehensible law' and has nothing to do with the IRS.''
</P>
<P>
   {Dear Fuming: Your grass-roots experience should be legally
required of every member of Congress and every member of every
tax-writing congressional committee. Such a law would force
Congress to adjourn from March 1 to April 15 each year to provide
everyone involved in tax policy the opportunity to perform tax-help
volunteer service. Then perhaps we'd get some simplification.}
</P>
<P>
   Moving from Main Street to Wall Street, our next contributor has
been pondering the last memorable occasion when everyone reassured
us, ``This time it's different.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I read your (column) on the value of Web stocks and was
reminded of something I read...about stocks in the late 1960s,
which were known as `the Nifty Fifty.' (I)nvestment managers
defined (their) risk not as the risk of overpaying (for them), but
as the risk of not owning them.''
</P>
<P>
   {Dear Sentimental: Ah, yes, those were the days, my friend, we
thought they'd never end (to quote the lyrics of a popular song
back then). Some of the Nifty Fifty companies are once again
nifties, but none escaped the damage of the 1973-74 bear market and
ensuing years in the doldrums. Meantime, it's worth noting, many
erstwhile nifties have long since been relegated to the trash heap
of Wall Street history.} &QL;
</P>
<P>
   What would a mailbag column be without a letter about Social
Security? It would be a mailbag column that ignores much of the
mail's focus. Here's one, though, with a different wrinkle.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of smoke is being blown about Social Security....The
question I have is this: Is the private sector any better off?
Right now, the stock market is flying high, (but) what's going to
happen when the baby boomers decide to stop throwing cash at the
market and start saying, `I want to cash in my stocks for some real
money'? I would think there is going to be a liquidity crunch.''
</P>
<P>
   {Dear Curious: It could happen, and probably will someday. But,
then, demographic trends ebb and flow in the same way the stock
market's strength does. There are a couple of key differences
between the Social Security situation and the stock market. One is
that buyers and sellers determine a stock's market value. The
Social Security trust fund comprises nonmarketable securities
representing claims against the Treasury. This means the fund is an
accounting fiction containing IOUs whose value depends on the
willingness of society to honor the debt.}
</P>
<P>
   Keep those cards and letters comin', hear?
</P>
</TEXT>
