<HEADER>
A9441 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-UTAH-JUDGE-NYT &LR;      05-08 0758
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-UTAH-JUDGE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ENVIRONMENT AND POLITICS ENTER DEBATE ON JUDGESHIP  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By NEIL A. LEWIS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Ted Stewart, chief of staff to Utah's governor,
would not seem a likely choice for President Clinton to want to
nominate as a federal judge.
</P>
<P>
   Stewart has been a veteran aide to several Utah Republicans. A
lawyer who headed the state's Natural Resources Department, he has
been a harsh critic of the president's land-use policies and
politics and, in turn, has been disliked by major environmental
groups. Nonetheless, the White House has decided that it will
probably soon name Stewart to fill a vacancy on the U.S. District
Court in Utah, a senior administration official said this week.
</P>
<P>
   Stewart's most compelling qualification, as far as the White
House is concerned, is that he has been proposed by Sen. Orrin G.
Hatch, the Utah Republican who heads the Senate Judiciary
Committee. As chairman, Hatch has enormous influence over the
administration's other choices to be federal judges.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, White House officials say that unless they agree to
nominate Stewart to the bench, they believe Hatch will block
several of their other judicial candidates. Hatch's aides depict
that fear as an exaggeration, arguing that they merely want a
decision soon on whether the president will nominate Stewart.
</P>
<P>
   The case of Stewart illustrates the sometimes tangled and
strange politics behind who gets to be a federal judge at a time
when that issue has become immensely politicized. Stewart's
candidacy has involved not only the president and a powerful
senator but also Vice President Al Gore.
</P>
<P>
   Gore, who is seen by the environmental groups as their greatest
supporter within the administration, has been pressed by them to
block the nomination. But Gore, in the words of one White House
official, ``has taken a pass on this one,'' choosing not to try and
buck the larger political issues involved.
</P>
<P>
   While administration officials may believe that if they do not
accommodate Hatch he will not allow any other nominations to go
forward, Hatch's aides deny that is so. But the senator told
reporters for Congressional Daily and The Deseret News in Utah that
he recently spoke by telephone with the president to press
Stewart's nomination. Hatch was quoted as saying that the president
assumed that his nominations were being held hostage to the Stewart
nomination ``and I did not disabuse him of that notion.''
</P>
<P>
   Hatch's spokeswoman, Jeane Lopatto, said the Judiciary Committee
had, in fact, processed some nominees in recent weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``One would think that given Senator Hatch's demonstrated
bipartisan consideration of judicial nominees,'' Ms. Lopatto said,
``the White House would have made a decision on this particular
judgeship, which has been vacant since November 1997.''
</P>
<P>
   The Utah Democratic Committee has sent a letter to Clinton
opposing the Stewart nomination, as has a coalition of the
Wilderness Society, the Sierra Club, the Natural Resources Defense
Council, Defenders of Wildlife, Friends of the Earth, the National
Environmental Trust and the Environmental Defense Fund.
</P>
<P>
   The Democratic committee letter describes Stewart as a ``highly
partisan political operative'' who should not be given a lifetime
judicial appointment by a Democratic president. The environmental
coalition complained about Stewart's tenure as director of the Utah
Department of Natural Resources, saying that, among other things,
he worked to reduce the ability of the department to protect
wildlife.
</P>
<P>
   Greg Wetstone, legislative director for the Natural Resources
Defense Council said, ``We just think that Orrin Hatch should not
have to be rewarded with the right to name Utah's version of James
Watt to the federal bench.''
</P>
<P>
   Nan Aron, director of the Alliance for Justice, a liberal
Washington group that monitors judicial selection, said that if the
Clinton White House nominated Stewart it would be ``an abdication
of their constitutional responsibility.''
</P>
<P>
   But Cullen Battle, a Salt Lake City lawyer who is active in
environmental causes and represents the Sierra Club and the Nature
Conservancy, said he believed that it was unfair to depict Stewart
as an anti-environmentalist.
</P>
<P>
   Battle said that when Stewart was the head of the Natural
Resources Department, he was a strong supporter of habitat
protection throughout the state.
</P>
<P>
   Stewart, who since 1992 has worked under Gov. Michael O.
Leavitt, a Republican, declined to comment when reached in Salt
Lake City.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
