</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-U.N.-CHINA-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SECURITY COUNCIL EXPRESSES `SHOCK AND DISMAY' AT BOMBING
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Eds: replaces KOSOVO-U.N.-CHINA)   (rk) 
 By JUDITH MILLER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   After weeks on the political periphery of the Kosovo crisis, the
U.N. Security Council made a dramatic return to diplomatic center
stage early Saturday, as an outraged China denounced the United
States and its NATO allies for their bombing of its embassy in
Belgrade and demanded an immediate halt to the airstrikes.
</P>
<P>
   In a rare emergency meeting that began after midnight Friday and
adjourned just before dawn, Qin Huasun, China's representative at
the United Nations, condemned NATO for what it called its
``flagrant'' attack, which he said constituted a ``crime of war
that should be punished.''
</P>
<P>
   But he failed to persuade a majority of the 15-member council to
condemn the bombing of its embassy or even investigate it. Instead,
the council issued a statement expressing ``shock and concern'' at
the attack on the Chinese Embassy and extended condolences to China
for the attack.
</P>
<P>
   The statement carries no legal weight, but it reflects what
little consensus exists among the council members, who apparently
were as deeply divided over NATO's military intervention Saturday
morning as at the beginning of the conflict 46 days before.
</P>
<P>
   These divisions have been largely responsible for keeping the
Security Council until now on the periphery of military and
diplomatic efforts to resolve it.
</P>
<P>
   Having aroused representatives from the 15-member council from
dinner parties and their beds to attend the emergency session,
China made clear that it might take unspecified ``further
actions.'' But Qin made no immediate demand for another emergency
meeting and gave no further indication Saturday morning of his
country's intentions.
</P>
<P>
   Sergey Lavrov, the Russian representative to the United Nations,
used the occasion to reiterate his country's demand for an
immediate halt to the airstrikes, which he called ``a necessary
prerequisite'' to any diplomatic solution of the conflict.
</P>
<P>
   Clearly on the defensive, the United States and its allies
stressed that the attack, which NATO was still investigating, was
an accident. Peter Burleigh, the acting U.S. representative, told
China and the other council members that NATO would never
deliberately target either civilians or an embassy.
</P>
<P>
   Britain, as it has since the NATO air campaign got under way on
March 24, took a somewhat more hawkish line, noting in the angry
debate that it was a ``gross distortion'' for Qin to imply that the
embassy had been deliberately attacked.
</P>
<P>
   After extending his apologies to China, Burleigh urged fellow
council members to keep ``the big picture'' in mind. He said the
ultimate blame for the Chinese casualties lay with President
Slobodan Milosevic of Yugoslavia. ``We worked for months and months
on a negotiated settlement with Milosevic,'' Burleigh said. ``He
never agreed. And as the world knows, he triggered a human
catastrophe.''
</P>
<P>
   This prompted an irate retort from Lavrov, whose tone within
council deliberations has remained acerbic even as the Russian
special envoy, Viktor Chernomyrdin, has shuttled back and forth to
Belgrade, trying to help the United States achieve a diplomatic
solution.
</P>
<P>
   ``How many people must be left homeless,'' Lavrov said, ``how
many countries must be destabilized in order to punish that one
single person?''
</P>
<P>
   The ``big picture,'' he added, ``is not the fact that one single
person is responsible for all this,'' but that NATO's military
adventurism ``has been used as a slogan to cover up NATO attempts
to destroy world order.''
</P>
<P>
   Other countries used the session to vent longstanding grievances
against the United States. Saeed Hasan, Iraq's representative, said
NATO had deliberately targeted the Chinese Embassy, calling the
attack a ``barbaric act which violates the charter of the United
Nations.''
</P>
<P>
   China, as one of the five permanent members of the council, has
a veto over council actions, has staunchly opposed the NATO bombing
campaign in Yugoslavia and had previously often expressed its
suspicion about the motives of the Western alliance.
</P>
<P>
   Still, while diplomats at the United Nations acknowledged that
the bombing might complicate efforts to win council endorsement of
an international military force to maintain peace in Kosovo, few
thought that China would veto such a resolution if Russia and the
United States succeeded in producing a diplomatic accord to end the
conflict.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard for us to believe that China would deliberately
block a peaceful resolution to the Kosovo conflict,'' a Western
diplomat said Saturday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
