A9451 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TWA-800-CRASH-NYT &LR;      05-08 0719
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TWA-800-CRASH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SAFETY BOARD COMPLAINS ABOUT DIFFICULTIES WITH FBI INVESTIGATNG TWA
CRASH  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By MATTHEW L. WALD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ After prolonged jurisdictional jostling between the
FBI and the National Transportation Safety Board over the
investigation into why Trans World Airlines Flight 800 exploded
three years ago, the safety board is throwing some political
punches.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, three staff members from the board are expected to
tell a Senate subcommittee that the FBI withheld a report ruling
out a bomb or missile. The report was prepared by the Bureau of
Alcohol, Tobacco and Firearms shortly after the crash.
</P>
<P>
   Last Thursday, NTSB Chairman James Hall asked Congress for ``an
explicit statutory basis'' for asserting primacy over law
enforcement agencies in cases like Flight 800, in which crime was
initially suspected but never proved.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I failed in asserting our interest and authority'' in
the Flight 800 investigation, Hall told the aviation subcommittee
of the House Transportation Committee.
</P>
<P>
   The plane, a Boeing 747, exploded a few minutes after it took
off from Kennedy International Airport on July 17, 1996, killing
all 230 people on board. In theory the safety board has
jurisdiction over all plane crashes unless they are shown to
involve crimes. But in the case of Flight 800, the FBI quickly
seized control of the wreckage, at one point barring safety board
investigators from taking photographs.
</P>
<P>
   In the months that followed, the safety board investigators
worked alongside counterparts from the Bureau of Alcohol, Tobacco
and Firearms and understood informally that the latter had no
evidence of a bomb or missile, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   By October 1996, three months after the crash, safety board
officials were saying publicly that the cause of the explosion was
probably mechanical, and not sabotage, a view that was not endorsed
by the FBI. By December, the board was issuing recommendations to
prevent future crashes based on its belief that the cause was
mechanical.
</P>
<P>
   The ATF report ruling out a bomb or missile was completed around
the end of 1996. A spokesman for the FBI in New York, Joseph
Valiquette, said the FBI had found a letter from James Kallstrom,
the special agent in charge of the New York office, to Hall, dated
March 17, 1997, conveying the report. But Ted Lopatkiewicz, a
spokesman or the board, said the board became aware of the letter
only after it received a copy from the Senate subcommittee in
preparation for Monday's hearing, and that no one at the board
recalled seeing the report.
</P>
<P>
   The FBI waited until May 1997 to say publicly that evidence
pointed to a ``catastrophic mechanical failure'' causing the crash,
and it did not formally withdraw from the inquiry until November
1997. The safety board held hearings on the crash the following
month.
</P>
<P>
   The board has not formally established the cause of the crash,
but it has said the plane was destroyed by an explosion of fumes in
the center fuel tank. It is still searching for the source of
ignition.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate Judiciary Committee's subcommittee on Administrative
Oversight and the Courts, which has previously delved into problems
at the FBI's crime laboratory, has been investigating the FBI's
role in the TWA case and will hold a hearing on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Officials of the board say the FBI's involvement created
difficulties for them. One was being excluded from the initial
witness interviews, and thus not being able to ask questions
related to a possible mechanical cause, as opposed to a crime. In
the end, however, witness information did not prove important.
</P>
<P>
   Hall, the board chairman, said in a written submission to the
House subcommittee on Thursday that legislation was needed to
insure that the board could lead future accident inquiries.
Congress established the board 30 years ago as an independent
agency to supervise all government work after transportation
accidents.
</P>
<P>
   Board officials say that in past cases, in which crime has been
shown, they have been quick to relinquish jurisdiction. For
example, when a recorder on a Pacific Southwest Airlines flight in
December 1987 captured the sound of a disgruntled employee shooting
the pilots, the board yielded control to the FBI.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
