<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-ITALIAN-OPEN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VENUS WILLIAMS TOPPLES HINGIS AT ITALIAN OPEN  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER CLAREY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROME _ Like the picture-snapping American tourists in front of
the Pantheon and the Trevi Fountain, Venus Williams will have fine
memories of her trip to Rome when she heads back across the
Atlantic.
</P>
<P>
   For the second consecutive year, Williams is in the final of the
Italian Open, and she got there Saturday by beating Martina Hingis,
the world's No. 1 player in three uneven but consistently
compelling sets, 6-4, 1-6, 6-4.
</P>
<P>
   It was Williams' first victory on clay over Hingis, and it came
one day after the Swiss teen-ager had her way with Venus' sister
Serena on the very same sun-drenched center court, winning 6-2,
6-2.
</P>
<P>
   ``Serena didn't play her best yesterday,'' Venus Williams said.
``Today I had a good day.''
</P>
<P>
   Like Williams, Mary Pierce, her final-round opponent Sunday,
lives in Florida. Unlike Venus, Pierce represents France, and in
Saturday's first semifinal in the Foro Italico she defeated another
talented Frenchwoman, Amelie Mauresmo, 6-7 (1-7), 6-2, 6-4.
</P>
<P>
   At this year's first Grand Slam event, the Australian Open,
Mauresmo lost to Hingis in the final. Venus Williams was beaten in
the quarterfinals by Lindsay Davenport, but as the year's second
Grand Slam event, the French Open, rapidly approaches, the pecking
order has now shifted. Davenport has a left wrist injury that is
taking longer than expected to heal, and Venus has lifted her level
of play significantly.
</P>
<P>
   She has won three of her last four tournaments and 18 of her
last 19 matches. Now, she has beaten Hingis in their first
encounter in nearly a year, and though Hingis still holds a 6-3
career edge over her fellow 18-year-old, she did not look like a
teen-ager with an edge in the final game Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Williams won the opening point with the sort of well-timed,
reasonably well-disguised drop shot that Hingis likes to hit.
Hingis made a forehand error, and then, tellingly, pushed a short
forehand wide moving forward that she normally would have stroked
with much more confidence. That made it 0-40, but Williams would
not need more than one match point as Hingis made another unforced
forehand error.
</P>
<P>
   While Williams did a little jig on the clay and pointed toward
her mother Oracene and other supporters in the stands, Hingis
jogged forward and tossed her racquet in disappointment. The
handshake was cordial, but Hingis made it clear that she wants to
be in a better, more triumphant mood the next time they meet at the
net.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even though I lost today, I'm going confident into the
French,'' she said. ''I don't think I was too far away today, and I
don't think I played my best.''
</P>
<P>
   She added, ``It's more important, the French, so watch out
Venus.''
</P>
<P>
   Early in the third set, it appeared that Williams might also
have to watch out in Rome. Though she had played excellent
attacking tennis in the opening set, frequently overpowering the
Swiss and winning points consistently at the net, she had then lost
her way. Hingis won the second set in 20 minutes, breaking Williams
all three times she served. Like sister Serena on Friday, the
unforced errors were coming in bunches, and Hingis was mixing her
shots and spins effectively.
</P>
<P>
   Hingis broke Williams again in the opening game of the final set
and jumped out to a 2-0 lead, but her run would stop there.
Williams held with ease in the next game and then broke Hingis to
get even.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm really good at comebacks these days,'' Williams said. ``I
felt I could win the match, and I knew I wanted to win the match.''
</P>
<P>
   If she wants to become the first woman with four WTA titles in
1999, she must now defeat Pierce in a final for the second time in
two weeks. Last week in Hamburg, it did not take long for her to
win, 6-3, 6-0. The fact that Pierce, seldom short on injuries, had
to play the last two sets against Mauresmo with her left leg
wrapped tightly because of a groin strain will not increase her
chances of changing her luck in Rome. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
