<HEADER>
A9455 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBO-NOTEBOOK-2TAKES-N     05-08 0755
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-NOTEBOOK-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THERE'S A NEW MAN IN ST. LOUIS, AND HE HAS ONLY 60 MORE TO GO  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mo., Texas, Calif., Mass., Ind., Canada)   By MURRAY CHASS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A couple of general managers who transacted some business at the
trading deadline last July were in Baltimore last Monday for the
Orioles' game with Cuba and had dinner together. Baseball talk, of
course, was on the menu.
</P>
<P>
   ``Remember, Walt,'' Doug Melvin said to Walt Jocketty at one
point, ``if he leads the league in runs batted in, you owe me
another player.''
</P>
<P>
   Jocketty, the St. Louis general manager, did not choke on
Melvin's words. He knows a joke when he hears one.
</P>
<P>
   The player they were talking about, though, is no joke. Fernando
Tatis, the Cardinals' third baseman, is establishing himself as one
of the bright young stars in the National League. He entered the
weekend tied for the league lead in home runs (11) and runs scored
(28), and second in rbi (32).
</P>
<P>
   Melvin, the Texas general manager, can only watch from a
distance and take consolation in knowing that Tatis is fulfilling
the expectations the Rangers had for him before they traded him and
pitcher Darren Oliver to St. Louis for shortstop Royce Clayton and
pitcher Todd Stottlemyre.
</P>
<P>
   ``We always thought he was going be a 30-home run, 30-stolen
base guy,'' Melvin said. ``He's a good defensive player, too.
That's the risk that goes with trying to win. You make a decision
and live with it.''
</P>
<P>
   On the same day they reluctantly traded Tatis, the Rangers
acquired third baseman Todd Zeile from Florida for two minor
leaguers. ``We could not have won without making the deals,''
Melvin said, referring to the American League West title.
</P>
<P>
   Stottlemyre beat the Anaheim Angels twice in the last two weeks
of the season, including the game that put the Rangers in first to
stay. Zeile reached base 11 consecutive times on 5 hits and 6 walks
in a critical three-game stretch that culminated in the Rangers'
clinching the division championship.
</P>
<P>
   Noting that two weeks before the Tatis trade he sent Warren
Morris, a promising young infielder, to Pittsburgh for pitcher
Esteban Loaiza, Melvin said: ``We're trying to build a reputation
for winning. If winning wasn't important, I wouldn't have made any
of those deals. I'd still have Morris and Tatis.''
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinals are happy for the Rangers. Having Tatis enables
them to be magnanimous.
</P>
<P>
   In two months in St. Louis last season, Tatis batted .287, hit 8
home runs and drove in 26 runs in 55 games. His eighth home run was
sort of overlooked. He hit it in the last game of the season, the
one in which Mark McGwire swatted his 69th and 70th.
</P>
<P>
   Now Tatis, a 24-year-old native of the Dominican Republic, is
carrying the Cardinals' load while McGwire struggles to get
untracked. How hot has Tatis been? He hit his 11th home run in the
Cardinals' 27th game Thursday night. Last year McGwire hit his 11th
in the 27th game.
</P>
<P>
   ``When he came over here last year, I think it was a big
adjustment for him,'' Jocketty said. ``He left a situation that was
comfortable for him. But we have a few more Latin players this
year, and Jose Oquendo is our bench coach.''
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinals have another new coach to work with Tatis on his
hitting, the former outfielder and designated hitter Mike Easler,
who played with Tatis' father in the Houston organization in the
early '70s. It was less than two years ago that Tatis located his
father, whom he had not seen since he was 3.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mike has a great relationship with Fernando,'' Jocketty said
of Easler, whom Mo Vaughn credits with making him the hitter he is
today. ``He's taken him under his wing and worked with him. He
found some things they started working on in spring training. He
got his hands down. Mostly Fernando has gained confidence. He's a
highly motivated kid.''
</P>
<P>
   No one expects Tatis to maintain his home run lead over McGwire,
who had hit six through Friday, but on the far-out chance that he
does, the day (April 23) Tatis caught and passed McGwire will be
long remembered in baseball history. That was the day Tatis hit two
grand slams in the same inning, a feat never before accomplished.
</P>
<P>
   McGwire, who was ``the man'' last season, saluted his younger
teammate by saying, ``Now Fernando's the man.''
</P>
<P>
   If Tatis should finish the season as the rbi man, would Jocketty
consider sending Melvin another player? ``I bought dinner for him
in Baltimore,'' Jocketty said. ``That should suffice.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   A Clemens Deal Footnote  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Boston Red Sox's trade of Jeff Bagwell for Larry Andersen in
1990 stands as one of the most notorious examples of a team's
swapping a minor league prospect for an established veteran who it
feels can help it win a pennant. The Red Sox won the division title
that season, but Bagwell has become one of the game's biggest
stars.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the Fernando Tatis trade may one day be remembered in
the same way. But Doug Melvin is so certain that such trades have
to be made that he was prepared to make another during spring
training this year. Ruben Mateo, a 21-year-old outfielder, is the
Rangers' No. 1 prospect, but he could have been in Toronto's minor
league system.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was prepared to do that if I had Clemens from Day One,''
Melvin said, meaning if he could have had Roger Clemens from the
first day of the season.
</P>
<P>
   In discussing a possible trade of Clemens, Melvin said, the Blue
Jays had asked for Mateo as part of a package. Rusty Greer, Rick
Helling and Tom Goodwin were other players mentioned. Melvin said
it finally came down to Mateo, pitcher Esteban Loaiza and Jonathan
Johnson, a minor league pitcher, for Clemens.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would have been a risky deal, but we basically agreed on
it,'' Melvin said. He said that Gord Ash, the Toronto general
manager, told him he was ready to make the deal, but he wanted to
go back to the Yankees first. ``He said he needed to make one more
call, but he didn't think they'd give him the player he wanted,''
Melvin said. The Yankees, however, surprised Ash. They said yes to
David Wells, and Mateo remains with the Rangers.  &QL; 
 &QL; 
Down to the Minors . . .  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Brett Tomko and Tony Saunders were in their third major league
seasons. Tomko, 26, had an impressive 24-19 record for Cincinnati
in his first two years. Saunders, 25, had only a 10-21 record, but
pitching for Florida in 1997 he beat the Atlanta Braves three times
and started a game in the World Series. Tampa Bay then made him the
first player selected in the expansion draft.
</P>
<P>
   Now Saunders and Tomko are in the minor leagues. Saunders had a
2-3 record and 8.67 earned run average in six starts, allowing a
ratio of 22 base runners per nine innings. Tomko had an 0-1 record
and 7.76 era in five starts, averaging 16.5 base runners per nine
innings.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to give him time to get his feet back on the ground,''
Larry Rothschild, the Devil Rays' manager, said of Saunders. ``We
want him to get good command of his fastball and get his confidence
back. He just wasn't doing his job. We could've put him in the
bullpen and brought him back slowly, but I think the more drastic
move will get him back to where we want him to be. He should be a
third starter here. The other way he could be the fifth.''
</P>
<P>
   Rothschild said the club was not putting a time frame on
Saunders' return. ``I don't want him to think he can have one good
start and come back,'' the manager said. ``It's going to take him
time to establish what he needs. He knows that.''
</P>
<P>
   Jim Bowden, the Reds' general manager, said Tomko had been hit
hard in all five starts, ``and he wasn't making any adjustments; he
was just getting worse.'' The Reds, Bowden said, hope that Grant
Jackson, the pitching coach at Class AAA Indianapolis, ``will get
him back to pitching the way he did the last couple of years.''
Asked how long he thought Tomko would be in the minors, Bowden
said, ``Hopefully it won't be too long if he's going to win 12 to
15 games for us.''
</P>
<P>
   Back to the Big Leagues For Righetti  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Dave Righetti returned to the major leagues last week. He had
not been there since he pitched for the Chicago White Sox in 1995.
His visit was brief but long enough for him to enjoy a new
experience.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I go to the ball park, I don't have that thing in the pit
of my stomach,'' Righetti said. ``I can relax. When you're playing
and having the job I had for a few years, I don't know if I enjoyed
it. All that nervous anxiety you went through. Now it's fun to go
to the park.''
</P>
<P>
   Righetti, 40, is in his first year as a roving pitching
instructor in the San Francisco Giants' organization. He joined the
parent club last Monday to fill in for Ron Perranoski, the pitching
coach, whose mother suffered a stroke.
</P>
<P>
   ``They threw me right into the fire,'' Righetti said.
``Throw-overs and pickoffs, getting guys up, talking to guys,
seeing who can pitch, who can't.''
</P>
<P>
   Referring to the Giants' manager, Dusty Baker, Righetti added:
``Dusty said: `You're not here just as a fill-in. Your job is to
help these guys.' I have a feeling that it's partly grooming to see
if this is what I want some day. But I'm perfectly happy doing what
I'm doing. Roving is a pretty good job.''
</P>
<P>
   Righetti, who pitched a no-hitter for the Yankees in 1983,
became a reliever and gained 223 saves for them in the next seven
seasons. He was out of baseball for three years until the Giants
lured him back last year.
</P>
<P>
   He worked with the Giants' instructional league team last
November, then went to spring training and became their roving
instructor. The job provided an unexpected bonus when he was
summoned to fill in for Perranoski. The closer Robb Nen, for one,
appreciated Righetti's presence.
</P>
<P>
   In the ninth inning of Righetti's first game with the Giants,
Nen gave up four runs, turning an 8-5 lead into a 9-8 loss.
Righetti said that Nen told him: ``I can talk to a lot of guys, but
they don't know what I go through. It's nice to talk to someone who
knows what I'm going through.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
