<HEADLINE>
NBC SEES STORY LINES AS FOCUS FOR THE FINALS 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By MIKE WISE    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   An Indiana-Utah final is generally seen as a prime-time
nightmare for NBC: two small-market, veteran teams with declining
vertical leaps, vying for pro basketball's championship a year
after Michael Jordan's farewell tour.
</P>
<P>
   A series without Kobe Bryant, Shaquille O'Neal, Patrick Ewing or
Pat Riley would seem to point to fewer viewers. But the network
contends that it is not playing favorites, that small-market teams
can sell under the right circumstances.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a big believer that for the finals to work, you have to
have stories,'' said Dick Ebersol, the president of NBC Sports.
``With Reggie Miller and Larry Bird, you have ready-made stars. And
Utah has been in the finals the past two years. If they were to end
up playing each other, that's an enticing series.''
</P>
<P>
   The finals draw more casual fans than do the regular season or
early playoffs. And a great angle _ or a pop-culture star like
Jordan, Charles Barkley or Shaquille O'Neal _ certainly attracts
them in bigger numbers.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, the average rating for the six games between the Jazz
and the Bulls was 18.7, the highest ever for the finals. (Each
rating point represents 980,000 households.) The 1993 finals
between Jordan's Bulls and Barkley's Phoenix Suns were second at
17.9.
</P>
<P>
   ``The two most important factors _ in order _ are story line and
length of series,'' said Ed Markey, an NBC spokesman. ``Market size
is gravy.''
</P>
<P>
   He added: ``The bigger cities carry more TV viewers, and more
ratings weight. So if everything else was equal, you may get a
little bit higher rating if the cities were major market. But not a
lot.''
</P>
<P>
   Even a marquee matchup like Lakers-Knicks would not guarantee
incredible ratings, especially if it were one-sided.
</P>
<P>
   Last year's World Series, which the Yankees swept from San
Diego, was the lowest-rated in history at an average of 14.1. In
1980, the World Series between the Philadelphia Phillies and the
Kansas City Royals _ the latter being a comparatively small market
_ achieved a 32.8 rating, the second-highest ever. The 1995 NBA
finals featured O'Neal and Anfernee Hardaway, along with Hakeem
Olajuwon trying to repeat as champion and Clyde Drexler trying to
win his first title. But it was a Houston sweep and ended with a
13.9 rating.
</P>
<P>
   As for a Jordan-less post-season, ``We factored in about a 15
percent decline over all,'' Ebersol said. ``When a transcendental
figure like that leaves the game, it's just natural. In many ways,
we've been spoiled.''
</P>
<P>
   Soon after NBC struck a deal with the NBA in 1990, taking the
rights away from CBS, the league's longtime partner, a CBS official
said his network was ``getting out just in time.'' A Cleveland-Utah
final seemed likely, he added.
</P>
<P>
   Led by Jordan, the Bulls won their first of three straight
titles, and six in eight seasons, the following season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought it was a rather snide remark, showing how little
people thought of Michael's long-range possibility as a champion,''
Ebersol said. ``We were clearly spoiled.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; 2 Unmade Knicks Bids &LR;
</P>
<P>
   It has become fashionable to knock the Knicks' front office for
some of the acquisitions it has made over the last few seasons. But
deals not made may have been more detrimental to the franchise than
any trade completed.
</P>
<P>
   David Falk, the agent for Patrick Ewing and many of the league's
top players, confirmed that he was trying to orchestrate a deal
after the lockout ended in January that would have brought Rod
Strickland, one of the league's most accomplished point guards,
back to New York.
</P>
<P>
   Strickland's contract negotiations with Washington had stalled,
and Falk said he tried to broker several deals in which the Wizards
would have signed Strickland and then traded him. His client
eventually re-signed for $40 million over four years with the
Wizards.
</P>
<P>
   ``The truth is, we worked very hard to get Rod there,'' Falk
said Friday. ``They weren't comfortable doing the deal. Patrick
knew about it and supported it, but management was not comfortable
accepting it. I don't know who made the decision, but I was told
that certain commitments had been made already.''
</P>
<P>
   Falk would not divulge which players would have been involved in
the deal, but soon after the lockout ended the Knicks committed $27
million to Charlie Ward.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they could have done that deal again at the trade deadline,
they would have,'' Falk added. ``But they simply couldn't because
of their salary cap situation.''
</P>
<P>
   Through a spokesperson, Dave Checketts, the president of Madison
Square Garden, declined to comment on any possible trades involving
Strickland.
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks also lost out in the Stephon Marbury sweepstakes at
the trading deadline, entering the bidding process long after Falk
had orchestrated a three-team deal that insured the Nets of getting
the Timberwolves' young floor leader.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Checketts said at the time that other forces might have been at
work to prevent the Knicks from getting Marbury _ a thinly veiled
reference to behind-the-scenes maneuvering by Falk.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Payton Is Unhappy  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   After a loss to Portland on April 28, Seattle's Gary Payton
fumed. In front of teammates and reporters, he blurted out to his
agent, Aaron Goodwin, ``Aaron, you got to do something about
this!'' The two retreated to another room to discuss the matter.
</P>
<P>
   It was the clearest sign yet that the All-Star point guard was
fed up in Seattle, which did not qualify for the playoffs at 25-25,
and was apparently interested in forcing an off-season trade.
Goodwin admits that his client is unhappy, but also said last week
that the chances of Payton's winding up in New York or anywhere
else are slim.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's false that he has asked to be traded and that he wants
Wally Walker's head to roll,'' Goodwin said, referring to the
Sonics' general manager. ``I won't let him deny that he's unhappy
and that he wants change. This is a player who has won an average
of 56 games the last six seasons. But he wants to finish his career
in Seattle.''
</P>
<P>
   Goodwin added: ``I can tell you now that Seattle has no thoughts
about moving him. He's not going to New York unless they're willing
to give a franchise player back, and I can't see the Knicks wanting
Gary without also having Patrick.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked if Payton's relationship with Paul Westphal, who replaced
George Karl as coach after last season, could lead to Payton's
departure, Goodwin said: ``He's got a good relationship with Paul.
It's not like his relationship with George Karl, but those things
take time. With the lockout, there wasn't an opportunity for that
relationship to jell this season.''
</P>
<P>
   Payton may be the league's most accomplished floor leader, but
his constant mood swings have been a source of angst for the team's
front office, a fact that may ultimately lead to the team moving
him. He has three years left on his current contract at $12
million, $13 million and $14 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't see him traded, but stranger things have happened,''
Goodwin said. ``Hey, Gary's a high-octane person. That's him.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Union Notes Higher Pay &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Billy Hunter, executive director of the players association,
sent an end-of-the-season mailing to his constituency last
Wednesday. Comparing salaries before and after the new
collective-bargaining agreement, the letter seems to dispel the
notion that the union was pummeled during the contentious labor
negotiations that led to the shortened season.
</P>
<P>
   The average salary jumped from about $2.3 million to $2.8
million; the median salary went from $1.4 million to $1.7 million.
For the first time, there are veteran players (those with more than
10 years experience) making the $1 million salary exception that
both sides agreed to. The 22 players earning the $1 million
exception would most likely have been making much less under the
old agreement.
</P>
<P>
   Last season, 74 players made $1 million to $2 million. This
year, 112 players made that much. Over all, the players took in
$1.12 billion in nonprorated salaries _ a 17 percent increase from
last season.
</P>
<P>
   While the middle class is clearly doing better, the major
concession by the union _ putting limits on high-end salaries _ has
affected some of the game's marquee players. In particular, Kobe
Bryant and Allen Iverson signed deals far below what they could
have commanded in a bidding war. But only one player, Rik Smits,
hit the absolute ceiling for veteran limits; the Pacers center
 &UR; settled &LR;  for $14 million a season.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Sprewell Is Litigious &LR;
</P>
<P>
   More than 18 months after his suspension for choking P.J.
Carlesimo, Latrell Sprewell's continuing attempt to recoup lost
money from the NBA and the Golden State Warriors keeps costing him.
</P>
<P>
   According to an NBA official, Sprewell must pay roughly $150,000
in court costs for the league and the team after a federal judge in
San Francisco rejected his lawsuit for a second time last month and
ordered Sprewell to compensate the defendants.
</P>
<P>
   Sprewell's lawyers argued that many of the hours billed by the
league's lawyers were extraneous, and an exact fee has yet to be
agreed upon. Meanwhile, Sprewell presses on.
</P>
<P>
   Despite urgings from the players association and others to drop
the case, Sprewell has given his lawyers the go-ahead to file yet
another appeal.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
