<SLUG> BC-BKN-RHODEN-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORS COLUMN: THE FATHER UNDERSTANDS THE PRESSURE HIS SON FACES  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ky., Tenn.)   By WILLIAM C. RHODEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ You could hear the relief in Wade Houston's voice. He
was flying here for Game 1 of the Knicks-Heat playoff series, and
he was glad to be going as a father and a fan _ not a coach.
</P>
<P>
   It has been a crazy season in the National Basketball
Association, especially for the supposedly underachieving Knicks,
and no one, including Houston's son, Allan, has been spared
scrutiny. Now every game seems like some sort of referendum on
which players will stay, which will go. The longtime general
manager, Ernie Grunfeld, has been demoted. The head coach, Jeff Van
Gundy, reads every day that his job is on the line and endures open
speculation over who might take his place.
</P>
<P>
   There may have been a time when Wade Houston missed the coaching
business _ when he yearned a little to get back in _ but this
season, more than any in the last four years, has weaned him away.
Fandom is just fine.
</P>
<P>
   ``The longer you're away from it, the more you mellow,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   As a former coach, Houston can empathize with Van Gundy. He was
the head basketball coach at the University of Tennessee from the
1989-90 season until March 1994, when he resigned after a 5-22
season. The highlight of his career was having the opportunity to
coach Allan for each of his seasons at Tennessee. But Wade also
remembers the cruel, public process of job evaluation.
</P>
<P>
   ``You review tapes of a game and you hear announcers saying that
there are rumblings in Knoxville, and that the word is your job is
on the line,'' Houston recalled. ``Then recruits start to hear
this, and it's used against you by other coaches. Then it becomes
an uphill struggle. There are so many things, whether it's Ernie or
Jeff or me, that you can't control. It makes coaching a pretty
tough profession.''
</P>
<P>
   Allan Houston grew up around basketball. Wade Houston started
coaching at the high school level in 1966, five years before Allan
was born. He earned $200 as an assistant junior varsity coach,
$5,100 a year as a teacher.
</P>
<P>
   ``We coached because we loved the kids, we loved to impact
them,'' Houston said. ``From then to what it's come to now, is just
full circle.''
</P>
<P>
   Houston became an assistant coach at Louisville in 1976 under
Denny Crum, and recruited much of the Cardinals' outstanding
talent. Allan was 15 when the Cardinals won the National Collegiate
Athletic Association championship in 1986 and, as expected, he made
a committed to go to Louisville in 1989. Then Wade Houston made the
decision to leave Louisville and took the head job at Tennessee,
where he became the first black head coach in the Southeastern
Conference.
</P>
<P>
   Houston was dismissed as the Tennessee head coach in 1994. There
were possibilities of another job, but finally he decided he did
not want to go through it again.
</P>
<P>
   ``I probably could have had another job, but as I got more
involved in our business I became more removed from coaching,'' he
said. ``The time away provided me with a lot of time to reflect on
where I'd been, where I am, where I want to go.''
</P>
<P>
   Houston decided there were more pressing things than coaching _
like family, home and his own business to attend to. He is now the
president and chief executive officer of Mavis Specialized Carrier
Company in Louisville, Ky., a truck transportation business he
started in 1982. His wife, Alice, is the president of one of the
four divisions of the company.
</P>
<P>
   His oldest daughter, Lynn, became a two-time Atlantic Coast
Conference high jump champion at Georgia Tech. She begins graduate
school in engineering this fall and is pointing to the Olympic
trials. His youngest daughter, Natalie, begins medical school this
fall.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just been a Godsend to get a chance to spend time with
the family, to sit up in the stands and watch a track meet when
there were maybe 25 or 30 people there,'' he said. ``I've had a
chance to watch her over the last three or four years, which I
couldn't have done had I been coaching.''
</P>
<P>
   Allan, meanwhile, has been near or at the center of controversy
this season, ever since the Knicks traded for Latrell Sprewell. Can
the two guards coexist? Does Houston need to be less of a coach's
son and more of an aggressive gunner?
</P>
<P>
   ``I think they could complement each other very well,'' Wade
Houston said. ``It's not something that will happen overnight, and
it has not happened overnight. But when it happens _ I looked at
how the better team over the last several years has been Chicago.
When you look at what made them successful, they had a lot of
interchangeable players, players that could do a lot of things. So
hopefully, adding more interchangeable players to the Knicks could
make some of those things happen for them.''
</P>
<P>
   He doesn't feel Allan has to become selfish.
</P>
<P>
   ``Allan was part of the team concept,'' he said. ``He was always
listening to me talk about how the parts fit together to make the
team better _ even before he started playing for me. Getting people
involved on the team is important. He has enough skills, if they
want him to step up and do more, he has the ability to do that.
He'll do whatever they want him to do.''
</P>
<P>
   In any event, Wade Houston has his own life. He, Alice and Allan
will visit on Sunday, then Wade will fly to Detroit on Monday for a
business meeting. He really doesn't have any playoff predictions.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't have home-court advantage, so that's big,'' he said
of the Knicks. ``You just have to figure out a way to get some wins
on the road.''
</P>
<P>
   You get the distinct sense from Wade Houston that he's relieved
he doesn't have to go figure. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
