<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-08 17:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9464 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCHOOL-SUMMIT-0509-CO     05-08 0872
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCHOOL-SUMMIT-0509-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    POLICYMAKERS INFLUENTIAL PEOPLE RESPOND TO ANTI-VIOLENCE PLEAS
 &HT;    By ANDREW MOLLISON 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Catherine Murphy, a public housing policewoman in
New York City, engulfed Tom Mauser of Littleton, Colo., in a hug of
welcome and consolation.
</P>
<P>
   ``This year must be the year when enough is enough,'' Murphy
said Saturday in the East Room of the White House. Her son
Christopher was 11 in 1997 when he was shot to death in a
preventable accident by a gun stored unsafely in a neighbor's
house.
</P>
<P>
   ``What is it about our society that has gone wrong?'' asked
Mauser, whose son Daniel was 15 when he, a dozen other teenagers
and a teacher were slain by two teen gunmen in Columbine High
School last month. ``We may have the freedom to bear arms in this
nation, but we don't have freedom from fear.''
</P>
<P>
   Leaders from the White House, both parties in Congress and the
gun, movie, television, video-game, Internet and recording
industries -- as well as national groups of parents, clergy, law
enforcement officers and teachers -- will start responding this
week to those passionate pleas and the national agony that erupted
in the wake of the shootings in Littleton.
</P>
<P>
   Louis Sullivan, former Secretary of Health and Human Services in
the Bush administration, compared the massacre to an airplane crash
that leads to reforms in air safety.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are tragedies, but one special benefit may be that they
focus more sustained and serious national attention on the fact
that we have a problem,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In the week ahead:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  President Clinton will lead a ``strategy session'' of
representatives of all those groups Monday around a U-shaped table
in the White House. They will plan the formation of a nonprofit
organization that would lead public and private efforts to protect
children from violence, just as similar organizations worked to
lower teenage pregnancy rates, find jobs for welfare recipients and
encourage volunteerism in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will talk about how we can shield our children from
gratuitous violence, keep parents involved in their children's
lives, reach out to troubled young people early enough, and do more
to keep guns out of their reach,'' Clinton said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott, R-Miss., has scheduled a
debate to begin Tuesday on a juvenile delinquency bill. He said it
will include a chance for senators to offer amendments that could
add tighter limits on explosives and guns to the bill which revamps
federal programs that help states and localities cope with young
lawbreakers.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  House Speaker Dennis Hastert, R-Ill., has endorsed the White
House meeting, and said that he and Lott will also proceed with
their plans for a Republican-sponsored ``national dialogue on youth
and culture'' at locations outside of Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Touching all bases in the multi-sided process of
solution-seeking, Hastert said, ``While we should look at school
safety and gun violence, we also must examine other influences on
our society, such as drugs, video games, the entertainment
industry, the Internet, school prayer, parental responsibility and
family involvement.''
</P>
<P>
   He and Lott spoke separately about how moved they had been by
private pleas from parents at Columbine High School for help in
avoiding future massacres.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, gun control advocates took heart from a new,
tentative offer communicated to the White House by the makers and
sellers of firearms. Though stopping short of endorsing all of
Clinton's gun control proposals, the American Shooting Sports
Council went far beyond concessions offered since Littleton by
leaders of the National Rifle Association, the country's biggest
gun-owners' group.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're things we've been looking at and discussing for as
long as two years with Philadelphia Mayor Ed Rendell and the U.S.
Conference of Mayors,'' said Robert A. Ricker, executive director
of the council, which he described as an association of ``all
segments of the firearm, ammunition and shooting sports accessory
industry.''
</P>
<P>
   He said that, if the proposals are properly worded, the council
would accept a lifetime ban on gun sales to a juvenile convicted of
a violent felony; instant background checks for sales at gun shows;
raising the 18-year minimum age for gun purchases to 21; mandatory
tracing of all guns found at crime scenes, and laws holding adults
criminally responsible for allowing children unsupervised access to
guns.
</P>
<P>
   However, he said it would not support three other proposals
endorsed by Handgun Control, Inc.: restoration of the three-day
waiting limit before a gun sale; a limit of one gun sale per month
to an individual; and mandatory packaging of an optional trigger
lock with every gun sold.
</P>
<P>
   ``It does look like they are making some reasonable
concessions,'' Naomi Paiss, communications director for Handgun
Control, said Saturday. ``The fact that gun manufacturers recognize
that it does not help their cause to be providing their products to
kids and to criminals shows that some progress may be made in the
Senate this time.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
