<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-HASEK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HASEK, HOCKEY'S MOZART, SEEKS MORE HIGH NOTES WITH THE SABRES 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By ROBIN FINN    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Some people shrug into a hair shirt. Some attend
confession. Some cast the blame like a fishing line. For Dominik
Hasek, all it took was an afternoon of playing the focal point, and
voluntary target, in an up-tempo series of decapitation drills at a
suburban practice rink Friday to atone for the fact that he came up
uncharacteristically mortal in Game 1 of the Eastern Conference
semifinal series between his Buffalo Sabres and the Boston Bruins.
</P>
<P>
   ``I get over the loss only by working to get ready for the next
game,'' said the 34-year-old Hasek, who can even the series here
Sunday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   Also, Hasek savors the chance to remind Bruins goalie Byron
Dafoe, who upstaged him by 10-9 in the shutout stakes during the
regular season and leads Hasek by 2-1 in 1999 playoff shutouts,
just who the real understudy is in this series.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not personal,'' said Hasek, who rates the late-blooming
Dafoe among the top five goalies in the league. ``I like the way he
plays. He'll try to make the save even if it looks impossible.''
</P>
<P>
   Those kind of saves are pure Hasek, who flutters, flops and
flails like a drowning man, or a drowning butterfly, while tackling
rebounds that would provoke most goalies to surrender. With joints
that have apparently been reinforced by Silly Putty and a mind that
works like a camera shutter, Hasek makes impossible stops with
regularity, but not always.
</P>
<P>
   The Dominator unwittingly played the Accommodator in a 4-2 loss
to the Bruins on Thursday night at the Fleet Center, where his woes
included a catastrophic second period in which he yielded two goals
on four shots. Hasek was so bad, he inspired the hometown crowd to
bay like a pack of wolves when they weren't taunting him by
botching his name: ``Heah-shick! Heah-shick!''
</P>
<P>
   If he heard, he didn't let on. His powers of concentration,
after all, are legendary, and at one time or another have enabled
him to tune out everything and everyone from the former Buffalo
coach Ted Nolan, who received his walking papers after receiving
Hasek's cold shoulder, to the Czech army, which suspended him after
he refused to tend goal for the military team in a game that would
have caused the certain demotion of his boyhood club.
</P>
<P>
   No wonder the Boston hecklers failed to move him.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the lithe little guy who cannot fathom why the
chroniclers of sport insist on calling him the masked Mozart of his
genre _ ``How can you compare the Mozart of music to a hockey
player who stops pucks?'' Hasek said _ simply played on until the
bitter end. At that point, the Bruins scored an empty net goal, and
Hasek could be seen glowering behind his wire cage while confined
to the bench in favor of a sixth but ineffectual attacker.
</P>
<P>
   The Sabres trampled the Ottawa Senators in the first round, when
Hasek yielded a stingy six goals on 162 shots. It prompted more
than one Senator to speculate that the entire Czech Republic, which
declared the goaltender a god after he pulled off the gold-medal
shutout of Russia last year at the Olympics in Nagano, Japan, might
be onto something. But then Hasek fell to earth in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was average,'' he said, curling his lip around the forbidden
word as he sipped a succession of post-practice sodas in the lobby
bar of his Boston hotel.
</P>
<P>
   He was the only man in the place who wasn't nursing his first
cocktail of the weekend, not to mention the only man bereft of a
tie. With Hasek's sugar high came clarity. No, he did not
contemplate jumping out the window after his subpar evening brought
his undefeated 1999 playoff streak to a screeching halt. Not when
he finished the season with a career-best 1.87 goals-against
average and a personal as well as league-best .937 save percentage.
While he admits to a few sleepless nights when he was convinced his
mistakes cost his team a game, nights attested to by the gray hairs
that dust his sideburns, Thursday was not one of them.
</P>
<P>
   ``On two of the goals, I never even saw the puck, so I couldn't
really get mad at myself,'' Hasek said, ``and anyway, I'd never get
so depressed about losing a game that I'd jump out the window or
something.''
</P>
<P>
   After all, his college history degree tells him that it is far
better to learn from one's mistakes than flee them.
</P>
<P>
   ``All I want to do is win,'' he said, ``and I try to do
everything I can to make sure I win. But if you lose, then you're
sad, and that's all there is to it. I didn't feel I made big
mistakes in Game 1, but that doesn't mean I don't think about every
goal that went in. It doesn't mean I can't be better in my next
game.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, average, for Hasek, is inadmissible. This is the
Vezina trophy czar who, a year after becoming the league's first
goalie most valuable player in 35 years in 1997, coolly pocketed
the award again in 1998. That feat followed an Olympic tournament
that flowed like an aria: six games played, six goals allowed, and
a 20-save crescendo shutout against Russia in the gold-medal
finale.
</P>
<P>
   That performance turned him into a national hero back home,
where the Czech president, Vaclav Havel, suggested that Hasek
succeed him as head of state. Not bad for a goalie who was drafted
199th overall by the Blackhawks in 1983 (he waited six years to
go), was a flop in 1989 in his debut as a high school history
teacher (he lasted two months, just long enough to earn a college
degree), and cheerfully limits his domestic skills to ``taking out
the garbage and changing light bulbs.''
</P>
<P>
   While Hasek has no designs on Havel's job, he has already used
his chess master's skills to think ahead to what he will do when he
gets tired of stopping pucks. The next step for Hasek could happen
sooner rather than later, particularly if Buffalo decides not to
honor his $7 million-a-season contract through 2002.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I would be traded by Buffalo, then maybe I would say I
don't want to play anymore,'' he said. ``If that happens, I think I
can be almost 100 percent sure that I would say goodbye to
hockey.''
</P>
<P>
   Hasek has started a sportswear firm, Dominator, in the Czech
Republic, and plans outposts for the United States and Canada.
``Already I'm on the phone to Prague almost every day talking about
the business, about quotas and things.''
</P>
<P>
   Hasek still does splits that could make a cheerleader blush, but
with a tiny hernia in his groin after 30 years of snuffing shots,
tending profit splits instead of goal is starting to have its
appeal.
</P>
<P>
   With the exception of winning a Stanley Cup, there is not much
left undone in hockey for Hasek, who learned his craft at age 4 in
the doorway of the kitchen in Pardubice. He and his mother lived
with his maternal grandparents while his father worked 100 miles
away in a uranium mine. Every night, while his grandmother prepared
dinner, his grandfather tossed tennis balls at Hasek, who plied his
body like a carnival contortionist to stop them.
</P>
<P>
   ``My grandmother would be mad at me because I was always jumping
around and kicking her ankles while she was trying to cook,'' Hasek
said. ``Right there by the hot stove, that's where I learned my
style and started my career.''
</P>
<P>
   Right there in chilly Buffalo, with or without a Stanley Cup, is
where he wants to end it.
</P>
</TEXT>
