<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-08 18:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9470 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HEROIN-PDOPE-NYT &LR;      05-08 0425
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEROIN-PDOPE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW EXTRA-STRENGTH HEROIN: IS IT THE PURITY OR THE ADDITIVES? 
</HEADLINE>
   (sidebar with HEROIN-COUPLE)  
 (bl)  
 By CHRISTOPHER S. WREN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ As a nickname for heroin, P-dope has been around for
years. But among many current users, the belief has spread that
distributors are doctoring P-dope with adulterants to make it cut
through methadone, the heroin blocker, to avoid losing customers to
treatment clinics.
</P>
<P>
   Doctors who have studied addiction are skeptical, attributing
P-dope's greater potency to its purity.
</P>
<P>
   Jon Struan-Parker, who runs the AIDS Brigade, which distributes
clean syringes, agrees with the addicts. P-dope, he says, is cut
with anesthetics like lidocaine or procaine to hook users faster
and heighten their cravings. ``This is the crack of heroin,''
Struan-Parker said. ``It's more deadly.''
</P>
<P>
   A former heroin addict, Struan-Parker said the old heroin, cut
with quinine, left a user feeling blissfully mellow. ``When you do
P-dope,'' he said, ``you got a chip on your shoulder, you got an
attitude.''
</P>
<P>
   Other addicts collecting sterile syringes at his needle-exchange
table on 125th Street agreed that the heroin is being doctored.
Gerardo Ramos said, ``I'm on 80 milligrams of methadone, and it
goes right through.''
</P>
<P>
   But Dr. John Morgan, a professor of pharmacology at the City
University of New York Medical School, said that adding lidocaine
or procaine to heroin should not make it more addictive. Morgan,
who has studied the pharmacology of marijuana and other drugs,
suggested that P-dope's extraordinary purity was at fault.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was the low purity of heroin traditionally that caused
people to inject it,'' Morgan said. ``If it's a high enough purity,
it will override methadone.''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Edwin Salsitz, the director of a pilot methadone
prescription program at Beth Israel Medical Center, said the street
culture could also lead some addicts to sabotage their own
methadone treatment. ``Very often, these people don't have much
socialization outside of drugs,'' Salsitz said. ``They're
injecting, hanging around. It's not considered nice to pass up the
heroin.''
</P>
<P>
   Terry Furst, a sociological researcher who teaches at John Jay
College of Criminal Justice, said active adulterants in heroin have
proliferated since 1995. Because lidocaine and procaine reduce the
melting point of heroin base so it can be smoked more easily, he
speculated that some P-dope was created for smoking but was being
snorted and injected instead.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
