<DOCNO> NYT19990508.0157 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-08 18:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9471 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SOCCER-PLAYING-MOMS-A     05-08 1143
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOCCER-PLAYING-MOMS-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GETTING THEIR KICKS, WITH AN EYE ON THEIR KIDS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.C., Calif., Fla.)  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(jt) 
 By JERE LONGMAN    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   They were pioneers as American soccer players, star defenders on
teams that won a world championship in 1991 and an Olympic gold
medal in 1996, and now they are plowing new cultural ground as
soccer moms.
</P>
<P>
   Last December, facing six months on the road in preparation for
next month's Women's World Cup, residing at a training camp in
Orlando, Fla., and barnstorming the United States and Portugal to
play tune-up games, Joy Fawcett and Carla Overbeck negotiated to
have the U.S. soccer federation pay for a nanny to accompany the
team and to help care for their young children.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't pay for day care at home; we are our own day care,''
Overbeck said. ``We didn't think we should have to incur those
expenses in being uprooted for six months. The federation was
willing to help out. A big headache has been relieved.''
</P>
<P>
   There is no professional soccer league for women in the United
States, so the top players get their prime competition with the
national team, which can travel two or three weeks a month. In
previous years, Fawcett and Overbeck had to pay for their own nanny
on the road. The players split the cost and used friends or their
mothers as baby sitters. But flights, hotel rooms and meals added
up to big expenses, especially on international trips.
</P>
<P>
   ``We smuggled a lot of food from team meals,'' Overbeck said
with a laugh.
</P>
<P>
   She and Fawcett belong to the first generation of women able to
fully explore the possibilities of Title IX, the 1972 federal law
that essentially prohibited discrimination against women in
collegiate and high school sports. The two players have sought to
secure from U.S. Soccer, the national governing body, some of the
rights that women have attained in the corporate workplace, such as
maternity leave and child care.
</P>
<P>
   ``This gives a lot of hope for women's sports,'' said Nicolette
Richards, a 19-year-old who is taking time off from San Diego State
to work as a nanny for Fawcett and Overbeck. ``I think it's awesome
that the federation is so accepting and understanding. These girls
are like any other women who want to have a family, children and a
career.''
</P>
<P>
   Sports differs from most occupations in that the workplace is
constantly on the move, and women's soccer requires even more time
away from home. The Women's National Basketball Association, for
example, has no day care provision for its players, but they seldom
travel more than several days at a time. By contrast, Fawcett and
Overbeck are effectively on a six-month road trip, away from their
husbands and relatives except for a week's break each month, as
they prepare for the World Cup. During the three-week competition,
the children will attend the matches, but they will have to stay
with their fathers and other relatives so their mothers can
concentrate on soccer.
</P>
<P>
   The federation has budgeted $50,000 for the nanny, removing a
huge financial weight from the soccer moms, who, like their
teammates, are paid by U.S. Soccer and have endorsement contracts,
but play a sport where the average salary for the top Americans is
$30,000 to $40,000 a year. Some players, like Overbeck, work second
jobs as college coaches, while others have also played in
international leagues.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think U.S. Soccer has been very progressive,'' said Tony
DiCicco, the coach of the women's national team. ``They felt it was
the right thing to do, and they felt that the players had paid
their dues and had been here when there wasn't a lot happening
internationally for women's soccer. For them to be able to continue
their careers, they needed to do this.''
</P>
<P>
   Fawcett, 31, has long been considered by DiCicco to be the
world's best defender. She has two daughters _ Katey, who will be 5
in a week, and Carli, who will turn 2 this month. When Carli was
born in 1997, Fawcett was coaching the UCLA women's soccer team,
commuting two hours each way from her home in Orange County,
Calif., while also coaching a youth team and playing on the
national team.
</P>
<P>
   ``Breast-feeding at halftime, or on the sideline, that can get
interesting,'' Fawcett said. ``It's like, `I'll be back in a
minute.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Overbeck, who is celebrating her 31st birthday Sunday and and
who won four national championships at the University of North
Carolina, is a co-captain of the national team, which also won the
bronze medal in the 1995 Women's World Cup, and the player who sets
the bar in terms of fitness and preparation. Teammates and team
officials said she ran stadium steps during her ninth month of
pregnancy and lifted weights the day she delivered her son,
Jackson, who is 20 months old.
</P>
<P>
   Both Fawcett and Overbeck were important bricks in the
foundation of U.S. women's soccer, playing on the national team
that won the initial Women's World Cup in 1991. When the players
returned from China and told others they were world champions,
Overbeck said the frequent response was, ``We didn't even know you
had a team.''
</P>
<P>
   Five years later, the American women played in front of 76,481
in Athens, Ga., to win the Olympic gold medal and convince
officials that the 1999 Women's World Cup should be moved from
small stadiums on the East Coast into the same arenas that housed
the 1994 men's World Cup.
</P>
<P>
   The team's success turned its stars into role models for the 7
million girls who play soccer in this country, including Richards,
who said she jumped at the chance to become the nanny. As a high
school player in Coeur d'Alene, Idaho, Richards had posters of team
stars like Mia Hamm, Julie Foudy and Kristine Lilly on her wall.
``My brother had Michael Jordan to look up to,'' Richards said.
``This was the start of girls having someone to look up to.''
</P>
<P>
   The women's national team travels with equipment bags and diaper
bags, a double stroller, car seats, a bag of soccer balls for the
players and a bag of toys for the kids. Richards earns $750 a week
and has her living and travel expenses paid by the soccer
federation.
</P>
<P>
   When the team is training in Orlando, Richards lives with
Fawcett, her two daughters and Shannon MacMillan, a forward on the
national team.
</P>
<P>
   On the road, Richards gets her own hotel room. And she is
getting a crash course on the joys and responsibilities of
motherhood.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I could take any break from school, this is the perfect
one,'' Richards said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's also the best birth control that money can buy. I've
decided I'm going to wait until I'm more than ready to have kids.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   During camp, Overbeck lives in a home in Orlando with her son
and teammates Foudy and Lilly. ``They do everything,'' Overbeck
said of Foudy and Lilly. ``Well, they haven't changed a diaper yet.
I'm waiting for that.''
</P>
<P>
   Like Fawcett, Overbeck rooms with her child in hotels.
</P>
<P>
   The mothers say that Richards and their teammates have been
indispensable, watching the kids during practice, helping to feed
and bathe them, taking them swimming and on walks, playing on the
computer, coloring in coloring books.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like having 20 aunts,'' Richards said.
</P>
<P>
   It is still rare to see mothers in international soccer.
MacMillan, who played professionally in Japan in 1996 and 1997,
said players there quit the sport when they get married. When the
Japanese national team came to Atlanta and Charlotte, N.C., to play
the Americans in two recent World Cup tune-ups, the Japanese
players seemed surprised and happy, yet a bit wistful, to find that
Fawcett and Overbeck could continue their careers as mothers,
MacMillan said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Seeing our players doing it as mothers gives them hope that
they may be able to do it, too,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Like many working mothers, however, Fawcett and Overbeck have
conflicted emotions. Feeling pressure that was either real or
self-imposed, Fawcett returned to scrimmaging with the national
team three weeks after Katey was born in 1994 because ``I was too
scared to say no.''
</P>
<P>
   Overbeck, who took a year off after the Olympics, was back
playing seven weeks after her son was born. ``You start thinking,
`Am I going to be able to play at that same level mentally and
physically?' '' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The kids miss their fathers, and the fathers miss their kids.
Inevitably, there are tearful departures when the mothers and
children leave home. Greg Overbeck, a restaurateur in Chapel Hill,
N.C., tries to see his son every two weeks. Walter Fawcett, a
computer analyst, relocated from Southern California to Florida
during previous training camps, Joy said, but was unable to do so
this year for the World Cup. He puts his daughters to bed when they
are home, but now he does it by phone, a continent away.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's tough, it's hard, but I understand why we go through it,
and I totally support what Carla is doing,'' Greg Overbeck said.
``To see how far they have come is amazing. Before the 1991 World
Cup, they didn't get paid, there was no insurance, no exposure, no
endorsements. Not enough to make a living at it. Carla worked at an
elementary school.''
</P>
<P>
   After 1991, many players might have quit, he said, except that
women's soccer was being considered for the Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   ``They had sacrificed relationships and careers, put everything
on hold, then they reached the pinnacle and had nothing to show for
it,'' he said. ``They were very discouraged. To turn around and see
what they've become, it's great for women.''
</P>
<P>
   Fawcett and Overbeck want to play in the 2000 Olympics in
Sydney, Australia, and team officials said they believed the nanny
program would continue. But Katey Fawcett will be in kindergarten
next year and has already signed up to play in a soccer league at
home. Joy said she hoped the Olympic training camp would be in
California instead of Florida.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the beginning, I questioned whether this was good for the
kids,'' Fawcett said. ``I talked to other moms, and their kids eat
at 8 and sleep at 12, and it's all so regular. My kids eat when
they can, sleep in the stroller. But they're adaptable. Things
don't bother them too much. I think it's good. They get to see the
world, and it allows me to play soccer.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
