<HEADER>
A9473 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EDIT-GIULIANI-SCHOOLS     05-08 0807
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-GIULIANI-SCHOOLS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: POLITICS AND THE SCHOOLS 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Sunday, May 9:
</P>
<P>
   Term limits being what they are in New York City, Mayor Rudolph
Giuliani's present job ends on Dec. 31, 2001. Thus, the mayor has
been casting an eye on other possibilities, most noticeably a run
for the U.S. Senate in the year 2000. Such yearnings are now
raising questions about how well the mayor is balancing his quest
for a new national office next year with his management of the most
important and diverse city in the world. To put it more bluntly,
will the mayor's political ambitions harm New York City?
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani bridles at the question, but it has begun to register
on the city's political sensors in a number of ways, most noisily
these days on the issue of education. In some ways, the mayor has
been acting like a man trying to rewrite the recent history of the
New York City public school system. He says the system should be
``blown up.'' He has been freezing out his Chancellor, once a
cigar-smoking pal who did the mayor's bidding until he threatened
to resign over the Giuliani voucher plan and blindsided the mayor
with a public defense of the school system. Giuliani wants to
abolish the Board of Education, which he has now shown that he can
control, and he is also pushing changes that, while politically
correct within the Republican Party, may not work as well for 1.1
million public school students in New York City.
</P>
<P>
   If this is an effort to revamp the system before next year's
election, or simply to ``stir things up,'' as he puts it, it is
awfully late. If it is an effort for the mayor to say that the last
five years at city schools were somebody else's problem, it doesn't
work. The New York City school system may be a political hot
potato, but it belongs on Giuliani's plate.
</P>
<P>
   The mayor has vigorously denied any political motives for these
latest outbursts. He is right, of course, that the reforms he is
pushing now are not recent additions to his political agenda. But
the urgency and harshness of his effort are a new development. With
time running short before next year's campaign, the mayor is
stepping up the pressure to start an experiment with vouchers, to
halt social promotion and to dismantle the school boards and Board
of Education.
</P>
<P>
   We favor dismantling the boards, while recognizing that the
effort faces many hurdles. But we have severe misgivings about the
timing, implementation and content of the mayor's other
initiatives. Chancellor Rudy Crew has said he will resign before
starting a voucher program. On social promotions, the chancellor
last Monday hurriedly outlined such a tough plan for next year that
he estimates about 300,000 students could fail. Even in Chicago,
the model city on this issue, a no-pass plan was phased in slowly
to keep from overwhelming the system.
</P>
<P>
   The five-year capital improvement plan suddenly created by the
mayor and his Board of Education majority also invites skeptical
political analysis. The mayor's plan cuts the chancellor's budget
for improving school facilities from $11 billion to $7 billion, an
amount the mayor believes is closer to reality. Of the remaining
funds, larger chunks go to Queens, which desperately needs
facilities, and to Staten Island, where the need is far less
urgent. The mayor says that need is what matters here, not
politics, but the boroughs that won in his plan are more
politically in tune with him than the three that could lose the
most money _ Manhattan, Brooklyn and the Bronx. Moreover, dealing a
chastening loss to the chancellor feels like a major reason for
this vote. Crew has rebelled publicly. Now the mayor has sent his
thunderbolt as a sign he is boss.
</P>
<P>
   It is not only what the mayor is proclaiming on the education
front that is troubling. Some important issues seem to be getting
less emphasis these days. New York City schools are clearly among
the neediest in the state _ a point the mayor made well about three
months ago in Albany.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of squabbling with the chancellor, the mayor should be
pushing the governor and state Legislature to spread the wealth
beyond schools in the Republican-rich suburbs. The STAR program, a
tax cut especially popular in suburban and upstate areas, came with
a promise of more money for prekindergarten and smaller classes.
That promise is now in jeopardy in Albany _ an injustice that the
mayor also has not been battling with his usual fervor.
</P>
<P>
   The mayor may be trying to balance his job overseeing the
schools in all five boroughs with his courting of Republican
campaign donors and upstate voters. A future Senate seat may depend
on what he says, but 1.1 million public school students from all
five boroughs need his support today.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
