<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-CONGRESS-IMMIG-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: FAIR TREATMENT FOR LEGAL IMMIGRANTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   When Congress makes a mistake that inflicts undue hurt on
individuals and their families, it has a duty to correct the
injustice.
</P>
<P>
   Harsh deportation rules adopted in 1996 condemn many productive
legal residents to automatic expulsion based on low-level offenses
they committed long ago, and for which they have paid their debt to
society. The problem arises because Congress failed to draw a
distinction between immigrants who committed murder, rape and other
serious crimes worthy of deportation and those who committed a
minor theft or were found in possession of a small quantity of
drugs. Hundreds of longtime legal residents with minor offenses
have been abruptly wrenched from their families and sent back to
their birth countries.
</P>
<P>
   A corrective measure sponsored by Reps. Barney Frank, D-Mass.,
Martin Frost, D-Texas, and Lincoln Diaz-Balart, R-Fla., would
restore judicial discretion and due process rights that Congress
unwisely obliterated three years ago. Meanwhile, Attorney General
Janet Reno should provide some immediate relief by allowing waivers
in cases already pending when the law went into effect.
</P>
<P>
   On a related issue, Congress has not fully corrected the unfair
treatment of legal immigrants under the 1996 welfare reform law.
The welfare law was primarily intended to move welfare recipients
to work. But it exacted a much harsher, unjust toll on legal
immigrants. It declared them ineligible for many kinds of cash and
nutritional aid, even though legal immigrants pay taxes to support
safety-net programs like everyone else.
</P>
<P>
   Since then Congress has scaled back some of the most drastic
cuts to immigrant children and the disabled, but not enough. A new
bill sponsored by Sen. Daniel Patrick Moynihan, D-N.Y., would fully
restore Supplemental Security Income assistance and food stamp
benefits to all eligible immigrants who were in this country
legally prior to welfare reform, and would restore SSI eligibility
to those who have come after 1996 if they become disabled. It would
also allow states to enroll immigrant children in the new Child
Health Insurance Program and provide Medicaid coverage to pregnant
women and children whenever they arrive.
</P>
<P>
   The cost of the Moynihan proposal would be about $2.7 billion
over five years. That is a small price to restore basic fairness to
immigrants who are a vital part of this society.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-08-99 1822EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990508.0161 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-08 18:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9475 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EDIT-OBSERVER-BANKRUP     05-08 0695
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-OBSERVER-BANKRUPT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL OBSERVER: BANKRUPTCY REFORM THAT SPARES THE WEALTHY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Texas, Fla.)   (bl)  
 By FLOYD NORRIS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Watching a rich man stiff his creditors while walking away with
millions can grate on people. Yet a gaping loophole in the
bankruptcy laws routinely allows that to happen.
</P>
<P>
   That loophole enabled such people as Martin Siegel, the former
investment banker who was convicted of insider trading; former
baseball commissioner Bowie Kuhn and actor Burt Reynolds to emerge
from bankruptcy with ample assets _ sometimes valued in the
millions _ even as their creditors suffered huge losses.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, amid much rhetoric about how outrageous it was that
people who could afford to pay some of their bills were able to
walk away from all of them, the House of Representatives passed a
bankruptcy reform bill. If enacted, the bill will make it much
easier for creditors _ particularly credit card companies _ to
collect money from bankrupts.
</P>
<P>
   But while it will become harder to evade a few thousand dollars
of credit card debt, it will not be any more difficult for
millionaires to shelter their assets while declaring bankruptcy.
</P>
<P>
   The wealthy can often stay millionaires because the laws in a
handful of states _ most notably Florida and Texas _ set no limit
on the value of a home that a bankrupt person can keep even as his
debts are discharged by the court. So some people, as bankruptcy
nears, sell their homes in states like New York and buy
million-dollar homes, for cash, in Florida.
</P>
<P>
   A fair bill would put a limit on the amount of home equity that
could be protected from creditors. The Senate tried to do that last
year, with a limit of $100,000, but that bill was killed. The House
wants no limits on what state legislatures let the rich keep.
</P>
<P>
   The House bill will make life harder for poor and middle-class
people who file for bankruptcy. People whose income has been above
the regional median income will be forced into plans requiring some
repayment of debts, even if future income is likely to be less
because the person has lost his previous job. The calculations
regarding how much a person can afford to pay may not take into
consideration his actual living costs. It is reasonable to try to
force bankrupts to pay what they can afford, but this bill, with
its lack of discretion for bankruptcy trustees and judges, is
likely to bring unreasonable hardship for some.
</P>
<P>
   This bill was pushed by the credit card companies, who worry
that people abuse them by taking on credit card debts and then
going broke. The companies already can challenge any bankruptcy on
fraud grounds, but doing so costs money and may not seem to be
worth it when only a few thousand dollars or less are at stake in
any one filing. They hope that strict rules will enable them to
force many more people to repay at least some money.
</P>
<P>
   The 1990s have seen booms in bankruptcy filings _ and in credit
card issuance. Last year, 1.45 million people filed for bankruptcy,
up 3 percent from 1997, while credit card companies sent out 3.4
billion card solicitations, a 15 percent increase. It would appear
that rising bankruptcies have not yet caused lenders to grow more
cautious.
</P>
<P>
   One interesting feature of the House bill is that it requires
the government to pay for random audits of bankruptcy filings to
see if people are cheating. Yet Congress will not spend money to
let the IRS conduct random audits of tax returns. Protecting Visa's
revenues would seem to be a higher priority than protecting those
of the government.
</P>
<P>
   Two centuries ago, it was common for states to allow creditors
to throw people into prison if they had not paid their debts. But
even then, the creditor had to pay the state the cost of
imprisoning the man. Now, if this bill passes, the taxpayers will
foot the bill to force people to pay their debts.
</P>
<P>
   Unless, of course, they are once-rich people who can afford to
buy expensive houses in Texas or Florida. Those people are to be
protected even as the government cracks down on middle-class people
who have fallen on hard times.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-08-99 1823EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990508.0162 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-08 18:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9477 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AUCTION-GENIUS-KAN &LR;      05-08 1182
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUCTION-GENIUS-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SALE FOCUSES ON A LIFETIME OF MECHANICAL GENIUS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAMES FISHER  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KNOB NOSTER, Mo. _ Last Sunday, five miles northwest of here,
hundreds of cars, trucks and trailers turned 40 acres of tranquil
farmland into a parking lot.
</P>
<P>
   A quarter-mile up the road in another pasture, 1,500 to 2,000
men, women and children _ an authentic throng for a Sunday here in
Johnson County _ ebbed and flowed, following a portable public
address system.
</P>
<P>
   A small country and western concert? A revival? Even an oddly
scheduled field crop demonstration?
</P>
<P>
   Nope. It was an estate sale, the last of three such offerings in
the past couple of months that have netted _ from the holdings of a
man who was essentially a farmer and a blacksmith _ more than
$580,000 for medical research.
</P>
<P>
   Two earlier sales _ bric-a-brac, household furnishings and farm
equipment _ had also drawn droves. Last Sunday's, though, was the
whopper: On sale was what Donald G. Skidmore had been renowned for:
antique machinery, vintage tractors and Model T Fords.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guarantee the news was all over the country _ even
overseas,'' said Don Merrill, who lives in Warrensburg, Mo. ``Had
been for months. You'd hear, `Don Skidmore's stuff is up for
auction,' and people would just say, `When?' He was known all
over.''
</P>
<P>
   Skidmore's genius _ and that word was used unsparingly last
weekend _ was threefold:
</P>
<P>
   He could take an old tractor that had been abandoned for years
in a hedgerow and restore not only its exterior to a gleaming
newness but make its innards hum like the day it came off its
assembly line.
</P>
<P>
   Lacking a part, he could make it from scratch in the shop out
behind his home. Any part.
</P>
<P>
   With an engineer's intuition, he could see faults in an original
design and then come up with a fix that worked better. Skidmore,
incidentally, had only a high school education.
</P>
<P>
   It was a common sight to find Skidmore in the shop behind his
house from dawn to well past dusk shaping wheels, machining gears,
bending sheet metal, cutting steel. Metal work was his passion,
friends said. He didn't drink. Tobacco was anathema, as reflected
by a prominent sign outside the shop put up years ago: ``No Smoking
on This Farm _ No Exceptions.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll tell you how good he was,'' said Charles Swearngin, a
friend and executor of the estate. ``See that little John Deere
crawler over there? Half-scale. A little bulldozer. Look at it
close. Every detail is perfect.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once we were at an Iowa show and, naturally, Don had taken
best of show with that crawler. This old guy comes around, looks
that crawler up and down, and then said he's been a John Deere
dealer for 40 years and he sure didn't recollect the company ever
making any crawlers that small.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don looks right at him and says it was a `very limited
production run.' And that old dealer bought it and walked away
satisfied.''
</P>
<P>
   Swearngin told another story: When Skidmore came up with one of
his simpler ways to do things, say a better way to connect the
transmission linkage so it would last longer, be easier and cheaper
to make and assemble, and mean less servicing, he would fire off a
suggestion to the manufacturer.
</P>
<P>
   ``And pretty soon,''said Swearngin, ``you'd go in the dealership
and there'd be the new model with just what Don had recommended.
Only it was always just a little bit different so they wouldn't
have to pay him any royalties.''
</P>
<P>
   Merrill said Skidmore, a species once common to every village
and hamlet in America but which now has all but disappeared, had a
touch with metal that had to be seen to be believed.
</P>
<P>
   ``One day I found him welding on a pipe tobacco can.'' he said.
``You or I trying that would catch the can on fire, burn it to a
crisp. The metal's that thin. Not Don.''
</P>
<P>
   The other thing recalled about Skidmore was an uncanny ability
to look ahead and figure out what might be valuable.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have to start this by telling you he went in the Army and
got assigned to the motor pool,'' said Swearngin. ``Hated it.
Nothing but Dodges and Chevys. He was a Ford man.
</P>
<P>
   ``What he did, over 50 years ago, was start going around to Ford
dealerships, asking if they had any old Model T or Model A parts.
They did, especially these little-bitty dealers that used to be in
every small town.
</P>
<P>
   ``He went all everywhere _ way out West, down South, back East.
Sometimes he'd pay a little, but usually the dealer would just
throw the stuff at him, glad to get rid of it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don would bring truckloads home _ motors, fenders, frames,
seats, upholstery, absolutely everything. He knew those cars would
make a comeback, that somebody down the road would want them.''
</P>
<P>
   Skidmore, of course, was in the catbird seat. With the detritus
from hundreds of dealerships he was able to build Model T's and
Model A's. Not many. Nor at an assembly-line pace. But when he was
done, he had a virtually new car. Last Sunday, one Model A here,
believe it or not, had two miles on the odometer.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, said Swearngin, Skidmore never was boastful about his
ability to make a silk purse out of a sow's ear. To strangers he
was just a lanky Missouri farmer with worn hands, a craggy face and
a taciturn manner. To his friends he was an original.
</P>
<P>
   Besides running cattle, Skidmore built, among other things, farm
trailers that he'd haul to weekend antique tractor and car shows
and sell. Then he would return home with some old tractor or a load
of fence posts he'd bought or traded for. There were no wasted
trips.
</P>
<P>
   In 1978, Skidmore was diagnosed with pancreatic cancer,
invariably a death sentence. A tumor the size of a grapefruit was
removed. Skidmore recovered.
</P>
<P>
   In 1988 cancer was found in his liver. Chemotherapy held that in
check.
</P>
<P>
   In 1991, Skidmore's wife, Ruby, died. The couple was childless.
</P>
<P>
   Then a couple of years ago Skidmore's heart weakened because of
fluid buildup caused by the ongoing chemotherapy for his liver. He
died in November, age 73, at a Kansas City hospital of congestive
heart failure.
</P>
<P>
   At the sale here last Sunday 30-plus old tractors sold, six of
the remaining Fords (most assembled out of unused parts), plus
hundred of old parts, tools, iron implement seats, trailers, steam
whistles, license plates, even several hog rendering kettles.
</P>
<P>
   The miniature John Deere crawler brought $8,500; the cars $7,500
to $11,000. The total Sunday, said Swearngin, was $260,000. Add
that to $348,000 from the two earlier sales, he said, and there's
well over half a million dollars to be split evenly between the
lung and heart associations.
</P>
<P>
   Which will be a legacy for Skidmore. But maybe a more personal
tribute was paid when auctioneer Densil Allen paused in his
rapid-fire pitch and announced that unlike most sales there
wouldn't be any starting of engines to make sure they ran.
</P>
<P>
   ``We knew Don Skidmore,'' said Allen. ``If it was on his place,
it ran.''
</P>
<P>
   Several people in the crowd smiled and nodded. The engines
remained still. The bidding continued.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
