<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-08 18:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9478 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOORE-TORNADO-KAN &LR;      05-08 1373
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOORE-TORNADO-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR MANY STORM VICTIMS, JOY OF SURVIVAL TRANSCENDS LOSS OF
POSSESSIONS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICK MONTGOMERY  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOORE, Okla. _ Why was Leigh Tucker laughing?
</P>
<P>
   She stood in the flattened remains of her home holding only a
small stack of cards _ her driver's license, voter identification,
video-rental card and Sears charge card. Save for the dining-room
chairs and some coffee-table books, almost everything else had been
blown away. Fifty-nine years' worth of earthly possessions, blown
away.
</P>
<P>
   A year ago Tucker decided to stop making the $50 monthly
payments for homeowners insurance. Oh, she could just kick herself!
She had owned this place nearly 30 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hey, Leigh?'' one of her art students said as he pulled a book
out of the debris. ``This yours?''
</P>
<P>
   And Tucker broke out laughing again: ``Ha, ha, ha _ thank
goodness!'' The book was The Joy of Sex, and yes, it was hers.
</P>
<P>
   You might think Leigh Tucker is acting strangely. But then, has
your house ever been ruined by a tornado? Have you ever crawled out
of a hallway closet, dazed but uninjured, and known what it was
like inside one of the most powerful twisters ever recorded _ what
experts call an F5?
</P>
<P>
   If you were Leigh Tucker, your material possessions might seem
about as valuable as they looked there in the mud, broken and
scattered and coated with dust. Junk, that's all. ``Five-and-dime
goulash,'' as one of Tucker's neighbors described it in Moore, this
ravaged Oklahoma City suburb.
</P>
<P>
   ``You might as well laugh than cry,'' Tucker said. ``I guess I
used to be sort of materialistic, before my father died a few years
back. I'm not that way anymore.''
After the shock
</P>
<P>
   That is a common reaction, said Terry Pace, associate professor
of counseling psychology at the University of Oklahoma in nearby
Norman.
</P>
<P>
   ``For tornado victims who don't lose family members _ and that's
the key distinction _ the first stage is shock: What are we going
to do? But that may last from only a few hours to a day or two,''
Pace said.
</P>
<P>
   ``By now, what you're seeing is a practical focus. ... People
are saying, `OK, we're alive. We've got a lot of work to do.' It's
not just a cliche: The things you really cherish after an event
such as this are your health, your family's health and your
connections with friends.''
</P>
<P>
   At least a half-dozen persons died and 1,000 homes were
destroyed in Moore, population 40,000, where the largest of Monday
night's tornadoes hit full force. Hard adjustments lie ahead, as
hundreds scramble to find temporary housing, schooling for their
children and any federal help available to resume their lives.
</P>
<P>
   By week's end, however, wisecracks and laughter broke through
Tucker's neighborhood of brick, middle-class homes. A photo album
or an heirloom found intact was cause for celebration.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tom, isn't that dresser heavy?'' asked one homeowner to a
younger, burlier neighbor who heaved the bureau onto a Ford truck.
</P>
<P>
   Tom replied: ``Does a one-legged duck walk in circles?''
</P>
<P>
   Joy Watson, 69, silently stared at what remained of her house of
22 years. A few walls. No roof. No garage, no bedrooms or kitchen.
Craft magazines everywhere. Only her husband's neckties dangled in
a skylit closet.
</P>
<P>
   A reporter asked how she was holding up, and Watson gazed deeply
into his face and said, ``Honey, you need some sunscreen.'' She
marched to the cab of her pickup _ the same truck that allowed
Watson and her husband to escape the tornado. She grabbed a tube of
lotion and urged the reporter to use it all.
</P>
<P>
   Watson wore a ratty fishing cap. ``I was so happy to find my
hair curlers in this mess,'' she whispered with a chuckle. ``I
won't have to look like this forever.''
</P>
<P>
   There is misery, and it comes in waves. When the survivors
arrive in the morning to start another cleanup day, the depression
is thick, obvious. When they come back from lunch and view the mess
again, depression returns.
</P>
<P>
   But in the hours between, they help one another and hold
together.
</P>
<P>
   What else can they do?
</P>
<P>
   ``My husband and I have never been through this, so I'm not sure
what happens next,'' said Watson, who for the moment is living in
her son's home. ``We're insured. ... I suppose we get an apartment.
Shop some garage sales. We have to keep living.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe your sense of humor is the last thing to go. If you
don't have that, you're dead.''
A changed landscape
</P>
<P>
   At the height of the storm, Tucker was certain that death raged
behind that closet door, rapping with all its might to get in.
</P>
<P>
   She reached up from her crouched position beneath the coats to
grab the knob with both hands. Even there in the closet, the wind
tossed her hair. Just outside the door it was moving at nearly 300
mph.
</P>
<P>
   Then all turned quiet. Tucker creaked the door open. Where there
once had been a dining room with art deco furniture, salmon-colored
walls and arched entryways, there now was ... daylight.
</P>
<P>
   She stumbled into the yard. What happened to the double garage?
Where was the sunset maple tree with the burning red leaves that
you could see all the way from Interstate 35?
</P>
<P>
   A part-time art teacher, free-lance fashion illustrator and
activist Democrat, she and her ex-husband had bought this house
just out of college. She had raised a daughter here. But in her
last few years alone, with the house paid off, she succumbed to
rising utility bills and her distrust of insurance firms. She
stopped paying her homeowners' premium.
</P>
<P>
   Tucker's driveway was littered with campaign signs that she had
stored in the garage after her failed bid for the state Legislature
in 1996. ``Leigh Tucker _ Your Ticket for Change!'' they read.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly she was facing more change than she had ever thought
possible.
</P>
<P>
   But she was alive.
</P>
<P>
   Her sister in Houston, Dee McCants, would not learn of Tucker's
fate for hours; she drove all the way to Oklahoma as the car radio
blared reports of the tornado damage. Their mother, who is 83, was
so distressed that night, she vomited.
</P>
<P>
   Tucker was grief-stricken the first day. ``What will I do?'' she
asked. ``Where will I stay?'' But when her sister found her, and
her brother Tommy Noah of Oklahoma City found her, the whole family
hugged and wept and eventually laughed. Tucker said she learned
that she hadn't lost what mattered.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now this is art,'' she said Thursday, spreading her arms in
front of a cracked and mud-splattered wall in her old bedroom.
``It's a Pollock! Ha, ha, ha.'' If artist Jackson Pollock could
make millions splattering paint on canvas, Tucker asked, then why
couldn't she make a couple of bucks off this wall?
</P>
<P>
   Acquaintances came calling. ``Oh, Leigh, this is much worse than
you described on the phone,'' one tearful friend said. They would
embrace, Tucker would say, ``Well, you dear,'' and soon they would
burst out laughing about something.
</P>
<P>
   Across the street at the Gannaways, Kevin R. Kemper helped with
the cleanup.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't see how a person gets through this without family,
without friends to support them through the whole process,'' said
Kemper, a Baptist preacher from Hartshorne. ``Some people out there
have nobody, not to mention no insurance. They'll have a hard time
surviving.''
</P>
<P>
   The Gannaways, Butch and Billie, fished through the rubble with
daughter Lori, who drove in from Hartshorne, and with Butch's
brother Harlan and his wife, Anita, who live down the way.
</P>
<P>
   The Gannaways were insured. They survived the tornado by packing
into a storm shelter with 22 other persons and a dog.
</P>
<P>
   Their house was lost. But something strange, almost magical,
happened as Lori crawled beneath a wall that had fallen on the
stereo cabinet. From deep in that mess trickled the faint sound of
a music _ ``Hark! the Herald Angels Sing'' _ and Lori pulled out a
musical snow globe of the Nativity.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't even scuffed.
</P>
<P>
   She set it beside other bits of buried treasure _ the ``Gannaway
Reunion Tape 1990,'' and a video of granddaughter Lauren, now 10,
singing songs when she was a toddler.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're finding those things that we wanted the most,'' Lori
said.
</P>
<P>
   Those are things not even an F5 tornado could destroy.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
