A9482 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BIKE-DOPING-NYT &LR;      05-08 0782
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIKE-DOPING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DOPING INVESTIGATION GATHERS STEAM IN FRANCE
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By SAMUEL ABT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ Patrick Keil, the publicity-shy, 36-year-old magistrate
who leads the French investigation of doping in professional
bicycle racing, has a busy morning ahead of him Monday.
</P>
<P>
   At 9:30 a.m., he is scheduled to meet in his office in the
northern city of Lille with three of the prime figures in what
became known as the Festina Affair in the last Tour de France. They
are Bruno Roussel, the French team's former coach; Willy Voet, a
former masseur, and Richard Virenque, the team's former leading
rider.
</P>
<P>
   This will be their first confrontation since Voet's arrest in a
car full of illegal performance-enhancing drugs last July set off
an investigation that has led so far to the suspension of six
riders and destroyed reputations and friendships. Roussel and Voet
confessed to a systematic program of doping and the two accused
Virenque of participating. The rider's constant defense has been
that he has not failed a drug test.
</P>
<P>
   The three are among 12 people notified by Keil that they were
officially under investigation, a status short of being charged.
Three others have been similarly notified by a magistrate in Reims,
where a drug case involving the TVM team from the Netherlands has
been proceeding more slowly. None of the participants in the Monday
meeting is talking beforehand.
</P>
<P>
   An hour after the Festina gathering, Keil is scheduled to meet
with Hein Verbruggen, the dapper 57-year-old Dutchman who has
headed the International Cycling Union, known as UCI, the overseer
of the sport, since late 1991. Verbruggen was exceedingly willing
to talk beforehand, and to talk caustically.
</P>
<P>
   From his headquarters in Lausanne, Switzerland, he denounced as
nonsense and cheap talk the criticism of UCI suspensions of riders
for six and seven months as too lenient. Charges by French riders
that they are handicapped by new and stringent drug tests that
riders from other countries do not face were dismissed as
``rubbish'' and ``stupid.''
</P>
<P>
   ``How many times did they win last year and the year before in
the classics? Or premier one-day races? I don't know why the French
don't win,'' Verbruggen said. ``But we should stop saying
automatically that those who do win use doping.''
</P>
<P>
   Verbruggen has as many supporters as he has critics.
</P>
<P>
   There is general agreement that Verbruggen has done well for the
sport: as a member of the International Olympic Committee, he
helped open the Olympics to professional riders; he has developed
the World Cup series of classic races into a prestigious contest,
and he has given the computerized point system that ranks riders a
rational importance.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond that, there is less agreement. Supporters claim he has
revolutionized the racing season's calendar, moving the world
championships to October from August and the Vuelta a Espana to
September from May. While the change has revitalized the Spanish
race, critics say it has robbed the championships of some of
racing's biggest stars.
</P>
<P>
   On doping, supporters say that Verbruggen instituted a health
program of testing riders' levels of red blood cells, an indication
of the use of the synthetic hormone EPO, a year before the Festina
Affair exploded. Critics say the tests are badly administered and
are only a rough, easily evaded guide.
</P>
<P>
   As for the Festina Affair, supporters say that he has exerted
himself in quiet damage control that has kept the sport from
falling apart under suspicion. Critics, like l'Equipe, the French
sports newspaper, mock him in print as one of those, still pretty
numerous, who believe there wouldn't be any doping if journalists
didn't write about it.
</P>
<P>
   Because the majority of the nine-man Festina team returned to
action on May 1, the telephone interview focused on their
suspensions. Verbruggen was indignant that the six- and seven-month
suspensions could be considered too short.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think its nonsense to call this a slap on the wrist,'' he
said, adding that the IOC, at a doping conference this winter,
advocated a suspension of six months to two years for a first
offense. ``But the lawyers say no way that they accept two years.
</P>
<P>
   ``My advisers say for a cyclist, the consequences of a two-year
ban are completely different than for a shooter, presumably a
biathlete,'' Verbruggen said. ``A shooter has a career of 40 years
and a cyclist has a career of 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you do this to a cyclist and it is generally accepted that
this means the end of his career _ it is not acceptable. I am
responsible for cycling in 173 countries. We have to have sensible
rules.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
