<DOCNO> NYT19990508.0170 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-08 18:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9485 &Cx1f; tba-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MILLENNIUM-WOMEN-GLAC     05-08 2463
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MILLENNIUM-WOMEN-GLACIER-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A SOCIAL GLACIER ROARS 
</HEADLINE>
   For release: May 16 or thereafter  
 By GAIL COLLINS  
 FROM: The New York Times Magazine  
 c.1999 The New York Times Magazine  
<TEXT>
<P>
   A century ago, people who looked ahead to 2000 had an
exaggerated faith in the promise of pneumatic tubes.
</P>
<P>
   For some reason, when people then thought long-term, they saw
everything from business correspondence to ready-cooked meals
whizzing across town through underground pipes. Nobody imagined
computers.
</P>
<P>
   Funny, the things we can't anticipate.
</P>
<P>
   When I was researching a book on the millennium a few years ago,
I was struck by how people's predictions about the future say much
more about the predictors' own era than about what will happen
next.
</P>
<P>
   Our ancestors were prescient about the invention of the radio,
but never conceived of nuclear warfare _ French cigarette cards in
1899 depicted 21st-century aviators in open planes, dropping little
bomblets on the enemies. A writer for an early edition of Ladies
Home Journal _ the magazine that made its mark by exposing the
evils of the patent medicine trade _ looked forward to our current
era and decided that we would all be fit, very fit: ``A man or
woman unable to walk 10 miles at a stretch will be regarded as a
weakling.''
</P>
<P>
   H. G. Wells, who had a particular horror of the clunky
19th-century kitchen, predicted the coal-burning stove would be
replaced by a ``neat little range heated by electricity'' that
would make cooking ``a pleasant amusement for intelligent invalid
ladies.'' We're still waiting for his self-cleaning windows.
</P>
<P>
   Until just a few years ago, women who dreamed of an independent
and fulfilling future generally started thinking they had to
separate themselves from men. The utopians drew pictures of
all-female communes or Amazonian civilizations, and those hoping
for a real-life career in which they could control their own
destinies generally applied to a convent.
</P>
<P>
   It was only recently _ speaking in millennial terms _ that
average women saw the possibility of achieving equality in the same
world as the opposite sex.
</P>
<P>
   Virginia Woolf thought that having a room of one's own and an
income of 500 pounds a year would do the trick. The flapper
generation, born at the turn of the last century, was the first to
enjoy the outer forms of sexual liberation, such as social drinking
and one-piece bathing suits. But even flappers knew that they had
little of substance, and that their well-being still hinged on
picking the right husband.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, why am I a girl?'' wails one of F. Scott Fitzgerald's
smart, semihysterical heroines, who complains of being born a
hundred years too early, ``with the brains to do everything, yet
tied to the sinking ship of future matrimony.''
</P>
<P>
   Women had no faith in their own ability to support themselves,
but they had confidence that their great-granddaughters would no
longer have to toss down one last cocktail, straighten their
shoulders and marry the wrong man because he was the one with the
money.
</P>
<P>
   Women who had been freed to cut their hair, discard their
corsets and cuddle in the rumble seat with the football hero would
eventually get the vote, get careers and get more efficient birth
control _ and before you knew it, the sinking ship of future
matrimony would be totally optional.
</P>
<P>
   History seldom evolves by tidy progression toward happy endings
_ the Muslims who welcomed Jews and Christians to tolerant kingdoms
like Granada a thousand years ago got driven out by the folks who
gave us the Spanish Inquisition.
</P>
<P>
   But in 20th-century industrialized nations, women really have
kept marching forward. In America, the proportion of women in the
work force has been steadily increasing since those flappers were
in diapers, while the number of children they bear has been
dropping.
</P>
<P>
   Women are now a majority of the electorate. They receive 55
percent of the nation's college degrees and are much more willing
to reinvent themselves as adults by returning to school. They live
longer, and because they survive their husbands they wind up
controlling a large share of the nation's personal wealth.
</P>
<P>
   They own more than a third of the businesses, employ a quarter
of the workers and make up nearly half the students in medical and
law schools. Among two-income families, nearly a quarter of the
wives now earn more than their husbands.
</P>
<P>
   That's a very narrow snapshot _ this is still the same planet on
which many women can be killed by their male relatives for refusing
to marry the man of the family's choice or on the mere suspicion of
promiscuity. The status of women has actually declined in parts of
eastern Europe since the collapse of communism.
</P>
<P>
   But you still might say _ with dozens of qualifications and a
nervous glance over your shoulder _ that women have won. If they
haven't achieved gender equality, then at least they've created the
tools to get it in much of the developed world.
</P>
<P>
   We mate by preference, not out of necessity. We can get all the
education we desire. If we do not all achieve the careers we want,
at least our chances are not dictated by Y-chromosomes.
</P>
<P>
   A romantic modern young man who builds castles in the air
generally presumes that his future wife will help pay the mortgage.
Men who may be chauvinists on the job and patriarchs in the living
room will nevertheless kill to make sure their little girls get all
the opportunities the little boys get.
</P>
<P>
   Given daughters' tendency to stick closer to their parents than
sons do, there is no better hedge against old age than a female
child with a good income.
</P>
<P>
   But it still seems doubtful that women will soon reach full
equality. At the present rate, it will be 2270 before women are as
likely as men to become top managers in corporations and 2500
before there is gender parity in Congress. So far, no culture has
constructed a truly level playing field for sharing family
responsibilities and job opportunity.
</P>
<P>
   ``Women in Sweden have lots of day care, but when you look at
where most of their jobs are, they work in the public sector,''
says Andrew Cherlin, a professor of public policy at Johns Hopkins
University. ``You can't make partner in a Stockholm law firm
working six hours a day. Mothers get more support caring for
children, but it doesn't remove inequities in the labor force.''
</P>
<P>
   We presume that all these things will change as women use their
present and potential power to remake the world. Analyses of how
women will vote and set social policy, in fact, generally seem to
presume that our instincts and priorities are just, well, better.
Women are less enamored of the use of force, leery of quick fixes
and more willing to pay more taxes for social concerns such as
feeding the poor.
</P>
<P>
   If women continue to gain economic and political power, the
government of the 21st century will probably spend more on nursing
homes and home attendants for senior citizens, and on better
schools. There might not necessarily be more access to abortion
services but there would be stronger gun controls. Their attitudes
also reflect an emotional conservatism, a fear of sudden moves or
drastic action.
</P>
<P>
   If women get to run the show, Americans had better hope they're
running it in other countries too, because our economy will
probably be more regulated and less able to compete against a
testosterone-fueled capitalism elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   Our attempts to hedge against disaster and provide more services
might also create a larger bureaucracy.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would have a strong safety net,'' says Heidi Hartmann,
director of the Institute for Women's Policy Research in
Washington. ``It's hard to know how bureaucratic it would become.
Women do tend to perhaps value security and stability more. If men
spent as much time being caretakers as women, their attitude toward
risk might be different too.''
</P>
<P>
   When most women lived on family farms, Hartmann noted, they ran
the truck gardens that produced a modest but steady income from
vegetable sales, while men focused on the large, high-risk crops.
``Women's economic strategy was always, Well, let's make sure we
have a little bit to count on here.''
</P>
<P>
   But all these projections say more about us now than in the
future. Right now we know we want children and careers, but we
don't want to be deprived of job advancement because of one or be
forced to scrimp on our attention to the other. We want our
husbands to take equal responsibility as parents, but are often
reluctant to drop our role as the primary caregivers.
</P>
<P>
   James Levine of the Families and Work Institute in New York says
he believes that while women often want men to do more of the
parenting, ``they want them to do it the `right way,' and if Dad
doesn't do it, Mom takes it back and the cycle continues.'' Levine,
the author of ``Working Fathers: New Strategies for Balancing Work
and Family,'' has been running workshops on this issue for 25
years. Whether he's in Omaha talking to the agricultural extension
or in midtown working with corporate executives, he hears the same
complaints.
</P>
<P>
   One classic involves getting kids ready for school. ``Dad is
dressing them and the preschooler comes down with purple pants and
an orange top. Mom says, `She can't wear that,' which is saying:
`You don't know how to dress the kid. I have to do everything
myself.'''
</P>
<P>
   Working-class parents are showing their wealthier peers a way
out of this particular battle: If Dad is the only adult in the
house when the kids are dressing for school, purple and orange
rules. Nearly half of fathers who have municipal jobs like fireman,
or service jobs like gas-station attendant, care for the children
while their wives are at work.
</P>
<P>
   ``All I do is watch the kids and work,'' says a Wisconsin
correctional officer who chose a night shift so he could be home
while his wife worked days.
</P>
<P>
   That is, of course, what women have been saying for decades, and
the ideal answer would be an economy that allows both sexes to
advance on the job without requiring so many hours at work. In that
early era we now refer to as ``the '60s,'' many young women
believed that's what the developed world would look like by the
year 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Technology would improve productivity, creating a society in
which job-sharing or 20-hour workweeks were the norm. Even single
mothers would be able to pursue careers and still get home in time
to pick up the kids after school. Needless to say, that leisure
society wound up in the same category as the self-cleaning windows.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, we got a global economy that pits the American factory
worker with a 12-year-old alone at home against a Third World
sweatshop in which the 12-year-olds are the workers. Unless the
underlying economy changes strikingly, our future will probably
involve opportunities that are limited only by our ability to come
up with jerry-built solutions to the competing demands on our time.
</P>
<P>
   The most significant development on the immediate horizon is the
graying of the industrialized world. People 65 and over accounted
for 4 percent of the U.S. population in 1900, but in 2015, some
say, they could be at least 20 percent, and two-thirds will be
women.
</P>
<P>
   If Social Security gets propped up and the political power of
seniors continues to increase, those older women will consume a
large portion of the national budget _ and control a hefty portion
of the assets.
</P>
<P>
   Our great-great-grandmothers waited a lifetime for the social
glacier to creak forward an inch. Charlotte Perkins Gilman, a
turn-of-the-century American utopian, spent her life agitating for
the liberation of women from the chains of household duties, for a
world where child care and housework would be done by well-paid,
well-trained specialists who preferred that kind of career and
where every family would enjoy ``the professional service of cooked
meals to the home.''
</P>
<P>
   When she started writing her autobiography in the 1920s, Gilman
admitted that she'd seen only the tiniest of changes after 37 years
of effort: ``Reason has no power against feeling, and feeling older
than history is no light matter,'' she said philosophically. It
would have been nice if she could have at least lived to order
takeout pizza.
</P>
<P>
   These days, you wake up one morning and a social phenomenon that
you thought immutable will have vanished. I must have written at
least a dozen essays decrying the fact that the entertainment
industry targets boys when it creates movies and television because
everybody knows that girls will watch male heroes but boys usually
won't watch girls.
</P>
<P>
   It was just the other day, really, that I noticed that teen-age
girls now seem to have their own TV network, WB, while teen-age
boys get professional wrestling and Ninja Turtle reruns.
</P>
<P>
   One of the most famous WB series is ``Buffy the Vampire
Slayer,'' in which a teen-age girl rescues humanity from extinction
every week. Last year she had to kill her vampire-boyfriend and,
though he has been resurrected, she keeps noting that it could
happen again at any time.
</P>
<P>
   Buffy really rides alone, just like the male heroes in the TV
westerns that dominated my own childhood. The most popular was
``Bonanza,'' the story of Ben Cartwright, a rancher and three-time
widower, and his three adult sons. The Ponderosa took out wives
faster than a toxic-waste dump. Even the least sophisticated viewer
eventually got the message that you could not have an interesting
time on the frontier if you were saddled with a woman.
</P>
<P>
   At some point while I wasn't looking, the idea that girls didn't
have adventures seems to have faded out of our popular culture,
just like the idea that only boys get to play rock music. The most
successful movie of the last decade is ``Titanic,'' in which a
young woman falls in love with a charming artist, who dies after
making a long speech urging her to seize the day. She lives for
about 80 years of thrills and romance before being reunited with
him after death.You do have the feeling that if he hadn't drowned,
he would have got in the way.
</P>
<P>
   I always hoped that some day women would become co-heroes with
men in entertainment programming. But instead, the sexes may just
be switching responsibility for suffering an untimely death in the
second act. Things progress, but never exactly the way you'd
expect.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Gail Collins, a member of The New York Times editorial board,
is the author, with Dan Collins, of ``The Millennium Book,''
published by Doubleday, in 1991.) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   -------------- &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
