<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-08 18:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9487 &Cx1f; tba-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MILLENNIUM-WOMEN-ETIQ     05-08 0924
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MILLENNIUM-WOMEN-ETIQUETTE-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOOD HOUSEKEEPING 
</HEADLINE>
   For release: May 16 or thereafter  
 By MARGARET ATWOOD  
 FROM: The New York Times Magazine  
 c.1999 O.W. Toad, Ltd.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   When I was in my 20s and inhabiting rooming houses, I was given
a book called ``Cooking in a Bedsitter,'' by the formidable
Katharine Whitehorn. It pointed out that although I was living in
squalor, I didn't have to live in total squalor. With a hot plate,
some herbs and a little foresight, a degree of elegance might be
achieved.
</P>
<P>
   I have been a grateful reader of such advice books and their
variants, women's magazine articles, ever since. (Grateful, though
sometimes bemused: Do I really want to marbleize an end table or
make a gingerbread chalet? Not today.)
</P>
<P>
   There's no shortage of such advice; nor is there any shortage of
women dishing it out. Where did they come from, all these kindly,
bossy, ersatz aunts, whether real or invented _ Fannie Farmer,
Betty Crocker, Martha Stewart and the rest?
</P>
<P>
   I'd say they trace their lineage to Mrs. Isabella Beeton.
</P>
<P>
   For most of our millennium, the few advice books for women were
likely to be religious or moral. Often the only women who could
read were nuns or noblewomen, and housework and cooking were done
by servants. If you were of the higher orders you supervised them,
a skill in itself; if not, you learned the basics from your mother
or from other servants.
</P>
<P>
   Advice books didn't arrive until the rise of a literate middle
class. The ``new money'' created in the 19th century by the
Industrial Revolution often meant young brides who were not only
unprepared to run large establishments but who were also unversed
in the manners required in the polite society to which they'd been
elevated.
</P>
<P>
   Along came the professional advisers, often calling themselves
``A Lady,'' offering bits and pieces of what you might require: a
cookbook here, an etiquette primer there.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Beeton was thus by no means the first of her kind. But
``Beeton's Book of Household Management'' was the first to use
tested recipes, with costs and sample menus. It was also the first
comprehensive book on running a household, telling readers what to
pay their servants and how to remove spots from lace. In addition,
the book had many helpful illustrations. (What does a stair brush
look like? How do you tell one breed of pig from another?)
</P>
<P>
   From her name, which suggests a round, industrious busybody,
you'd expect Mrs. Beeton to have been at least 40. Not a bit of it.
She was born in 1836, and through the death of her father and the
remarriage of her mother, she became the oldest girl in a family of
21 children, which gave her ample experience coping with domestic
chaos.
</P>
<P>
   She was only 23 when she began her magnum opus, in successive
numbers of The Englishwoman's Domestic Magazine, published by her
husband's company; it appeared in book form in 1861. She was
compiling a cooking dictionary and writing a book on needlework
when she died of childbed fever after the birth of her fourth
child. Se was 29.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Beeton is direct in her style and equally clear about her
aims. ``What moved me ... to attempt a work like this,'' she says
in her introduction, ``was the discomfort and suffering I had seen
brought upon men and women by household management. I have always
thought that there is no more fruitful source of family discontent
than a housewife's badly cooked dinners and untidy ways.''
</P>
<P>
   Unless you keep ``a comfortable home,'' she warns, the husbands
will flee to their ``clubs, well-ordered taverns and dining
houses''; it is with these that a wife must compete.
</P>
<P>
   One reason for her success was her acknowledgment of human
frailty. She knew that servants' references were likely to skimp on
truth, so she told employers to visit the reference giver: If her
own house is a wreck, don't hire the servant.
</P>
<P>
   She knew you could get caught short, so she explained not only
how to make butter but also how to make butter in a hurry. (Put the
cream in a bottle and shake it.)
</P>
<P>
   She advised the young wife about almost everything _ the
importance of keeping accounts, the best conversational topics
(entertaining histories), what to wear (green goes well with
violet) and how to spend evenings at home (the ladies do
needlework; the man reads aloud from some ``good standard work or
amusing publication'').
</P>
<P>
   And that's just in the first 17 pages. Her book is more than
1,000 pages long.
</P>
<P>
   Is there anything Mrs. Beeton left out that she might cover now?
Germs; they hadn't really hit the scene. And sex, of course, which
was unprintable.
</P>
<P>
   About ``female emancipation'' she was dubious, but far from
being a delicate Angel in the House, a Beeton woman was the
Generalissimo in the House, commanding an army of servants, men
included. Her work was emphatically work, and required
intelligence, tact, character, energy and dignity.
</P>
<P>
   Much of her advice is dated now, but her insight and common
sense endure. For Mrs. Beeton life is an art, and its aim is
enjoyment, one's own included. The woman practicing this art must
be a stage manager, but she is also the lead actress, saying her
lines effortlessly.
</P>
<P>
   And the details of this art, which some _ men, for instance _
might consider frivolous, are actually of deep importance, because
on them depends the happiness of all.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Margaret Atwood is author, most recently, of ``Alias
Grace.'') &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ----------------- &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
