</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990508.0174 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-08 18:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9490 &Cx1f; tba-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MILLENNIUM-WOMEN-CHIN     05-08 2505
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MILLENNIUM-WOMEN-CHINA-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE GREATEST LEAP 
</HEADLINE>
   For release: May 16 or thereafter  
 By SHERYL WuDUNN  
 FROM: The New York Times Magazine  
 c.1999 The New York Times Magazine  
<TEXT>
<P>
   To reach Zhang Hanzhi, one first has to navigate through a
traditional Chinese home. Peaceful open-air courtyards lead to
private rooms with shelves of Chinese classics and hanging scrolls.
The place is a walled-in maze, like Chinese boxes within boxes.
</P>
<P>
   And so by the time you reach Ms. Zhang in her modern office with
its computer loaded with Windows 95, the journey seems not only a
relief but also a metaphor for the distance women have traveled in
China these last 1,000 years.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Zhang, a hint of gray now peeking through her neatly permed
hair, offers a welcome in the same perfect English that she used to
try to teach Chairman Mao.
</P>
<P>
   She sits back in her chair in front of a large wooden desk and
reminisces amid the bountiful distractions. A tailor visits. A
government economist drops by. She gets a couple of calls from
Zhongnanhai, the sprawling compound where China's top leaders live.
</P>
<P>
   She offers a box of European chocolates and some French tea. The
surroundings are so refined that it seems incongruous when she
recalls her years in Mao's inner circle _ or the time after Mao's
death when she was imprisoned inside the Foreign Ministry as an
alleged ultra-leftist.
</P>
<P>
   She laughs easily about all that now, reaches for a chocolate
and takes a deep breath as she begins to tell the story of her
grandmother, a spunky woman born in a village near the coastal
Chinese town of Suzhou.
</P>
<P>
   The grandmother's name is unknown; in fact, she may never have
had one. As recently as the 19th century, many Chinese women were
simply called Daughter No. 1, Daughter No. 2 and so on.
</P>
<P>
   The clan matriarch, however, had a shrewd mind and good looks,
and early in this century she moved from the countryside to the
shadowy night district of Shanghai, taking her young daughter, Xi
Cuizhen, with her. It was a move that not only created a Chinese
revolution in her own family but also resulted in breathtaking
opportunities for her progeny.
</P>
<P>
   The tale of this woman _ and of the three generations of women
who followed her _ underscores how life has changed for Chinese
women in a remarkably short time. If one of the themes of this
millennium has been the increasing liberation of women, it perhaps
has even more resonance in the East than in the West, for nowhere
has the evolution in women's power been swifter.
</P>
<P>
   While no one family can do justice to the enormously varied
conditions of women in Asia _ from the child brides of India to the
tough women entrepreneurs of Taiwan _ the transformation
experienced by the women of Ms. Zhang's family is one that has
parallels across the region.
</P>
<P>
   For much of history, a Chinese woman considered herself a
servant first to her father, then to her husband and then to her
son. When her husband died, she showed her loyalty by not
remarrying, even if it meant she might have no livelihood; she
always had the option of dying of hunger.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a trifling when a widow starves to death,'' said Cheng
Hao, a prominent Confucian philosopher of the Sung dynasty. ``But
it is a very serious matter when she loses her chastity.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, not all Chinese women lived by this credo. In ancient
times, there were some famously strong and dynamic Chinese women.
But about the year 1000, the social noose around women tightened.
Philosopher-rulers designed a strict Confucian code of conduct they
hoped would impose stability; virtuous women were rewarded with
money and gifts.
</P>
<P>
   By the 14th century, attitudes had hardened. Prostitution became
common, but sadistic punishments were prescribed for socialites who
strayed from Confucian values. If a women had a ``yehe,'' an
extramarital liaison, one punishment was to ``peel the skin off the
bones _ to the death.'' Not surprisingly, many widows chose to
commit suicide when their husbands died.
</P>
<P>
   When the family's great-grandmother got to Shanghai, it was the
most sizzling city in Asia. The details of her adventures are
sketchy, but somehow she created one of the best nightclubs on Hui
Le Li, a street famous for bordellos.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were so many young girls looking for a better life, and
the only way was to find a man who could take care of them,'' said
Ms. Zhang. ``There was not much that China provided for them.''
</P>
<P>
   Shanghai's nightclubs were the setting for vibrant political
debate, as rising revolutionaries sought the secrecy of dimly lit
corners to map out political campaigns. The great-grandmother's
daughter, Xi Cuizhen, grew up partly in the club and met some of
the wealthiest men in Shanghai.
</P>
<P>
   One of those men was a scholar and lawyer, Zhang Shizhao, a
married man. A former Minister of Education, Mr. Zhang spent
considerable time in Shanghai's bordellos, where he enjoyed the
charms of the entertainers who poured wine, talked sweetly and
performed a dance or two.
</P>
<P>
   Xi Cuizhen was gracious with her mother's guests and obviously
caught Mr. Zhang's eye, but for her, dancing was virtually
impossible. That was because of her very small feet, which had been
bound when she was little. As with most other young girls in the
countryside, Xi Cuizhen's mother had wrapped white cloth around her
feet when she was probably 4 or 5.
</P>
<P>
   Every evening, the mother would unwrap and wash her daughter's
feet and then rewrap the cloth before Xi Cuizhen went to sleep. It
was extremely painful as her feet began to grow, and it was often
difficult to sleep with the throbbing pain. Eventually, though,
Xi's arches broke and her two small toes began to curl under, as
they were supposed to.
</P>
<P>
   Chinese women began binding their feet just at the turn of the
millennium. By the 13th century, foot binding had become a means to
curb women, an attitude captured by a poet who wrote: ``Why must
the foot be bound?/
</P>
<P>
   To prevent barbarous running around!'' The Mongols, who came to
power in 1279, outlawed the practice, but it still spread, as men
craved the beauty of the crescent foot, slender and pointed at the
toe. For women, foot binding was the price for a good marriage.
</P>
<P>
   The problem was that while women were supposed to be virtuous,
men were not. Zhang Shizhao ended up marrying Xi Cuizhen, and they
adopted a daughter: Zhang Hanzhi, my host. But Mr. Zhang never
divorced his first wife. Xi simply became the second wife.
(Eventually, he added a third.)
</P>
<P>
   The arrangement was not out of the ordinary. Women were often
forced to live in marital competition: Sometimes relations were
cordial; other times they were not.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of the time before 1949, all three wives were living in
Shanghai, but not together,'' said Ms. Zhang. ``It was part of
society. It became the status quo.'' Sometimes, Ms. Zhang added,
``he would have dinner with us, and then he went back to his third
wife.''
</P>
<P>
   In the 20th century, women gained status as Western ideas began
filtering into China. Reformers began demanding greater literacy
for women and an end to foot binding. Families who bound their
daughters' feet would find their names in the newspaper; a women's
movement spread.
</P>
<P>
   Communism extended the liberation of women, with Mao Zedong
preaching that women held up half the sky. Child weddings were
banned, concubines were outlawed and brothels were closed. Women
went to night school, studied sewing or joined the local factory.
Women drove combines and became pilots.
</P>
<P>
   ``Women finally gained financial independence,'' said Yufu
Huang, a scholar of women's issues at the Chinese Academy of Social
Sciences.
</P>
<P>
   After the 1949 Communist revolution, Mr. Zhang joined the top
leadership of the People's Congress and moved to Beijing with Xi
Cuizhen and their daughter, the young Ms. Zhang. Ms. Zhang went to
college at the Foreign Languages Institute, an achievement that
women in her mother's generation would never have dreamed of.
</P>
<P>
   She became a freethinking academic there and married Hong
Junyan, a Beijing University professor. Together they had a
daughter, Hung Huang.
</P>
<P>
   Then in 1962, after an encounter at Mao's 70th-year birthday
party, the Communist leader asked Ms. Zhang to give him his first
English lesson. He was impressed by her and in 1970 sent her to the
Foreign Ministry. ``We need women diplomats,'' he said. ``China
needs a woman spokesman.''
</P>
<P>
   At first, it was an awkward fit: Ms. Zhang with her
free-spirited academic ways and the Chinese Foreign Office with its
bureaucratic, formalistic approach. On her first day as a diplomat,
Ms. Zhang went to work carrying a green army bag with the phrase
``Serve the People'' spelled out in the red characters of the
Communist Party.
</P>
<P>
   From it, she took out her teacup _ a jam jar with a plastic net
that held the jar of hot tea so that she wouldn't burn her fingers.
Her conservative colleagues used porcelain teacups.
</P>
<P>
   ``They all examined my jar when I left,'' she says. ``I was like
someone from outer space dropping into the Foreign Office.''
</P>
<P>
   Then she was given a ruler, scissors, glue and a small desk and
told to read cables of foreign news articles from Chinese embassies
abroad and to scan for news about Pakistan. ``Just read the
Pakistan cables,'' she recalls her boss telling her. ``Don't read
the others, because they are confidential.''
</P>
<P>
   She had no idea what her new tools were for. Her male boss
explained, ``Use the ruler to draw a line around the article, cut
it with a scissors, stick it onto a piece of paper and give it to
me.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Zhang, demoralized, was ready to quit. But she persisted,
and her support from Mao and her command of English led her to
become one of China's top translators, interpreting for Henry
Kissinger on his secret mission to Beijing and then for President
Nixon on his visit to China in 1972. She worked closely with Mao
and was privy to some of the confidential talks that helped
establish the foundations of Chinese-American relations.
</P>
<P>
   In November 1971 Mao had nominated her to be an interpreter for
the first Chinese delegation to the United Nations. It was on that
trip to New York that she got the attention of Qiao Guanhua, the
Deputy Foreign Minister and a widower.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Zhang had to get Qiao's signature for a document, and when
she finally got a chance to see him, he said he was too tired and
wanted to take a nap. Disgusted, she tossed the document on the
desk and said, ``Well, it's up to you!'' and stalked out.
</P>
<P>
   The Deputy Foreign Minister was shocked that a woman dared to
behave so boldly. Still, he must not have been too appalled, for
two years later, in 1973, after Ms. Zhang had divorced her first
husband, she and Qiao married.
</P>
<P>
   That same year, Hung Huang, Ms. Zhang's 12-year-old daughter,
went to the United States as one of 28 children chosen as part of
an experiment to educate Chinese youth abroad. She lived with a
family in New York, who introduced her to ``The Cat in the Hat,''
``Sesame Street'' and Ray's Pizza.
</P>
<P>
   In 1977, however, Hung had to cut her schooling short and return
to China. With Mao's death, the political tides had turned against
her mother, who had been put under house arrest.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Zhang's guards wanted to get rid of her but didn't want any
blame, so they dropped hints. ``They left a pair of scissors one
day,'' said Ms. Zhang. ``Another day they left a rope. But not for
a moment did I ever think of killing myself. I knew how to
survive.''
</P>
<P>
   Hung remained in Beijing until her mother was released in 1980.
She then went back to the United States to go to college at Vassar.
On graduating, she returned to China to become a metals trader in
Beijing.
</P>
<P>
   Confucianism may have enslaved women for centuries, but
capitalism and commercialism have been enormously powerful in
helping women overturn history. Women in China now have real
freedom when it comes to choosing their careers _ freedom that will
be hard to strip away.
</P>
<P>
   But by no means is the transformation of female power complete.
Advertisements strongly hint that women should be housewives or sex
symbols. Women also face a confusing array of pressures and
options.
</P>
<P>
   As Yufu of the Chinese Academy said, ``Women are right in the
process of finding a path.''
</P>
<P>
   Hung has certainly stumbled along that path. Once, when she was
desperate to win a $60 million contract, she stayed for hours in
the offices of the two bureaucrats responsible for awarding the
deal. She answered their phones, pleaded with them, but won the
contract only after she broke into tears.
</P>
<P>
   Hung has also struggled to find a way to act in a male-dominated
business, sometimes with mixed results. One evening, in
time-honored tradition, she went drinking with customers and ended
up vomiting in their laps.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Hung sees these episodes as growing pains, the awkward
acts that come with any transition. Now she is a partner at a
high-powered consulting firm in Beijing. While her mother is an
enlightened traditionalist in her views about women, Hung, who is
37, is modern, individualistic and multicultural. She is on her
third marriage _ this one to a French diplomat.
</P>
<P>
   But unlike her forebears, Hung is much less dependent on men.
Like a growing number of women in China today, her achievements are
varied and distinctly her own. Women may still be treated like dirt
in many rural areas, but in the cities, the relationship between
the sexes is not all that different from the way it is in the
United States.
</P>
<P>
   The Zhang family's own troubled journey underscores some of the
changes between the sexes. For the great-grandmother and the
grandmother of the clan, the only opportunity to rise was to appeal
to men's passions.
</P>
<P>
   By the time Zhang Hanzhi came along, it was possible for a woman
to demonstrate her talents, but even Ms. Zhang was aided by her
marriage and her association with Mao. Now the next generation,
Hung Huang, is finally able to do whatever she can on her own, as a
person rather than as a woman.
</P>
<P>
   When Ms. Zhang's memoirs became a best-selling book in China
last year, readers got a glimpse of how Hung's mother, like other
women of her generation, views her own success. All they had to do
was read the title: ``Ten Years in the Storm: Remembering My
Father, My Husband and Chairman Mao.''
</P>
<P>
   While her success was very much her own, she still saw her life
path as intertwined and enhanced by the three powerful men in her
life.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would never have given that title to my book,'' says Hung.
``Link my achievements to the men in my life? Never.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Sheryl WuDunn is a Tokyo-based correspondent for The New York
Times who, with her husband, Nicholas D. Kristof, is author of
``China Wakes.'') &LR;
</P>
<P>
   __________ &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
