<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-08 18:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9496 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CT-BRIDGEPORT-SHAYS-N     05-08 0963
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CT-BRIDGEPORT-SHAYS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONGRESSMAN INVESTS IN BRIDGEPORT'S REVIVAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By MIKE ALLEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   BRIDGEPORT, Conn. _ As long as a member of Congress keeps a
place back home, the exact address is usually of little moment. But
when Rep. Christopher Shays moved 20 miles up Interstate 95 last
week, it was treated as a seismic political event in Fairfield
County.
</P>
<P>
   Shays left a large house in Stamford, a magnet for corporate
headquarters, and bought a snug colonial in Bridgeport, the poorest
part of his district in this richest county in the richest state in
the nation.
</P>
<P>
   Bridgeport is Connecticut's largest city, but no congressman had
lived there in more than 100 years. Shays said the reason for his
move is simple: he needed a lower house payment so he could pay the
tuition bills for his daughter, Jeramy, a freshman at Principia
College in Illinois, his alma mater. But in Bridgeport, his choice
is being treated as proof that a city that barely escaped
bankruptcy in the early 1990s is rebounding.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe now people won't be afraid to come into Bridgeport,''
said Jerry Swatt, a computer programmer and 30-year resident who
believes that his city's long decline is over.
</P>
<P>
   The move is in keeping with the reformist reputation of Shays,
53, a moderate Republican who has led a drive in the House to
change the way campaigns are financed and who agonized publicly
last year over whether to impeach President Clinton. Eventually, he
broke with his party and became one of five Republicans to vote
against impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   All the hubbub about the move is a reminder of the complications
of representing the 4th District, which is mostly composed of
white-collar commuter enclaves but also includes a few fallen
industrial areas. The district includes both New Canaan, with a
median family income of $110,000 a year, and Bridgeport, where that
figure is $33,000.
</P>
<P>
   Many Connecticut politicians see the move as the first step in a
race for governor, which Shays has said he might pursue in 2002 if
Gov. John Rowland, a fellow Republican, does not seek a third term
and if Lt. Gov. Jodi Rell is not interested in succeeding him.
</P>
<P>
   ``As long as I've been in politics, I've said I would love to
run for governor, if that works out,'' Shays said. ```If that works
out' is a giant escape clause. I may have that opportunity, but I
love what I'm doing.''
</P>
<P>
   That raises the possibility of a cross-town governor's race,
since a likely Democratic candidate four years from now is
Bridgeport Mayor Joseph Ganim. Asked about his new constituent,
Ganim, 39, said with a smile, ``I've never objected to the idea of
having a governor from Bridgeport.''
</P>
<P>
   Given the symbolic freight carried by Shays' moving van, it
seemed fitting that he wore a Peace Corps T-shirt as he puttered
barefoot amid the boxes in his new $490,000 house, which is about
half the size of the home in Stamford that he sold for $835,000.
</P>
<P>
   Shays jokes that his wife, Betsi, accuses him of choosing
Bridgeport ``to be closer to Home Depot,'' but he said it really is
part of the lifelong curiosity that took them to Fiji with the
Peace Corps.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any time you can get people to come back into your urban areas
and identify Bridgeport as a positive place, it helps all of us,''
he said. ``I have a community where the wealthiest care about the
poorest. The wealthy in my district don't want the poor to live the
way they're living, but they don't think the solution is government
handouts.'' Instead, he said, they want improved schools and
programs that encourage work.
</P>
<P>
   He recalls that within a few hours one day, he counseled a
prostitute with AIDS at a public housing development in Bridgeport,
then drove to a polo match in Greenwich that was held to raise
money for people with AIDS. He said that in Bridgeport, he meets
children who live two miles from Long Island Sound but have never
seen the water, and children whose parents tell them to hide in the
bathtub to escape gunfire.
</P>
<P>
   ``The best thing I can do for someone in Greenwich is get out of
the way,'' Shays said, sitting on his deck to escape the racket of
the workers sanding the floors inside. ``The urban centers are
where our challenges are and our diversity is, and that diversity
excites me. I believe that Bridgeport is a city on its way back in
a big way, and I'm saying I have a lot of faith in Bridgeport.''
</P>
<P>
   Shays, who lives on a waterfront lot that is among the nicest in
the city, said he has enjoyed seeing ``kids working with their moms
and dads on the front lawn _ they don't have a lot of lawn
service.''
</P>
<P>
   Although he maintains that his move is ``not a gesture _ it's an
investment,'' Shays is not averse to engaging in political theater
to draw attention to his centrist views. During the impeachment
debate, he drew international coverage with a town meeting that
lasted until 2 a.m., and demanded _ and got _ a private audience
with Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   The motives seem unimportant, though, to Bridgeport's citizens
and officials. At a picnic that Ganim held last week during opening
day for the Bridgeport Bluefish, a minor-league baseball team, even
Democrats said they were excited about the arrival of the Shayses.
``We need the help,'' Councilwoman Lydia Martinez said.
</P>
<P>
   The team, egged on by cheers of ``One fish, two fish, let's go,
Bluefish,'' plays at Harbor Yard, a park that opened last year on
the site of a former valve factory. City officials see Harbor Yard
as the first success in a renaissance that they hope will include a
million-square-foot mall, a hockey rink and a basketball arena.
Now, they've landed a congressman.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to convert him,'' said Councilman Michael Marella.
``Sign him up as a Democrat!''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-08-99 1851EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
