<SLUG> BC-TITLE-IX-DEBATE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INTERPRETATION OF TITLE IX IS SUBJECT OPEN FOR DEBATE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.J., Pa., Fla.)   (bl)  
 By STEVE POPPER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   BLAIRSTOWN, N.J. _ The lights dimmed in the small theater at
Blair Academy on Tuesday night and a video clip began from the
television show, ``20/20.''
</P>
<P>
   In the clip, a discussion of Title IX, the law that was enacted
27 years ago to prevent sexual discrimination in educational or
athletic programs, a coach at Merritt Island (Fla.) High School
detailed some of the maneuvers that had taken place at his school
to be in compliance under the law.
</P>
<P>
   One example, which involved shutting off an electronic
scoreboard for the boys' baseball team because the girls' softball
team didn't have one yet, drew nervous laughter from the crowd in
the theater.
</P>
<P>
   When the lights came up again and discussion evolved at the
gathering, a forum on Title IX, there was little disagreement that
something had gone awry in the interpretation of Title IX. This
consensus was despite the differing constituencies represented by
the panel.
</P>
<P>
   The moderator of the forum was Roger Reina, the president of the
National Wrestling Coaches Association and the head coach at the
University of Pennsylvania.
</P>
<P>
   Reina was joined on the panel by three speakers:
</P>
<P>
   _ Leo Kocher, the board president of the National Coalition for
Athletics Equity, as well as the head wrestling coach at the
University of Chicago and a member of the Joint Task Force to
Protect Wrestling.
</P>
<P>
   _ Ruth Gibbs, the head softball coach at Muhlenberg College in
Allentown, Pa., a founding member of the state tournament for
women's basketball in New Jersey. Gibbs is also a member of the New
Jersey State Interscholastic Athletic Association's transfer
committee to develop rules for female athletes following the
passage of Title IX.
</P>
<P>
   _ T.J. Hartford, the founder and president of Boston Terriers
United for Football, a nonprofit organization aimed at having
football reinstated as a varsity sport at Boston University.
</P>
<P>
   Title IX, which was originally enacted in 1972, added a
three-pronged test for compliance via a 1979 ruling by the
Education Department through the Civil Rights Office. Under this
test, schools have not only added opportunities for women, but in
an effort to move into compliance with the rule, which calls for
proportionality in college athletic programs, have also cut many
men's sports. Reina said that for every female opportunity gained,
3.4 male opportunities are lost, and between 1993 and 1997, 320
National Collegiate Athletic Association men's athletic programs
have been eliminated.
</P>
<P>
   ``Title IX is a great law,'' Reina said. ``It's really an
interpretation and enforcement problem. It's not a law at all. Some
argue that it's a gender quota, which is a violation of federal
law.''
</P>
<P>
   Gibbs added: ``I don't believe there is any reason for programs
to have to be dropped to fill quotas. I don't believe that this law
initially meant that. If we approach this with sheer logic, where
the interest is, the schools should provide opportunities.''
</P>
<P>
   Kocher said the problem cannot be solved in legal battles, so
his group is trying to spread the message of what it thinks is an
inequity. He cited as the example of Boston College's decision to
eliminate the men's lacrosse, water polo and wrestling programs,
which each had no scholarships and part-time coaches but were
eliminated to bring the school into compliance with the
proportionality test.
</P>
<P>
   ``The opportunity for females was made by society, not by law,
25 years ago,'' Kocher said. ``Society saw that it was not right. A
law was passed, and now it has been twisted by bureaucrats. It
gives females opportunities by deposing males. Schools are in a
bind, and one way to be proportional is to get rid of male
athletes. That's what's happening, and that's why there is a howl
and scream. Schools are trying to make themselves lawsuit-proof.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anybody who's looked at the problem closely realizes that the
three-prong test is where the problem lies. People suggest that the
interpretation should be reworked.
</P>
<P>
   ``But they,'' Kocher said, referring to those who think Title IX
need not be reworked, ``have pretty powerful allies _ the National
Organization for Women, the Women's Sports Foundation. The
government doesn't want to be seen as anti-women. Until people are
aware, there is not going to be change.''
</P>
<P>
   Reached at her office, Donna Lopiano, the president of the
Women's Sports Foundation, agreed with the panelists that schools
should not use Title IX as a cover to make budget cuts that slash
programs. But Lopiano said the blame for the problem goes to
schools' unwillingness to make football programs share the budget.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look at the reality of it,'' Lopiano said. ``Starting from a
much bigger budget, men's athletics operating costs grew by 139
percent in the last five years. Women, over the same period, grew
by 89 percent. I think it's absolutely unethical to cut men to
comply with an anti-discrimination law. But to blame that on Title
IX is an absolute smoke screen.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only way that schools can tackle this is to provide
finances, by raising money or reducing expenditures. But look at
the numbers and you see the football monster is growing. You can't
do anything for women or for men's programs like wrestling and
gymnastics that are being cut until you slow down the money that
football spends.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
