<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-08 19:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9507 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-U.S.-REFUGEES-     05-08 0972
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-U.S.-REFUGEES-ART-900(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AT FORT DIX, A NEW ELLIS ISLAND EMBRACES KOSOVO'S REFUGEES
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ala., N.C., N.Y., Pa.)  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036.) 
(rk) 
 By DIANA JEAN SCHEMO   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT DIX, N.J. _ Selim Berisha sat in a barracks carefully made
safe for old people and children, with pictures of murder running
through his head.
</P>
<P>
   On March 28, a holy day for Muslims, he recalled, the Serb
police and paramilitaries spilled into his neighborhood in
Pristina, the capital of Kosovo. They beat Albanians in the streets
and fired in the air and at houses. As the bullets shattered his
windows, Berisha, a 63-year-old taxi driver, hid in his cellar with
his family and neighbors _ 50 people in all.
</P>
<P>
   In the morning, they found a neighbor who had not made it to
shelter. He lay dead in his yard, his remains set upon by dogs.
``We buried him, and we escaped into the woods,'' Berisha said.
</P>
<P>
   Berisha was among the first Albanians from Kosovo who came to
Fort Dix to begin new lives, separated by thousands of miles, but
little time, from the loss of their homes and their worlds.
</P>
<P>
   In less than a week, Fort Dix has been transformed from an Army
base into a kind of sprawling Ellis Island, gearing up to be the
gateway to America for almost 20,000 Albanian refugees. The
military has named the relief operation Open Arms, and government
agencies have displayed a certain sensitivity to both the refugees
and to public relations.
</P>
<P>
   Almost overnight, swing sets and playhouses sprouted on the
base, and by Friday morning, the smiles of toddlers blossomed like
so many daisies at the playhouse windows. Signs in English and
Albanian lined the walls, one bare room had been turned into a
chapel, and officials made a point of not serving pork to the
Albanians, most of whom are Muslim.
</P>
<P>
   Soldiers were ordered to say ``dining facility'' instead of
``mess hall,'' and to call the place where the Immigration and
Naturalization Service fingerprints and photographs refugees upon
their arrival a ``welcome center.''
</P>
<P>
   Terry Wade, a staff sergeant from Fort Bragg, N.C., who helped
prepare the base, observed: ``We're kind of running this like a
hotel system. Welcome to the HoJo.''
</P>
<P>
   But 4-foot-tall wooden fences have also gone up over the last
week at Fort Dix, for the heart of Ellis Island was always
immigration screening. The fences are guarded by military police,
and the final authority over the refugees lies with the immigration
service.
</P>
<P>
   While the children play gleefully, as if Fort Dix were a
miniature Disneyland, their parents and older siblings remain
shaken by all they have seen and lost.
</P>
<P>
   Ilir Hoxha, a 45-year-old music producer, said he missed the
home he built for his family, a four-room house with two bathrooms
in Pristina.
</P>
<P>
   A few weeks ago, he was standing by the open door of that house
with his son, Arben, 20, when the Serbian police approached. They
forced Hoxha's wife and teen-age daughters outside and put a gun to
his throat, demanding German marks.
</P>
<P>
   Hoxha said he had none; indeed, he had been out of work for 10
years, since Serbs began choking the Albanian economy and culture.
</P>
<P>
   The Serbian police gave his family ``half a minute to get out,''
he said. Armed police officers stood on both sides of the road. The
family marched 40 minutes to the train station, staring straight
ahead. Asked what might have happened had she looked at the police
as she was climbing onto the train, Hoxha's 17-year-old daughter,
Arbreshe, said only, ``If ...,'' and burst into tears.
</P>
<P>
   The family sat at a picnic table in Doughboy Field at Fort Dix,
historically a place of transformation, where generations of boys
were turned into soldiers. As Hoxha told the family's tale, his
children and his wife, Hysnije, stared at the grass, as if
transfixed. Hoxha worried about a sister who remained behind. ``The
situation there is very dangerous,'' he said. ``They don't have
anything to eat or drink.''
</P>
<P>
   Hoxha has no relatives in the United States, and said the family
had no preference for living in one part of the country over
another. ``New York,'' Arbreshe whispered, and smiled. Her father
said he wanted most to return home, if he could only raise his
family in peace.
</P>
<P>
   The soldiers here appear genuinely touched by the refugees,
charmed by the children and moved by the adults. Early Thursday
morning, some 12 hours after they had completed their 13-hour
journey from Skopje, Macedonia, the refugees were finally getting
to bed after an initial screening by the immigration service and a
greeting from Hillary Rodham Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   A mother approached Spc &UR; . &LR;  Kenneth Sollano, 22, of Opp, Ala. She
laid her head on folded hands and tried to explain that her little
daughter could not sleep. The soldier handed her a doll, which the
toddler hugged as she finally dozed off.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the uniforms and the lack of freedom to move, the
compound at Fort Dix is far different from the overcrowded tent
camps of Macedonia, where the threat of disease looms and resources
are stretched. Perhaps afraid the scarcity might return, children
at the base cafeteria on Friday afternoon piled trays tall with
soup and heaps of spaghetti and meat, and many slices of bread.
</P>
<P>
   Wade said that some of the refugees did not know how to say
``thank you'' in English but expressed their gratitude in other
ways. ``I gave a little 2-year-old a stuffed toy, and he looked at
me and put his hand over his heart,'' Wade said. Adults, eager to
help, tried to pick up brooms and sweep.
</P>
<P>
   ``It put chills on me,'' Wade said, ``that I could do some good
for these people.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Mehde Shehu, 39, an Albanian who came here from the Albanian
Assistance Center in the Bronx, said the refugees, many of whom
were farmers, valued self-reliance. ``They should let them work in
the fields there, they would make them beautiful,'' Shehu said. He
had come to Fort Dix to see if he could talk to the refugees, but
was being kept at arm's length by officials after he tried Thursday
to pass a newspaper to a refugee.
</P>
<P>
   Though the plight of the Kosovar Albanians has touched a chord
in many people, so much that a phone line set up in New Jersey to
channel offers of help jammed Thursday night, immigration officials
are controlling access to the refugees.
</P>
<P>
   A day after the refugees arrived, a 14-year-old, Hassan Maliqi,
ventured to the gate to greet reporters and photographers. But
almost immediately, he was shooed back and surrounded by 13
soldiers in uniform, for while the compound is being called a
``village,'' it is really a ``containment area,'' one reserve
officer blurted out.
</P>
<P>
   The mayor of nearby Wrightstown, Jozsef Farago, a refugee from
the Soviet crackdown in Hungary in 1956, wanted to invite the
refugees to a picnic on May 15 to celebrate the centennial of the
Wrightstown Fire Department. He also encouraged families to help
the refugees however they could, perhaps just by inviting a family
over for an afternoon barbecue to show they cared. But the refugees
are not being allowed to leave the grounds, and for the moment,
Farago said, he has been told not to be so helpful.
</P>
<P>
   While here, the refugees are being screened and treated for
medical problems, while the immigration service tries to do
background checks and check for criminal records. They will also be
interviewed by asylum officers, who normally must ascertain that a
refugee indeed faces danger if he were to return to his home
country.
</P>
<P>
   In this instance, noted Carl Rusnok, an immigration service
spokesman from the Philadelphia office, that conclusion appears
obvious at the outset.
</P>
<P>
   Officials said the refugees were expected to stay here for about
two weeks, until private nonprofit resettlement agencies find
apartments for them to rent. The agencies are also to help them
assimilate to the United States, enrolling the children in schools
and helping the parents find work.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
