<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-08 19:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9515 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NJ-COLUMN-SCHOOL-SECU     05-08 0735
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NJ-COLUMN-SCHOOL-SECURITY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
N.J. COLUMN: SCHOOL SECURITY RULES CAN BACKFIRE 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By IVER PETERSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SOUTH BRUNSWICK, N.J. _ Last fall, town officials wanted to put
a full-time plainclothes police officer in South Brunswick High
School. The hope was that students would get to know the police a
little better and everyone would be a little safer. But some
seniors objected on principle, and the idea was shelved.
</P>
<P>
   Now there are two full-time officers in South Brunswick High, in
uniform, and their squad cars are parked conspicuously in front. In
this season of concern about school violence, nobody asked the
students about them, or about keeping more school access doors
locked or the new ban on wearing long coats or carrying backpacks
in school between classes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt so badly when I got on the school television and told
the students that times have changed,'' said principal Thomas
Kietrys. ``But the school is completely air-conditioned and there
is no reason to wear coats indoors, and they have lockers for their
books.''
</P>
<P>
   Kietrys' announcement came on a Friday in April, the day after
his school was closed because of a rumor about a bomb. As in so
many similar threats and near-threats that schools have been
getting since the school killings in Littleton, Colo., the police,
aided by bomb-sniffing dogs, discovered no explosives.
</P>
<P>
   But what the scare left behind is the sense, as the principal
said, that times have changed for the worse, even in a place like
South Brunswick, whose new, $51 million postmodern high school sits
in rolling countryside that is rapidly giving way to housing
developments, and looking for all the world like any prosperous,
fast-growing exurban school in California or Colorado.
</P>
<P>
   The students show a kind of hip skepticism about the new rules,
but with an underlying edge of concern. One, Nick Komadis, puts the
school authorities' ban on coats and backpacks down to a fear of
lawsuits, not a concern for safety, and others seem to agree with
him. So now students passing through the halls between classes
carry their books in see-through plastic bags, or _ as a mute
protest, apparently _ in plastic milk crates. The changes, some of
the seniors said, serve only to remind them of the danger.
</P>
<P>
   ``I look out the window right now and I see a cop car, and that
doesn't make me feel safe,'' said Sherine Aboelezz, a senior who is
headed to Rutgers and who plans a career in international law and
diplomacy. ``All the police and all the hall monitors and locked
doors can't stop everything that can happen, because if a person
isn't scared of getting caught by a teacher or the principal, he's
already at a certain level of `I don't care,' where having the
police aren't going to stop him.''
</P>
<P>
   And the backpack rule?
</P>
<P>
   ``Every student is against that rule,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Nick, who is also going to attend Rutgers, said, ``My take on it
is, they wanted to do it all along, and this was a justification.''
Nick has heard that besides banning backpacks, other schools are
making girls carry see-through purses. This brings a murmur of
objections.
</P>
<P>
   ``Girls carry things we don't necessarily want everyone to
see,'' said Stephanie Bergman, who is going to Ohio State, and
wants to be an astronaut.
</P>
<P>
   The seniors have a kind of luxury in their griping that is
missing from Kietrys' view of things. His school is built for 2,200
students and he knows from the district's elementary school
enrollment that it will hit 3,000 in four or five years. Families
are moving into the new housing rising across Ridge Road every day
and into dozens of other subdivisions in the township, bringing
strangers to South Brunswick with each moving van.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are rapidly changing, and that is one of our challenges,''
the principal said. ``We're not a little town where everybody has
known each other for years and years and years, and one of my jobs
right now is to make a big school feel small.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet South Brunswick High, as Kietrys put it, has lost its
innocence about violence, and whatever their disagreements about
the police and backpacks, some of the students sense it, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sooner or later, there's going to be another incident,'' Nick
said. ``Sooner or later it's going to happen, and basically, it's
all about how lucky you are that it doesn't happen where you are.''
</P>
</TEXT>
