</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DIALLO-SLAYING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DIALLO CASE FOCUSES ON TIME OFFICERS TOOK TO FIRE 41 SHOTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By KEVIN FLYNN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Investigators reviewing the shooting of Amadou Diallo
are focusing increased attention on how long it took the four
police officers involved to fire 41 bullets at him, law enforcement
officials say.
</P>
<P>
   Knowing the duration of the barrage could help determine whether
and to what degree the officers were reckless in firing so many
times at Diallo, an unarmed West African immigrant, in the
vestibule of his Bronx apartment building Feb. 4.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators are trying to enhance the audiotapes of telephone
calls to 911 about the shooting to see if any gunfire can be heard,
one official said. The sound of gunfire in such a phone call, whose
time could be determined, could help prosecutors establish how long
the shooting took.
</P>
<P>
   One caller to 911 has told investigators that she held the phone
toward the street during the incident so the police operator could
hear the shots. She called at 12:41 a.m., about 14 seconds after
the first call to 911 reporting the shooting, officials said. But
gunfire cannot be heard on the tape of the woman's call, and she
never told the operator that she was holding up the phone, one
official said.
</P>
<P>
   The officers, who have been charged with second-degree murder,
have said they thought Diallo was reaching for a weapon when they
confronted him just inside the front door of his building on
Wheeler Avenue.
</P>
<P>
   Several people who live nearby have told investigators that they
first heard three shots that night, followed by a short pause, and
then a volley of gunfire as all the officers apparently began
shooting. Two of the officers fired 16 times. One shot four times
and a fourth fired five bullets. A total of 19 of those bullets
struck Diallo.
</P>
<P>
   The 9-mm weapons used by the officers can fire 16 rounds in 5 to
10 seconds, according to firearms experts. The officers' lawyers
maintain the shooting was lightning-quick: that the officers had no
time to catch themselves after at least one mistook Diallo's black
wallet for a gun.
</P>
<P>
   The Bronx district attorney's case is based on the theory that
the officers clearly had the time and the opportunity to recognize
their mistake before firing some of the shots.
</P>
<P>
   A central dispute in the case, which may have some bearing on
the duration of the shooting, has been over the officers' assertion
that Diallo continued to stand even after being hit by 19 bullets.
One lawyer acknowledged this week that a shot might have struck
Diallo as he was falling.
</P>
<P>
   The Diallo family's lawyers have dismissed the officers'
version, pointing to an autopsy by their own pathologist that
indicates Diallo was knocked down and paralyzed quite early in the
barrage by a shot that ruptured his aorta and perforated his spine.
They have argued that, based on bullet trajectories, at least two
shots were fired after Diallo fell, including one that went through
the sole of Diallo's right sneaker.
</P>
<P>
   Several forensic experts said that the shorter the time span of
the shooting, the less contradictory these versions become.
</P>
<P>
   If the shooting truly occurred in a matter of seconds, then even
if one of the first bullets caused him to fall, many others might
have struck him simultaneously or as he fell, an event that often
takes as long as two seconds.
</P>
<P>
   ``Both versions could be right,'' said Dr. Henry Lee, a
prominent forensic scientist. ``The shooting can be very rapid, and
because it is a dynamic situation, no one can predict what really
can happen'' under such circumstances.
</P>
<P>
   The officers have given only a sketchy account of what happened
that night. Although several people have told investigators they
saw some of the shooting or its aftermath, no one besides the
officers has said they saw everything.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, the physical evidence has taken on added
significance. Police investigators and the FBI have painstakingly
collected ballistic evidence and traced bullet trajectories using
lasers and computer models.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, two of the 41 bullets were not recovered until 11
days after the shooting, according to police records. One bullet
was found in a closet in Diallo's apartment after it had pierced a
door and two walls. A second bullet was found in the frame of the
building's front door, not far from where other bullets were
recovered.
</P>
<P>
   Several forensic experts said the delay in recovery was trivial,
but Marvyn Kornberg, a lawyer for one of the four officers, Sean
Carroll, said it raised questions about the thoroughness of the
evidence-collection process.
</P>
<P>
   Another point in question is how dark it was in the vestibule
when the officers reportedly mistook Diallo's wallet for a gun.
Photographs taken that night show the vestibule was well-lighted by
two fixtures. Neighbors said the lights were routinely on at night.
</P>
<P>
   Another small mystery is whether two holes in the top of the red
ski hat Diallo wore that night were created by bullets. Crime scene
photographs show the hat resting snugly on Diallo's head, but an
autopsy by the city medical examiner found no wounds there.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
