<HEADLINE>
SOFTWARE CITED IN N.Y. AIR TRAFFIC CONTROL FAILURE 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Thursday morning's failure of a new air traffic
control computer in Ronkonkoma, N.Y., which delayed thousands of
passengers, was caused by a local software flaw and should have no
effect on a nationwide replacement program, Federal Aviation
Administration officials said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The new computers, like the old, send flight plans to printers,
so the air traffic controllers will have a paper backup giving
vital information for each plane, including its origin and
destination, in case of radar failure. But the new computers were
not sending messages properly to 4 of the 40 printers at the New
York Air Route Traffic Control Center, and that caused the
computers to stop processing data, said FAA spokesman Eliot
Brenner. Information on the malfunction has been distributed to the
19 other centers where the new equipment is being installed, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   The FAA has been planning for several years to replace the old
computers, but has sped the program to finish before the end of the
year, to avoid having to upgrade the old ones. Among the problems
with the old computers is that unless their programming is changed,
they will treat the year 2000 as if it is 1900, and will fail to
insert a leap day on Feb. 29.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
