<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NJ-DEATH-PENALTY </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REACTION SPLIT ON TIME LIMIT   FOR KILLER'S DEATH SENTENCE  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By ANDY NEWMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A New Jersey judge's unprecedented _ and largely symbolic _
imposition of a five-year deadline on the state to execute a newly
condemned man drew astonishment from legal experts Saturday, even
among those who oppose the death penalty.
</P>
<P>
   Some applauded the judge, Reginald Stanton of Superior Court,
for sending a message to higher courts that the appeals process for
death sentences is glacially slow and should be overhauled. But
others said that if the escape clause is upheld, which is unlikely,
it would only make the system less efficient, not more. One of the
defendant's own lawyers said she did not know what to make of the
ruling.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, after a jury in Newton sentenced Thomas J. Koskovich
to death for his role in the 1997 killings of two pizza
deliverymen, Stanton ruled that the sentence must be changed to
life in prison if Koskovich, 21, is not executed within five years.
</P>
<P>
   The judge who has been on the bench since 1975 and is the chief
Superior Court judge for Sussex and Morris Counties, admitted he
had no authority to make such a ruling, since New Jersey law gives
the trial judge no latitude to overturn a jury's death sentence.
But he said he wanted to put the nation's legal system on notice
that delaying executions can amount to cruel and unusual punishment
for people on death row.
</P>
<P>
   David A. Ruhnke, a New Jersey defense lawyer who has tried a
dozen capital cases, said that the years it can take for a
death-penalty case to work its way through the system are not
wasted.
</P>
<P>
   ``I suppose he's making a statement on how long it takes to
review death verdicts, but the answer to that is that it should
take a long time,'' Ruhnke said. ``I don't think that putting a
five-year deadline on it is good for Koskovich or is good for
capital jurisprudence itself.''
</P>
<P>
   In making his ruling, Stanton said: ``It may be that we would be
well advised to join most of the civilized countries of the world
in abolishing the death penalty. But if we are to have a death
penalty, then we should have the skill, the courage, and the
decency to carry out the death sentences in a reasonably
expeditious manner.''
</P>
<P>
   In cases around the country, the judge noted, executing a
condemned prisoner takes an average of 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   But James S. Liebman, a professor at Columbia Law School who
specializes in the death penalty and who, like the other experts
interviewed about Stanton's ruling, had never heard of a similar
decision, said that the judge's order, if upheld, would have ``the
perverse effect of aggravating exactly the problems that lead to
delay in the first place.''
</P>
<P>
   Already, he said, prosecutors try to cut corners and withhold
from the defense mitigating evidence that might lead a jury not to
impose a death sentence, or might provide the basis for an appeal
of a death sentence, and already defense lawyers stall as much as
they can after a death sentence is imposed, simply to prolong their
clients' lives.
</P>
<P>
   It would be more effective, Liebman said, for a judge to order
both sides to proceed in good faith. ``An interesting order would
be for the court to say, `State, I want you to agree to turn over
your entire file to the defendant immediately, and defendant, I
want you to agree to file the papers expeditiously,''' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Pamela Brause, one of Koskovich's state-appointed lawyers, said
she was puzzled by the ruling.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't exactly know what we think of it,'' she said. ``It
cuts both ways. In Koskovich's case, if the courts agree that the
judge could do this, it could end up being a huge benefit because
there's no way we could finish this in five years as the system
stands now.''
</P>
<P>
   People sentenced to death in New Jersey have an absolute right
to appeal their cases to the state Supreme Court, a process that
Ms. Brause said takes at least a year. If the verdict is upheld,
the state Supreme Court is then required to review the sentence to
see if it is warranted. If the sentence still stands, the defendant
can appeal to the federal courts.
</P>
<P>
   But if a five-year deadline became the law of the land, Ms.
Brause said, it could lend ammunition to those looking to restrict
the rights of capital defendants.
</P>
<P>
   ``If this policy became adopted then they would start looking to
restrict appeals,'' she said. ``There's people on the other side
who are talking about speeding up the process and they mean speed
up the process and kill people.''
</P>
<P>
   New Jersey has not executed anyone since restoring the death
penalty in 1982, and there are currently 15 prisoners in the state
on death row, including Koskovich.
</P>
<P>
   Dennis Curtis, a Yale Law School professor and an expert in
prisoners' rights, said that the judicial system needed more judges
to speak their minds as Stanton has.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think voices of judges coming from below, telling the courts
of appeal and the Supreme Court what they think, is a tremendous
asset to the development of law,'' Curtis said.
</P>
<P>
   He added that one of the most noteworthy things about the
judge's quixotic ruling is that it there did not seem to be much
that prosecutors could do to appeal it for now.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nothing has really happened yet,'' he said. ``They haven't not
executed him within five years. So a court might say, `There hasn't
been a delay amounting to five years. When it happens we'll talk
about it. If you execute him within five years, it's moot.'''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
