<SLUG> BC-BBO-NOTEBOOK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PITCHING-POOR CLUBS LOOK TO LESS-IS-MORE TACTIC
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By MURRAY CHASS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Lou Piniella did not sleep well Friday night. ``When you get
your butt beat, your mind starts working overtime,'' the Seattle
manager said Saturday, referring to the Mariners' 10-1 loss to the
Yankees the night before. ``That Energizer bunny kicks in around
2:30 in the morning. You keep searching for solutions.''
</P>
<P>
   As he lay awake at the Mariners' New York City hotel, Piniella
seized upon an idea: he would try to ease his pitching problems by
eliminating one starter and going with a four-man rotation.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was one of my brainstorms about 4 in the morning,'' he
said, showing no apparent effects of his lack of sleep or abundance
of thinking. ``Now, at 4 in the morning it seemed to work for me.
Whether it works at 7 o'clock at night or 1:30 in the afternoon,
I'm not sure.''
</P>
<P>
   With the lack of decent pitching all around baseball, both at
the back end of the starting rotation and in middle-innings relief,
it is curious that more managers don't adopt the four-man rotation.
Some teams have trouble finding a capable fourth starter, let alone
a fifth, so why not reduce the risk teams take with pitchers who
aren't ready to fill the starting role?
</P>
<P>
   Johnny Oates has done it in Texas. Since the Rangers were in New
York on April 20, Oates has used four starters _ Rick Helling,
Aaron Sele, Mark Clark and Mike Morgan. He doesn't plan to play the
rest of the season with only those four starters, but he'll go as
far as he feels he can.
</P>
<P>
   The only problem for the Rangers has been that they haven't
fared any better with four starters than they did with five in the
first three weeks of the season. With a five-man rotation, they had
a 7-7 record. With four, they had an 8-7 record entering Saturday's
game.
</P>
<P>
   Most teams have the kind of pitching problems the Mariners and
Rangers have had. The Yankees are one of the few who do not. The
Yankees, in fact, have encountered the opposite problem: they have
too many starters.
</P>
<P>
   After Hideki Irabu pitched seven strong innings against the
Mariners on Friday night, the Yankees have to decide whether to use
Irabu or Ramiro Mendoza in the rotation after Roger Clemens returns
from the disabled list.
</P>
<P>
   Clemens is eligible to do that Thursday, but indications are he
may take a few extra days to make sure his left hamstring is sound.
If he isn't ready Thursday, Irabu can start that game, giving the
Yankees additional time to make the choice between him and Mendoza.
</P>
<P>
   Piniella can only dream about such a problem. The AL West is
waiting for one of its four teams to establish dominance over the
other three, but no one has enough pitching to stake that claim.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a long year already and we just got started,'' Piniella
said, then, discussing his pitching staff, added: ``We started with
a $16 million pitching payroll and we lost four and a half million.
We're playing with an $11.5 million payroll. Kevin Brown makes $15
million a year himself. Randy Johnson makes $13 million.''
</P>
<P>
   Injuries have knocked out two of the Mariners' veterans for the
season. Butch Henry, who made four starts, has a torn labrum in his
left shoulder, and Mark Leiter, who relieved in only two games, has
a torn rotator cuff.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I had Leiter, we would've won two or three more games,''
Piniella said.
</P>
<P>
   The Mariners have suffered other key injuries as well. Carlos
Guillen, the rookie second baseman acquired in the Johnson deal
with Houston last July, is lost for the season with a torn knee
ligament, and Alex Rodriguez, the super shortstop, has been out
with torn knee cartilage since the first week of the season.
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez's return, which Piniella said may come Friday, will
help immeasurably, but it won't improve the pitching staff, which
is the worst in the league with a 6.37 earned run average, 319 hits
allowed and a .307 opponents' batting average.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're sorting out who can pitch and who can't,'' Piniella
said. ``We're finding out painfully. We've found a few who can
pitch.''
</P>
<P>
   Not enough, obviously. Certainly not enough to enable the staff
to make good on a pledge Stan Williams, the pitching coach, made to
his boss.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Steamer told me coming out of spring training,'' Piniella
said, ``that his goal was to get our ERA under four. I told him
last night if you get it under six, I'll be happy.''
</P>
<P>
   Piniella called Williams into his office in the visiting team's
clubhouse at Yankee Stadium for a meeting about the four-man
rotation idea. They brought in Jeff Fassero and Jamie Moyer, their
two veteran starters, and discussed the plan with them.
</P>
<P>
   When the meeting was over, Piniella pronounced: ``We're going to
try it. We have some days off through the 10th of June, so it makes
it easier.''
</P>
<P>
   Freddy Garcia, Saturday's starter, and Mac Suzuki, who made his
second start Friday night, will join Fassero and Moyer in the
five-week experiment.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll plug along,'' Piniella said. ``Or is it plod?''
</P>
<P>
   Then he paused and grinned, an obviously humorous thought
percolating in his fertile brain.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it works,'' he said, ``it might get me manager of the
month.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
