<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CALICHMAN-PROFILE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COAST TO COAST TO COAST FOR CALICHMAN OF THE REVOLUTION 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By ANDREW R. TRIPALDI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   One year ago at this time, life could not have been better for
Dan Calichman. He was the captain of the Los Angeles Galaxy, a
perennial Major League Soccer power, and he loved his teammates and
the surrounding environment.
</P>
<P>
   But that rosy picture changed drastically on May 7, 1998, when
Calichman inadvertently collided with Marcelo Balboa during a game
against the Colorado Rapids, breaking his right leg.
</P>
<P>
   Calichman underwent successful surgery on May 9 at the Kerlin
and Jobe Orthopedic Clinic in Los Angeles. Instead of putting a
cast on his right leg, Ronald Kvitne inserted a rod through the
broken bone. Calichman was able to start his rehabilitation only a
few days later.
</P>
<P>
   ``Breaking your leg is always a serious injury,'' Calichman
said. ``It's not as serious as tearing your ACL, but you have to
mend the bone and rehabilitate the muscles around the break to get
back into game shape.'' He was referring to the anterior cruciate
ligament.
</P>
<P>
   At the time of the injury, Calichman had played in eight games
for Los Angeles. The Galaxy finished the 1998 season without
Calichman with a 24-8 record and first place in the league's
Western Conference. The Galaxy was then eliminated in the second
round of the playoffs by the eventual league champion, the Chicago
Fire.
</P>
<P>
   After the season ended, Galaxy coach Octavio Zambrano decided
that Calichman, 31, no longer fit into the team's plans and traded
his stalwart defender to New England for draft picks on Dec. 30.
</P>
<P>
   Calichman, who played in 60 games in his first two seasons with
the team, felt his injury was a convenient excuse for the trade,
noting that Zambrano wanted to start a youth movement in Los
Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   Interestingly, featuring younger players, the Galaxy got off to
a disappointing 2-3 start. Management counseled a win-now
mentality, and on April 22, Zambrano was dismissed although his
career record with the Galaxy was 39-18. The former UCLA coach,
Sigi Schmid, replaced Zambrano.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, New England (2-3) and coach Walter Zenga welcomed
Calichman warmly. And his anticipation grew after the Revolution
acquired two more accomplished veterans, forward Giovanni Savarese
on Jan. 20 and midfielder John Harkes on Feb. 2.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a lot of talented players here in New England,''
said Calichman, who has started and finished all six games this
season before Saturday night's home game against the Miami Fusion.
</P>
<P>
   ``The problem is that there isn't a lot of chemistry right now
between the guys. That takes time to develop. The talent will
always be there, but good chemistry will always equal success.''
</P>
<P>
   Calichman calls Zenga, who played on the Italian national team,
a players' coach. As the Revolution goalie, Zenga is also the
league's first player-coach. ``When I began preparing for this
year, Dan Calichman was one of the players I wanted to have on the
Revolution,'' Zenga said. ``I believe he is one of the best
defenders in the league. He has tremendous experience, is a very
intelligent player and is very important on the field and in the
locker room.''
</P>
<P>
   Calichman was named the MLS defensive player of the year in 1996
by USA Today and believes that good defense leads to better
offense. One need look no further back for proof, Calichman said,
than France's victory in last summer's 1998 World Cup.
</P>
<P>
   Although Calichman relished the soccer-savvy fans of Southern
California, mostly adults who have been following the game for a
long time, his own roots are in the East.
</P>
<P>
   At Walt Whitman High School in Huntington Station, N.Y., from
1983-86, Calichman played soccer and lacrosse, basketball. A big
sports fan who rooted for the Mets and Islanders, Calichman closely
followed the old New York Cosmos of the North American Soccer
League, often making the journey to Giants Stadium to watch their
home games. Then as a four-time all-American soccer player at
Williams College from 1986-1990, Calichman had nine goals and eight
assists in his collegiate career.
</P>
<P>
   After graduating from college, Calichman went to Japan and was
the first American to play for Mazda F.C., which later became
Hiroshima San Frecce, from 1990-93. He came back to the United
States in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   Calichman called playing in Japan, where weekend crowds would
reach 50,000, ``a positive experience because I got to play
professional soccer 11 months out of the year.''
</P>
<P>
   Playing in New England, Calichman is looking forward to planting
seeds for the game's future here.
</P>
<P>
   ``In Massachusetts and the bordering states, there is a lot of
youth playing soccer and that correlates to increased popularity,''
he said. ``New England is always up there in attendance. The crowd
is mostly young kids and their parents.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
