r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-GALLOWAY-COLUMN-T     05-08 0753
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-GALLOWAY-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT'S NONE OF YOU BUSINESS WHY TUINEI DIED
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY GALLOWAY 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
FORT WORTH, Texas _ This autopsy report that's due shortly on Mark
Tuinei _ why do you care?
<TEXT>
<P>
   Or to be more blunt...
</P>
<P>
   Frankly, my dear, it's none of your damn business, or mine.
</P>
<P>
   A grieving wife and grieving family will know the results. And
if they want to privately inform grieving friends, so be it. The
Plano police have a death investigation to complete, making them
obviously the first to know.
</P>
<P>
   But unless the autopsy indicates that a crime might have been
committed by unknown persons, why can't Mark Tuinei rest in peace?
</P>
<P>
   Of course, open-record laws in this state will give the gawkers
and the parasites and the slimy sector of the local media the
opportunity to kick around a dead man. If, that is, the autopsy
shows Tuinei was involved in something he shouldn't have been,
resulting in his own death.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday was one of those days when you wonder whatever happened
to common decency. Tuinei was a public figure, he was found dead
under strange circumstances, so, therefore, it's a large story.
</P>
<P>
   I didn't do any public polls, but it seemed to me many more
people had a powerful lust to learn why Tuinei died instead of a
sadness over the tradegy of a 39-year-old good guy being found
lifeless in the driveway of his Plano home.
</P>
<P>
   Dale Hansen said it right that night on TV:
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know why he died. I don't know how he died. And I
don't care. ... I'm one of the lucky ones. I saw Mark Tuinei
live.''
</P>
<P>
   The public worship of jocks around here has long been
documented, and thank goodness for that. It has kept many of us
from ever having to hold a real job.
</P>
<P>
   But on behalf of Tuinei, let it be said he represented as a
player everything an adoring Cowboys fandom should want in its
heroes.
</P>
<P>
   Tuinei was a massive offensive talent who contributed greatly to
the winning of Super Bowls. In his quiet, friendly way, he did so
without an ounce of ego ever showing. In the good times and bad,
Tuinei was always a steady force, durable enough to constantly play
through pain and injuries for 15 long seasons.
</P>
<P>
   In a Valley Ranch locker room that became divided at times,
Tuinei was always a bridge to all groups. He was the most popular
player among teammates on the Cowboys.
</P>
<P>
   When image trouble dropped on the franchise like a nuclear bomb,
Tuinei's name was never linked to any of that. But yes, he had been
enrolled at one time in the NFL's substance-abuse program.
Actually, he was one of the original NFL players to be red-flagged.
Something about alcohol.
</P>
<P>
   To Tuinei's credit, however, he not only earned his way off the
substance-abuse list, he became privately known to league officials
as a prime example of how the NFL hoped the program would work. Not
that it always does, as other cases at Valley Ranch keep reminding
us.
</P>
<P>
   Tuinei did freely admit to growing up in Hawaii more street
tough than even football tough. He was kicked off the team at UCLA,
returned to the islands to play for the University of Hawaii and
did a three-month jail term there for assault.
</P>
<P>
   But once he arrived in Dallas as a Cowboys free agent in 1983,
Tuinei attempted to take his life to another level.
</P>
<P>
   What caused Mark Tuinei to die at age 39? Don't know. Like Dale
Hansen, don't care. I just wish there were more like him. I'm just
sorry he's dead.
</P>
<P>
   If that autopsy report brings ``bad'' news, and particularly if
current Cowboys are implicated in any way, some in the media will
rejoice. Hey, it's a hot story. It's another Cowboy-gone-bad
episode. And yes, the image disaster boils over again.
</P>
<P>
   One year after his retirement from the NFL, Tuinei may have
killed himself with whatever he was doing into the wee hours of
Thursday morning. That alone is the sickening tragedy.
</P>
<P>
   But this is not about some fool with a toe ache. Or a key player
caught in an Irving motel room with snort and strippers. Or a key
player crashing his Mercedes into a concrete wall at 80 mph. Or a
key player constantly flunking drug tests.
</P>
<P>
   All of that greatly impacted the Cowboys on the field. This
doesn't, but it's much, much more important. This is about dying
far too young.
</P>
<P>
   If the ``why'' part is important to you, then please leave your
name and number after the beep.
</P>
<P>
   Just so I can tell you again it's none of your damn business.
(Randy Galloway is a columnist for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
