   (NYT13) WASHINGTON -- May 8, 1999 -- DEA-MUSEUM, 5-08 -- Among
the drug paraphernalia used in 1970 is this homemade bong on
display at the Drug Enforcement Administration's new museum. The
bong, a water pipe for smoking marijuana, was once seized by agents
in the field. The museum entwines three themes: the trends in the
popularity of drugs, society's reactions to those trends and the
evolution of federal drug enforcement. (Stephen Crowley/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT12) ATLANTA -- May 8, 1999 -- SOCCER-MOMS-2, 5-08 -- Carla
Overbeck, 31, a star defender for Team USA, and her son Jackson
share some leisure time at Emory University. Overbeck and a fellow
teammate Joy Fawcett, have negotiated to have the U.S. soccer
federation pay for a nanny to accompany the team and to help care
for their young children. ``We don't pay for day care at home; we
are our own day care,'' says Overbeck. ``We didn't think we should
have to incur those expenses in being uprooted for six months.''
(Jim Middleton/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) ATLANTA -- May 8, 1999 -- SOCCER-MOMS, 5-08 -- Carla
Overbeck, left, a star defender for Team USA, and Joy Fawcett,
right, with their nanny, Nikki Richards, center, and Joy's
daughters, Carli and Katey. Overbeck and teammate Fawcett, have
negotiated to have the U.S. soccer federation pay for a nanny to
accompany the team and to help care for their young children. (Jim
Middleton/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) NEW YORK -- May 8, 1999 -- HEROIN-COUPLE, 5-08 -- Paul,
38, and Kathy Schroeder, 37, preparing to inject heroin with
another addict, lost their home in Wayne, N.J., and live in a
shelter in Harlem. Doctors and sociologists report that the use of
heroin has increased among whites because its unprecedented purity
allows users to obtain a high by inhaling, rather than injecting,
the drug. ``It's not where I planned to be at this time of my
life,'' says Schroeder. Their two daughters, now 17 and 13, and
son, now 10, have been taken in by relatives. (Edward Keating/New
York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) UNDATED -- May 8, 1999 -- LEMBA-JEWISH-GENES-3, 5-08 --
Matshaya Mthivha is a spiritual leader of the Lemba of Africa.
Scientists say that the Lemba have a Jewish ancestry. ``The Lemba
have clan names like Sadiqui and Hamisi that are clearly Semitic
and that are also found in the eastern Hadramawt,'' says Dr. Tudor
Parfit, director of the Center for Jewish Studies at the School of
Oriental and African Studies in London and has done research among
the Lemba for 10 years. (New York Times Photo/Courtesy of Dr. Tudor
Parfit)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) UNDATED -- May 8, 1999 -- LEMBA-JEWISH-GENES-2, 5-08 --
Lemba leaders at a stone wall from the original tribal settlement
in Zimbabwe. Scientists say that the Lemba have a Jewish ancestry.
``The Lemba have clan names like Sadiqui and Hamisi that are
clearly Semitic and that are also found in the eastern Hadramawt,''
says Dr. Tudor Parfit, director of the Center for Jewish Studies at
the School of Oriental and African Studies in London and has done
research among the Lemba for 10 years. (New York Times
Photo/Courtesy of Dr. Tudor Parfit)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) OXFORD, England -- May 8, 1999 -- LEMBA-JEWISH-GENES-1,
5-08 -- Dr. David B. Goldstein, a population geneticist at Oxford
University, has been trying to create a better genetic signature of
Jewish populations. Goldstein has found a particular set of genetic
mutations that are strongly associated with the priestly caste, not
so common among lay Jews, and very rare among non-Jewish
populations. ``In studying the priesthood, we happened into this
tool for distinguishing Jewish from non-Jewish populations,'' says
Goldstein. (Jonathan Player/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) FRAMINGHAM, Mass. -- May 8, 1999 -- ASSISTED-LIVING-3,
5-08 -- Enid Houlding sorts through her mail with the help of her
daughter-in-law, Margaret Houlding at the Heritage, an
assisted-living center in Framingham. Today, in one of the most
sweeping changes in the way the old live, assisted living is the
focus of the industry that has grown out of caring for the aging.
About 1.2 million people live in assisted-living facilities around
the country. (James Estrin/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) FRAMINGHAM, Mass. -- May 8, 1999 -- ASSISTED-LIVING-2,
5-08 -- Trudy Faessler, 87, third from left, her son Tom, with his
three daughters and wife Susan, far right, celebrate a birthday at
the Heritage, an assisted-living center in Framingham, the day
after Mrs. Faessler moved in. Osteoporosis has left Mrs. Faessler
too weak even to lift a tea kettle. She needs the services
available at Heritage, where her $2,750-a-month rent includes three
meals a day, housekeeping and help with bathing and dressing.
(James Estrin/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) FRAMINGHAM, Mass. -- May 8, 1999 -- ASSISTED-LIVING-1,
5-08 -- Ginny Sherwood helps her father, George, move into an
assisted living center in Framingham. Today, in one of the most
sweeping changes in the way the old live, assisted living is the
focus of the industry that has grown out of caring for the aging.
About 1.2 million people live in assisted-living facilities, and
communities across the country are asking developers to build more
so that their aging residents can stay close to home. (James
Estrin/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) VELIKA DOBRANJA, Yugoslavia -- May 8, 1999 --
KOSOVO-SERBIA, 5-08 -- In Velika Dobranja, an ethnic Albanian
village in Kosovo, Mehmet Llugiqi, 36, and his sister-in-law Minire
brought chairs for visitors. ``No one has bothered us here,'' says
Llugiqi. ``But we don't know what will happen tomorrow.'' Velika
Dobranja is a purely Albanian village set in the Kosovo plains, a
majority-Serb town. A number of the Albanians here speak Serbian,
and the KLA was never much of a presence. So the Yugoslav Army and
militarized police have largely left the village to its own
devices. (Steven Erlanger/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) ST. PETERSBURG, Fla. -- May 8, 1999 -- SUICIDE-BRIDGE-2,
5-08 -- The Sunshine Skyway Bridge which spans Tampa Bay. Hoping to
stop a steadily rising number of suicides on the bridge, which
links St. Petersburg with Florida's southwest coast, Gov. Jeb Bush
is pushing state transportation officials to build a barrier and
install special telephones that would quickly connect people
considering suicide there with counselors. (Ricardo J. Ferro/New
York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) ST. PETERSBURG, Fla. -- May 8, 1999 -- SUICIDE-BRIDGE-1,
5-08 -- Cpl. Gary Schluter, a Florida Highway patrolman, on the
Sunshine Skyway Bridge which spans Tampa Bay. Hoping to stop a
steadily rising number of suicides on the bridge, which links St.
Petersburg with Florida's southwest coast, Gov. Jeb Bush is pushing
state transportation officials to build a barrier and install
special telephones that would quickly connect people considering
suicide there with counselors. Schulter has been credited with
saving four lives in two years on the skyway. (Ricardo J. Ferro/New
York Times Photo)
</P>
