<DOCNO> NYT19990508.0196 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-08 19:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9530 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEN-KAFELNIKOV-510&AMP;AD     05-08 1024
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-KAFELNIKOV-510&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TOP-RANKED KAFELNIKOV TAKES A BREAK FROM THE STRESS
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By CHRISTOPHER CLAREY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   There is not much reason to pity the best men's professional
tennis players, for whom the airport lounges and hotel suites begin
to run together in a gilded blur. But last week, an exception could
have been made for Yevgeny Kafelnikov.
</P>
<P>
   His dream had finally become reality. He was No. 1 in the world,
the first Russian to reach that position. But the timing was
rotten.
</P>
<P>
   The computer said he was supposed to be the toughest man to beat
in tennis, but the truth is, he could not win a match.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a double-edged sword,'' said Larry Stefanki, the
Californian who is Kafelnikov's coach. ``As an athlete, you're
stuck in the mode of how you are playing, and so Yevgeny's
overjoyed and excited in one way and quite depressed in the other.
He feels so bad for not playing well, and I'm just trying to get
him to focus on the big picture. To get to No. 1 is an unbelievable
accomplishment. I've had to literally shake him, and say: `Wake up.
Life's too short. Enjoy this moment.'''
</P>
<P>
   Kafelnikov put himself in position to reach the top by winning
the Australian Open, the year's first Grand Slam event. But he has
now lost six matches in a row, and instead of starting his reign
last week as planned on clay at the Super 9 event in Hamburg,
Germany, he withdrew with what officially is a viral infection and
what unofficially is burnout.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel a little bit weak, mentally and physically tired,''
Kafelnikov said after losing in three sets to Richard Fromberg in
his error-riddled opening match at the Czech Open in Prague two
weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's healthy, just mentally fried,'' Stefanki said. ``He
hasn't had a week off since Australia, and after a while, you get
like a mouse on a treadmill.''
</P>
<P>
   That is, of course, not the way Stefanki would have planned it.
Since Kafelnikov became a force on the men's tour in 1994, some of
his advisers have been trying to get him to tame his schedule and
conserve his resources for big events.
</P>
<P>
   But until now, the tall and graceful Russian has done little
more than pay lip service to the concept, and it remains unclear
whether his post-match comments in Prague _ ``I should probably
change my schedule and devote more time to rest'' _ represent a
genuine shift in philosophy or just another despondent jerk of the
knee.
</P>
<P>
   Kafelnikov has long believed that he needed a lot of matches to
be at his best, and though his neocapitalistic instincts have
certainly been a factor, it has not just been about the money. It
has also been about keeping busy for fear of losing his edge.
</P>
<P>
   Stefanki, a relentlessly upbeat sort who began coaching
Kafelnikov this season after helping Marcelo Rios of Chile reach
No. 1 last year, is hopeful but uncertain that his new pupil can
evolve.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yevgeny is just one of those guys who has to reach conclusions
on his own time, to learn by his own mistakes and own decisions,''
Stefanki said. ``It takes him a little bit longer to get a clue. He
just doesn't realize how important it is to have the desire and be
a little bit nervous to play instead of just showing up.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Of course, without a surplus of desire, there is no way
Kafelnikov could have made it this far.
</P>
<P>
   Massive change is part of the package in professional tennis,
but while middle-class youths like Pete Sampras and Carlos Moya and
Richard Krajicek have seen their lives altered radically, none had
to negotiate political upheaval before they turned professional.
Kafelnikov did.
</P>
<P>
   His father, Alexander, once played volleyball in the Soviet
First Division for the powerful Red Army club in Moscow, but
Kafelnikov grew up in more mild southern climes in Sochi, a resort
town of several hundred thousand inhabitants on the shores of the
Black Sea where the fishing and tennis are good year-round.
</P>
<P>
   He was raised in a system where talent was identified and
nurtured early by the state, but shortly after turning 17 in 1991,
Kafelnikov was operating in a void. Where once there had been a
stable of national coaches and ample support for training, there
was only uncertainty in the wake of the dissolution of the Soviet
Union.
</P>
<P>
   But Kafelnikov, long considered less promising than his former
Soviet teammate Andrei Medvedev, had two things in his corner
amidst the tumult. First, he had played well enough as a junior to
attract a small amount of seed capital from International
Management Group. Second, he had the support of Anatoly Lepeshin,
the former Soviet junior coach who decided to remain based in
Moscow and cast his lot with Kafelnikov instead of selling his
skills abroad.
</P>
<P>
   Kafelnikov could serve better for a man of his height _ 6 feet 3
inches _ but he returns serve beautifully and is a fluid force from
the baseline, able to read the flight of the ball quickly and
handle the rhythm of a high-velocity ground-stroke exchange as well
as Andre Agassi in his prime.
</P>
<P>
   With Lepeshin's moral and technical support, Kafelnikov quickly
emerged from the satellite and challenger circuits and nearly upset
Sampras in the second round of the Australian Open in 1994. Little
more than two years later, he beat Sampras en route to his first
Grand Slam singles title at the 1996 French Open. He then dropped
back again, but after an emotional year in which he split with
Lepeshin, got married and celebrated the birth of his first child,
he has replaced Sampras as No. 1.
</P>
<P>
   The trouble is, he has done it more by default than domination.
Sampras skipped the Australian and has played abysmally of late by
his standards. And though the ATP Tour's soon-to-be-scrapped
ranking system only counts a player's 14 best results during a
year, it is self-evident Kafelnikov has not had a result worth
counting since February.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's sad that people are focusing on that instead of his play
the last 12 months,'' Stefanki said. ``He started the year
tremendously, and I'm just trying to keep him from being gutted by
all this.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
