<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-08 19:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9534 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NATO-EMBASSY-BOS &LR;      05-08 0918
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NATO-EMBASSY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEAPONS-SUPPLY OFFICE WAS TARGET, ALLIANCE AIDES SAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By AARON ZITNER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ NATO officials said Saturday they had intended to
strike a Serb weapons-supply office when they accidentally bombed
the Chinese Embassy in Yugoslavia Friday night, killing at least
three people.
</P>
<P>
   NATO Secretary General Javier Solana apologized for the ``tragic
mistake'' but vowed more assaults until Yugoslavia withdraws its
forces from Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Major General Walter Jertz, a NATO spokesman, said military
planners believed the embassy building was Yugoslavia's
``directorate for supply and procurement.'' Neither NATO nor US
officials would say how the mistake was made _ or which country
made it _ but one possibility was that planners were working from
outdated maps.
</P>
<P>
   The bombing, the latest of at least seven incidents in which
NATO forces attacked non-combatants, brought new complications to
the diplomatic efforts to find a peaceful ending to the war.
</P>
<P>
   Russia's foreign minister canceled a trip to Britain to discuss
a proposed peace plan. But Russia's Balkans envoy, Viktor
Chernomyrdin, pressed forward with a visit to Germany to discuss
the plan with Chancellor Gerhard Schroeder.
</P>
<P>
   That peace plan, drafted last week by Russia and the Group of
Seven industrialized nations, is considered the best hope at the
moment for ending the war. Chernomyrdin is expected to arrive
Sunday in Belgrade, the Yugoslav capital.
</P>
<P>
   The aid of Russia _ a traditional ally of Yugoslav President
Slobodan Milosevic _ is considered central in negotiating a peace
plan. China has the power to block the G-7 and Russian proposal,
which calls for UN-approved peacekeeping forces in Kosovo. As a
member of the UN Security Council, China can veto that approval.
</P>
<P>
   Western leaders offered condolences to the victims of the
embassy bombings, but vowed to continue NATO's bombing campaign.
</P>
<P>
   NATO chief Javier Solana, at alliance headquarters in Brussels,
offered ``sympathy and condolences'' to the victims of the bombing
and to the Chinese government. ``But I think it's appropriate at
this very moment also to say that NATO will continue to pursue its
goal _ and its goal is none other than to stop ethnic cleansing and
to ensure that Kosovars can return to their homes,'' Solana said.
</P>
<P>
   Kosovo is a province of Yugoslavia, but NATO nations have said
Western interference is necessary because of atrocities that
Milosevic's forces have committed against the ethnic Albanians who
live in Kosovo. Milosevic, a Serb, has been trying to force ethnic
Albanians from the province. At the same time, an armed movement of
ethnic Albanians has been trying to restore autonomy to Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   The bombing came during what NATO officials called the most
intensive raid yet on Belgrade since airstrikes began March 24. In
addition to the Chinese Embassy, NATO warplanes struck a
presidential command bunker and a hotel that is believed to house a
paramilitary group called the Arkan Tigers, which has been accused
of atrocities in Kosovo, Bosnia, and Croatia.
</P>
<P>
   The embassy bombing came just hours after NATO planes struck a
hospital grounds and residential neighborhood in Yugoslavia's
third-largest city, Nis, reportedly killing 15 and injuring 60.
Jertz, the NATO military spokesman, Saturday said that attack had
been aimed at Serbian aircraft parked at the Nis airfield, as well
as air defense systems and support vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once again, of course, civilian casualties were never
intended, and NATO regrets the loss of life and injuries
inflicted,'' Jertz said.
</P>
<P>
   In recent weeks, NATO planes have also struck a passenger train
and have killed people in a residential section of the Aleksinac,
south of Belgrade. A convoy of ethnic Albanian refugees in Kosovo
was also bombed, leaving a reported 64 people dead.
</P>
<P>
   NATO has said it has taken care to avoid killing non-combatants,
but that civilian casualties were always possible. ``There's no
such thing as clean combat,'' Kenneth Bacon, the Pentagon
spokesman, said Saturday. ``We have the best pilots in the world.
We have the best weapons in the world. We have the best-planned
missions. We have the best-trained forces.
</P>
<P>
   ``But there is no way to avoid collateral damage or unintended
consequences when weapons are employed to solve what might have
been solved diplomatically.''
</P>
<P>
   In other developments Saturday:
</P>
<P>
   -- More than 5,000 refugees arrived in Albania from Kosovo, the
United Nations High Commissioner for Refugees reported. Kosovars
seeking refuge in Albania total more than 407,000, with refugess to
all nations topping 718,000 since March 1998.
</P>
<P>
   -- Ibrahim Rugova, Kosovo's leading ethnic Albanian moderate,
flew to Bonn from Rome to meet with Chernomyrdin before the Russian
envoy heads on to Yugoslavia this morning. Rugova was also to meet
separately with Schroeder and with Carl Bildt, a former Swedish
prime minister who was recently named as UN Secretary General Kofi
Annan's envoy to the Balkans.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, anger was the primary emotion among the Chinese
community in the United States after the embassy bombing.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Hsueh, host of ``Chinese American Voice'' radio show in
New York, said his lines were flooded with callers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course they are angry about this,'' Hsueh said. ``There
have been too many mistakes, too many errors in this invasion.
People are asking, `Why such a big mistake?' ''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
