<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGELS-NOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOLTZ PAYS PRICE FOR ANGELS' INJURIES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- Angels manager Terry Collins looked at his roster
Friday night after catcher Matt Walbeck was knocked woozy in a
home-plate collision in the seventh inning.
</P>
<P>
   There were two names on the list, the same two names that were
there to begin the game -- Charlie O'Brien and Tim Unroe. With Tim
Salmon (sprained left wrist) and Randy Velarde (stiff lower back)
unavailable but still on the active roster, Collins' choice of
reserves was limited.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday he did something about it, as the Angels sent reliever
Mike Holtz to triple-A Edmonton and called up infielder Dave
Silvestri. Silvestri, who can play second, third and shortstop, was
hitting .439 (29 for 66) with one homer, seven doubles and 12 RBIs
in 16 games for Edmonton. He began the season playing for Durham,
the Tampa Bay Devil Rays' triple-A club before being released.
</P>
<P>
   Holtz was 1-1 with a 1.42 ERA, but simply had not been getting
enough work lately because the club was carrying 12 pitchers. He
had pitched twice in the past 10 games.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was surprised a little bit,'' Holtz said of his demotion.
``But you learn in baseball to expect the unexpected. Now I've got
to go there and bust my (rear) to get back. I just need to go
pitch.
</P>
<P>
   ``There haven't been too many situations that dictated me being
in there. I don't think it's because I've pitched that poorly.''
</P>
<P>
   Holtz spoke with his wife, Kristie, outside the Angels clubhouse
quietly for about 30 minutes before talking with reporters Saturday
morning.
</P>
<P>
   ``My main concern is my wife,'' Holtz said. ``She's pregnant
(due in August) and I don't want her worried about things like this
right now.''
</P>
<P>
   Collins said Silvestri, 31, will start today's game, but he
didn't say at which position.
</P>
<P>
   The Boston Herald seemed to get a little loose with the truth in
its gossip column in Friday's editions. The column said that 25
strippers from ``The Foxy Lady'' -- a club Mo Vaughn visited while
he played in Boston -- would be sitting behind the Angels dugout
for Friday's game.
</P>
<P>
   In truth, there were a few women behind the dugout who held
signs like the one that said: ``Mo, We Miss You. The Foxy Lady.''
</P>
<P>
   The column also said Vaughn would leave after Friday's game with
the women to go to a club called ``The Rack. However, Vaughn left
Fenway Park Friday with family members.
</P>
<P>
   Five weeks into the season and only one Angels starting pitcher
-- Omar Olivares (3-3) -- has more than one victory. Chuck Finley,
Tim Belcher and Steve Sparks each are 1-3; Ken Hill is 1-1. ...
Despite a sub-.500 record, the Angels went into Saturday's game
ranked relatively high in team statistics -- they were No. 6 in
team batting (.272), No. 5 in team pitching (4.62 ERA) and No. 4 in
team fielding (.982).
</P>
<P>
   The Angels and Red Sox play the final game of their three-game
series today at 10:05 a.m. at Fenway Park. Hill (1-1, 3.44 ERA)
will start for Anaheim against Boston's Mark Portugal (2-1, 4.45).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
