<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RENOVATIONS-REAL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN THE BEGINNING, IT SEEMED SO SIMPLE ... 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By TRISH HALL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Eventually, it took two and a half years, tens of thousands of
dollars and endless hours of effort. But it started with a very
simple idea.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't want to go down the spiral staircase at 3 in the
morning,'' says Greg Frank. He and his wife, Christine
Alloggiamento, live in an Upper West Side duplex condo apartment
whose master bedroom was built some years ago on the top floor of
the building. It is blessed with dazzling light and views, but it
stood alone up there. A trip to the bathroom in the middle of the
night required an encounter with a spiral staircase, a popular
space saver but hardly a comfortable path to traverse in a
somnolent state.
</P>
<P>
   So they decided to build a bathroom next to their bedroom, a
bathroom that would take up part of their wraparound deck. And
since they were going to be building a new structure anyway, they
figured it might as well have great views and a Jacuzzi, the wading
pool of choice for affluent adults.
</P>
<P>
   In the suburbs, it would be considered a basic bath. In the
city, it became a major production. They are both bankers, with
limited experience in design or construction. If they had been
really unlucky, they would have had trouble with their architect,
or their contractor, or both. Fortunately, they found an architect
they liked, John Lee, and hired as their contractor Frank's cousin,
Marion Smit.
</P>
<P>
   Their problems lay elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   In December 1996, they began work. An expediter investigated the
relevant rules, because they needed not only a building permit but
_ because the building is in a historic district _ approval from
the Landmarks Preservation Commission. Their architect drew up a
number of plans, giving them options, and they chose one, a design
that used a curved wall made of glass block to provide both privacy
and light.
</P>
<P>
   Their first effort to gain landmarks approval went nowhere,
because the commission mistakenly thought their building was a
co-op, a situation that would have required the correction of any
violations in the building before their work could proceed. They
reapplied, and after some time were informally rejected, because
their plan was not in keeping with the building. So Lee drew up a
whole new design, this time dropping the curves in favor of
something quieter. The local community board also evaluated the new
plan, with one member disapprovingly comparing their future
bathroom to Disneyland, saying it would look like a glowing candle
on top of the building.
</P>
<P>
   By July 1997, after many phone calls and many visits to the
relevant agencies, they had approval from the community board, the
city and the landmarks commission, and in August, after a delay
necessitated by their contractor's prior commitments, work began.
</P>
<P>
   And began, and began and began. Because ultimately, almost every
object they needed was damaged, shipped incorrectly, installed
incorrectly or shipped late. Not the kind of people to spend money
without paying attention, the couple met continually with the
architect. ``We would have these amazing marathon meetings starting
at 7, eating potato chips and drinking soda,'' said Lee. ``Everyone
was in a coma.''
</P>
<P>
   But most of all, they were trying to make sure they were getting
what they wanted, and what they had paid for.
</P>
<P>
   Take, for instance, the windows. When the windows were
installed, they were all scratched. When Ms. Alloggiamento called
the company, she recalled, ``the person who answered the phone said
the windows always arrive scratched.''
</P>
<P>
   The company kept insisting the windows were fine, and the
ultimate supervisor never seemed to be around. ``I had to march in
there and insist on talking to the guy,'' said Lee. ``I thought he
was hiding in there, and I was right.''
</P>
<P>
   They had to demand more new windows, and then more new windows,
until finally they ended up with their fourth set, and only then
did they have windows that were not scratched, and windows that
opened and closed properly. Of course, in the process of reaching
that goal, the people who were fixing the windows sliced into the
marble on the tub, so that had to be fixed.
</P>
<P>
   Or, take the floor. They wanted slate tiles from Italy. They
didn't anticipate that the boat would take six weeks to get here,
and then have trouble unloading because the correct papers weren't
on board.
</P>
<P>
   When the tiles did make it to the Upper West Side, and the
contractor began putting them down, she couldn't believe what she
was seeing. They were different colors, and different heights. So
they had to wait nearly two more months for another shipment from
Italy.
</P>
<P>
   Or, take the marble-topped Jacuzzi. They went to the trouble to
visit the stoneyard to pick out a large piece of Carrara, and pay a
premium for it, so they would end up with a continuous top with no
visible lines. When it was installed, however, they came home from
work and discovered that they had, instead, a seam. ``We
contemplated taking it out,'' said Frank, ``but fortunately, we
came to our senses.'' Insisting on perfection, he said, would have
meant that ``this would have gone on forever.''
</P>
<P>
   Cheerful, positive people, Frank and Ms. Alloggiamento don't
want to sound negative about the experience, which had plenty of
other glitches too numerous to detail, including a budget that rose
from $40,000 to $80,000. Construction of their bath was completed
about a year ago, giving them a rooftop aerie that is lovely during
the day and hauntingly beautiful at night. And, a few weeks ago,
they received papers from the city certifying that the plumbing
inspection had been completed, finally putting an end to the long
process.
</P>
<P>
   Asked whether they have any advice for those who come after
them, they do put it simply and clearly: Be very specific about
what you want, and no matter how small the detail or the request
may seem, put it in writing.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
