<SLUG> BC-BKN-HILL-COLUMN-LBPT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DRAFT VS. SCHOOL DAZE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY HILL  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   We are here on the Day of the Mother to evict the mother-in-law
of sports-journalism commandments.
</P>
<P>
   Please hold for the commandment. OK, here's the commandment:
Stay in school!
</P>
<P>
   Commandment update: Stay in school ... unless leaving school can
provide you with more Benjamins than an illegal fireworks stand
below the Mason-Dixon line.
</P>
<P>
   Here's the deal. Demonstrating a bruised morality that's not
available in any store, the career counselors of sports journalism
have begun their annual caterwaul. Basketball players are leaving
college early to begin compensated lab work in the NBA, and our
brothers and sisters don't like it.
</P>
<P>
   Baseball players skip college for much less money every year,
but this exodus doesn't seem to be twisting anyone's conscience.
</P>
<P>
   So why the gnashing of teeth over enterprising basketball
players? Why are high horses being saddled because Duke freshman
Corey Maggette is having trouble choosing between two million NBA
scoots or another season with Mike Krzyzewski? Maggette, for those
of you with poor reception in the cave, is a 6-foot-5 small forward
with shooting-guard aspirations and more athleticism than a stray
cat.
</P>
<P>
   He averaged 10 points for Duke this past season, but wasn't a
starter because he's as raw as Eddie Murphy doing stand-up on
cable. Maggette also invites skepticism with his jump shot, an
unorthodox baby that makes the kid from Chicago look like an
accountant aiming a memo at the wastebasket. But after a year in
the Coach K empire, why does that remain a problem?
</P>
<P>
   Anyway, if he chooses to enter the 1999 NBA Draft (barring
disaster on the personal-tryout tour), Maggette could be chosen
among the top six picks. One explanation is the annual indictment
of the draft pool; this year, the sharpies think the available
talent is weaker than a Dennis Rodman alibi. Another excuse for
Maggette's popularity is that astonishing ability to run fast and
jump high.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he comes out,'' said one league scout who agreed to
surrender anonymity in exchange for the pleasure of immediately
killing us, ``teams picking five or six will be scared to death to
pass him up.''
</P>
<P>
   Yeah, most NBA talent hounds would prefer having every player
exhaust his college eligibility before entering the draft. That
way, there's less risk, and teams don't have to spend millions
developing a prospect. College coaches can do the dirty work while
their athletic department eats the bill.
</P>
<P>
   However, everyone in pro sports wants an edge, which is swell,
because many athletes are ready to perform at an early age. And it
could be argued that the best place to prepare for an NBA career is
the NBA.
</P>
<P>
   As an example, we give you Kevin Garnett.
</P>
<P>
   You may recall that KG and his shaky high school transcript
completely skipped college. But had he been able to spend three
seasons at Michigan or North Carolina, do you truly believe that in
this, his hypothetical rookie season, Garnett could have led the
Minnesota Timberwolves - after the defections of Tom Gugliotta and
Stephon Marbury - into the post-season?
</P>
<P>
   Do you think two seasons flying on the hyperbole of Dick Vitale
would diminish the ego of 1999 Clippers rookie Kobe Bryant?
</P>
<P>
   If you had the opportunity to be paid $2 million (the going
annual rate, give or take, for the fifth or sixth pick) by leaving
school early, would you turn it down? Remember, you'll never be
able to make up that $2 million loss.
</P>
<P>
   If you answered ``yes'' to any of those questions, we hope you
have to spend the balance of this day with your mother-in-law.
</P>
<P>
   Note: The preceding sermon does not apply to rascals who are
incapable of impressing anyone enough to be drafted.
</P>
<P>
   `Most' wonderful time
</P>
<P>
   The runaway question at this point in the NBA season? The winner
is ``Doesn't Rex Chapman play that photographer in the sitcom `Just
Shoot Me'?'' Finishing second is ``Who in the heck is the MVP?''
</P>
<P>
   Our vote goes to San Antonio's Tim Duncan, because his
shot-blocking presence on defense is superior to Karl Malone's
hack-and-flop technique.
</P>
<P>
   But if we had to nominate one player for future domination, it
would be the aforementioned Garnett. At 7-feet, the 22-year-old KG
had more rebounds, assists, blocks and steals than Malone, while
committing fewer turnovers and scoring just three fewer points per
game. What is missed in the statistical blitz is the versatile
Garnett's competitive fire and ability to defend almost any player
in the league.
</P>
<P>
   However, he must choose a money move in the post, a signature
shot that will hike his field-goal accuracy above the current 46
percent.
</P>
<P>
   Our rookie of the year is Toronto's Vince Carter, who has his
own TV show. You may have heard of ``SportsCenter.''
</P>
<P>
   Guilty of being this season's most-improved player is Houston's
Othella Harrington. Eric Snow deserves mention, but the improvement
has more to do with getting minutes than improving his skills.
</P>
<P>
   The coach of the year is Philly's Larry Brown, but in honor of
Larry tradition, we reserve the right to alter this decision.
</P>
<P>
   Weakly draft update
</P>
<P>
   According to league sources who weren't crossing their fingers,
Rhode Island's Lamar Odom is leaning toward skipping the NBA for
another season of college ball.
</P>
<P>
   Odom, a 6-9 fast-break entrepreneur, could be the first pick
this summer. But his mentor, Jerry DeGregorio, recently was
elevated from assistant to head coach at Rhode Island after Jim
Harrick left for Georgia. Regardless, we'll be stunned if Odom
stays.
</P>
<P>
   According to snitches in the Baron Davis camp, UCLA's sophomore
point guard still is expected to enter this summer's draft (he has
another week to make this claim). Davis' agent decision should be a
slam dunk. Take Arn Tellem and give the points.
</P>
<P>
   Yao Ming, the 18-year-old center from China, may enter the '99
draft, after all. Ming - listed at 7-6, but closer to 7-3,
according to eyewitnesses - has signed with an outfit called
Evergreen Sports. Ever and green. Perfect.
</P>
<P>
   If he makes the move, Ming could be the first legit center
selected.
</P>
<P>
   Shot-clock violations
</P>
<P>
   Unless the Lakers pull the plug on Kurt Rambis, expect Phil
Jackson to follow the less-political path of spiritual adjunct to
presidential candidate and Knicks teammate Bill Bradley. ...
Jackson recently skipped an exploratory meeting with the New Jersey
Nets, who were very impressed with the performance of interim coach
Don Casey. Nets players, by the way, are wild about ``Case.'' ...
If the Utah Jazz manage to win the championship in Salt Lake City,
would it be unlawful to chase whine with champagne?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-08-99 2000EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990508.0207 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-08 20:03 </DATE_TIME>
