r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RAC-HORSES-LADN     05-08 0908
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-HORSES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BATTLE LOOMS OVER HORSE RACING'S FUTURE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By FRANK C. GIRARDOT  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   INGLEWOOD -- The new owners of Hollywood Park hope that some
portion of horse racing's future resides on ``The Track of Lakes
and Flowers.''
</P>
<P>
   In a fast-paced world of 24-hour instant sports and
entertainment options, the snail's pace of a day at the track has
become an antiquated relic of simpler times.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, that relic became an harbinger of things to come.
Churchill Downs -- best known for hosting the Kentucky Derby --
said it would purchase Hollywood Park race track and casino, a
237-acre complex, for $140 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
   It could mark the beginning of a battle for domination of the
American horse racing industry that pits the corporate owners of
Hollywood Park against the corporate owners of Santa Anita in
Arcadia. The two companies are locked in a struggle for control of
what some analysts believe will be a $10 billion industry in the
next decade.
</P>
<P>
   If both companies have their way, horse racing in the next
century will be a 24-hour interactive event, featuring in-home
betting on cards from around the world. They believe the changes
will increase profits while bringing excitement and new customers
to an age-old game.
</P>
<P>
   Churchill Downs will add Hollywood Park to its growing roster of
racetracks and off-track betting parlors around the country. Those
tracks include Calder Race Course in Miami and namesake Churchill
Downs in Louisville, Ky. The off-track betting parlors (known as
OTB) are sprinkled throughout the Midwest.
</P>
<P>
   But, ownership of Hollywood Park means that Churchill Downs will
be able to supply some 800 racetracks and OTB facilities around the
country with top-quality thoroughbred racing programs for most of
the year, according to Thomas Meeker, the president and Chief
Executive Officer of Churchill Downs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think as we move down the road we hope to create a product
that is much like ESPN is to cable operations,'' Meeker said. ``If
you are an OTB operator in Sheboygan, or wherever it might be, you
will not be able to deliver your simulcast product unless you have
the Churchill Downs simulcast network as part of your package.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's our objective.''
</P>
<P>
   The sale of Hollywood Park completes a cycle on the Southern
California horse racing scene that began with Canadian entrepreneur
Frank Stronach's purchase of Santa Anita for $126 million in
December.
</P>
<P>
   While both groups had bid on the Arcadia track, Stronach won
largely because Churchill Downs couldn't raise enough cash for the
purchase. Thanks to a series of other buys that allowed Churchill
Downs to increase its corporate line of credit from $50 million to
$250 million in a little under a year, Meeker's corporation was
able to outmaneuver and outbid Stronach for the Hollywood Park
property.
</P>
<P>
   Stronach conceded as much in a recent interview.
</P>
<P>
   ``They wanted too much,'' he said of Hollywood Park. `'I
couldn't see paying that.''
</P>
<P>
   A rumor circulating on the racing scene indicates Stronach is
now interested in purchasing the Gulfstream Park race track in
Hallandale, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Santa Anita Vice President Rick Cowan said there was no
foundation to the rumor.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have no knowledge of that at all,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   If Stronach were to buy Gulfstream, he would control the two
premier winter horse race meets in the country. Meanwhile,
Churchill Downs would have control of the top spring and early
summer meets -- at Hollywood Park and Churchill Downs.
</P>
<P>
   In the short term it could drive up the price of race tracks
around the country. In the long term it could be the end of smaller
venues that run cheap horses.
</P>
<P>
   None of these machinations is occurring in a vacuum.
</P>
<P>
   Instead this is all going on in the shadow a full-scale effort
by the National Thoroughbred Racing Association to get horse racing
back into the mainstream of American sports. Part of that effort is
linked to the planned July launch of TVG, an interactive betting
network that will start cropping up on cable systems throughout the
country.
</P>
<P>
   TVG will allow anyone with access to cable television and a
telephone to place bets on races from around the country. The money
will be part of the overall mutual pool at any given track.
</P>
<P>
   A similar option is already available in some states on the East
Coast, notably Pennsylvania.
</P>
<P>
   Churchill Downs and Fox Television are providing some financial
muscle for the fledgling TVG network, based in Santa Monica. But
some say that Stronach has already kicked them in the teeth.
Instead of feeding his signal to TVG during the just-concluded
Santa Anita spring meet, Stronach opted to broadcast on the
Internet via youbet.com.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's our signal to market,'' Cowan said. ``And what we charge
for it is based on supply and demand.''
</P>
<P>
   What happens next?
</P>
<P>
   For Cowan, ``It's a hard question to answer right now,'' he
said. ``We're planning and strategizing for the next steps. We're
lucky to have a visionary like Frank Stronach.''
</P>
<P>
   As for Hollywood Park and Churchill Downs, R.D. Hubbard, who
sold the track and surrounding property, had a prediction.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's been a lot of changes in racing over the years; you
are going to see a lot more in the near future,'' Hubbard said.
``In my opinion the company that is going to lead the way is going
to be Churchill Downs.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
