<SLUG> BC-OKLA-STORMS-CLINTON-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON ORDERS JOB RELIEF IN AFTERMATH OF TORNADOES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (SUBS to update; some material repeats, but substantially new.)  (lh) 
 By DAVID E. ROSENBAUM   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DEL CITY, Okla. _ Clearly shaken by the extent of the damage
here from last Monday's tornadoes, President Clinton Saturday
promised the families who had lived in one devastated neighborhood
that the federal government would temporarily hire thousands of
Oklahomans who had lost their jobs in businesses that were
destroyed by the storms.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't have to make up these jobs,'' the president said,
standing in what was once the driveway of a flattened brick house
and sweeping out his arm to point out the destruction around him.
``There's a lot of work that needs to be done here.''
</P>
<P>
   The jobs will be on construction crews and relief teams.
</P>
<P>
   Taking a detour from what was scheduled to be a political
fund-raising trip to Texas, Clinton flew over the area in a
military helicopter with Gov. Frank Keating and James Lee Witt,
director of the Federal Emergency Management Agency.
</P>
<P>
   Then, with several members of Oklahoma's all-Republican
congressional delegation, he walked through a leveled subdivision
of one-story houses in this suburb south of Oklahoma City.
</P>
<P>
   In the driveway of the wreckage at 4212 Angela Drive, where
David and Catrina Haider and their two children had lived, Clinton
told several hundred families that he was familiar with tornado
damage from his years as governor of Arkansas but that Saturday was
a new experience for him.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the most devastating tornado I've ever seen,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   The Haiders _ he is a technician for America Online, she works
in a check-processing center _ said they rode out the storm huddled
in a closet as their house collapsed around them.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton told them and their neighbors on Angela Drive that he
hoped they would consider tornado safety when they rebuilt their
houses, and he noted that the law allows part of federal emergency
loan money to be used for this purpose.
</P>
<P>
   ``For goodness sake,'' he said, ``build a safe room in your
house.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said he would support money for a national weather
center at the University of Oklahoma, where he hoped research could
be done into how to ``deflate the strength of some of these very
powerful tornadoes before they hit.''
</P>
<P>
   Earlier, on the helicopter tour, the president seemed stunned by
the destruction. ``It's frightening,'' he said to Keating. ``It
didn't matter what room you were in. You can't imagine the power of
these things.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton told the governor that when he was growing up in
Arkansas, most houses had storm cellars, but few houses in Del City
have them today. He suggested that perhaps housing codes should
require them.
</P>
<P>
   The tornadoes killed 46 people and injured hundreds more in
Oklahoma and Kansas, with suburban areas around Oklahoma City the
hardest hit. About 12,000 homes were destroyed in the two states.
The list of the missing, which at one time numbered about 100
people, has been narrowed to four, and rescue workers said that
they may never be found.
</P>
<P>
   In his weekly radio address Saturday, Clinton said he had
instructed the Labor Department to spend more than $12 million to
provide temporary jobs for 3,500 men and women whose jobs were lost
in the tornadoes.
</P>
<P>
   ``They'll be able to feed their families by rebuilding their
communities,'' the president said.
</P>
<P>
   He also said he would ask Congress for an additional $372
million for the Federal Emergency Management Agency to pay for
disaster relief.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton alluded to the political fault line that he believes
divides Democrats from Republicans, who favor reducing the
influence of government. ``The federal government,'' the president
said, ``has the responsibility to provide individuals with the
tools they need to improve their own lives.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton flew here from Texas. After returning to Washington
Thursday night from meetings with allies in Europe on the war in
Yugoslavia, he spent Friday at political fund-raising events in
Houston and Austin that were expected to raise a total of $700,000
for the Democratic Party.
</P>
<P>
   In Texas, he departed from his standard political speech to talk
about the tornadoes in Oklahoma. At a lunch in Houston, where
supporters donated $20,000 per couple, he said:
</P>
<P>
   ``This maybe belongs more in a sermon on Sunday than a political
speech, but the lesson is, no matter how well America does, a
little humility is always in order. We are not in full control. And
we have to be sensitive about this, especially here in this part of
the country. We have to do more to try to prepare ourselves for
these storms, and we have to do more to try to minimize their
impact when they occur.''
</P>
<P>
   Then, at a poolside Mexican dinner at a supporter's home in
Austin, the president brought up the storm again. He said: ``I'm
thinking about what we can do to try to prepare better for the next
one. I'm thinking about what we can do if we know we're going to
grow and expand in areas that have been tornado alleys _ what we
ought to do to build houses that will do a better job of
withstanding them or have quicker escapes to places that will be
safer.''
</P>
</TEXT>
