Some free advice for Rangers' new president 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By T.R. SULLIVAN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
FORT WORTH, Texas _ Jim Lites is new to baseball, so before he
fouls everything up, we should give him a short primer on what he
needs to know as the Rangers' president. 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's the least we can do. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Attend: &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Ruben Mateo for Curt Schilling? No. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Doug Melvin knows what he's doing. If he needs your help, he'll
call. He'll also let you know if a new manager is needed. Right
now, definitely not. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Scouting and player development have to be the foundation of the
franchise. Remember, nobody outspends George Steinbrenner.
Baltimore's Peter Angelos tried and failed miserably. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Pick up a geography book. Locate the Dominican Republic and
Venezuela. Plan a short vacation down there to meet some very
important people. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   You are against the DH. Got that? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   You're allowed to make up your own mind on interleague play and
realignment. But remember, we don't need another round of playoffs.
Think pennant race. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   When in doubt, bet the red dot. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Ruben Mateo for Kenny Rogers? No. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   No advertisements on uniforms. Baseball does not _ repeat, does
not _ need more revenue. There is plenty of revenue now; it just
needs to be shared more equally among ballclubs. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Spend some time with Astros president Tal Smith. Listen to him.
He has been around. Introduce yourself to Sandy Alderson, Major
League Baseball vice president in charge of baseball operations.
Talk to Pat Gillick, now retired but one of the best general
managers ever. Other owners you should talk to include John Moores
(San Diego), Jerry McMorris (Colorado), Bill DeWitt (St. Louis),
and Andy MacPhail (Cubs). &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Don't listen to Angelos, Steinbrenner, Jerry Reinsdorf (White
Sox), Claude Brochu (Montreal), anybody who owns the Mets, or
Rupert Murdoch's errand boys. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Don't panic if you sometimes can't understand what commissioner
Bud Selig is saying. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The grass here occasionally turns brown in the summer. A Zamboni
won't help. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Don't be afraid to take a player to salary arbitration. They
deserve firsthand knowledge of an issue so vital to their union.
Don't worry if you offend them. It's almost impossible not to. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Remember, most players care less about state income tax,
annuities or deferred payments. They just want more money than the
next guy. That's what they mean by market value. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Union chief Don Fehr could care less who you are or what you've
done in hockey. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Don't overlook Maui, Tahiti or the U.S. Virgin Islands as
potential spring-training sites. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Convincing the players to accept a salary cap is hopeless. Stay
off that bandwagon. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   If people suggest abolishing the amateur draft, listen to them.
Smart teams will have the upper hand and Major League Baseball will
be forced to spend more money on this country's amateur programs. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   See if you can do something about the service at the Front Row
Grill. It can be infuriatingly slow and erratic. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Ruben Mateo for Roger Clemens? No. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
\Nsubheds:Yankees vs. Cuba &QL; 
Several New York Yankees watched the Baltimore Orioles get trounced
by Cubans on Monday and were openly angry at the way they played. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``They embarrassed everyone the way they played,'' pitcher
Mariano Rivera said. ``To get beat like that, it was embarrassing.
I don't even know why they even agreed to the game. I saw
\RAlbert\S Belle, standing there, taking pitches. That's not him.
You could tell the Orioles weren't interested.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   There are reports the Yankees want to play the Cubans next year,
and pitcher David Cone is practically begging for it. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I would try to win that game as hard as any game I've ever
played in,'' Cone said. ``I would love to pitch against them.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Said Tino Martinez: ``We obviously have better teams and better
players. But right now, they've got to be thinking they can play at
our level.'' &QL; 
\Nsubheds:Short hops &QL; 
A high-ranking baseball official is supposedly saying Mike
Prentice's $75 million bid to buy the Royals won't pass because the
group has too many investors. That doesn't seem likely. Baseball
would welcome with open arms anybody willing to invest in a
small-market team these days. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   After going 1-for-11 in a three-game series against the Mets,
frustrated Giants third baseman Charlie Hayes called Orel
Hershiser, Allen Watson and Masato Yoshii the ``three worst
starters we've faced all year.'' Said Watson, ``He must be the
worst third baseman we've faced.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Seattle's Lou Piniella saw in USA Today the odds were 6-1 he
would be the first manager fired. Said Piniella, ``I opened the
season at 10-1. I lose a couple of veteran pitchers, my odds went
down.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The latest report is the tumor in Braves first baseman Andres
Galarraga's back has been reduced 75 percent. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It is bad enough the Marlins went 2-11 on their recent
homestand. But it's worse that Milwaukee pitcher Scott Karl, after
a 2-0 shutout, said, ``No offense to the Marlins, but if we played
here 162 games, we'd be looking at the postseason.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Twins reliever Rick Aguilera, who has a no-trade clause, has
apparently changed his mind and now says he would be willing to be
traded to the Cubs and be a setup reliever for Rod Beck. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Pirates general manager Cam Bonifay said he won't trade
outfielder Jose Guillen, even though Guillen was demoted to the
minors last month. Bonifay said a number of teams have called. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Bohanon quiets critics &QL; 
with his best start ever &QL; 
 &QL; 
Colorado's Brian Bohanon is 5-1 with a 3.83 earned-run average
after losing to Philadelphia yesterday. Perhaps it should be
pointed out that four of those five victories were on the road, not
at Coors Field. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But Bohanon's start is the first sign that those of us who
criticized the Rockies for giving him $12 million over three years
might be off-base. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Might. Let's not draw any conclusions yet. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   He still has never won more than seven games in one season. He
still could have his tenuous confidence take a beating after
extended duty in Coors. However he is pitching quite well. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I had my critics going in, but now hopefully I've shut them
up,'' Bohanon said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Hard to believe it's been 12 years since the Rangers made him
their No. 1 draft pick in 1987, one year after doing the same with
Kevin Brown. Makes you want to take another look at Jonathan
Johnson or find out whatever happened to Dan Smith. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Bohanon has learned how to pitch. His best fastball is mid-80s
but he knows how to spot his assortment of junk. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Manager Jim Leyland, who pushed for Bohanon over Todd
Stottlemyre, said, ``Hey, we didn't expect him to be 5-0, but we
thought we'd get a good pitcher.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
Randy Johnson recorded his 2,400th strikeout Wednesday and passed
Sandy Koufax for ninth place in all-time strikeouts by a
left-handed pitcher. The top ten, left-handed and right-handed. &QL; 
Left-handed &QL; 
1. Steve Carlton 4,136 &QL; 
2. Mickey Lolich, 2,832 &QL; 
3. Frank Tanana 2,773 &QL; 
4. Warren Spahn 2,583 &QL; 
5. Jerry Koosman 2,556 &QL; 
6. Jim Kaat 2,461 &QL; 
7. Sam McDowell 2,453 &QL; 
8. Mark Langston 2,426 &QL; 
9. Randy Johnson 2,400 &QL; 
10. Sandy Koufax 2,396 &QL; 
Right-handed &QL; 
1. Nolan Ryan 5,714 &QL; 
2. Bert Blyleven 3,701 &QL; 
3. Tom Seaver 3,640 &QL; 
4. Don Sutton 3,574 &QL; 
5. Gaylord Perry 3,524 &QL; 
6. Walter Johnson 3,509 &QL; 
7. Phil Niekro 3,342 &QL; 
8. Ferguson Jenkins 3,192 &QL; 
9. Roger Clemens 3,176 &QL; 
10. Bob Gibson 3,117 &QL; 
(T.R. Sullivan covers baseball for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
