<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-RANGERS-FENCES-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RANGERS' JUAN GONZALEZ WOULD LIKE A SHORT PORCH OF HIS OWN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SIMON GONZALEZ 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Let others be like Mike. Juan Gonzalez wants to be like Hank and
Ted.
</P>
<P>
   Gonzalez joined baseball Hall of Famers Hank Greenberg and Ted
Williams when he won his second American League most valuable
player award last year. Now the Rangers right fielder wants to be
like them in another way. He wants the fences moved in.
</P>
<P>
   Gonzalez happened to mention, as part of his off-and-on
negotiations for a contract extension, that the deep, 390-foot
power alley in left-center field at The Ballpark in Arlington costs
him home runs. It might make him more inclined to sign an
extension, he said, if the fences were moved in.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's talked to me about that in the past, but I have told him
that I don't think it's going to happen,'' said Tom Schieffer,
former club president who is now a consultant for the team. ``While
I'm sure that Juan loses some home runs in this ballpark, I know
that our pitching staff saves a lot of home runs because they're
caught in the outfield. We really need to help pitching more than
we need to help power hitters.''
</P>
<P>
   So much for being like Hank and Ted.
</P>
<P>
   In 1940, the Boston Red Sox did move the fences in for Williams.
In 1947, the Pittsburgh Pirates did it for Greenberg, too.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, tinkering with the dimensions to suit a particular
player, team or playing style is almost as much a part of baseball
tradition as draping the bunting on Opening Day.
</P>
<P>
   The most famous examples of a team doing it to suit a particular
player involved Williams and Greenberg.
</P>
<P>
   Williams arrived in the majors in 1939 with a smooth, powerful
left-handed swing. He also arrived to find fences that were 332
feet away to the right-field foul pole and 405 feet away in
right-center at Fenway Park.
</P>
<P>
   The Red Sox shortened the distance for the 1940 season by
building bullpens in front of the fence. The right-field foul pole
was put at 304 and right-center was 382.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were built to help Ted pop some into the bullpen,'' said
Phil Lowry, author of Green Cathedrals, a book about ballparks.
</P>
<P>
   The bullpen area became known as Williamsburg, but it didn't
immediately help its intended beneficiary. Williams actually
dropped from 31 homers in '39 to 23 in '40. However, he hit 37 and
36 the next two seasons and went on to hit 521 home runs in his
Hall of Fame career.
</P>
<P>
   The Pirates tried a similar thing for Greenberg in 1947.
</P>
<P>
   They purchased the right-handed slugger after he hit an American
League-leading 44 homers for the Detroit Tigers in 1946. The
left-field foul pole at Forbes Field was 365 feet from home plate,
so the Pirates erected a short fence constructed of chicken wire in
front of the scoreboard, shortening the distance to 335 feet.
</P>
<P>
   The area was named Greenberg Gardens, but its namesake didn't
take advantage. Greenberg hit just 25 homers _ his lowest total in
a full season in the majors _ and retired after the season.
</P>
<P>
   However, another right-handed slugger thrived. Ralph Kiner led
the National League with 23 homers in '46 and hit 51 in 1947.
</P>
<P>
   Greenberg Gardens became Kiner's Korner, and this time it was an
appropriate name. Kiner led the league in home runs every season
through 1952. Kiner's Korner was dismantled after he was traded to
the Chicago Cubs during the 1953 season.
</P>
<P>
   Sluggers have long benefited from favorable home conditions.
</P>
<P>
   Yankee Stadium, the House that Ruth Built, was built for Babe
Ruth's left-handed power stroke. It opened in 1923 with the
right-field foul pole a mere 295 feet away from home plate, which
is where it stayed throughout his career. It's now at 314 feet.
</P>
<P>
   Fence moving still goes on. Just this year, for instance, Edison
Field became the House Built for Mo.
</P>
<P>
   The fences at the Anaheim Angels home were moved in from 408 to
400 feet in center field, and from 397 to 387 feet in the
left-center power alley. It just so happens that Mo Vaughn, the
club's prize free-agent acquisition, hits a lot of balls to left
center even though he is a left-handed hitter.
</P>
<P>
   Vaughn said he didn't ask for the fences to be moved in his
contract negotiations, but it's generally believed to have been a
factor in his decision. The Angels deny it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those alterations are something that was a topic of discussion
throughout last season,'' general manager Bill Bavasi said. ``When
the renovations were taking place, we discussed leaving available
the option of moving the fences forward in the future.''
</P>
<P>
   After the 1997 season, Albert Belle joined Gonzalez in
requesting that fences be moved in.
</P>
<P>
   Belle hit a league-leading 50 homers in 1995 and 48 more in '96,
but when he moved from the Cleveland Indians to the Chicago White
Sox in '97 his long-ball total dropped to 30. In the off-season, he
said Comiskey Park was costing him homers, and said he'd like the
fences moved in. The request was laughed off, and the distances
remain 347 feet to the foul poles and 375 feet to the power alleys,
although the batters' backdrop was changed from blue to black.
</P>
<P>
   Belle's homers were back up to 49 last season, with 29 of them
coming at home, proving that the park wasn't really to blame.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Comiskey is not a hitters' park, unlike the one Belle
plays in now.
</P>
<P>
   In this past off-season, Belle signed with the Baltimore
Orioles, who play at cozy Camden Yards, with a 364-foot power alley
to left-center.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was built to evoke Ebbetts Field, which was a small
ballpark with lots of home runs,'' said Lowry, who was a consultant
when the Orioles designed the park that opened in 1992. ``The
purpose was not to give offense more of a chance. The purpose was
to evoke the old-time style ballparks. Ebbetts Field was a small
ballpark, it was asymmetrical, and that's how we got Camden
Yards.''
</P>
<P>
   The park Belle rose to stardom in, Jacobs Field, was also
designed to be a hitters' park. Opened in 1994, it's dimensions are
325 to the foul poles, 370 to left-center (although a 19-foot-high
wall tends to turn homers into doubles) and 375 feet to
right-center.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was designed with the idea in mind that people like seeing
runs scored and home runs hit,'' said Bob DiBiasio, the Indians'
vice president of public relations. ``We did definitely have that
goal in mind, to have an offensive showing at the ballpark to
generate excitement.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers went the opposite way when The Ballpark opened in
1994. They had a trio of right-handed sluggers in Gonzalez, Jose
Canseco and Dean Palmer, but Schieffer, who oversaw the design,
purposely wanted a deep power alley in left field and a reachable
home-run porch in right.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first thing we decided was we weren't going to build the
ballpark for any particular player,'' Schieffer said. ``What we
wanted was a ballpark that would be timeless. We wanted it to be
neither a home-run park nor a pitchers' park. We wanted it to be
kind of neutral to the game, and just let the play of the
individuals determine whether it was a home run or a well-pitched
game.''
</P>
<P>
   If Juan wants to be like Ted and Hank, therefore, he'll just
have to keep putting up big numbers _ despite the big ballpark _ to
join them in the Hall of Fame.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
