<HEADLINE>
GOLF LEGEND BYRON NELSON SHOWS NO SIGNS OF SLOWING DOWN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DAVID A. MARKIEWICZ 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ When some athletes of distinction reach a
certain age, we don't expect to see them in public anymore, or at
least not very often. Their appearances are mostly ceremonial,
owing to their poor health and fatigue, or our own waning interest
in them.
</P>
<P>
   Then there is Byron Nelson. At 87, he not only is active enough
for a man half his age, he is more in demand than ever. That fact
will be seen again this week when his namesake golf tournament, the
32nd GTE Byron Nelson Classic, is held at the Four Seasons Resort
and Club in Las Colinas.
</P>
<P>
   Just consider a recent stretch of commitments Nelson fulfilled
in the weeks before the tournament: There was a trip to Arkansas
where he was inducted into that state's golf hall of fame; a flight
to Los Angeles where he appeared at a charity golf tournament; a
several-days-long, golfing-and-cowboy art event in Kerrville, where
he has a second home; plus numerous corporate golf outings in
between.
</P>
<P>
   The man they call Lord Byron is so popular and so willing to
accommodate this demand for his presence that when he doesn't show
up, people worry and wonder why.
</P>
<P>
   This is a source of some amusement to the man himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a funny thing,'' Nelson said last week while sipping an
orange and cranberry juice in the grill above the TPC course where
his tournament will be played. ``Because of my age, I guess, if I'm
wanted to be somewhere and I'm not, they get in touch with Peggy
\Rhis wife\S and say, `Why, is he all right?' ''
</P>
<P>
   He is.
</P>
<P>
   ``My health, other than my hip problem,'' Nelson says, ``is as
good as it's ever been in my life.''
</P>
<P>
   Good enough to shoot his age on the golf course. Good enough to
have fired a 76 last summer at Cottonwood Valley, the other course
used for tournament play.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hit some good shots and some like a beginner,'' he says.
``But I still enjoy playing. The problem is that I haven't had the
time to practice or work on my game.''
</P>
<P>
   It's easy to see why. On this day he already has had to deal
with a problem of downed pecan trees at his Roanoke ranch, the
result of the killer storm that blew hardest through Oklahoma. Then
there was this interview and a photo shoot. And, finally, a
corporate golf event at his golf school at the Four Seasons.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fortunately,'' he says, before going out to hit some balls,
``I have good energy.''
</P>
<P>
   Nelson has accomplished much in his career, notably his 11
consecutive victories in 1945, his 52 wins on the PGA Tour overall
and his victories at the Masters, the U.S. Open and the PGA.
</P>
<P>
   But it is the tournament named for him in 1968 that means most,
he says. That's mainly because of the involvement of the members of
the Salesmanship Club of Dallas, which sponsors the event and which
donates tournament proceeds to programs that help at-risk youth.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has meant more to me, golfwise, than anything,'' he says.
``The thing of it is, this has been going on for 32 years now. And
I've been involved with this very unusual group of people. I've
never heard or known any one of those men \Rin the Salesmanship
Club\S to say or do anything that would hurt anybody.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sure, I'm proud of my accomplishments. But those are records
made to be broken. What's happened here won't be broken because
it's permanent.''
</P>
<P>
   Nelson's tournament has some permanence as a PGA Tour event
thanks to contractual agreements announced earlier this year. The
longevity of the event _ it is now the 12th oldest on the PGA Tour,
if you count its early days as The Dallas Open _ is amazing, and a
tribute to Nelson, especially considering its humble beginnings.
</P>
<P>
   When the event began in the 1940s, ``The tournament was not
successful,'' Nelson recalls. ``It didn't get very much
publicity.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, after the first three tournaments, won by Nelson, Sam
Snead and Ben Hogan, in 1944, 1945 and 1946, there was a 10-year
period in which there was no Dallas Open. The tournament was
revived and played at Oak Cliff until 1968, when the event was
moved to Preston Trail and renamed for Nelson.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was flabbergasted,'' Nelson says of when he was told by
tournament managers that he would be the first player to have a
tournament named after him. ``How could I be more honored than
that?''
</P>
<P>
   Nelson says the tournament's facilities, including a plentiful
supply of hotel rooms, nearby restaurants and a nursery, plus easy
airport transportation and a crack volunteer staff, all help
attract top PGA Tour players who, in turn, lure sell-out galleries.
But PGA Tour pros themselves often cite Nelson himself as the
primary reason they come to Irving every May.
</P>
<P>
   They, like members of the Salesmanship Club, call Nelson a
legend and his tournament a legacy.
</P>
<P>
   It is a mantle Nelson wears responsibly.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's something you think about,'' he says, referring to his
image. ``It makes you realize how careful you have to be, the
things you say and do.''
</P>
<P>
   Not that Nelson doesn't like to have fun with his legend. There
was the time, he recalls, when he sawtwo men observing the
larger-than-life bronze statue of him at the TPC course.
</P>
<P>
   ``I walked up to them and said, `So, do you think that looks
like me?' Well, you never saw two fellas ... it was like they saw a
ghost. Then, they turned around and looked and said, `Yeah, it
does.' '' nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
