<HEADER>
A9575 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PREAKNESS-PREVIEW-TEX     05-08 1073
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PREAKNESS-PREVIEW-TEX </SLUG>
 
Based on Derby performance, Menifee should win Preakness 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY MOSS 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
FORT WORTH, Texas _ Prairie Bayou finished second in the 1993
Kentucky Derby, but those who studied the race carefully knew his
performance deserved an asterisk in the history books. 
<TEXT>
<P>
   He was so clearly the best horse in the Derby that his trainer,
Tom Bohannan, almost had an anxiety attack getting the 3-year-old
gelding up to the Preakness Stakes, where he blew away the
competition in the second leg of racing's Triple Crown. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A relieved Bohannan explained later that he had never felt such
pressure. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew the only way Prairie Bayou could get beat was if I
screwed him up,'' he said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Preakness is seldom that easy, but an important key to
handicapping the race at Pimlico Race Course in Baltimore is always
to accurately decipher the two minutes of hysteria known as the
Kentucky Derby. The best horse often doesn't win the Derby because
of pace or traffic problems, but the Preakness can be a more
form-fitting race. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A close study of the Derby is particularly crucial this year
because, at this writing, a dozen of the 19 starters in last
weekend's Derby are being considered for the Preakness. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In the 1993 Derby, Prairie Bayou had a 19-horse field to
navigate, too. He started far back in the pack, then streaked
around seven horses on the Churchill Downs stretch turn despite
racing eight-wide. He was fanned 10-wide into the lane to lose all
momentum, yet still doggedly passed seven more horses in the final
quarter-mile to lose by only 21/2 lengths to Sea Hero, who had
benefited from a brilliant ground-saving ride by Jerry Bailey. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But perhaps the most dramatic example of Derby misfortune
occurred in the centennial running of 1974. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   That year, Little Current came away from the gate last in a
record 23-horse field at Churchill Downs. Along the way, the colt
was bounced and squeezed and jostled. Turning into the stretch, he
was in a hopeless position: 17th place and 171/2 lengths behind the
leader. Yet Little Current passed a dozen horses in the last
quarter-mile and wound up only 61/2 lengths behind winner
Cannonade. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Professional race watchers couldn't get enough of Little
Current. He not only won the Preakness convincingly, but he
captured the Belmont Stakes, too. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A similar trip spoiled Risen Star's hopes in the 1988 Derby; he
also rebounded by taking the Preakness and the Belmont. Snow Chief
faded badly after unwisely pressing a torrid pace in the 1986
Derby, and he, too, won in the Preakness. The list of Derby victims
turned Preakness heroes goes on and on. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   This year's demolition Derby yielded mishaps, too, although
perhaps not as many as originally believed. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A videotape of the stewards head-on view of the Kentucky Derby
obtained from Churchill Downs shows that eight horses had traffic
trouble of varying degrees during the race, and others were surely
intimidated by the cramped quarters created by a huge field and a
slow pace. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Interestingly, however, runner-up Menifee wasn't among the
horses in trouble, as originally believed. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Menifee passed a dozen horses in the stretch, despite being
compromised by slow fractions. But footnotes from the original
Daily Racing Form and Equibase chart reported Menifee was ``checked
in traffic on the turn'' and ``raced behind a wall of horses''
entering the stretch, and the head-on replay doesn't justify that
analysis. Menifee resembled Gale Sayers as he darted between and
among rivals through the long stretch. Although jockey Pat Day was
forced to pick his spots carefully and perhaps delay his closing
run, films show that the colt never had his forward progress
disrupted. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the official chart was revised on Thursday, and both
references to Menifee's traffic trouble were deleted. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Charismatic, a neck ahead of Menifee as the long-shot winner of
the Derby, was three-wide around both turns and somehow remained
clear of any bumping and grinding. So did Cat Thief, Prime Timber,
Worldly Manner and Vicar. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The worst Derby trips clearly belonged to General Challenge,
Adonis, Three Ring and First American. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   With any good fortune at all, Adonis and First American almost
certainly will turn in better performances in the Preakness.
General Challenge and Three Ring aren't running. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Listening to post-race commentary from Bob Baffert and jockey
Kent Desormeaux, one would have thought the other filly in the
Derby, Excellent Meeting, had been mugged at gunpoint. She did have
a worse trip than Menifee _ she was crowded at the start and had to
wait briefly while crowded again around the stretch turn _ and she
ran commendably to be fifth. But she actually saved ground around
the clubhouse turn, so her trip was hardly a Shakespearean
tragedy. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Stephen Got Even, who ran 14th, was sandwiched from both sides
in the bumping around the first turn. But that doesn't qualify as a
nightmarish trip, either. He held his position despite the bumps
and was simply outrun on the backstretch and the second turn. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   After perusing the videotape, it appears that Menifee, who
started from post No. 18, was the best horse in the Derby, not
because of a troubled trip, but rather the pace disadvantage he
nearly overcame. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Because the first six furlongs were run in a slow 1 minutes,
12.52 seconds, the Derby's early leaders should have been too fresh
for Menifee to rush past them in the stretch as he did. That makes
his effort a remarkable one. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Unless Menifee is caught in a bad spot in the expected 14-horse
Preakness field, he should join Prairie Bayou, Risen Star and the
other unlucky Derby losers who gained redemption in Baltimore. &QL; 
(Randy Moss covers horse racing for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram) &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
Preakness possibles &QL; 
Possible entrants, ranked by career earnings, for Saturday's
Preakness at Pimlico Race Course in Baltimore: &QL; 
Horse earnings &QL; 
Silverbulletday $2,091,750 &QL; 
Charismatic $1,278,064 &QL; 
Excellent Meeting $1,193,824 &QL; 
Cat Thief $800,112 &QL; 
Vicar $745,756 &QL; 
Menifee $722,000 &QL; 
Kimberlite Pipe $520,583 &QL; 
Prime Timber $503,200 &QL; 
Stephen Got Even $494,800 &QL; 
Adonis $413,640 &QL; 
Worldly Manner $250,104 &QL; 
First American $222,777 &QL; 
Badge $222,630 &QL; 
Torrid Sand $141,400 &QL; 
Patience Game 111,776 &QL; 
Lead Em Home $95,487 &QL; 
Valhol $44,100 &QL; 
NOTE: Starting field limited to 14 horses &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
