r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-NLNOTES-LADN     05-08 0864
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-NLNOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GALARRAGA OPTIMISTIC
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ After three months of chemotherapy, Andres
Galarraga's doctors have told him the tumor in his lower back has
been reduced by 75 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The Atlanta Braves first baseman, diagnosed with lymphoma in
February, is planning to install a batting cage in his West Palm
Beach, Fla., home this week and hopes to join the Braves on a road
trip soon.
</P>
<P>
   But Galarraga faces two more rounds of chemotherapy and there
has been no talk of him making a comeback this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if it's even fair to speculate on that,'' Atlanta
GM John Schuerholz said. ``He's got cancer and is fighting through
the disease. We're delighted for all the good that is happening,
but I haven't even thought about that. We're just going to keep
hoping he continues to win his fight.''
</P>
<P>
   BIG NAMES
</P>
<P>
   Randy Johnson passed Sandy Koufax in career strikeouts during a
5-1 victory over Cincinnati on Wednesday, getting eight to give him
an even 2,400, which is ninth among lefties in major-league
history. Koufax, whose advice helped Johnson get through some hard
times in his early years in Seattle, finished with 2,396. ``He sent
me a real nice letter then,'' said Johnson, who has struck out at
least 10 batters in 106 games. ``He said something to the effect of
congratulations on passing me, but it's going to be a little harder
passing Nolan (Ryan 5,714). Any time you pass people that you
really admire, that's great.''...
</P>
<P>
   Ken Griffey Jr. stopped by Cinergy Field on Tuesday, an off-day
for the Cleveland-bound Mariners, to take batting practice off his
dad and receive some fatherly hitting advice.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody knows my swing better than him,'' Junior said. ``I've
been fighting myself a little.... He usually stays in my head. He's
still the dad and I'm still the little kid.''
</P>
<P>
   BIG MONEY BO
</P>
<P>
   Former Dodger Brian Bohanon, who signed a three-year contract
with Colorado, set a club record by starting the season 5-0. And
all five followed Rockies losses. Bohanon was throwing 80-81 mph in
the spring but has increased that to the mid-80s, and is spotting
his assortment of cutters and off-speed junk.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hear guys all the time who get to second base say, `This guy
doesn't have anything,''' Rockies second baseman Mike Lansing said.
``I go, `How come you're 0 for 3, 0 for 4?'''...
</P>
<P>
   Bobby Bonilla returned to the Mets starting lineup for the first
time in eight games Tuesday night and was booed after going 0 for 4
against the Astros and failing to make a sliding catch on Jeff
Bagwell's looping fly ball in the fourth inning. After an
injury-plagued season with the Dodgers and Florida, Bonilla was
expected to be his old self. Between 1993-97, he averaged 28 home
runs and 101 RBI a year. Now, Bonilla is batting seventh, with a
.153 average and just two HRs and nine RBI....
</P>
<P>
   LOOKING UP
</P>
<P>
   Pittsburgh catcher Jason Kendall went 5 for 5 against San
Francisco without scoring a run or driving one in, just the eighth
time that has happened since 1970 and the first since Atlanta
Braves shortstop Jeff Blauser did it June 10, 1996. The Giants'
Jeff Kent also had five hits, marking the first time two NL players
had five in the same game since June 3, 1988, when the Dodgers'
Mickey Hatcher and Steve Sax did it....
</P>
<P>
   Phillies Rookie of the Year candidate Marlon Anderson headed
into the weekend hitting just .207 and has made seven errors. But
12 of his 19 hits have been with runners in scoring position,
including a two-run home run in an 11-1 rout of the Padres on
Wednesday. The Phillies are hoping Anderson duplicates what he did
last year when he hit .187 in April at Triple-A
Scranton/Wilkes-Barre, then recovered to bat .306 and lead the
International League in hitting....
</P>
<P>
   CLOSING IN
</P>
<P>
   Tony Gwynn, nearing 3,000 hits, got his first off the Phillies'
Sid Monge on July 19, 1982.
</P>
<P>
   Gwynn got his first hit in his fourth plate appearance and first
baseman Pete Rose, the all-time hit leader, trailed him to second,
saying, ``Don't catch me in one night.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure Pete made the comment to get a laugh, but it had me
thinking,'' Gwynn said. ``Wouldn't it be great to do some of the
things he has done? For a young guy, that comment hit me like a ton
of bricks.''
</P>
<P>
   Monge now works as a rookie-league pitching coach for the Padres
in Arizona and was called in to pitch batting practice in
Philadelphia because the Padres don't have any left-handers on
their coaching staff....
</P>
<P>
   Giants closer Robb Nen was 9 for 9 in save opportunities, but he
allowed three runs in the ninth of a 9-8 loss to Pittsburgh. It
overshadowed Kent's cycle _ the first for a Giant since Robby
Thompson on April 22, 1991 _ and prevented Joe Nathan from becoming
the first Giants pitcher since Juan Marichal in 1960 to begin his
career 3-0.
</P>
<P>
   They are still in first place without Barry Bonds, but there are
warning signs, including a 5.00 ERA, second-to-last in the league,
and 14 errors in seven games entering the weekend, dropping them
from fifth to 15th in the NL.
</P>
</TEXT>
