<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-08 21:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9577 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-ASTROS-COLUMN-HNS     05-08 0901
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-ASTROS-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
McCraw's video collection receives two thumbs up
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By DALE ROBERTSON &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1999, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   According to Dr. Tom McCraw, the Astros' batting professor,
hitting a baseball is brain surgery _ but without the scalpel and
forceps.
</P>
<P>
   McCraw doesn't teach swinging so much as he teaches thinking.
Although he gives mechanics their due, he believes the key to
smacking the ball where they ain't lies in preparation and
concentration. As you might have noticed, the Astros have been
doing a bang-up job of same recently _ their team batting average
leads the National League by a cushy margin _ so it seems a good
opportunity to take a knife to Mack and see what makes him tick.
</P>
<P>
   Hitting, that's what. He admits he lives to talk hitting.
</P>
<P>
   ``Could go on all night about it,'' he said. ``It fascinates
me.''
</P>
<P>
   First of all, though, it's probably best we clear up something
here. McCraw, 58, is at least as much a student as he is a teacher.
He didn't invent the principles of mind over matter he espouses; he
learned them from those who practiced what he preaches. As a career
.246 hitter, he had to seek the counsel of others.
</P>
<P>
   And he did. Lots of them, with names like Rose, Robinson,
Puckett, Gwynn and Brett, among many, many others.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pete Rose and Frank Robinson were two entirely different kinds
of hitters,'' Mack says, ``but they approached hitting exactly the
same way. They never went up to the plate without a very specific
plan. They always waited for their pitch to hit. They didn't let
the pitcher dictate to them.''
</P>
<P>
   McCraw knows this because he has spent hours talking to these
guys. Not casual conversations, either, mind you, but actual
interviews, replete with instructional films and videotape. His
homemade collection, which he has been building for almost 30
years, is extensive, forming the basis of his Astros curriculum.
</P>
<P>
   Ted Williams, who had a pretty good handle on the subject, got
Mack's own thinking straight when he managed him with the Senators
in 1971. The untimely death of Roberto Clemente the following
offseason inspired the evolutionary process that transformed McCraw
into an expert on a subject he never mastered.
</P>
<P>
   ``All the knowledge that went to the grave with Clemente, all of
it lost forever,'' he said. ``That was a tragedy in its own way,
too. It was then that I started talking to the great hitters,
making a permanent record of what they had to say.''
</P>
<P>
   When he started coaching the year he stopped playing _ 1975 _
his fledgling video collection acquired a practical purpose. He has
been showing the movies to players ever since to help him get his
points across.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mack's tapes might be worth hundreds of thousands of dollars
to a collector,'' said Astros general manager Gerry Hunsicker, who
saw the value in McCraw's methods when both were employed by the
Mets and thus recommended him to Larry Dierker after his hiring as
manager. ``It's amazing what he's put together, and it allows him
to get between the players' ears, which he does as well as any
coach I've ever seen.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what hitting is all about. It's more confidence than
mechanics and what Mack teaches builds confidence.''
</P>
<P>
   McCraw doesn't treat everyone equally, though. A Jeff Bagwell
doesn't require as much care and nurturing as, say, a Tim Bogar.
For the Bagwell-Biggio-Bell-Caminiti marquee crowd, Mack is just a
glorified consultant, stepping in when needed. They're far more
likely to come to him, than he to them.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were .300 hitters before I came along,'' he said. ``I
don't mess with them unless they ask me to, although I will look
for little things they might not be aware of. I won't hesitate to
make suggestions.''
</P>
<P>
   Without being overbearing.
</P>
<P>
   ``The players listen to Mack,'' Hunsicker said, ``because he
doesn't have an agenda, and he won't try to beat them over the
head. He's an excellent communicator. He makes them want to hear
what he has to say.''
</P>
<P>
   With the younger established Astros, the
Everett-Gutierrez-Hidalgo crowd, McCraw is more of a coach. He
talks to them almost every day. He doesn't give a flip about
sounding repetitious. With the kids, the Glen Barkers and Paul
Bakos, he admits he's inclined to flat-out nag.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to keep saying it,'' he said, ``until they get it.''
</P>
<P>
   Bogar is the resident Mack authority. Bogey has been a disciple
for almost 13 years, since he was drafted by the Mets. While his
.229 average in the majors before this season would suggest McCraw
never has fully gotten through, chances are Bogar wouldn't even be
around if not for the coach's dogged harping.
</P>
<P>
   And Bogey is batting .255.
</P>
<P>
   ``The great hitters do things the right way instinctively,''
Bogar said. ``The rest of us have to always be thinking about what
we're doing, and what usually happens is we start worrying about
our mechanics. Mack tells you, `Forget the mechanics. Have a good
game plan and stick to it.'''
</P>
<P>
   McCraw likes to point out that Robinson claims to have hit at
least 500 of his 586 home runs off fastballs.
</P>
<P>
   ``So why should a Tim Bogar or a Glen Barker be up there
sweating sliders and curves?'' Mack said. ``If a Frank Robinson got
to hit fastballs, they will, too. Be patient. Wait for the
fastball.''
</P>
<P>
   Sounds simple? It is. It just requires a little brain surgery.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
