A9578 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-ROCKETS-COLUMN-HN     05-08 0818
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-ROCKETS-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
More than merely a series is at stake
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By FRAN BLINEBURY &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1999, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   INGLEWOOD, Calif. _ Tick tick tick.
</P>
<P>
   It's not a bomb ready to go off. Just the sound of the clock
running out.
</P>
<P>
   On the Rockets. And the Lakers.
</P>
<P>
   But the effects could be just as devastating. The loser might
just be left in pieces.
</P>
<P>
   No other NBA first-round playoff series has as much at stake on
both sides as today when NBC's team takes on AARP's team in Game 1
at the Great Western Forum.
</P>
<P>
   It's a battle of the ages. Young and old.
</P>
<P>
   It's a fight against time, for different reasons.
</P>
<P>
   For the Rockets, it's a simple case of the grains of sand
running through the hourglass on their Big Three of Hakeem
Olajuwon, Charles Barkley and Scottie Pippen.
</P>
<P>
   For the Lakers, it's a more complicated matter of youth and
impetuosity and egos and chemistry. Or lack thereof.
</P>
<P>
   The Rockets had better win now, because they're getting older _
and not necessarily better _ every day.
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers had better win right now, before kid leaders
Shaquille O'Neal and Kobe Bryant decide to take their heated
rivalry _ with each other _ to the WCW's Monday Nitro to settle
things in a steel cage match.
</P>
<P>
   There is cause for alarm in both camps.
</P>
<P>
   Because the Rockets are plotting their escape route _ hint:
think rookie backcourt _ and whispering satisfaction with the
on-the-fly season for the sole reason everybody gets along.
</P>
<P>
   Lakers could splinter
</P>
<P>
   Because the Lakers know of the clause in Shaq's seven-year, $121
million contract that allows him to opt out and become a free agent
after this season and the big fella is playing coy on the subject.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why should I think about something like that, especially
now?'' says Shaq one minute.
</P>
<P>
   Then when somebody points out LA coach Kurt Rambis is under
pressure because his contract runs out after the playoffs, Shaq
says: ``So does mine.''
</P>
<P>
   At 36, 36 and 33, Olajuwon, Barkley and Pippen are running out
of time. At 27 and 20, Shaq and Kobe are running out of patience.
</P>
<P>
   Because of their contracts, a Rockets team that comes up short
will be stuck with each other. Because of their egos, a hoped-for
Lakers dynasty that comes up short might scatter to the winds.
</P>
<P>
   It is safe to say neither the Lakers nor the Rockets expected to
be in their current positions, banging heads in this affair that
will bring a premature end and a label as one of 1999's tremendous
underachievers to one team.
</P>
<P>
   You'll remember that when the Rockets signed Pippen in January,
he rode into town in a white stretch limousine with a police
escort, and team owner Leslie Alexander surely was envisioning
similar triumphant motorcades when he introduced him as ``a guy who
can bring us a championship, many championships.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, that was before Pippen often looked as uncomfortable
in the offense as a prisoner in chains and before the Rockets blew
the home-court advantage in this series with losses to Dallas
(twice) and the LA Clippers.
</P>
<P>
   You'll remember the Lakers were coming off a 61-win season when
they made it to the Western Conference finals and supposedly were
more committed than ever to pulling it all together.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, that was before the Lakers stumbled out of the
starting gate, got coach Del Harris fired, reached out to wacko
Dennis Rodman for stability, watched him go AWOL, cut him, traded
for sharpshooter Glen Rice, kept right on foundering and were
hammered by 27 and 22 points in back-to-back games in San Antonio
and Houston less than two weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   Rockets battling time
</P>
<P>
   The Rockets closed out the season with three consecutive wins
and say they finally have discovered the key to playoff success
with a new determination to push the ball up the court and thereby
perform with more energy and emotion at both ends of the court.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no team out there in the playoffs that we can't
beat,'' Pippen says.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can play with anybody,'' Barkley says.
</P>
<P>
   But for how long in the gantlet of five- and seven-game playoff
series they would have to survive to just reach the NBA Finals?
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers responded to their whipping at Compaq Center by
closing the regular season with four straight wins and claim to be
brimming with confidence and reading from the same page of the
playbook, even though Shaq and Kobe hiss at each other like a pair
of tomcats from opposite sides of the locker room.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just want to be the best team player possible,'' says Shaq,
an obvious crack at the shot-happy Kobe, whom he calls ``Boy
Wonder.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no need for that Party of Five stuff, where you sit
down and talk about life,'' Kobe says. ``It doesn't mean we have to
like each other.''
</P>
<P>
   But how far can you go on envy?
</P>
<P>
   Rockets. Lakers. No more time for excuses.
</P>
<P>
   The clock's running.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
