<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVAR-AT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KOSOVO WILL ALWAYS BE HOME, TEXAS WOMAN SAYS
</HEADLINE>
 HEART-TEX (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KAREN ROUSE 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PLANO, Texas _ Mejdija Vraniqi was just 18, the mother of a
6-month-old girl, when she fled Kosovo in 1980.
</P>
<P>
   As ethnic Albanians under Serbian rule, Vraniqi and her husband,
Mustafa, had little freedom and few civil rights. In the Serbs'
eyes, she said, ``We didn't deserve to have better schools.''
</P>
<P>
   ``When I saw my 6-month-baby, we decided to give a better future
to her: freedom.''
</P>
<P>
   She told her mother, four sisters and two brothers that she was
taking a vacation. Then she left, certain that she would return
someday.
</P>
<P>
   ``For 19 years, that was my dream,'' said Vraniqi, of Plano.
``Now I can't do that, because now everybody is refugees.''
</P>
<P>
   Vraniqi's personality is bubbly and radiant. But, like many of
her people, she suffers a broken spirit, a constant aching for her
homeland.
</P>
<P>
   She, her husband and oldest daughter became U.S. citizens in
1986. America, she said, has given her ``everything:'' She has four
beautiful children, a home, a job. But it is not home.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's nothing to me,'' Vraniqi said. ``It's not mine. My body
is here. But my soul and my heart, every single day is there.''
</P>
<P>
   Now Vraniqi grieves for the unwanted: the ethnic Albanian
refugees who will begin arriving in North Texas on Sunday. ``I know
they are going to be miserable,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The United States, the major partner in the NATO force that
started bombing Yugoslavia on March 24, agreed last month to take
in 20,000 Kosovar refugees from camps in Macedonia. About 1,000
arrived last week. Most went to McGuire Air Force Base at Fort Dix,
N.J., for processing. Others went directly to relatives across the
United States.
</P>
<P>
   Vraniqi, a member of the Albanian-American Cultural Club in
Carrollton, Texas, is helping to prepare for those who will arrive
in the Fort Worth-Dallas Metroplex.
</P>
<P>
   She has organized mostly ethnic Albanian Muslim women in North
Texas to help the refugees by collecting furniture, tables, pots
and pans, baby beds and other items to furnish apartments.
</P>
<P>
   They are also aiding refugees who remain in camps outside
Kosovo. Plano and Richardson mosques have raised more than $6,500
to purchase dried food, toiletries and clothing, which will be
delivered through the Feed the Children organization in Oklahoma
City beginning May 12.
</P>
<P>
   Fort Worth doctors are collecting antibiotics, painkillers, cold
remedies and other medicines. Al Hedaya Islamic School in
Arlington, Texas, has packed 80 bags of clothing.
</P>
<P>
   Vraniqi, a floral shop manager at a Tom Thumb grocery, is eager
to meet the refugees' physical needs. But she wonders how they will
deal emotionally with the loss of relatives, possessions and
culture.
</P>
<P>
   Vraniqi said she misses the mountains, flowers and greenery of
her homeland, and the aroma of fresh-picked tomatoes. Even the
rocks, she said, ``look like marble.''
</P>
<P>
   And every evening, she remembers family tea time. ``We used to
read or crochet or make the doilies _ everybody with two hands
making doilies at 5 o'clock in the evening,'' she said, laughing.
``The neighbors used to come, and you fix them tea. You had so much
love and attention.''
</P>
<P>
   Vraniqi has spoken to relatives only twice since March 30.
</P>
<P>
   When she asked her brother, who escaped Kosovo, about their
mother, he was evasive. ``He said, `Mom, she is at Prizren.' When I
asked more questions about Mommy, he started crying and said, `Mom
is at Prizren.' ''
</P>
<P>
   She believes that her mother is among the many older Albanians
who have chosen to die in their own villages.
</P>
<P>
   ``My mom raised seven children in the same house,'' Vraniqi
said. ``My father died in that house. We got married in that house.
Even if they kick her from her home, she's not going to go. She's
going to die there. She has those seven children's memories. The
grandchildren. She will die by Serbians' guns.''
</P>
<P>
   Vraniqi could have returned to Kosovo, but it would have been a
harsh life for her children, ages 19, 17, 16 and 14. But she may
someday return to her hometown, Prizren, on her own.
</P>
<P>
   ``I will be more happy there in my tarnished land than in some
different country's heavenly place,'' she said. ``As long as I
live, (Kosovo) will be my homeland.''
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
