<SLUG> BC-BOX-BOXING </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOMETHING HAS TO GIVE IN NUNN-GUTHRIE MATCH 
</HEADLINE>
 NOTEBOOK-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON BORGES  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ For once, everybody is at risk, even the promoters.
</P>
<P>
   Normally in boxing, the fighters take the risk and everyone else
makes the money, but when former light heavyweight champion William
Guthrie and ex-middleweight and super middleweight titleholder
Michael Nunn go at it Sunday night in Minot, N.D., the men who
promote them, Dan Goossen and Mat Tinley, will be sharing the risk.
</P>
<P>
   Goossen and Tinley, who are partners in a promotional company
called America Presents, direct the careers of both light
heavyweight contenders and thus are well aware that while they
stand to win by the time the night is over, they also stand to
lose. This is not a position promoters often have an interest in
assuming, but here they are, and Goossen claims it is proof they
are different from the boxing establishment.
</P>
<P>
   ``Having two guys we promote fighting each other is a statement
that we won't hold back one of our guys just because he could kill
off another,'' Goossen said from his office in Denver. ``We've
promised our fighters opportunities, and the way the business is
today, a lot of times the best opportunity has to come from inside
your own organization.
</P>
<P>
   ``As promoters, you might not like that, but it's not a conflict
in our eyes. The winner goes on to better himself and the loser
becomes less valuable. We've promised our fighters an opportunity
even if it's at our expense, which it is in this case. No matter
who wins, we've got a downside here. That's just reality.''
</P>
<P>
   It's also what the 34-year-old Nunn and 32-year-old Guthrie
agreed to accept, in part because both found their careers stalled.
Even when he became a mandatory challenger, Nunn was unable to
force World Boxing Association-World Boxing Council champion Roy
Jones Jr. to fight him. Instead, Nunn had to opt for a fight with
interim WBC champion Graciano Rocchigiani, who won a controversial
split decision last March in Germany.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, Nunn has pursued Jones and International Boxing
Federation champion Reggie Johnson without any luck. Guthrie laid
off for 15 months after Johnson stunned him with a one-punch
knockout that took the IBF title from Guthrie at a time when he was
believed by some to be a threat to Jones. For his part, Guthrie
(24-1, 21 KOs) still believes he is, but he first must get by Nunn
and prove that the weak training habits that led to his undoing are
behind him.
</P>
<P>
   ``The second you lose, you find out the guy who was carrying
your bag for you isn't carrying it any more,'' Guthrie said from
his home in Delaware. ``I carry my own bags now. I don't need no
entourage.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew that night I was no longer world champion. That's the
other side of boxing. The reality check happens right away. You
don't get no season to lose your title. It's not drawn out. It all
happens in one night.
</P>
<P>
   ``After I lost, a lot of people were saying, `See, he's nothing.
Guthrie's nothing.' But a lot of good trainers weren't saying that.
They wouldn't let their fighters in with me. So I was surprised
Nunn gave me this opportunity.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to get right back in with Reggie at first, but he
went another way. And Jones never did want to fight me. The day
before I fought Johnson, Jones said there were no fights for him in
the division. He said he couldn't make no money and was moving to
heavyweight. Then I got knocked out and he's been a light
heavyweight ever since. He made plenty of money because the money
was always there.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jones talked about me but let me tell you, Roy Jones is not
ever fighting me. But I don't worry about that any more. Nunn is
the break I needed. It's a great opportunity for both of us.''
</P>
<P>
   It is also a double-edged sword for Goossen and Tinley, who know
that bringing back the loser a third time may be almost impossible,
while getting the winner a title shot if Jones unifies the
175-pound championship against Johnson June 5 may be nearly as
difficult.
</P>
<P>
   But Goossen insisted that while his organization might be losing
one contender Sunday night, it is creating another.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe the winner deserves to be the No. 1 or No. 2
contender,'' Goossen said. ``Guthrie was an undefeated champion
until he got hit with a great shot by Reggie. Other fighters have
overcome that. He just has to win this fight and show that he's
decided to pay the price not only to become champion but to stay
champion.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Guthrie wins, he deserves to be No. 1. I feel the same way
about Nunn. In our eyes, the winner is the one true challenger for
Roy Jones at 175 pounds so this is do-or-die for both guys. Neither
is making a great deal of money this fight. It's more risk than
reward for both of them.''
</P>
<P>
   For once at least, you could say the same thing about the
promoters.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Jones, meanwhile, is preparing to fight more than Johnson. He
received a threatening letter from attorneys for promoter Don King
last week claiming he had defamed King by his comments following
the draw in the Lennox Lewis-Evander Holyfield heavyweight
unification fight. Jones, who was a commentator on the pay-per-view
broadcast, said, ``Any time Don King is involved, you can expect a
draw to come from somewhere. Ask Pernell Whitaker about the Julio
Cesar Chavez fight. You know something like that was in the air if
he's here.'' Attorney Alvin B. Davis wrote Jones in a letter dated
April 28, ``These allegations are false and defamatory.'' He
demanded Jones prove them or send a letter ``clearly stating that
you had no basis for making the allegations.'' Pensacola attorney
Fred Levin responded May 6 with a letter stating, ``You asked for
any information that Mr. Jones relied upon in making this statement
in order that your law firm could complete its investigation.
Please do not spend a lot of money in your investigation. Simply
get tapes of the Holyfield/Lewis and Whitaker/Chavez fights. We
understand Don King and/or Don King Productions, Inc. promoted both
fights. If Mr. King decides to file suit . . . please provide us
with a list of dates that Mr. King and his staff would be available
for depositions under oath in regard to both fights . . . Finally,
Roy just called me and told me to `circle the wagons.' I guess that
means, `Let's get ready to rumble.' '' Levin sent copies of that
letter to Arizona Sen. John McCain, whose second bill to help clean
up boxing was just sent to the Senate for a vote, and Florida
attorney general Elliott Spitzer. Don't expect to hear much more
from King's attorneys on this . . . Jones is used to not being able
to find an opponent, so he wasn't all that shocked last Thursday
when he turned up in Biloxi, Miss., to hype the Johnson fight and
found no one waiting for him. Johnson did not show for the
scheduled press conference, claiming he was training in Houston.
Jones was less than pleased, but already there was much bad blood
between the two, dating back to the days when Jones's father
trained them both in Pensacola, so what's a little more? Jones
asked his father to drop Johnson, believing he would eventually
have to fight him, and his father's refusal became one of the bones
of contention that led to an ugly breakup in 1992. They have not
worked together since then and seldom speak. Johnson (39-5-1, 24
KOs) is a two-time light heavyweight champion, having won the title
in 1992 and then winning it back last year by knocking Guthrie
cold. Jones said he was not fazed by Johnson's absence, believing
he won't be around long June 5, either. ``I will do a number on
him,'' Jones said. ``Reggie can't beat me.'' . . . Sometimes guys
still get paid for what they do in sports after they do it. That's
the case for Davey Hilton (36-1-3) and Stephane Ouellet (25-2), who
will earn $200,000 each May 28 when they fight a rematch of their
stirring 1998 fight for the Canadian middleweight title. That
night, Ouellet held an insurmountable lead going into the last
round only to be stopped with five seconds left by Hilton, who had
begun to hammer him more and more late in the fight. A $200,000
purse is big money for 99 percent of the world's boxers and 100
percent of the ones fighting on ESPN2's ``Friday Night Fights'' . .
. HBO's ``Real Sports'' is doing a profile on Teddy Atlas's newest
protege, undefeated Elvir Muriqi, an ethnic Albanian whose father
returned to Serbia from New York City to fight for freedom in
Kosovo. Muriqi is 6-0 . . . How sick is this? Danish promoter
Mogens Palle is touting hapless Brian Nielsen for tying Rocky
Marciano's record at 49-0. The IBO champion hasn't fought a guy who
could lick Marciano in his present condition _ which is dead for
almost 30 years. . . . Here's how quickly things change in boxing.
A year ago, Frank Warren was the promoter and chief defender of
World Boxing Organization featherweight champion Prince Naseem
Hamed. Warren was given the sack by Hamed at year's end and now
promotes WBO junior bantamweight champion Marco Antonio Barrera.
When Warren had Hamed, he wanted no part of Barrera and got to
avoid him when Barrera was knocked cold by Junior Jones three years
ago. Then he avoided Jones instead. Now he's pushing HBO to make a
Barrera-Hamed fight that he never wanted before . . . Israel
``Pito'' Cardona has done an admirable job of avoiding IBF
lightweight champion Shane Mosley. He has twice been offered a
title shot but has sought other routes to a title against
less-imposing champions. Now it seems he may have won his gamble
because Mosley is ready to abdicate and move up to 140. If he does,
Mosley's promoter, Cedric Kushner, will push to match Cardona with
Angel Manfredy for the IBF 135-pound title. Cardona then would have
a reasonable shot of winning the title he didn't want when Mosley
held it . . . Well shot Tyrell Biggs is out as Andrew Golota's June
26 opponent in Poland. ``They caught us,'' joked Golota's promoter,
Mike Boorman of Main Events, when asked what happened. Efforts to
substitute Al Cole failed, so the search goes on.
</P>
</TEXT>
