<HEADLINE>
WHAT WILL CELTICS SACRIFICE TO MAKE PLAYOFFS 
</HEADLINE>
 NOTEBOOK-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL HOLLEY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Maybe the question needs to be changed. Maybe no one
should be asking, ``Will the Celtics make the playoffs next
season?'' The better query might be, ``Which of their top four
players will they trade so they can get to the playoffs?''
</P>
<P>
   It appears more likely that this is a ``when'' situation rather
than ``if.'' In the past few weeks, Rick Pitino has sounded like a
cross between Joe Namath (circa 1969) and a Promise Keeper, nearly
guaranteeing victory and deliverance. The Celtics coach has said
that his team will be improved, dramatically, in 1999-2000.
</P>
<P>
   As you think of those words, look at the Celtics' roster. Look
at the players who have reputations as rebounders around the NBA
block. There is one. His name is Popeye Jones and he happens to
have a left knee that a couple of months ago was the size of Maine.
Jones has had two operations on the knee in less than two years. He
is in for a long summer of rehab, his second consecutive one.
</P>
<P>
   It has been proven that you don't need a dominating center to
win a championship or make the playoffs. But you can't do anything
with a lineup of shorties. Antoine Walker has averaged 9.3 rebounds
in his first three seasons, but the team believes he is more of a
small forward than a power forward. If Pitino didn't feel that way,
he wouldn't have told Walker to develop a ``Scottie Pippen-type''
body. Vitaly Potapenko is strong, but has never been a rebounder.
Tony Battie is not known as a rebounder. Paul Pierce rebounds well
for a small forward, but that's not his full-time gig. What does
all that mean? A trade.
</P>
<P>
   The draft story has been recited here many times, so we know a
new player isn't going to come from there. We'll just say that it's
unlikely the Celtics will be able to keep their semi-protected pick
by coming up with a top-3 choice. And we'll also add that if Corey
Maggette is available with the seventh pick and the Cavaliers take
him, they will like him and Boston will miss him. Unless Boston
gets a Maria Grasso miracle, there will not be enough cash for a
significant free agent. So the only way a rebounder comes is
through a trade.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Pierce is probably untouchable, based on his game and his
secure contract status. Walker says he will ``be here for a long
time'' and that fans ``should get used to me.'' He must know that,
to paraphrase the Scriptures, it is easier for a camel to pass
through the eye of a needle than it is for a rich man to be traded
with a contract like that. Kenny Anderson will be tough to deal
and, even if he weren't, he's still a point guard and the Celtics
would rather have him than Dana Barros. That leaves Ron Mercer.
</P>
<P>
   It is probably not a good idea to trade a 6-foot-7-inch guard
who can make 20-footers just as easily as he can throw down
one-handed alley-oops falling away from the basket, as he did
against the Hornets. But the team thought about a trade _ a lot _
before Mercer's contract extension became an issue. And the only
way they will get rebounding is to acquire it, because it probably
can't be developed.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the team can always keep its top four intact and
remix the rest of the roster. But doing that will not ensure the
playoffs, and that's a problem because this team has to make the
playoffs next season. If it doesn't, fans will remind Pitino that
they expected playoff success. And they'll remind him with his own
words.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   There was plenty of speculation last week when M.L. Carr said he
was ``disappointed'' with the Celtics' season and that he found it
``insulting'' that the organization would be mentioned in any type
of analogy with an expansion team.
</P>
<P>
   First, Paul Gaston wanted it known that Carr spoke on his own
and did not consult with the chairman of the board. Carr, now the
team's executive vice president of corporate development, also said
that he was speaking for no one but himself. Some people also
wondered why Carr would be critical of Pitino when Pitino can fire
him. But the truth is that Pitino cannot fire Carr; only Gaston
can. And if that were to happen, it probably wouldn't be the wisest
move for the organization when you consider that Carr has three
years remaining on a deal that he and Gaston brokered in the spring
of '97.
</P>
<P>
   Carr becomes uncharacteristically mum when pressed for specifics
on that renegotiated contract (he had two years remaining on his
original deal when he and Gaston reworked it), but word is that
marketing perks are included in the new contract as well. So,
obviously, if the team were to fire him it would still have to pay
him. And pay him well.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   If I'm David Stern, one thing terrifies me more than anything.
It is not the image of the players in my league. It is not the
dynamics of the next television contract. And it is not the
ownership situation in Charlotte. The most frightening stat for the
basketball present and future is scoring. Quick: Guess how many
teams averaged more than 100 points per game this season. One (the
Kings). The last time that happened, the Celtics had a role player
named Togo Palazzi, the Baltimore Bullets began a season and
decided to disband after 13 games, and the best player in the
Schayes family _ Dolph _ was going for 18 points and 12 rebounds
each night for the Syracuse Nationals. That was the 1954-55 season,
the first season of the 24-second shot clock. We all know that
coaches have obsessive, computer-assisted scouting techniques,
right? Well, let's hope that when the Y2K problem strikes at the
end of the year, only the computers of NBA coaches will be
affected. That way, maybe 114-107 scores can be seen again . . . My
choice for WNBA champion: The previously pathetic Washington
Mystics. The reason is obvious. With the first pick in the draft,
the Mystics selected Chamique Holdsclaw. The former Tennessee
forward won a championship every year in high school and three out
of four seasons in college. She'll be a rookie MVP candidate in the
pros. She'll be the league's Michael Jordan . . . Joe Dumars will
retire whenever the Pistons' playoff run ends. Many will remember
Dumars as an old-school guard, one who could play the position no
matter what you called it _ point guard or shooting guard; neither
was a problem. His last game in Boston, April 27, wasn't great. He
scored a point and had three assists. But after the game, Pistons
coach Alvin Gentry praised him and talked of his impact on the team
. . . Wonder what Craig Ehlo was doing Friday. Probably hiding his
calendar. Friday _ May 7 _ was the 10-year anniversary of The Shot,
Jordan's improbable 18-footer at the buzzer to beat Ehlo and
Cleveland in Game 5 of a first-round series . . . This from Pat
Riley, who hasn't coached a championship team since 1988: ``All
I've done for 11 years is win without winning _ a lot of winning
without any real winning. What I've done for 11 years isn't
winning. I know that. And I'm very frustrated by it. I'm not going
to go to pieces over it. I'll just work harder. The last eight
years, taking two franchises and turning them completely over, has
been very hard. Hard, hard work. I'm getting a little bit
impatient.'' Imagine how he feels this morning, following the
Heat's 20-point home loss to the Knicks Saturday. If Riley wants a
championship this season, his team will have to win in New York,
where the Heat have an all-time record of 3-21 . . . The Lakers,
who will move into a new arena next season with the Clippers, have
already notified the league that they plan to modify their classic
uniforms. And speaking of the move, it is probably more accurate to
say that the second-class Clippers are moving in with the Lakers .
. . Since we are having this very rare Clippers Discussion Moment,
let's also remember to keep people less fortunate than ourselves _
such as Chris Ford _ in our prayers. The 9-41 team Ford coached is
a mess and it will probably get worse since the team's best player,
Maurice Taylor (nearly 17 points per night), is up for an extension
and may not want to sign it. The Clippers actually have a Web site.
On it, visitors are prompted to view the results of the Clippers'
Greatest Moments. Even the great moments are mediocre. The top
five:
</P>
<P>
   --April 16, 1992: Clips secure first playoff appearance in 16
years.
</P>
<P>
   --March 30, 1993: Clips beat Lakers to ``clinch the City Series
for the first time since the Clippers moved to LA.'' Whoa. The
Lakers' record in '93 was 39-43.
</P>
<P>
   --April 28, 1992: Clips defeat Utah in first home playoff game.
They lost the series, of course.
</P>
<P>
   --May 5, 1993: Clips defeat Houston to force fifth game of
playoff series. They lost the series, of course.
</P>
<P>
   --March 13, 1998: Clips blast Raptors with 152 points and 69
percent shooting from the field. The Raptors finished that season
16-66. But the Clippers were better. They were 17-65.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Celtics will certainly tinker with their roster in the
offseason; will there be tinkering with those who talk about their
games, too? The team has Howard David, one of the top play-by-play
radio men in the country, calling games. But the contract of his
partner, analyst Cedric Maxwell, will expire before next season . .
. As usual, I waited until the final hour _ literally _ to fax my
postseason awards ballots to the NBA. I was stumped by the vote for
MVP. I define that award in the simplest terms: Who would you give
the ball to in a tie game; and which player has skills that are
obviously valuable to his team but, more important, the league?
Alonzo Mourning? No way I give him the ball when my team needs a
hoop or free throws. Tim Duncan? Close. Real close. Karl Malone?
Reluctantly, yes. Malone did not deserve to be MVP in '97. And
every time I think of him, I always expect to see Jordan pop up
behind his back, poking the ball away to set up his final hoop
(Malone probably can't forget that Finals moment from Game 6,
either). But Malone's teams win, he is an incredible scorer, and he
consistently gets to the line more than any other player in the
league . . . Chauncey Billups still needs to work on his field goal
shooting (39 percent), but guess who led the league in free throw
shooting? That's right, Billups made 91 percent of his freebies,
missing only 14 the entire season.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-08-99 2129EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
