<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-NFL </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WILLIAMS SHOULD SAY BYE NOW, PAY LATER 
</HEADLINE>
 NOTEBOOK-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON BORGES  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Just before last month's NFL draft, Leland Hardy, one
of the agents representing Heisman Trophy winner Ricky Williams,
said he would get his client one of the largest contracts in NFL
history. That became unlikely the day the New Orleans Saints gave
up their entire draft to get Williams, and now as talks grind
slowly along, Hardy's best chance is to refuse up-front cash and
take a novel approach to negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   Because of a quirk in the NFL's collective bargaining agreement
called the 25 Percent Rule, Williams will be hurt long-term by
being the only player in the Saints' draft _ even though logically
you might think otherwise _ and if he insists on the normal
multimillion-dollar signing bonus, he will be severely hurt
financially over time.
</P>
<P>
   Each NFL team has what is called a rookie pool, which is the
total sum of money the league allots a club to pay its rookies. The
more players or the more top picks, the larger the pool. For
example, New England had two No. 1 picks this year as well as a No.
2 and two No. 3s, so its pool was $3,401,861. Cleveland, which had
the first pick in the draft and extra picks, has a pool of
$5,165,897. San Diego, without a No. 1 choice, was alloted only
$1,618,642.
</P>
<P>
   The Saints, who ended up making the fifth overall selection by
trading their entire draft to Washington, have been allocated
$1,479,185. Out of that, they must pay Williams and whatever rookie
free agents they sign (and there will be many to round out their
80-man roster). Under the rules, the Saints cannot pay Williams
more than their total pool for this year and can give him only a 25
percent raise in base salary from the first to the second year.
After that, they can give him increments equal only to the
difference between his first- and second-year salary (unless they
completely rework the contract).
</P>
<P>
   Because of this, the wisest negotiating course for Williams's
side is to ask for little or no signing bonus and as much money in
first-year base salary as he can get; but that could be a problem
for his agent in the future because other agents would argue to
prospective clients that Hardy had failed to get the most
productive running back in NCAA history a dime up front. That would
be a powerful argument to many college players, even though Hardy
would have done the best thing for his client.
</P>
<P>
   Few college players come into the NFL with anything in their
heads but thoughts of a huge signing bonus, even though they
immediately lose half of it in taxes. It is something they've read
about for years, and with many of them coming from low-income
backgrounds, instant cash is a psychological lure difficult to
overcome.
</P>
<P>
   ``That will be a problem for Hardy,'' predicted Boston-based
agent Brad Blank. ``Players expect to get that bonus. If you tell
them it's an advance against future earnings instead, it doesn't
mean the same to them.
</P>
<P>
   ``For Hardy, it will make it interesting because other agents
will try to use it against him if he does the right thing by his
client.''
</P>
<P>
   If Williams is thinking in the traditional way, he loses,
because every dime he puts into a signing bonus will cost him
significant money over the life of his first contract. Here's why.
</P>
<P>
   Say the Saints signed no undrafted free agents and have their
entire rookie pool of $1,479,185 available. If he signed a
seven-year deal, which is the type New Orleans would like, and
takes a $5 million signing bonus, he could be paid no more than
$764,899.30 in base salary his first year because of the pro-rated
signing bonus. If he received the maximum 25 percent increase in
base pay his second year, it would move him up to $956,124.12. The
difference between his first- and second-year pay would be
$191,224.82. That would be the maximum that could be added to his
base each year for the next five seasons without renegotiation.
</P>
<P>
   That means Williams would have salaries of $1,147,348.90 in his
third year under this model, $1,338,573.70 in his fourth,
$1,529,798.50 in his fifth, $1,721,023.30 in the sixth, and
$1,912,248.10 in the seventh for a total of $14,370,015, including
the signing bonus.
</P>
<P>
   If he were to get a $9 million signing bonus, his base salary
his first year would be only $193,470.80 because the bonus would be
spread over the seven years at $1,285,714.20 per year. If you take
25 percent of his rookie base pay _ $48,367.70 _ and add it to his
first-year salary, it comes to only $241,838.50 the second year. As
you can see, that is a two-year total of $435,309.30 in salary
against a two-year total base of $1,721,023.50 with the $5 million
bonus. His salaries for years 3-7 with a $9 million bonus would be:
$290,206.20, $338,573.90, $386,941.60, $435,309.30, $483,677.00.
</P>
<P>
   Thus, with a $5 million signing bonus Williams's total package
would be $14,370,015 but with a $9 million signing bonus it would
total only $11,370,016. On a per-year average, Williams would be
paid $2,052,859.20 per year with the $5 million bonus and
$1,624,288 with a $9 million bonus.
</P>
<P>
   The higher the bonus, then, the less Williams actually makes.
Hence, he doesn't really need an agent to negotiate his contract,
he needs an accountant, because there's little to negotiate with
the rookie pool and the 25 Percent Rule in place. All Hardy can
fight for is length of contract and as much money in guaranteed
base salaries as he can get.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, if Williams were to ask for no signing bonus and put
all of his money in base salaries he would greatly increase his
total package. If New Orleans could give him its entire rookie
pool, he would earn $1,479,185 in base pay this season. The 25
Percent Rule addition for Year 2 would be another $369,796.20, for
a second-year total of $1,848,981.20. Now comes the big money.
Under the repetitive-effect rule, Williams would then have
$369,796.25 added to his base pay each year for the remainder of
the contract.
</P>
<P>
   Thus, by accepting all salary and no bonus, Williams's base pay
in years 3-7 would be: $2,218,774.40, $2,588,570.60, $2,958,366.80,
$3,328,163.00 and $3,697,959.20 for a total package without a bonus
of $18,120,000.00, a yearly average of $2,588,571.40.
</P>
<P>
   That would mean a difference with no bonus of $6,749,984 against
a $9 million signing bonus and $3,749,985 if he took a $5 million
bonus before the hefty tax hit he would take on any bonus is
figured in.
</P>
<P>
   As Blank points out, ``Williams is hurt by being the only
drafted player for New Orleans because when there is a full
complement of draftees, the top guy can basically steal money from
the lower draftees. There ends up being a much larger cash pool and
the No. 1 choice usually gets most of it. Williams can't do that
because he's all alone.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams's agents, who were hired after he first fired Woolf
Associates and who have never done an NFL deal, must understand the
financial implications of the 25 Percent Rule and then persuade the
Saints to carry huge base salaries, which they might try to avoid.
But the upside for New Orleans is that it would make the contract
far easier to trade because there would be no automatic
acceleration onto its salary cap because no pro-rated bonus money
would be hanging over the team.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond that, Williams would have little else to bargain about
except salary guarantees. Blank says a smart agent would want the
latter years, where the most money is earned, guaranteed while the
first years would not be because Williams would be in little danger
of being released.
</P>
<P>
   Williams's leverage comes only from being the Saints' sole pick
and the guy Mike Ditka has staked his reptuation and future on. A
protracted holdout would cost the Saints dearly.
</P>
<P>
   So if Williams has the strength to continue on the odd road his
career began on _ by asking for no signing bonus _ he will maximize
his income in a most unusual way.
</P>
<P>
   There is, of course, another way Williams could make more money.
He could save the agent's cut by negotiating the deal himself,
because in his odd case there's not much to talk about.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Patriots vice president for personnel Bobby Grier was shocked
when he saw Bruce Armstrong at the team's offices recently. ``Bruce
is down to 290,'' Grier said, indicating a drop of nearly 15
pounds. ``Bruce is a prideful guy and he's taken the right
approach. He's doing what Lomas Brown did. When Lomas got into the
latter part of his careeer, he realized he had to play at a little
bit lighter weight and he dropped some pounds. When I saw Bruce, I
didn't recognize him at first, his face was so thin.'' Armstrong
struggled with speed rushers last year because he played with a
stress fracture in his leg all season. His leg was never right from
the start of training camp but Armstrong never used the injury as
an excuse, refusing even to admit to its existence once the regular
season began. With his weight reduction and a return to health, the
Patriots are hopeful that he will return to the dominant play that
made him a six-time Pro Bowl selection . . . Grier has an
interesting point of view on rookie running back Kevin Faulk.
``He's not small, he's just short,'' Grier said of his No. 2 pick.
``Kevin goes over 200 pounds, and some of the best backs in the
league _ Emmitt Smith, Barry Sanders, and Thurman Thomas _ are no
more than an inch taller than he is. I believe this kid is going to
end up being our (regular) back.'' . . . The Patriots continue to
look at former Redskin running back Terry Allen, who was recently
released after two injury-marred seasons, but they are concerned
about his durability and asking price. The nine-year veteran rushed
for more than 1,000 yards in 1992, 1994, 1995, and 1996, but
slipped to 724 and 700 the past two seasons. His playing time also
fell and his carries dropped from a career-high 347 in 1996 to 210
and then 148 because of injury. In '98, Allen still averaged 4.7
yards a carry before his season was cut short for the second
straight year, and the concern is that his 208-pound body is
starting to turn brittle after 1,684 career carries . . . The early
assessment in Foxborough on Andy Katzenmoyer is that weak-side
plugger, the position Todd Collins played, is better-suited to his
talents than middle linebacker, but to play it effectively,
Katzenmoyer will have to learn how to better use his hands to keep
blockers off him. If he does, he starts Sept. 12 . . . By the way,
unless your name is Jamal Anderson, it was much ado about nothing
that his name came up on draft day in a potential trade with the
Patriots. You'd have to be an idiot to make such a deal for a
player in the final year of his contract on short notice, which is
what the Falcons gave the Patriots. Anderson is asking to be paid
like Sanders and Terrell Davis and in fact may have already taken
more hits than you'd like. Fans forget that despite his brilliant
season, Anderson was backing up Byron Hanspard until Hanspard was
lost early in the season.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Patriots cornerback Ty Law continues to pay the price to achieve
greatness. He has been working out regularly at Bob Kersee's speed
and conditioning camp in Los Angeles, along with Steelers running
back Jerome Bettis. Law returned home for Mother's Day Saturday but
will fly back to LA this week and stay in Kersee's program until
the Patriots' June mini-camp. After that, he is scheduled to return
to Los Angeles and work at the UCLA track until the end of June,
then take a short break before training camp. That is called paying
the price, something not enough Patriots understood the past two
years. Law was never one of them, which is why he's a Pro Bowl
cornerback today while others with great talent have languished
below their potential . . . Daniel Snyder may have finally come up
with an $800 million deal to buy the Redskins that the NFL owners
will approve at the end of the month, but the league hasn't seen
the end of spurned suitor Howard Milstein. When Milstein withdrew
his own $800 million offer (in which the 34-year-old Snyder was a
minority partner) after becoming convinced he could never muster
the number of votes needed for approval, the owners thought they
had gotten him to agree not to sue them, even though his offer had
been accepted by the trust selling the Redskins. Well, maybe not.
Milstein has retained noted Washington litagator David Boies, who
earns $600 an hour just for taking your phone call. Boies led the
government's lawsuit against Microsoft and Bill Gates, while also
opening up a private practice that has grown to include 34 lawyers
in just 13 months. According to his publicity sheet, the
57-year-old Boies spent 30 years as a corporate lawyer at the Wall
Street firm of Cravath Swaine &AMP; Moore and lost only one of more
than 45 cases. He represented the Federal Deposit Insurance Corp.
in its insider-trading litigation that ended with junk bond king
Michael Milken paying a $1.1 billion settlement. More than a few
folks have written to ask how a guy could offer $800 million for
the Redskins and have his application rejected. The factors were
many, but Milstein has been a disaster as owner of the NHL's New
York Islanders and it was feared he would soon be pushing alongside
Jerry Jones to break up the lucrative agreement that allocates most
NFL Properties revenue equally among the league's 31 teams, despite
the fact that some _ such as the Cowboys and Raiders _ account for
the bulk of the sales. Many also were fearful about his not putting
up much cash or risking personal assets. Now they may have a
disastrous situation of another kind if Boies gets into things . .
. Meanwhile, one of the men who had opposed Milstein now says he
will vote in favor of Snyder at the owners' meeting in Atlanta. New
Cleveland owner Al Lerner was among the four who led the
anti-Milstein forces, and his opposition may very well have been
personal. Milstein and Lerner duked it out when the Cleveland
Indians were for sale, and it cost each of them a lot of money. The
Browns were joined most vocally by Denver, Pittsburgh, and New
Orleans . . . Michael Huyghue, the Jaguars' senior vice president
of football operations, is famous for signing draft choices
quickly, but he outdid himself when he signed second-rounder Larry
Smith, a defensive tackle from Florida State, to a four-year deal
worth more than $8 million a week after the draft. Smith is only
the second drafted player to sign. Overall No. 1 choice Tim Couch
was the first.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
