<HEADER>
A9584 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RAC-PREAKNESS-HNS &LR;      05-08 1021
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-PREAKNESS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Trainers keeping their options wide open before Preakness Stakes
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By ALAN TRUEX &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1999, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   To a horse racing purist _ is that an oxymoron or what? _ the
125th Kentucky Derby was an eyesore. The Run for the Roses
certainly didn't smell like one. Too many horses, no speed, no
viable strategy.
</P>
<P>
   You've seen the analogies: stampede, rodeo, Roller Derby,
Oklahoma Land Rush, bumper cars, ping-pong, crapshoot, lottery. So
enough of that. Bring on the Preakness!
</P>
<P>
   But will next Saturday's Second Jewel of the Triple Crown be
much better? One thing's for sure: The field will be smaller, cut
from 19 to a maximum of 14.
</P>
<P>
   That in itself, however, is no reason to celebrate. The Pimlico
Race Course of Baltimore is narrower than Churchill Downs and has
sharper turns. A horse in the 14th hole may not feel much different
from the 19th Derby starter. Getting hung wide on the turn can be
fatal in the Preakness Stakes.
</P>
<P>
   That's why Carl Nafzger, trainer of Fountain of Youth and
Florida Derby winner Vicar, said he'll scratch his horse if stuck
with an outside post in Wednesday's draw. Bob Baffert threatened
the same with superfilly Silverbulletday.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Baffert, who won last year's Derby and Preakness with
Real Quiet, is considering bypassing the Second Jewel altogether.
</P>
<P>
   ``With the large field and all, there's no reason for going up
there,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Baffert is ``on the fence'' with the Derby's fourth-place
finisher, Prime Timber. ``He was tired coming out of the Derby, and
he's lost weight,'' the trainer explained, saying he would decide
Monday whether to send the colt in the Preakness.
</P>
<P>
   He's also straddling with Silverbulletday, who has won 10 of 11
races. She is cross-entered in the Preakness and the Black-Eyed
Susan Stakes for fillies only. ``I'll see how she draws, then
decide,'' Baffert said.
</P>
<P>
   Silverbulletday, who skipped the Kentucky Derby, would be a key
newcomer to the Triple Crown campaign. She could be the second or
third pick in the morning line.
</P>
<P>
   Another key addition could be Torrid Sand, a front-runner who
finished third in the Arkansas Derby and was promoted to second
when the winner, Valhol, was disqualified because jockey Billy
Patin allegedly carried an illegal battery.
</P>
<P>
   Trainer Randy Morse tried to enter Torrid Sand in the Kentucky
Derby but failed to make the cut because of insufficient
graded-stakes earnings. With the purses from the Arkansas Derby
redistributed, Torrid Sand makes the field of the 124th Preakness.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Valhol's owner, Jim Jackson of Rockdale, intends to
run his gelding in the Preakness despite his 15th-place Derby fade
and the cloud of scandal and disputed money.
</P>
<P>
   Without the purse from Arkansas, Valhol doesn't have enough
career earnings to qualify for the Preakness if more than 14
attempt to enter, which appears to be the case.
</P>
<P>
   Valhol was admitted to the Derby only because of a court order,
and it may take another judicial ruling to put him in the
Preakness.
</P>
<P>
   If this is going to be a good, clean race, early speed is
essential. The Derby was sabotaged by a combination of too many
horses and no leadership to string out the field. The half mile of
47 seconds was the slowest in 30 years.
</P>
<P>
   The filly Three Ring was supposed to provide pace, but her
saddle slipped as she burst out of the gate, and she was never a
factor. She won't run in the Preakness, but Torrid Sand, who has
been training sharply, should prove an adequate front-end
replacement.
</P>
<P>
   While many horses were battered and bruised, the Derby's top
three finishers emerged unscathed.
</P>
<P>
   Wayne Lukas, trainer of 30-1 long-shot winner Charismatic and
the show horse Cat Thief, goes for his fifth Preakness victory with
two horses he said he ``cannot separate'' in ability.
</P>
<P>
   Cat Thief ran near the front throughout the Derby and had the
lead early in the stretch before fading slightly, as he tends to
do.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been working all spring with him trying to get him to
blow by horses,'' said Lukas, who observed that the colt takes
after his grandfather, Alydar, runner-up to Affirmed throughout the
1978 Triple Crown campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Cat Thief has been in the money 12 straight times but lacks a
killer instinct. ``He has a little Alydar in him,'' Lukas said.
``He hangs.''
</P>
<P>
   As for Charismatic, he's had an exceptionally hard career: 15
starts already. This will be his third race in six weeks. But
Lukas, who has won 11 Triple Crown events, insisted, ``He's that
come-back-in-two-weeks kind of horse.''
</P>
<P>
   Menifee was perhaps the most impressive horse in the Derby,
driving to second from far off the pace in a race that had no pace.
He's the likely Preakness favorite, but he may need to run closer
to the front on a track famous for early speed holding.
</P>
<P>
   Also dangerous in the Preakness is Worldly Manner, the Arabian
import who battled for the lead at the top of the lengthy Churchill
stretch before tiring and finishing seventh.
</P>
<P>
   Because he had not competed in any prep races, Worldly Manner
was not expected to last. But the Derby may have conditioned him
for the Preakness, which is half a furlong shorter.
</P>
<P>
   Some horses who flopped in Louisville will try again, excused
because of the unusual circumstances of their last race. Thus, Nick
Zito will start Stephen Got Even and Adonis, who finished 14th and
17th, respectively, in the Derby.
</P>
<P>
   ``Both horses had excuses, and we've got to go forward,'' Zito
said. ``Stephen was one of my biggest disappointments in racing. He
trained like Man o' War. And I thought Adonis was going to be right
there. I've never had two horses train up to the race like these.''
</P>
<P>
   Stephen Got Even was slammed hard shortly after his release from
the gate. He suffered minor cuts and never found his stride. Adonis
was jammed on the rail and was forever searching for a lane; he
ended up running about 10-wide, all alone, on the far turn.
</P>
<P>
   Now they get a second chance in the Second Jewel. It's an
opportunity for the sport as a whole to redeem itself.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
