<HEADER>
A9586 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-NHLNOTEBOOK-BOS &LR;      05-08 1893
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-NHL </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RANFORD LATEST EXAMPLE OF BOWMAN'S DEEP THINKING 
</HEADLINE>
 NOTEBOOK-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN PAUL DUPONT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ It's a safe bet that Bill Ranford won't win another
Conn Smythe trophy this spring as the playoff MVP, but the former
Bruins goalie put on a pretty remarkable performance Friday night,
stepping in to backstop Detroit's 3-2 win over Colorado.
</P>
<P>
   Ranford was last seen here when the Bruins said farewell to
their Grumpiest Old Men, beaten out of town with fellow oldsters
Adam Oates and Rick Tocchet, essentially identifying them as the
unholy trio that led the Bruins to last place overall. They took
the hit for a lot of bad deal-making, payroll decisions, and
coaching inexperience, but, hey, who remembers all that in these
heady times, right?
</P>
<P>
   Now on his third team since Boston, Ranford hadn't played a game
since April 14 before getting the surprise start ahead of Chris
Osgood, who was hobbled by a knee injury earlier in the week. After
falling into a 2-1 hole at 12:34 of the first period, Ranford kept
his cage clean for the next 51:44, until Kirk Maltby banged home
the winner for the Winged Wheels.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fatigue factor was my big concern,'' said the 32-year-old
Ranford, ``but I just tried to shut that out.'' As the game got
along, he shut everything out.
</P>
<P>
   Don't you love how the Wings win? Ranford subs for Osgood and
there isn't an inch of give in net. Maltby bangs home the winner,
and of course the key helper goes to Kris Draper, another of the
no-name Detroit diggers.
</P>
<P>
   The Wings, two Stanley Cups rich, have a lot of things going for
them, not the least of which is the brilliant Scotty Bowman behind
their bench. But most impressive of all is the premium they put on
depth, which translates directly into owner Mike Ilitch's desire to
win, to be the best.
</P>
<P>
   When the March trade deadline came around, they didn't flinch at
the millions it would take to add to their foundation, bringing in
the likes of Chris Chelios, Ulf Samuelsson, Wendel Clark, and
Ranford, who was deemed as a throw-in but immediately was labled an
``insurance policy'' by Bowman.
</P>
<P>
   Are the Wings going to win it? Check this space in coming weeks.
Even if they don't, however, give them credit for taking the
calculated, and costly, risks necessary to attempt to win it.
They've come to expect excellence, they strive for it, and they've
been rewarded for it. Sometimes it does work that way.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Word circulated late last week that former Bruin Craig Janney
was ready to call it a career. Not so, says his agent, Rick
Scimone. ``Craig's got some medical issues that need attention,''
said Scimone. ``As of right now, though, he's planning to be back
playing next season.'' Janney had a strong start in Tampa Bay last
October, but ultimately was dealt to the Islanders (the Kings had
interest, too). He exited the Uniondale lineup in March when blood
clots in his leg required him to be hospitalized. Janney will be 32
in September and is an unrestricted free agent as of July 1 . . .
After getting dismissed again in the first round of the playoffs
following a highly successful regular season, the Devils won't
offer new deals to Bob Carpenter or Dave Andreychuk (a former Pat
Burns favorite in Toronto). Robbie Ftorek's job as coach also
didn't sound so safe when owner John McMullen said of Pittsburgh's
Kevin Constantine, ``He's a pretty good coach. It's not the first
time he's done this, beating a favored team. He did it in San Jose,
too, when they beat Detroit in the seventh game. He might have been
the difference in the series.'' The sight of the Devils, on the
bench with their heads down every time the Penguins scored in the
clincher, was chilling. Bad body language. Basic execution was
poor, too. Example: the botched line change that led to Jaromir
Jagr and Martin Straka bolting out on a two-on-none for a goal
against the defenseless _ and very mediocre _ Martin Brodeur . . .
Vancouver general manager Brian Burke has said that longtime
assistant coaches Stan Smyl and Glen Hanlon have jobs next year if
they want them, but both are scouting around. Smyl might have an
offer in Europe. Hanlon, the former goalie, would like to land a
head coaching job in the NHL or the minors. Marc Crawford, brought
in to replace Mike Keenan as head coach last season, will bring in
Andy Murray as his top aide next season . . . Jeff Norton, formerly
of Acton and Cushing Academy, didn't score a goal for the Sharks in
their first-round loss to Colorado, but he did lead all San Jose
point-getters with seven assists. An excellent skater, Norton has
been overbilled as a high-powered scorer at times during his
career, but his skating and sense for moving the puck make him a
valuable asset.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   With tongue in cheek, coach Jim Schoenfeld staked his job on the
Coyotes beating the Blues in Game 7 of their first-round series. It
went to double OT before Pierre Turgeon won it for the Blues, 1-0,
and Schoenfeld followed the crushing defeat by saying he was only
trying to take the heat off his players. Noble. But the bet here is
that Schoenfeld gets the gate. Yes, they were banged up, and they
would have had even more guys out if they had made it past the
Blues. Nonetheless, they're 0 for 3 in their three springs in the
desert, and this isn't a team with a poor player mix. ESPN reported
over a month ago that Jeremy Roenick won't be back, but ditching JR
would be a harder sell than offing Schoenfeld, especially after
Roenick's valiant return for Game 7 vs. the Blues . . . The final
pennies haven't been counted, but the average NHL salary in 1998-99
was just a few bucks shy of $1.3 million . . . Look for the Flyers
to shop defenseman Luke Richardson. He didn't dress for a single
game against the Leafs; coach Roger Neilson believed he was just
too slow. Look for GM Bob Clarke to tap into his favorite pipeline
and send Richardson to the Lightning, perhaps for Rob Zamuner . . .
A couple of former Bruins, defenseman Jamie Huscroft and checking
forward Mike Sullivan, are among Phoenix's five unrestricted free
agents. Huscroft wouldn't fit the plan in the Hub, but the
31-year-old Sullivan, lost in the Nashville expansion draft (and
later dealt to the Coyotes), still has the skills to contribute.
Remember, too, there's no guarantee the Bruins will pay to keep Tim
Taylor, who is free to walk in July because he's a 10-year pro
making less than the $1.3 million average. Don't forget the Bruins
let the likes of Dave Poulin and Dave Reid walk when their tabs got
too high . . . The scouting report on Robyn Regehr, destined to be
on the Flames' blue line next year, is that he'll be another Adam
Foote, a big, tough defenseman. If you lost track, the Flames
plucked him from the Avalanche in the Theo Fleury swap, after
Colorado drafted Regehr No. 19 overall last June with the
first-round pick it acquired from Boston in the Landon Wilson deal
. . . No knowing yet whether Brian Sutter will be back as Flames
coach. GM Al Coates is on record as saying he'll recommend to the
owners that Sutter be brought back (the club holds the option), but
there's no guarantee that Coates will keep his job, either . . .
The water only gets murkier in Pittsburgh, where unresolved
bankruptcy proceedings leave the league not knowing how to proceed
with scheduling and a litany of other key issues (player contracts,
etc.). Another possible new suitor, Mark Cuban, entered the picture
last week. Cuban is the founder of Broadcast.com and grew up in
suburban Pittsburgh. Former superstar Mario Lemieux submitted a
plan, endorsed by the NHL, to bankruptcy court, and Cuban might
join the Lemieux group. At least one other group, headed by
investment banker Chip Gesner, formerly of Connecticut, is
considering a bid. Cuban has the deep pockets preferred by the NHL.
Last month, Yahoo agreed to buy Broadcast.com for $5.7 billion, and
Cuban's cut was approximately $1.2 billion. There will be an
emergency court hearing Tuesday in Pittsburgh, but there is no
guarantee that anything will get resolved before early this summer
. . . The Rangers could make offseason bids for Fleury and/or
Vincent Damphousse, both of whom are unrestricted free agents.
Coach John Muckler has scouted both of them during the playoffs.
Meanwhile, Damphousse and the Sharks didn't make it out of the
first round _ they were losers to Fleury's Avalanche _ which means
the Habs must settle for a second-round pick in 2000 as
compensation for sending Damphousse to San Jose. The deal had the
Habs getting a first-rounder this year if the Sharks made it to
Round 2.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Anaheim GM Pierre Gauthier sounds like an easy mark when he
says, ``My philosophy is, whether it's Paul (Kariya) or anyone
else, it's a business deal that shouldn't be a fight.'' Kariya's
contract is up and his new pact undoubtedly will bring him upwards
of $10 million a year, if not more. In the Disney regime, that's
just another guy making Mo Vaughn kind of money, but it could be
more of a tussle than Gauthier is fashioning. The price of Disney
stock is down, following disappointing earnings the last quarter.
Kariya is a great talent, but you can bet Uncle Walt's bean
counters are going to look at the franchise's abysmal postseason
record (4-11 in just three series over six seasons) and consider
ways to run a leaner (i.e. more profitable) operation . . . Alexei
Yashin, last seen as the centerpiece of a Senators foldup against
the Sabres, is playing for Russia in the World Championships. He
has one more year on his deal, worth more than $3 million for next
season, but it's a good bet GM Rick Dudley and Yashin's agent, Mark
Gandler, will get to work on a new long-term deal this summer. The
Senators were at the bottom of the league with a $20 million
payroll in '98-99. Yashin projects to about $10 million a year on
his new pact, which would boost the payroll to about $27 million .
. . Paul Rebillard, formerly of Concord, just finished up his
fourth season of officiating pro hockey in Switzerland and one day
would like to work on this side of the Atlantic. ``I'd love to be
in the International League or the American League, or NCAA
Division 1,'' said the 34-year-old Rebillard, reached by phone just
outside Geneva.The difference between the North American game and
the European brand? ``Stick work,'' said Rebillard, a linesman.
``There's more passing and playmaking, too, but here if you really
nail a guy, it's pretty much a guarantee he'll come back and knife
you with the stick.'' . . . Please, no more backslapping over the
local NFL entry staying in Foxborough. Someone on Beacon Hill or in
City Hall must have the smarts to bring the Patriots and Red Sox to
the table and get them both in downtown arenas. Instead, we're
supposed to feel good about $70 million-plus being spent on highway
infrastructure (hey, wow, look at those guardrails). The Vault is
by no means the best of the new buildings, but it is downtown, and
the basic law of real estate holds true: Location is everything. It
can't be this hard to get things right in Our Town. The fact that
it is so difficult, especially with the economy so robust, should
tell all of us that those at the wheel only keep screwing it up,
then saving it, as a pathetic plot to keep their jobs.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
