<SLUG> BC-GLF-GOLF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NOTHING WRONG WITH CALLING 'EM AS YOU SEE 'EM 
</HEADLINE>
 NOTEBOOK-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM McCABE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Players don't particularly like the situation, but they
had best get used to the golfing public calling in rules violations
to tournament authorities. Not that tournament officials like it
either, but, said Charlie Lanzetta, the head pro at Rockland Golf
Club, ``We're living with it now; it's been accepted.''
</P>
<P>
   Lanzetta, one of the top rules officials with the PGA of
America, did not see the recent incident involving Seve
Ballesteros, but he has been in the middle of enough decisions to
know how it played out. At the Spanish Open, Ballesteros hooked his
drive on a par-5 and then tried to hit a long fade around trees. He
lost his second shot in trees left of the green, returned to the
original spot, and re-hit. To be diplomatic, one would say that
Ballesteros took a questionable drop; many of his competitors _ and
those from the TV audience who called in _ were far less forgiving,
saying Ballesteros illegally dropped closer to the hole and away
from the tree that had been his obstacle to begin with.
</P>
<P>
   The tournament's chief referee heard Ballesteros's argument _
that he tried to find his original spot and asked spectators for
help _ and ruled that there was no penalty. Ballesteros, said the
referee, had dropped closer to the hole, but since the distance was
great (230 yards) there was no ``serious breach.''
</P>
<P>
   The fact that Ballesteros was not penalized (shame on him; he
was guilty and should have been DQ'd) overshadows the larger issue:
He never would have been forced to explain himself had TV viewers
not called in to complain.
</P>
<P>
   Should TV viewers, or spectators at an event, be allowed to get
that involved?
</P>
<P>
   ``If the phones are manned and the video is rolling, we'll
listen,'' said Lanzetta. ``There are mixed emotions on both sides,
but until all bodies (PGA Tour, PGA of America, US Golf
Association, Royal &AMP; Ancient) agree, whether it is right or wrong,
we'll keep doing it.''
</P>
<P>
   Why shouldn't viewers or spectators be allowed a voice? The
Rules of Golf, while arguably tedious at times, are not that
complex; an awful lot of people who don't play for millions of
dollars know them well and follow them faithfully. They expect
nothing less from the professionals. Just ask Craig Stadler, Paul
Azinger, Nick Faldo, Jesper Parnevik, and Lee Janzen, all of whom
in recent years have been caught in rules violations thanks to TV
viewers or spectators.
</P>
<P>
   If the idea is to make sure that the rules are followed, who
cares who discovers the wrongdoing? Perhaps this situation will get
the players to start paying closer attention to the rules so that
they don't give each other bad advice, as happened to Esteban
Toledo last week. He hit into a lateral water hazard and after
taking his drop, he was standing on a railway tie. So he wanted
relief, which playing partner Eric Booker said he was entitled to.
Toledo took a second drop, played his shot, and was quickly
penalized by a Tour official. You don't get relief in a hazard.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are so engulfed in their game, a lot of times it's not
that they don't know the rules, but they're not that aware of it,''
said Lanzetta.
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately, many people are aware. And tournament officials are
listening.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Combined, they have won 74 PGA Tour events, 10 majors, and
enough cash to live comfortably the rest of their lives. But Tom
Kite, Lanny Wadkins, and Tom Watson are like anxious folks in a
waiting room _ just trying to keep busy until the door opens. In
this case, the door opens onto the Senior PGA Tour. Watson turns 50
Sept. 4, Wadkins Dec. 5, Kite Dec. 9, and their current playing
status indicates that it can't come soon enough. In 1999, this
once-great trio has combined to miss the cut in 18 of 27 tournament
appearances.
</P>
<P>
   Kite and Wadkins have made just two cuts apiece in 10 and nine
starts, respectively. Watson has made five of eight, but only in
Hawaii (T-16) has he finished in the Top 25, and he missed the cut
at Augusta, stretching to six the number of consecutive majors in
which he has failed to reach weekend play.
</P>
<P>
   Add up their scores and they are 118 over par in 1999, so it is
no surprise that Kite (73.19) and Wadkins (72.96) rank toward the
bottom in scoring average. This is truly frustrating for Kite, who
can point to one main problem: putting. The 1992 US Open winner has
had no problem reaching greens in regulation (he ranks seventh on
Tour), but once he gets there, the woes multiply. He ranks
next-to-last in putts per hole, 1.879.
</P>
<P>
   Assuming they choose to head to the Senior Tour, it will be
interesting to see how they do. Hale Irwin is struggling _ at least
by his standards _ Gil Morgan has been inconsistent, and Ray Floyd,
closing in on his 57th birthday, hasn't visited the winner's circle
since 1996. Larry Nelson, who won last week, is steady, but the the
older circuit these days is being dominated by fellows who hardly
ever stepped into the pro spotlight _ people like Bruce Fleisher,
Allen Doyle, Dana Quigley, Bob Duval. No longer are such players
out there to round out fields so that marquee names can collect big
paychecks.
</P>
<P>
   If Kite, Wadkins, and Watson expect to win on the Senior Tour,
they had best polish their games a little and get hungrier, because
if there is a common denominator among Fleisher, Doyle, Quigley,
and Duval, it is their unquenchable appetite to play. They know the
window of opportunity is small, that those aged 50-55 win most of
the events, and they are prepared to tee it up every week.
</P>
<P>
   ``I used to drive all over New England for $5,000 purses,''
Quigley will tell you, ``so do you think I'm going to miss a
million-dollar event?''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   This week's LPGA stop, the Titleholders, is one of the tour's
oldest and most honored events, but until Mercury stepped in a few
weeks ago, it did not have a sponsor. It also is being played
without last year's star attraction, Se Ri Pak, who is collecting
appearance money to play in Japan. She has taken some heat, but to
be fair, another Tour standout, Liselotte Neumann, also is in
Japan. Unfortunate, but this is what happens when money, not the
game, becomes the overriding issue. Pak and Neumann are just
further examples of how loyalty can't match greed. In a few weeks,
the Colonial MasterCard will be contested while Tiger Woods and
Mark O'Meara are playing in Germany. The bronze statue of Ben Hogan
outside stately Colonial may shed a few tears over that sad reality
. . . Speaking of Woods, after a blazing start as a pro, he has
continued to make money by the bucketful, but without the predicted
pile of victories. He has just two wins in his last 30 events,
though honestly he is a threat to run away and hide every time he
tees it up. While his putting has been suspect (he has hit nearly
70 percent of his greens to rank fourth, but is 98th in putting),
most glaring has been his poor final-round scoring: 71.78, ranked
44th . . . More stats: Phil Mickelson has come back with the putter
(he's ranked 20th; he was 80th last year), but he tends to take
Sundays off (152d with a 74.33 average) . . . O'Meara's final-round
average is a surprisingly poor 73.33 . . . Corey Pavin is the only
ranked Tour player with a driving average under 250 yards (249.4) .
. . Chip Beck made the cut this past week in New Orleans, but there
is a good reason why he has had a tough time getting past Friday:
Of 187 players who have played enough to be ranked, Beck is 186th
in three crucial categories _ scoring average, all-around, and
greens in regulation (51.9 percent) . . . John Daly is cruising
along with an average drive of 307.8 yards, with Woods a distant
second (290.0) . . . Brad Faxon deserves his reputation for putting
prowess (he's ranked second), but his driving accuracy (60 percent)
and greens in regulation (57.3) rank 166th and 173d, respectively .
. . And if the US Open is described as fairways and greens, how is
it that two-time winner Lee Janzen is hitting greens at just a 59.7
clip this year to rank 145th?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
