<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-08 22:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9604 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TORNADO-CLINTON-HNS &LR;      05-08 1182
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TORNADO-CLINTON-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON TOURS AREAS HIT BY TORNADOES
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)
<TEXT>
<P>
   By GREG McDONALD &QL; 
and KEVIN MORAN &QL;
</P>
<P>
   c. 1999 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Houston Chronicle &QL;
</P>
<P>
   DEL CITY, Okla. _ Calling it the worst tornado devastation he
has ever seen, President Clinton toured hard hit areas Saturday and
tried to encourage Oklahomans to rebuild strong, safe
neighborhoods.
</P>
<P>
   State and federal officials still are adding up the damage from
the massive tornadoes that hit Oklahoma and Kansas last Monday but
various counts have placed the number of homes destroyed at 3,400
with more than 10,000 buildings damaged.
</P>
<P>
   The death toll stood at 41 Saturday, although four people remain
missing. More than 750 people were injured and many remain
hospitalized.
</P>
<P>
   Hoping to give some measure of comfort and hope to victims of
the devastating storms, Clinton spent several hours listening to
stories of heroic survival and heart-wrenching loss, as Oklahomans
recounted their horrific ordeals for him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have been going to these (disaster) sites for 20 years and
this is the most devastating tornado I have ever seen,'' Clinton
told several hundred residents of the Del Air neighborhood, where
dozens of homes were ripped from their foundations.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have never seen so much complete destruction of homes over
so wide an area,''' he said, following a tour by helicopter of one
tornado path that cleared a swath a half-mile wide in some places
and nearly 60 miles long.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton addressed the Del Air residents amid piles of debris.
Furniture, clothing, bent and twisted bicycles, damaged cars and
splintered timbers were resting where they were dropped by the
winds. As he spoke, some families continued to pick through the
remnants of their lives, trying to clean up what was left. For
some, there was nothing left to sort through.
</P>
<P>
   One middle-aged couple planted an American flag atop what was
left of their home, a pile of rubble, as Clinton approached the
area accompanied by Oklahoma Gov. Frank Keating.
</P>
<P>
   They were miffed at Clinton's visit here, not because they
dislike him, but because it interrupted the cleanup efforts their
community had organized.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just want to get on with it, and rebuild in a new place,''
said Robert Sieger.
</P>
<P>
   But while the Siegers were frustrated by Clinton's visit, dozens
of their neighbors said they were glad to see the president on hand
to witness what they'd been through.
</P>
<P>
   ``How else can our leaders know the kind of pain people have
been through unless they see it for themselves,'' said one young
woman whose home was destroyed.
</P>
<P>
   She cried when Clinton told the crowd, ``Our hearts go out to
those who have lost so much and especially to the families of those
people who lost their lives.''
</P>
<P>
   Preliminary assessments indicate the tornadoes also destroyed
hundreds of small businesses, a high school, an entire shopping
mall and other commercial and public facilities. The storms,
officials said, left behind more than 220 million cubic yards of
debris, most of it unsalvageable. In all, they said the damage is
likely to exceed $250 million just in the Oklahoma City-Del City
area.
</P>
<P>
   Before his arrival here, Clinton announced in his weekly radio
address that the federal government would provide $12 million in
assistance to help create an estimated 3,500 jobs across 11
counties that were hardest hit by the storms. The money will be
used to put people who lost their jobs to the tornadoes back to
work for up to six months helping to rebuild their communities.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said the temporary jobs would be primarily in
construction and relief efforts aimed at making sure people are
supplied with food, shelter and other necessities.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the employment aid, Clinton also said he plans to
ask Congress for an additional $372 million to help replenish the
nation's disaster relief fund, which is administered by the Federal
Emergency Management Agency.
</P>
<P>
   He encouraged the crowd to take advantage of the federal loan
programs being offered by FEMA and build what he called ``safe
closets'' in the new homes they plan to construct. ``The average
cost of these safe closets is only about $2,000,'' he said. ``If
you don't remember anything else I say today, remember this: For
goodness sake, build a safe room in your house when you rebuild.
</P>
<P>
   ``The federal government has a responsibility to provide
individuals with the tools they need to improve their own lives,''
Clinton in his radio address. ``That's what we're doing in Oklahoma
this week. Natural disasters test our faith, but they also show us
that the old-fashioned American values of neighborly care and
concern are still very much alive. And they remind us of the
enduring power of the American people to emerge from calamities
even stronger.''
</P>
<P>
   The American Red Cross was scheduled to open service centers
today in Moore, Guthrie, Dover, Tuttle, Del City and Mulhall.
</P>
<P>
   At least three FEMA service centers, where storm victims can
pursue requests for federal financial assistance, including some
lost income, are expected to open early this week.
</P>
<P>
   While FEMA normally requires storm victims to register within
days for possible financial aid, Clinton on Saturday extended the
deadline by 30 days for victims of Oklahoma's storms.
</P>
<P>
   After touching down at Tinker Air Force Base in Air Force One,
Clinton took to the skies again by helicopter for a tour of several
areas that were reduced to rubble when one tornado cut a path a
half-mile wide and at least 12 miles long.
</P>
<P>
   The tornadoes that ripped through Oklahoma, Kansas and parts of
Texas were part of a swarm that the National Weather Service
reported Monday across the Midwest.
</P>
<P>
   The list of missing increased from three to four between Friday
and Saturday, a spokesman for the Oklahoma chief medical examiner's
office said.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Edward Nelson, 40, was on the missing list on Thursday but
was removed after a friend called the medical examiner's office and
said he'd been seen after Monday's tornado. The information later
was found to be inaccurate and Nelson was placed back on the list
Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Nelson was believed to be in Midwest City when the storm struck.
</P>
<P>
   For thousands of children in tornado-stricken areas, the school
year is essentially over, said Sandy Garrett, Oklahoma
superintendent of public schools. Some schools can't reopen and
others will reopen only briefly, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Garrett said most school records survived the storm. Only
records at a high school destroyed in Moore will be hard to
re-create, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Amazingly, the list of dead from the nighttime storm included no
school-age children.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it had been in the day time, I fear we would have had many
more fatalities, particularly because of the fact that Kelly
Elementary in Moore was totally destroyed,'' Garrett said. ``The
hallway is where we usually tell them to go in tornado evacuations
and that hallway is no longer there.''
</P>
<P>
   Two area schools were destroyed and five damaged beyond repair
for this school year, Garrett said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
