<HEADLINE>
SUNS STUMBLE DOWN STRETCH IN LOSS TO BLAZERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB YOUNG  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PORTLAND, Ore. _ Experience in the postseason was supposed to be
the Suns' ace in the hole during their first-round playoff series
against the youthful Portland Trail Blazers.
</P>
<P>
   But it was the Suns who lost their poise, made mental mistakes
on the defensive end and rushed too many shots during the crucial
final minutes of Game 1 Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   The Trail Blazers exploited those blunders and Portland guard
Isaiah Rider, who may not show up for shootarounds but didn't miss
much else, scored 25 points to lead the Trail blazers past Phoenix,
95-85, at the Rose Garden.
</P>
<P>
   With the victory, the Trail Blazers placed pressure on the Suns
to win Game 2 Monday night in the best-of-five series that will
return to Phoenix for Game 3 and, if necessary, Game 4.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was right there,'' said Suns guard Jason Kidd, wincing at
the thought of an opportunity lost. ``We got kind of quick
offensively. We have to be more patient. We knew we were close, and
I still think this was a good game for us.''
</P>
<P>
   The Suns led, 73-72, with 7:34 to play after Danny Manning's
18-foot shot, and they got there on a day when Rex Chapman was
again struggling to hit shots, center Luc Longley had been eclipsed
by Portland's Arvydas Sabonis and Kidd was playing only like an
All-Star instead of a Most Valuable Player.
</P>
<P>
   They were ahead despite getting pounded in the paint by the
Trail Blazers and seemingly having no way to stop Rider.
</P>
<P>
   But just as they had in three regular-season losses to Portland,
the Suns crumbled in the final minutes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Their defense disrupted us down the stretch,'' Suns Coach
Danny Ainge said. ``We lost our poise offensively, and we had two
breakdowns defensively on two three-point baskets that were mental
lapses. Those were backbreakers at a crucial time of the game.''
</P>
<P>
   With Manning and George McCloud combining to score 29 points off
the bench, the Suns were in position to steal the first game and
put some serious doubt in the minds of a Portland team that had
lost four of its last five regular-season games. And the Trail
Blazers are attempting to exorcise the demons of six consecutive
first-round exits from the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   But after Manning's shot, the Trail Blazers went on a 13-2 run.
The Suns played as if they had rarely been in the postseason,
turning the ball over five times and making just one of six shots
during the decisive stretch.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's more pressure on you when you're the home team,'' said
Portland guard Greg Anthony, whose defense on Kidd was a critical
factor in the outcome. ``If they get a win, then that changes the
whole way the series is going to be played. We were fortunate to do
what we had to do. Nothing has been accomplished yet. We were
supposed to win at home and we did. They probably feel a little bit
better about themselves because they did some good things in this
game as well.''
</P>
<P>
   The Suns agreed with that point.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know they know we can beat them,'' said McCloud, who scored
15 points and had six rebounds. ``Without a doubt, we know we can
beat them. It's up to us to go out and make them play bad Monday.''
</P>
<P>
   The Suns were beaten on the boards, 46-34, but didn't feel as if
they lost that battle. They had seven second-chance points off of
six offensive rebounds and the Trail Blazers had only four off of
seven offensive boards.
</P>
<P>
   Ainge said he'd have taken those numbers before tip-off.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was a focus for us,'' he said. ``They outrebounded us,
but a lot of that was our bad shooting. I believe we can win Game
2, and if we do it will still be a successful trip to Portland.''
</P>
<P>
   The end came abruptly for the Suns as they got impatient when it
mattered most.
</P>
<P>
   Kidd turned the ball over and Jimmy Jackson converted for a
74-73 Portland lead with 6:58 to go. McCloud, who had shot the Suns
into the lead, missed an open three-pointer from the corner and
Rider scored at the other end.
</P>
<P>
   Robinson forced a three-point shot, Gugliotta turned it over,
Kidd finally scored, but McCloud missed another three-pointer and
Rider scored again at the other end. When Kidd forced yet another
three-point shot from 24 feet, and Gugliotta put up another that
missed from long range, the Suns were forced to foul.
</P>
<P>
   And the Trail Blazers made 14 of 16 free-throw attempts in the
final 2:57 to seal the win. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
