<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-08 22:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9662 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-COYOTES-YEAR-REVI     05-08 1442
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-COYOTES-YEAR-REVIEW-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MORE QUESTIONS THAN ANSWERS AS COYOTES HEAD INTO OFFSEASON 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 Analysis 
 By BOB MCMANAMAN  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - They were two minutes and one second away from a
second chance, another life. Just 121 ticks from a second overtime
and maybe, just maybe, the second round of the Stanley Cup
playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   But it all came screeching to a halt for the Coyotes with one
redirected shot in a scoreless game. A fluke, really. Scott Young's
shot somehow clipped the stick of Pierre Turgeon and the deflection
was too quick for Nikolai Khabibulin. Bing, bang, boom and lose.
Game 7 and the first-round series went to the St. Louis Blues.
</P>
<P>
   They came close, but another early playoff exit _ the team's
eighth straight _ once again has spurred questions about the
Coyotes. Where did they go wrong? How much did injuries really play
a factor? Was there enough depth? Enough chemistry? Did they make
the right trades?
</P>
<P>
   Is the head coach safe? Is the general manager safe? Will the
team payroll, which ranks among the bottom third in the NHL, be
further slashed by an owner who already is claiming losses of $5
million annually?
</P>
<P>
   Everyone's asking questions.
</P>
<P>
   ``With the club we have right now,'' forward Rick Tocchet said,
``are we good enough to go to the Stanley Cup Finals? Have we
improved? Do we just need to keep everybody together, add a few
people, a couple free agents? We can do it. Everybody believes it.
Of course, it's easy to say that the next day after you get blown
out.''
</P>
<P>
   Coach Jim Schoenfeld will learn within the next two weeks
whether he will get blown out. The players want him back for a
third season, but it's now out of their control. Had the Coyotes
eliminated St. Louis, however, it probably wouldn't be an issue. It
never has been for Schoenfeld.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only thing that matters to me, and I've said this before,
is while I do it, I give everything I can for them to perform at
their highest level,'' he said before the playoffs began. ``If it
isn't good enough, make the (coaching) change. Or if it's not
deemed good enough, make the change. I have the Stanley Cup dreams
of my players, and that is so much more important than my future in
the organization.''
</P>
<P>
   What about the future of General Manager Bobby Smith? Owner
Richard Burke secretly signed him to a three-year contract
extension earlier in the season, but Smith has said his job should
come under scrutiny if the Coyotes continue to falter in the first
round.
</P>
<P>
   What's more, Smith's name has been linked to persistent rumors
concerning a top front office position with the expansion Minnesota
Wild, which begins play in the 2000-2001 season. But if the Wild
wants Smith, it will want him sooner rather than later to help
shape team strategy and make key hires.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have a contract, and I've said it before, as long as
Richard's here with this team, I'll be here if he wants me,'' said
Smith, who spent nine of his 15 NHL seasons as a player with the
North Stars, who made him the first overall pick in the 1978 draft.
</P>
<P>
   It's conceivable that Schoenfeld ``and'' Smith could be gone. If
Burke and the Coyotes lose the stadium district vote May 18, so
could a star player or two in order to pare the budget.
</P>
<P>
   But one of them won't be star center Jeremy Roenick, who made a
dramatic return in Game 7 of the playoffs despite a surgically
repaired broken jaw and a fractured thumb that wasn't completely
healed. According to team sources, Roenick, 29, has been assured he
won't be traded during the off-season.
</P>
<P>
   The popular Roenick has put a face on Burke's team, has given it
an image to howl about. Dealing him away in a cost-cutting move
could be even more desperate than cutting off one's nose to spite
his face.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very confident I'll finish my career in Phoenix,'' said
Roenick, the team's leading scorer this past season, who has two
years remaining on a five-year, $20 million contract.
</P>
<P>
   Not having JR for the first six games of the Blues series,
thanks to Derian Hatcher of the Dallas Stars, was critical. So was
the loss of hard-working Finnish forward Juha Ylonen, who suffered
a fractured foot at the hands of an Al MacInnis slap shot in Game
1. Additionally, the Coyotes were without left wings Greg Adams and
Mike Sullivan for much of the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we have a healthy team to start the playoffs,'' Roenick
said, ``we're playing Dallas right now in the second round. No
question.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe. But the Coyotes have went to the injury card all three
years now since relocating from Winnipeg. In 1997, they blamed
losing Roenick to a knee in jury in Game 6 for getting eliminated
in seven games by Anaheim. In 1998, it was groin pulls to
Khabibulin and defenseman Teppo Numminen that hurt their chances in
a six-game series with Detroit. And now this.
</P>
<P>
   But don't forget, the Coyotes had a 3-1 series lead against
Blues. Without Roenick. Without Ylonen. And for the most part,
without Adams.
</P>
<P>
   Some detractors might say they also were without Robert Reichel,
the skillful center from the Czech Republic who virtually
disappeared in the postseason. He had three assists but only one
goal, and he looked nothing like he did the first two weeks after
Smith acquired him from the New York Islanders just before the
trading deadline for Brad Isbister and a swap of draft picks.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the problem was Reichel's refusal to carry the puck
through neutral ice and create. Too often, he simply stopped at the
blue line and dumped the puck in and let others chase after it.
Schoenfeld tried having Reichel operate behind the net, but that
didn't solve the problem.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, Reichel's linemates struggled just as badly. Keith
Tkachuk had one goal. Tocchet had none. And now Reichel, who
becomes a restricted Group II free agent on July 1, will demand to
have his $1.7 million salary almost doubled or he will return to
the Czech Republic permanently.
</P>
<P>
   If that happens, the team would be wise to go after a
second-line center on the free agent market such as Vincent
Damphousse, whom they liked almost every bit as much as Reichel.
Damphousse, who wound up with the San Jose Sharks, will go into the
corners to bang for a puck.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the Coyotes already had a pretty good No. 2 center
behind Roenick in veteran Cliff Ronning, who had seven points in
the team's first seven games. But then he was dealt to Nashville
for future considerations as a way to dump some salary and give the
ice time to rookie Daniel Briere. It didn't work. Though incredibly
gifted, Briere wasn't ready. From an offensive standpoint, neither
was Ylonen.
</P>
<P>
   But that problem was cloaked by the Coyotes' 17-5-3 record in
the 25 games after the Ronning trade on Halloween. The first line
dominated during the stretch, Khabibulin was on fire, and the
defense was holding opponents to two goals or less almost every
game.
</P>
<P>
   The blue liners, though, eventually broke down. A shoulder
injury to newcomer Jyrki Lumme affected the Finnish defenseman for
the entire second half of the season. It was so bad that he could
barely fire a shot from the point. But he kept playing anyway
because he could weave through traffic and pass.
</P>
<P>
   Numminen, the Iron Finn who has appeared in 297 consecutive
regular season games, the second-longest active streak in the NHL,
also could have used rest late in the year. He had tired legs as
the playoffs wore on, and many, including a handful of players,
thought he _ or Schoenfeld _ should have ended the streak for the
good of the team.
</P>
<P>
   And where was Oleg Tverdovsky? Two seasons removed from an
All-Star appearance, when he finished fourth among NHL defensemen
with 55 points, the 22-year-old Russian took a major slide. The
fifth-year pro never got it going and was ridiculed throughout much
of the season. It got so bad that Schoenfeld benched him for Game 7
against the Blues.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's got to be a better player,'' Tocchet said. ``His heart is
there, he's just got to find his focus.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith said he intends to re-sign the restricted free agent, but
many NHL insiders expect Tverdovsky to be dealt this summer.
Depending on where the Coyotes are next March, Tocchet could be
history as well. The Coyotes hold a one-year option on him for next
season, but he easily could be trading deadline fodder because
Smith likely won't sign the 35-year-old to an extension.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like our team,'' Tkachuk said, ``and I want everybody back.
. . . I feel confident this team is going to make a big jump next
year. We're getting better and better, and we've built a solid
base.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-08-99 2207EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
