<DOCNO> NYT19990508.0236 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-08 22:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9665 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STADIUMS-SUITES-AZR &LR;      05-08 2204
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STADIUMS-SUITES-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUITES NO LONGER A LUXURY FOR STADIUM BUILDERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By LES POLK  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - Back in the late 1980s, luxury suites became all the
rage in professional sports as the National Basketball Association
kicked off a building boom in new sports facilities across America.
</P>
<P>
   Now, a suite is just a suite. It's no longer a luxury. You can't
put up a major new sports building anymore without them.
</P>
<P>
   Those luxury suites and premium club seats that came on the
scene as splendid new hangouts for corporate America and fans with
cash to burn gave the first wave of smart team owners the momentum
to generate the money to build new facilities and ratchet up
revenues.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, for one season, 1992-93, the Phoenix Suns led the
National Basketball Assocation in revenue, playing at America West
Arena in just the 19th-largest market and with the eighth-highest
ticket prices.
</P>
<P>
   Now suites, club seats and the occasional personal seat licenses
that go with them are an absolute necessity for survival, a
permanent part of the sports scene.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's important because the other teams have these streams of
revenue available to sign free agents and stay competitive,'' said
Michael Bidwill, vice president and general counsel of the
Cardinals.
</P>
<P>
   From high schools to universities to professional sports, suites
and premium seats have become the sweet road to financial success
for pro teams and amateur athletics programs.
</P>
<P>
   And if you think the Cardinals and Coyotes should be content
with what's available to them at Sun Devil Stadium and America West
Arena, respectively, think again. It's simple: The pot is bigger if
you play in your own building, and the revenue is all yours.
</P>
<P>
   That means better players, better revenue, and if the team is
successful, a better bottom line.
</P>
<P>
   From Ravenna (Ohio) High School's ongoing campaign to sell seat
licenses for construction of a new football stadium to more than
two dozen major universities with luxury suites to every big-league
sports facility being built, suites and their sidekicks are the
cash cow that drives the buildings and helps owners and athletic
departments keep up with their competitors.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the only vehicle given today's NFL economic structure
that separates the haves from the have-nots,'' said Rick Horrow,
facility development consultant for the NFL and a visiting expert
on sports law at Harvard University who has worked closely with the
Cardinals on the stadium component of Rio Salado Crossing. ``Suites
are an absolutely critical component of the modern-day sports
facility,''
</P>
<P>
   NFL teams share a lucrative TV pot to the tune of $70 million
for each team this season, but they don't have to share the revenue
from suites, club seats, signage, stadium naming rights, parking
and other cash sources.
</P>
<P>
   With that much TV revenue _ double the amount just two years ago
_ suites may be less important to the NFL than to other sports,
particularly the NHL, where teams get only $4 million to $5 million
a year in TV revenue. But they're still a key component.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Dorsey, executive director of the Cincinnati-based
Association of Luxury Suites Directors, said suites have become the
driving force for arenas and stadiums in the '90s.
</P>
<P>
   The organization has grown to 700 members representing
facilities in North America, Australia and England.
</P>
<P>
   ``Suites are what get the buildings built,'' he said. ``Banks
will not accept if's, then's and possibilities based on projected
attendance. Suites represent guaranteed leases and revenue. They're
a funding tool to plan debt service.''
</P>
<P>
   Suite revenue also provides teams with more money to sign
players.
</P>
<P>
   The Dallas Cowboys, for example, have 378 suites.
</P>
<P>
   ``That gives them a huge advantage,'' Dorsey said. ``It's one of
the reasons they can sign a lot of players.''
</P>
<P>
   Another moneymaker is personal seat licenses, where you pay a
sum for the right to purchase tickets to games for your seats.
</P>
<P>
   At the Toronto Maple Leafs' new Air Canada Centre, 1,500 PSLs
were sold for $15,000 each _ in addition to the building's 150
suites.
</P>
<P>
   The Coyotes and Cardinals have no plans for selling seat
licenses should they get new facilities built.
</P>
<P>
   For the Coyotes' president, Shawn Hunter, the new building
itself _ holding about 18,000 unobstructed-view seats for hockey,
20,000 seats for other events such as concerts, 1,500 to 2,000 club
seats and 65 to 70 suites _ would provide enough revenue
opportunities to turn the franchise around.
</P>
<P>
   ``Teams with new venues and revenue streams have been able to go
out and spend new money on players, both for the cream of the crop
and to add depth,'' Hunter said.
</P>
<P>
   Hunter said the Coyotes' total player salaries ranked 19th of 27
teams in the NHL, and that their other expenses _ front office,
marketing, etc. _ ranked 24th.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel like we're running a good, tight ship,'' Hunter said.
``But we underachieve at the bottom line.''
</P>
<P>
   He said the Coyotes were losing $6 million to $10 million a year
playing at America West Arena.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to run a viable business,'' Hunter said. ``This is a
very exciting business, but it is a business. Staying at America
West is a formula for disaster for us.''
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the National Football League, the NHL has no cap on
salaries.
</P>
<P>
   But the Coyotes said they'd reached a cap on revenue at America
West Arena.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's as good as it gets right now,'' Hunter said.
</P>
<P>
   Because of its lease, the hockey club is only allowed to use
about 5 to 6 percent of the total signage in the building and has
access to 72 of 84 suites, although that might grow next year,
Hunter said.
</P>
<P>
   They sell 58 to 60 suites for the season at $45,000, and the
rest go for individual games or partial-season tickets. And Hunter
said the team got a ``competitive share of concessions.''
</P>
<P>
   The difference at the new building _ for which the Coyotes would
pay 100 percent of the estimated $140 million to $150 million in
construction costs _ is controlling all revenues (receipts,
marketing, suites, concessions).
</P>
<P>
   ``All the things we really don't have access to now,'' Hunter
said.
</P>
<P>
   Hockey and baseball have similar financial pressures because
neither has a player salary cap.
</P>
<P>
   ``You'll never see a building without (suites) again,'' said
Jerry Colangelo, Diamondbacks managing general partner and Suns
president. ``That's just a fact of life.
</P>
<P>
   ``In baseball, you need to generate all you can out of the
building.'' Bank One Ballpark has 69 suites in eight different
styles, ranging in price from $95,000 to $125,000 a year, at lease
options of seven or 10 years. For certain suites, a half-season
package is available. There also are six party suites, the swimming
pool and four kinds of premium seating.
</P>
<P>
   More than 90 percent of the suites are leased for the season
this year, and the rest are sold on a per-game basis.
</P>
<P>
   At America West Arena, the Suns' 88 suites are sold out for
five- or eight-year leases, priced at $100,000 or $110,000. There
also are six party suites available on a game-by-game basis.
</P>
<P>
   Another important revenue producer is concessions, especially at
Bank One Ballpark, where the Diamondbacks retain all
baseball-related revenue.
</P>
<P>
   To help generate concession revenue, the Diamondbacks had $30
million in upgrades done to the kitchens and concession facilities.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the largest investment ever made in a ballpark for
kitchens and concessions,'' Colangelo said.
</P>
<P>
   Why would a ballpark kitchen be important?
</P>
<P>
   Dorsey, the suites' organization director, said that although
people sitting in regular seats spend an estimated $6 to $8 on
concessions at a game, people in suites, where the food is fancier
and more expensive, spend about $30 each.
</P>
<P>
   And that's just one piece of the revenue pie.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is extreme pressure on teams and municipalities on these
building that you build into them all of these opportunities for
revenue streams,'' Colangelo said.
</P>
<P>
   Horrow, the NFL consultant assisting the Cardinals, said that if
Rio Salado were approved, the Cardinals would face ``extreme
pressure'' to sell their suites and club seats because of the
revenue demands.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Cardinals have a lion's share of the risk,'' he said. ``If
the Cards' commitments don't materialize, the project ceases. Their
income sources are based on the ability to market.''
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinals would be marketing 70 to 75 suites and 7,500 club
seats in a new stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Bidwill and Hunter both said that with the possibility of four
major league sports venues in the Valley, marketing and competitive
teams would become even more important.
</P>
<P>
   At Sun Devil Stadium, the Cardinals' original 10-year license
agreement for suites expired this year and was reworked.
</P>
<P>
   The original deal called for 60 skyboxes to be built and sold by
the Cardinals, and that for the $40,000 purchase price, holders
would have the suites for Cardinals and Arizona State University
games, plus the Fiesta Bowl
</P>
<P>
   Under the new deal, the license is split, and both ASU and the
Cardinals can sell the suites for their own games.
</P>
<P>
   The suites are being remodeled and renovated this season. There
will be 54 suites this season and two larger hospitality suites
built out of the space occupied by six regular suites.
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinals last year sold out their suites at $45,000 to
$65,000 a year, and sold out 5,000 club seats at $75 to $200 a
seat.
</P>
<P>
   ASU has an opportunity to increase its revenue by about $850,000
to $1 million this season because of the suite deal, assistant
athletic director Tom Collins said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody is trying to find new revenue streams,'' Collins
said.
</P>
<P>
   ASU has sold about 30 of the suites so far for prices ranging
from $19,000 to $23,000.
</P>
<P>
   Sun Devil fans can purchse the rights to a loge seat for a gift
premium of $350 to $1,000.
</P>
<P>
   With more, higher-priced suites in a modern stadium, and their
own deals on all the other revenue producers, the Cardinals would
have an opportunity to boost their revenue significantly.
</P>
<P>
   But they also will have at least a $75 million upfront
contribution to Rio Salado to pay off, and salaries that are
growing higher.
</P>
<P>
   The team has forged ahead with efforts to become more
competitive by shelling out high salaries for stars such as
quarterback Jake Plummer - not knowing whether they will have a new
facility generating more revenue or not.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Cardinals are banking on the future without the business
certainty that other teams have,'' Horrow said. ``Usually a team
will not enter into long-term commitments without a stadium. That's
a very important perspective for fans to understand.''
</P>
<P>
   The Milwaukee Brewers, for example, have signed several key
players to long-term deals, banking on their new ballpark, Miller
Park, set to open next season, to help provide the additional
revenue needed to lift one of baseball's have-nots into the a
competitive situation.
</P>
<P>
   The park will have 70 suites available for $75,000 to $100,000.
</P>
<P>
   The Minnesota Twins, another have-not, have a proposed new
stadium with 52 suites, three party suites and 4,300 club seats. If
it's not built, the Twins are likely to leave for a sweeter venue
elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   Even successful teams with their own venues are looking for
suite deals. The St. Louis Cardinals have proposed a new $240
million baseball stadium just south of historic Busch Stadium. Why?
</P>
<P>
   Because other than raising ticket prices, revenue sources at
Busch are limited. The new park would expand concession stands,
make luxury boxes more luxurious, and add ``premium seating''
packages.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, stadiums and arenas across the country are adding
suites at a feverish pace:
</P>
<P>
   In the NFL, the Washington Redskins' new home, Jack Kent Cooke
Stadium, has 199 luxury suites, 1,506 loge seats and 14,958 club
seats.
</P>
<P>
   The Charlotte Hornets want to move from their 24,000 seat
Charlotte Coliseum built in 1988 to a new building because the
Coliseum doesn't have enough suites.
</P>
<P>
   Boston's FleetCenter, which opened in 1995, has 104 luxury boxes
that go for $158,000 to $258,000 a year.
</P>
<P>
   The NBA Atlanta Hawks and expansion NHL Thrashers have already
sold out the 90 suites at Philips Arena, which opens in the fall,
at $145,000 to $225,000, and close to half the 1,800 club seats,
priced at $8,000 to $9,500.
</P>
<P>
   At the college level, Clemson University's football stadium has
100 suites that lease for $22,000 each. The University of Iowa has
17 suites which leased for 10 years at $120,000 to $180,000 a year.
The University of Wisconsin's $76.4 million Kohl Center basketball
arena has 36 luxury suites which were leased at $35,000 per season,
and Ohio State University's Schottenstein Center has 46 suites
which lease from $45,000 to $65,000.
</P>
<P>
   Whether it's a four-sport major league city such as Phoenix or a
college town, the demand for suites appears to be unprecedented.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no indication that any city has ever hit a saturation
point,'' Dorsey said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's amazing, but there are usually sellouts at different
stadiums for different sports, especially with the economy as it
is.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
