<SLUG> BC-BKN-BLAZERS-GAME-1-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RIDER REALLY SHOWS UP FOR THIS GAME 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By NORM FRAUENHEIM  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PORTLAND, Ore. _ On the Trail Blazers roster, he's Isaiah. His
teammates call him J.R. There are a lot of names for Rider. But
only one fits.
</P>
<P>
   Call him wild.
</P>
<P>
   Wild Rider.
</P>
<P>
   He is a volatile mix of self-destructive elements and talent.
Handle with care.
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday, the Suns couldn't handle him at all. Before the
Blazers' 95-85 victory in a playoff opener, an anxious Portland fan
behind the Blazers bench held up a sign that included Rider's face
and a bomb.
</P>
<P>
   Tick-tick-tick.
</P>
<P>
   Neither the fan nor Riders' teammates knew whether to duck or
cheer. This isn't exactly a smart bomb. But, on this afternoon,
there was no implosion. Rider exploded for 25 points. He led the
Blazers to a key playoff win just a few days after it looked as if
he were leading them into a self-designed ambush.
</P>
<P>
   After scoring almost at will against Rex Chapman, George McCloud
and anybody else in a Phoenix uniform, Rider offered no apologies
for last week's misadventures. He showed up late for practices. He
was benched. He left the bench during a game.
</P>
<P>
   But he did talk. He talked the way he scored _ constantly.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't feel like an apology was really necessary,'' said
Rider, who had 16 of his points in the second half.
</P>
<P>
   But an explanation was.
</P>
<P>
   Rider said he met a few days ago with Blazers General Manager
Bob Whitsitt, Coach Mike Dunleavy and his teammates.
</P>
<P>
   ``In my conversation with Whitsitt, he told me `We need you to
win,' '' said Rider, who began to exploit a mismatch with Chapman
in the game's opening moments. ``He said: `If you don't do what we
need you to do, there will be consequences. So, what are you going
to do?'
</P>
<P>
   ``Basically, today was my answer.''
</P>
<P>
   Then, Rider said he spoke to his teammates, who were hearing
speculation that their late-season skid was rooted in a locker room
that had begun to boil over with angry impatience at his
unpredictability.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a good, healthy talk,'' said Rider, who has been in and
out of trouble and, a couple of years ago, offended the city of
Portland with comments that painted the entire community as racist.
``It was nothing too serious.
</P>
<P>
   ``If anyone was distracted, I'm sorry for that. But if we're
friends, I told them to pick me up, watch my back, let me play my
game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I get down on myself sometimes. I said: `You know, if I miss
three shots in a row, I get down.' I told `em, `When I do, tap me
on the shoulder. Let me know. Tell me to just keep playing.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Rider said his playing problems were not the result of
distractions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those are your distractions, not mine,'' he said. ``Look, I
don't read the newspapers. I don't watch channel
whatever-whatever-whatever.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sensitive. I don't want all that stuff getting into my
head. If things are going on around me, I can feel the vibes. But I
just want to focus on playing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Truth is, I haven't been playing well since March 11, the day
before my birthday. It's just good to get into a rhythm. It's
gut-check time. Time for me to step up.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was trying to be assertive.''
</P>
<P>
   Rider boldly predicted that he would be that and more a few days
ago when he flatly said the Suns could not stop the Blazers from
scoring. Above all, they couldn't stop him.
</P>
<P>
   Exploitation of the Rider-Chapman mismatch was a key to
Portland's game plan.
</P>
<P>
   ``Chap is a small cat,'' Rasheed Wallace said. `J.R. is a true
big guard. It's definitely a mismatch.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can see it just by looking at it. Once J.R. gets going, it
time to just feed him. Treat him like a pig.''
</P>
<P>
   And just hope the other guy gets slaughtered. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-08-99 2208EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
