<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-08 22:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9669 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-SUNS-GAME-1-AZR &LR;      05-08 0642
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-SUNS-GAME-1-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AINGE FACES TOUGH DECISIONS ON CHAPMAN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB YOUNG  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PORTLAND, Ore. _ Suns Coach Danny Ainge admits he faces some
tough choices with the Suns down 0-1 in their best-of-five
first-round series with Portland.
</P>
<P>
   Does he stick with guard Rex Chapman, whose regular-season
shooting woes carried into a Game 1 loss as he hit three of 12
shots? Portland guard Isaiah Rider is a tough defensive matchup for
the smaller Chapman, and he scored 25 points to lead the Blazers to
victory.
</P>
<P>
   Or does Ainge go to George McCloud or Chris Morris, who at
6-foot-8 are big enough to guard Rider when he tries to post-up
low? Both are good shooters, but a good portion of the Suns'
offense is designed for Chapman coming off screens.
</P>
<P>
   Or does Ainge just try to adjust defensively, send a second
defender more quickly to help Chapman and hope that doesn't create
opportunities for the rest of the Blazers?
</P>
<P>
   ``George is a better defender against Rider,'' Ainge said. ``If
Rex doesn't make enough shots to warrant his presence on the court,
that's the dilemma we have.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have a lot of confidence in Rex, and we knew that was going
to be a tough (defensive) matchup for us. I will say this: It
wasn't just Rex not defending (Rider). Our plan was for Rex to
force him to certain places on the floor. Our help was late getting
there, or nonexistent.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There were times when Rex did his job and other guys didn't do
theirs.''
</P>
<P>
   The Suns will live with the defensive shortcomings if Chapman
starts hitting shots, and when he confidently knocked in a
17-footer on his first attempt, they figured he was off and
running.
</P>
<P>
   ``No,'' Chapman said flatly. ``I don't think making the first
one means much. I felt good. There aren't any excuses, I just need
to make open shots. I had a few that bobbled in and out. It happens
sometime.''
</P>
<P>
   It happened too often for Ainge, who went with McCloud at the
start of the fourth quarter and stuck with him until the final
minutes when the Suns trailed and he put all his three-point
shooters on the floor.
</P>
<P>
   McCloud hit a couple of big three-point shots in a
fourth-quarter run that gave the Suns the lead, but he missed two
down the stretch as Portland mounted a 13-2 run and took control.
</P>
<P>
   Controlling Rider isn't easy. Just ask Portland Coach Mike
Dunleavy. But the Suns have to adjust for Game 2.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just have to guard his (butt),'' McCloud said. ``There's
not much you can do when the guy gets it going. He gets confidence,
and then they're going to stay with him and keep going to him.''
</P>
<P>
   Ainge said the Suns needed to ``mix it up'' defensively against
Rider to keep him from getting comfortable.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's definitely a tough matchup for us, and he made us pay,''
Ainge said. ``When he's taking those fade-aways that start at eight
feet and end up at 20, there isn't anything you can do about that.
He was making those on George, too. But we can do a better job on
(him.)''
</P>
<P>
   A quick double-team is a possibility, or at least that's what
Rider said he was anticipating when he got the ball in the low
post.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like the post,'' he said. ``Obviously, that's my bread and
butter. Just like Jason Kidd or Gary Payton when they get the
little point guards on them, they eat them up. When I get
(shooting) guards on me that weight 20 pounds less, I can outpower
them, period. They're going to come on the pass now and double-team
me right away.''
</P>
<P>
   And Ainge will have to make a quick decision on whether Chapman
can carry the load in the Phoenix backcourt against Rider.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike during the regular season when he could wait for Chapman
to emerge from his shooting slump, there is immediacy in the
playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Absolutely,'' Ainge said. ``We can't wait as long.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
