<HEADLINE>
ROBINSON BEAT DEMONS, NOT THE BLAZERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By NORM FRAUENHEIM  
 and BOB YOUNG  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PORTLAND - Before tipoff, Suns forward Clifford Robinson
dismissed questions about his history for playoff futility.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't have any demons to exorcise,'' said Robinson, whose
playoff reputation has its roots in his eight years with the Trail
Blazers.
</P>
<P>
   No demons, perhaps, but the questions remain.
</P>
<P>
   Robinson continued to struggle Saturday in the Suns' 95-85 loss
to the Blazers in a playoff opener. He had 9 points on 4-for-9
shooting and four rebounds before he fouled out with 34.2 seconds
left.
</P>
<P>
   ``J.R. (Rider) hit a lot of good shots, and they got into a
comfortable groove in their offense,'' said Robinson, who also drew
the primary defensive assignment on Rasheed Wallace. ``We have to
do a better job of not letting those offensive spurts happen.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have another game Monday. That give us a chance to make
some adjustments.'' &QL; 
Old look
</P>
<P>
   It looked as if Rex Chapman put an end to goggle-gate by
smashing the offending specs at a Suns practice the other day.
</P>
<P>
   But appearances aren't always what they seem.
</P>
<P>
   Chapman didn't wear goggles in Saturday's playoff opener at
Portland.
</P>
<P>
   But that's not because he eliminated them with a well-placed
heel. The Suns, in fact, packed three spares, just in case Chapman
relented and decided he would wear a pair as protection against
further injury of a fractured eye socket.
</P>
<P>
   But don't bet on it. Given Chapman's antipathy toward the
eyewear, there's a better chance he would show up at tipoff with a
snorkel. Besides, you don't need a pair of goggles to see he can't
stop Isaiah Rider. &QL; 
How about some pingpong?
</P>
<P>
   Might as well.
</P>
<P>
   Not only couldn't the Suns beat Portland, they couldn't win a
coin flip either.
</P>
<P>
   They lost a flip Friday with Boston for the number of chances _
represented by pingpong balls _ in the upcoming lottery for draft
picks.
</P>
<P>
   The Suns own Dallas' first-round pick, which they acquired in a
draft deal last summer. Boston and Dallas finished with the same
record.
</P>
<P>
   By winning the flip, Boston will get the seventh-highest number
of balls in the hopper. The Suns will get the highest number.
</P>
<P>
   Translation: The Suns will have no worse than the No. 11 pick in
the next draft. With a lot of luck, they could have the No. 1.
</P>
<P>
   They also will get the No. 16 pick. They had the same record as
New York and Sacramento, whose first-round pick belongs to Atlanta.
In another series of coin flips, New York got the 15th pick and
Atlanta got the 17th with the Suns landing between the two. &QL; 
Jam session
</P>
<P>
   With 5:05 left in the first half, Suns forward Tom Gugliotta
suffered a dislocation of the ring finger on his right hand in a
collision with Kelvin Cato.
</P>
<P>
   Suns trainer Joe Proski got the call to do some emergency work.
</P>
<P>
   ``Joe was looking at it,'' Gugliotta said. ``I said: `Joe, just
pull it. It hurts.' ''
</P>
<P>
   The injury wasn't serious.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a little swollen, but I've done it before,'' he said.
``My golf game might struggle.'' &QL; 
Briefly
</P>
<P>
   The Blazers announced a crowd Saturday of 20,040, their 15th
sellout of the year. But there were plenty of empty seats. It is
NBA policy not to announce the no-show count.
</P>
<P>
   With Saturday's victory, the Blazers lead the Suns in their
overall playoff history, 12-11.
</P>
<P>
   The Blazers have been eliminated in the playoff's first round
six straight times. Saturday's win was a good sign. They have won
12 of the 13 series in which they've won the opener. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
