<SLUG> BC-BKN-NOTEBOOK-YOUNG-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COLANGELO: IT'S TIME TO CLEAN UP GAME 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB YOUNG  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Suns President  &UR; Jerry Colangelo has seen enough ugly basketball,
and now that the NBA is through its lockout-marred season, he said
it was time to address the game itself.
</P>
<P>
   Colangelo joined the Suns in Portland on Saturday after
attending an NBA owners meeting and said Commissioner  &UR; David Stern
and Director of Operations  &UR; Rod Thorn will put together a committee
to address the scoring drought that has seen scoring slowly dry up
over the past 10 seasons.
</P>
<P>
   The league scoring average dropped from 95.6 points a game last
season to just over 91 points a game this season. Shooting
percentages also were down, with no team shooting 47 percent. It's
a downward scoring spiral that has continued through the 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   In contrast with the Rules and Competition committee, made up of
29 members, Colangelo said a six- to eight-person committee _ of
which he'll be a member _ will try to find ways to return the flow
and tempo to a professional game that has become nothing but a
post-up contest.
</P>
<P>
   ``The reality is the trending for 10 years is toward lower
scoring and shooting percentages,'' Colangelo said. ``We have to
take a look at the basic ingredients of the game itself. I'm not
going to go into specifics, but the changes will fall into certain
categories.
</P>
<P>
   ``One is the clock, and not necessarily the 24-second clock.
Defense is another area. Some are proponents of going to any kind
of defense. Another is widening the lane.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got to talk about where we are and how we got here. The
mentality of coaching now is a half-court game and post-up game.
That dictates how many shots are taken, and that even goes down to
the colleges.
</P>
<P>
   ``Somehow, someway, we have gone away from the athleticism. We
need to clean up the game.''
</P>
<P>
   Colangelo said players and coaches will have input, but the
committee wants changes implemented by next season.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the time to do it,'' he said. ``You're going to see a
different game next year, and that's exciting.''
</P>
<P>
   There has been resistance in the past to dramatic changes, in
part because the Rules and Competition committee has become so
large _ 29 members.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was unwieldy,'' Colangelo said. ``There are too many
opinions, too many self-serving interests. Some have coaches who
want to coach a certain style, some have big guys and they want
advantages.
</P>
<P>
   ``The overriding thing is we have a great game. But we have to
be guardians of the game. We have to be watching over the game. It
has to be fixed. You can feel it.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a trend over the last 10 years, and the statistics
bear it out. We have to adjust. In my opinion, we'll have a
stronger game if we adapt.
</P>
<P>
   ``The lockout magnified some of it, but the fact is if you look
at the trends, it tracks it about to a `T.' We don't have
continuity in the game. We don't have the flow.
</P>
<P>
   ``The committee will be working on this big time. If we change
the rules, players will adjust and officials will adjust.
</P>
<P>
   ``We even looked at what some of our players have been saying.
You read their comments, and they talk about how it was an ugly
game or a lousy game. You don't want your players saying things
like that. They've got to feel good about the game. It's a great
game, but it's time to give it a little shot.'' &QL; 
He was right &QL; 
Miami's  &UR; Pat Riley contended before the playoffs that anybody in
the Eastern Conference field could lose a first-round series.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the East, it's very equal, a lot of parity from teams 1
through 8. I think anybody can beat anybody if you're not on top of
your game,'' he said. ``Indiana is the one team I think that has
everything. Experience. Depth. Talent. All of that. They've
struggled at times, but they have the package. I think we're close
to that.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe not. The Knicks spanked Miami in Game 1 of their series in
Miami.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the West, the changing of the guard is maybe a year away,''
Riley said. ``Maybe next year, San Antonio could be the team for a
long period of time, as long as  &UR; (David) Robinson and  &UR; (Tim) Duncan
stay together.''
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Confident &QL; 
Atlanta's  &UR; Steve Smith is apparently convinced the Hawks are going
to make noise in the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't care who we play or where we play,'' he said. ``Bring
'em on, and we'll go to work.''
</P>
<P>
   Of himself, Smith added, ``I'm pretty much there (as the best 2
guard in the league). I do everything. And I don't need to score to
help my team. There are some good players out there, but I just
might be the best.''
</P>
<P>
   Head start &QL; 
Boston Coach  &UR; Rick Pitino isn't wasting any time, even if the
Celtics are out of the playoffs. He held a two-day minicamp this
week.
</P>
<P>
   Pitino might want to include a current events segment. Before
the team's last game, rookie  &UR; Paul Pierce found a cap in front of
his locker with  &UR; ``Bill Bradley'' inscribed on the front.
</P>
<P>
   Asked by a reporter if he'd vote for the former Knick for
president, Pierce replied, ``I don't even know who he is.''
</P>
<P>
   Teammate  &UR; Ron Mercer said: ``He's a rookie. He isn't ready for
the tough questions.'' &QL; 
Eye of the beholder &QL; 
In Denver, the Nuggets held a ceremony in honor of the final game
played at McNichols Sports Arena. The club is ready to move into
the new Pepsi Center next season, and Denver's  &UR; Antonio McDyess
wasn't exactly nostalgic.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's great memories for some people,'' McDyess said. ``For
some people, it ain't.'' &QL; 
Includes information from other media sources. Bob Young can be
reached at (602) 444-8271 or at bob.young(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
