<SLUG> BC-MONTINI-COL-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GREETING CARD FROM AN ORPHAN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By E.J. MONTINI  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   When I was a boy my mother used to tell me that, someday, if God
and the Blessed Virgin Mary paid attention to her prayers, my
brother and I would become orphans.
</P>
<P>
   It would take a little luck, she believed, as heaven was a busy
place and very far from our house at 121 Third Ave. in a western
Pennsylvania steel town.
</P>
<P>
   But, that was her wish.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the way it should be,'' she said, always adding, ``God
willing.''
</P>
<P>
   I'm not sure how the subject came up. Or exactly why.
</P>
<P>
   But I know in the weeks before Mother's Day, the nuns at St.
Titus Grade School, where I was a student, made certain we included
in our daily invocations a prayer for the world's orphans.
</P>
<P>
   We'd spent a portion of each afternoon fashioning homemade
Mother's Day cards out of construction paper, glitter and glue,
while the Sisters of St. Joseph reminded us how fortunate we were
to have someone to present with such a gift.
</P>
<P>
   I must have told my mother about the prayers (though not the
cards, which we all presumed would come as a complete surprise,
despite coming home for days with glue on our fingers and glitter
on our shoes.) &QL; 
PAIN OF DYING CHILDREN
</P>
<P>
   This was about the same time my mother and her sister became
orphans.
</P>
<P>
   Their elderly parents died within six months of each other, one
from a heart condition, one from a broken heart.
</P>
<P>
   My grandparents came to the United States as young people,
leaving behind everything and everyone they knew in order to
scratch out a living in the coal mining and steel producing towns
of the East Coast.
</P>
<P>
   They'd hoped for a big family, but each time a boy was born to
them, he turned blue and died within a day. They had no money for
doctors who might explain to them the complexities of genetics, and
no treatment in those days to fix it.
</P>
<P>
   So, only their two daughters survived.
</P>
<P>
   It was not the way it was supposed to be, my grandmother told
her girls.
</P>
<P>
   A parent should never outlive a child. It's too difficult. Too
painful. It's the parents who should go first, and only after their
children have become adults with children of their own.
</P>
<P>
   My mother believed this with all her heart. She believed we must
pray long and hard for it to happen, heaven being so far away. And
she believed as well that we needed good fortune.
</P>
<P>
   It worked. &QL; 
KIDS GET LUCKY
</P>
<P>
   About a month and a half ago, my brother and I got lucky.
</P>
<P>
   We became orphans.
</P>
<P>
   Our father died quietly in a hospital bed, staring at the
ceiling, at something beyond the ceiling, at my mother, who had
passed away about a year earlier.
</P>
<P>
   By then she'd had plenty of time and plenty of opportunity to
cash in all the prayers she'd so carefully deposited, heaven no
longer being far away for her.
</P>
<P>
   She'd gotten her wish.
</P>
<P>
   Her children were grown, with children of their own. Everything
happened in the order she hoped it would, which is good and the way
it should be except it's Mother's Day and I've got nowhere to send
a greeting card.
</P>
<P>
   And no gift to buy.
</P>
<P>
   And no phone call to make.
</P>
<P>
   When you're a child praying for the orphans of the world you
sympathize for them, and relate to them, as children.
</P>
<P>
   What you can't know at the time is that it doesn't change when
you become an orphan at 44. Or any other age.
</P>
<P>
   We spent last Mother's Day trying to keep my father occupied,
not realizing it worked as well on us as it did on him. My mother
knew, though.
</P>
<P>
   When you hope and pray for your children someday to be orphans _
and we all should _ you've got to leave behind a memory to help
them through difficult days.
</P>
<P>
   A few years back on Mother's Day, I couldn't reach my parents'
house by phone because the lines were jammed. My mother was in bed
before I finally got through.
</P>
<P>
   I told her I'd been trying to call all day when she stopped me
and laughed and said, ``Hey, I know. I know.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
