<HEADLINE>
ANGRY PROTESTS IN SEVERAL CHINESE CITIES 
</HEADLINE>
   (SUBS to update and reorganize.) 
 (lh) 
 By ELISABETH ROSENTHAL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIJING _ Large, angry protests erupted around U.S. government
offices in several cities on Saturday as Chinese learned that NATO
bombs had hit their embassy in Belgrade, killing at least three
people sleeping inside.
</P>
<P>
   In Beijing, thousands of well-organized university students,
cheered on by other Beijing residents, held tense noisy protests on
the streets surrounding the U.S. Embassy, as police looked on. But
the initially peaceful march quickly turned violent, as small
groups of students and residents threw rocks through embassy
windows, pummeled cars belonging to embassy employees and burned
American flags.
</P>
<P>
   It was the by far the largest anti-American demonstration in
China since well before President Nixon's historic visit to China
in 1972 and the largest political protest since the student rallies
in Tiananmen Square 10 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now we hate America,'' said Ma Zhang Lu, a 20-year-old male
student with shoulder-length dyed hair, who had just hurled a rock
at the embassy. ``China has been especially friendly to the
American people. But we have been rebuffed, and now the Americans
have broken international law.''
</P>
<P>
   The protests marked an extraordinary moment in a controlled
country where such outbursts are normally forbidden and almost
never occur, though Saturday's demonstrations clearly had some
measure of government approval.
</P>
<P>
   The protests also comes just two weeks after Buddhist Law, a
spiritual group seeking official recognition, held another huge
rally in the city center.
</P>
<P>
   In Shanghai, a large, chanting crowd threw rocks and bottles at
the U.S. Consulate. Similar demonstrations were reported in
Guangzhou. And in the southern city of Chengdu, protesters set a
fire at the U.S. consulate early Sunday, but it was put out. A
Chinese guard was reported hurt.
</P>
<P>
   In Beijing after nightfall on Saturday, large unruly throngs
roamed the embassy district, defying police requests to go home.
Several times crowds pushed against lines of police officers,
linked arm in arm, who held them away from the U.S. and British
embassies.
</P>
<P>
   At one point, a group of 50 demonstrators burst through police
lines, only to be stopped by a row of police five deep about 50
yards from the U.S. Embassy compound. The police, who did not carry
weapons, made no arrests.
</P>
<P>
   Late on Saturday afternoon, the U.S. Embassy ``strongly
protested'' inadequate police protection, after students were
allowed to press up against the embassy's street-side gates and
throw rocks through windows of an office building still holding 15
to 20 embassy staff members, including James Sasser, the U.S.
ambassador.
</P>
<P>
   Virtually all protesters said they thought the bombing was
intentional.
</P>
<P>
   The protests began early Saturday afternoon when angry people
started gathering on the tree-lined streets in front of the embassy
in Beijing. Around 4 p.m., they were joined by thousands of angry,
chanting students, not die hard Communist Party cadres but
thoroughly Westernized youths, wearing baseball caps and Nike sweat
pants.
</P>
<P>
   The Beijing students marched in groups of several hundred behind
their university banners carrying hand-painted signs, some in
English, like ``USA Nazi Killers'' and chanting slogans like ``The
blood of Chinese must be repaid.''
</P>
<P>
   Each group paused in front of the iron gate at the embassy, just
15 feet from its front door, to chant, sing patriotic songs and
deliver a variety of petitions.
</P>
<P>
   At first, an officer from the embassy's political section came
out solemnly to accept the papers. But the protests quickly turned
violent, as students from several universities pelted the embassy
with rocks and water bottles. Each broken light and window was
greeted with thunderous cheers.
</P>
<P>
   Although most students returned to their campuses around
nightfall, many remained in the embassy district, and by 9 p.m.
raucous students and other demonstrators had regrouped near the
embassy, smashing cars with U.S. Embassy plates, identifiable by
the red character for embassy, followed by the number 224. An
American flag was burned outside Sasser's residence.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
