<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-NOTEBOOK-MCMANAMAN-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUFFALO, HASEK MIGHT PART WAYS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB MCMANAMAN  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   There was some intense speculation out of New York that
all-world goalie  &UR; Dominik Hasek could be on his last tour of duty
with the Buffalo Sabres, who are hurting for money and must pay the
``Dominator'' an average of $8 million a year over the next three
seasons.
</P>
<P>
   They have a top goalie prospect  &UR; (Martin Biron) ready but would
have to protect both in the expansion draft, thereby exposing more
precious position players. If they protect only one goalie, they're
going to lose the other. And as good as two-time Hart Trophy winner
Hasek is, he's getting up in age and the Sabres can't afford to
lose a youngster like Biron.
</P>
<P>
   ``Darcy told me it's a complete lie and I believe what he
says,'' Hasek said, referring to Buffalo General Manager  &UR; Darcy
Regier. ``I don't think it's true at all.''
</P>
<P>
   We shall see. But don't be shocked if the Sabres move Hasek in a
blockbuster deal this summer. &QL; 
Yashin in rumors, too &QL; 
He's a finalist for the Hart Trophy. He scored 44 goals and 94
points. And he could be on the move, too, because the Ottawa
Senators won't be able to afford the $8 million to $10 million that
superstar &UR; Alexei Yashin wants.
</P>
<P>
   Yashin has one year left on his current deal, which pays him
$3.3 million, but he wants to renegotiate for a multiyear pact. If
the Senators don't do something, they'll lose him to an offer sheet
in another year. Bank on it.
</P>
<P>
   Which means the most likely scenario is a trade. The New Jersey
Devils are said to be interested and reports are that they would
part with  &UR; Bobby Holik, Jason Arnott, Lyle Odelein and a
first-round pick to get Yashin. That might be too much for Ottawa
to pass. &QL; 
Protected Coyotes? &QL; 
The expansion Atlanta Thrashers will get to pluck at least one
player from each of the existing 27 clubs next month a day before
the draft in Boston. Most teams will protect one goalie, along with
five defensemen and nine forwards.
</P>
<P>
   The catch is that each team must expose one defenseman who is
under contract for next season and two forwards who also have
deals. What will the Coyotes do?
</P>
<P>
   For starters, they will protect  &UR; Nikolai Khabibulin, exposing
both backup  &UR; Mikhail Shtalenkov and free agent  &UR; Jimmy Waite, the
latter whom they don't want back but may have to re-sign if
Shtalenkov gets picked up by Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   The five defensemen expected to be protected are  &UR; Teppo
 &UR; Numminen, Jyrki Lumme, Keith Carney, Oleg Tverdovsky and probably
 &UR; Stan
 &UR; Neckar. Deron Quint is most likely to be claimed.
</P>
<P>
   Among the forwards, the protected list likely will include
 &UR; Keith Tkachuk, Jeremy Roenick, Rick Tocchet, Robert Reichel, Dallas
 &UR; Drake, Shane Doan, Daniel Briere, Juha Ylonen and/or  &UR; Bob Corkum
and
 &UR; Greg Adams. They could lose  &UR; Mike Stapleton, Mike Sullivan, Louie
 &UR; DeBrusk or  &UR; Stephen Leach. &QL; 
Flyers fallout &QL; 
 &UR; Ed Snider, controversial chairman of the Philadelphia Flyers, said
a whole lot more the other day than just questioning the integrity
of officiating, which brought about a $50,000 fine after his team's
first-round ouster from the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   Snider made a few remarks that had many speculating he might be
done running the organization. He even went so far as to say  &UR; Pat
 &UR; Croce, colorful president of the NBA's Philadelphia 76ers, could be
his replacement.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't rule it out and I don't rule it in,'' Snider said.
</P>
<P>
   Croce said his commitment is to the basketball team, but he
added: ``I'm not going to lie to you, it has crossed my mind.''
</P>
<P>
   Whatever happens, General Manager  &UR; Bobby Clarke is keeping his
job for at least another year. &QL; 
Draft lottery &QL; 
The NHL's weighted draft lottery for the 11 non-playoff teams (or
those clubs that now hold their draft choices) and the expansion
Thrashers shouldn't make a whole lot of difference when it comes to
who gets the No. 1 overall pick.
</P>
<P>
   It still likely will be the Tampa Bay Lightning, which has a 26
percent chance to get the top pick.
</P>
<P>
   The odds for the rest: Atlanta and Vancouver (16.9 percent), the
Islanders (10.8), Nashville (8.3), Washington (6.4), Los Angeles
(4.8), Chicago (3.7), Calgary (2.7), Montreal (1.9), the Rangers
(1.1) and Florida (0.5). &QL; 
Slap shots &QL; 
Detroit defenseman  &UR; Niklas Lidstrom continues to warn that he and
family may move back to his native Sweden rather than accept a
long-term deal from the club this summer.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know eventually we're going back to Sweden,'' Lidstrom
said. ``It's just when's the right time? When's the right time for
the kids to go to Swedish schools? When's the right time to have
them grow up with their extended families?''
</P>
<P>
   After he signs and honors a three- to five-year deal worth $5
million to $6 million _ which he will _ that's when.
</P>
<P>
   How's this for a golf foursome:  &UR; Michael Jordan,
 &UR; John Elway, Wayne Gretzky and  &UR; Mario Lemieux? It's probably going
to happen, too, at Lemieux's charity tournament June 10-13 near
Pittsburgh. Jordan and Elway have committed and Gretzky will, too,
the minute he is asked.
</P>
<P>
   Sources in Pittsburgh said Lemieux's reorganization plan for the
Penguins will be approved, without haste, and that the league's
backup plan to either sell and move the team or terminate the
franchise and hold a dispersal draft will never see the light of
day. Here's hoping.
</P>
<P>
   A record number of close games were played in the first round of
the playoffs _ the most since the league went to a best-of-seven
format for openers in 1987. Of the 44 games, 23 were decided by one
goal (52.3 percent) and 35 by two goals or fewer (79.6)
Additionally, 11 games went to overtime, the most since 14 in
1993. &QL; 
Includes information from other media sources. Bob McManaman can be
reached at (602) 444-8326 or at bob.mcmanaman(at)pni.com via
e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
