<HEADLINE>
EX-CARD JOHNSON GET DOCTOR'S OK TO WORK OUT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE SCHOENFELD  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Former Cardinals running back  &UR; LeShon Johnson never will forget
May 5, 1998.
</P>
<P>
   That was the day he was diagnosed with non-Hodgkin's lymphoma,
putting his NFL career in doubt.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson had joined the Giants earlier in the spring, two months
before a routine chest X-ray revealed he had a malignant tumor in
his chest.
</P>
<P>
   A year later, Johnson has been cleared by Giants doctors to
resume workouts with the team.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't wait to run out on the field in that blue uniform,''
Johnson said. ``Then I will have completed my mission.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson will be back on the field this week when the Giants
begin their off-season conditioning program and minicamp. His
doctor,  &UR; David
 &UR; Wolf, said Johnson's white blood count is high enough for him to
participate.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no doubt about it _ I will be back,'' Johnson said
last week. ``I feel good. This is the first time I've felt so
confident.''
</P>
<P>
   He isn't guaranteed a job, however. The Giants drafted two
running backs _  &UR; Joe Montgomery of Ohio State in the second round
and  &UR; Sean
 &UR; Bennett of Northwestern in the fourth _ to go along with veterans
 &UR; Gary
 &UR; Brown and  &UR; Tiki Barber.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson isn't worried about the competition. He's just glad to
be practicing again.
</P>
<P>
   ``The guy is amazing,'' said Giants Coach  &UR; Jim Fassel, former
offensive coordinator of the Cardinals. ``He always has a smile on
his face when you see him in the locker room. He's an inspiration
to the other guys.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson still needs to gain weight. He's down to 202, 10 under
his playing weight.
</P>
<P>
   The Giants plan to use him as a third-down back and a kickoff
returner. After what he has been through, he'll accept any role.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm on a mission,'' he said. ``My speed is still there. My
heart is still there. And by me sitting on the sidelines, I got to
sit back and watch, and now I feel like I know how to use my
ability _ when to use my speed and when not to.''
</P>
<P>
   Cardinals coaches thought Johnson used to try to hit the holes
too quickly. They joked that he was a kamikaze runner who often
took huge hits.
</P>
<P>
   His former coaches and teammates are just glad he has regained
his health and is back on the field.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hey, `Cowboy' is a good guy,'' Cardinals safety  &UR; Kwamie
Lassiter said of Johnson, also a rodeo cowboy. ``For somebody like
him to go through that and come back, he'll appreciate the game
even more. We're pulling for him.'' &QL; 
Talk isn't cheap &QL; 
The agent for New Orleans Saints first-round pick  &UR; Ricky Williams
and team official  &UR; Terry O'Neil have found a new and fun way to
negotiate.
</P>
<P>
   They talk business on golf courses in the mid-South, playing 18
holes every day while trying to agree on a contract.
</P>
<P>
   The two plan to keep playing daily until they come to terms.
</P>
<P>
   ``Part of it, I love the game,'' agent  &UR; Leland Hardy said. ``I'm
not revealing anything about the nature of our discussions, but
Terry has the slight upper hand on the golf course so far.'' &QL; 
Crystal ball &QL; 
Arizona State running back  &UR; J.R. Redmond is projected by one mock
draft to be the No. 1 overall pick in the 2000 draft.
</P>
<P>
   The ``Brian Stevenson Draft Notebook'' has Redmond going to
Philadelphia with the first pick.
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinals are projected to pick 22nd and take University of
Arizona running back  &UR; Trung Canidate, the Camelback High School
graduate. &QL; 
Dumb move &QL; 
The Vikings didn't help themselves in their quest to get a new
stadium by forcing out  &UR; Jeff Diamond, the senior vice president of
football operations who recently was named ``Sporting News'' NFL
Executive of the Year.
</P>
<P>
   Diamond, who has worked for the team for 24 years, was pushed
out after losing a power struggle to Coach  &UR; Dennis Green and
General Manager  &UR; Tim Connolly.
</P>
<P>
   It was Diamond who kept the team in business last season when it
didn't have an owner. He still was able to re-sign running back
 &UR; Robert
 &UR; Smith, defensive lineman  &UR; John Randle and offensive tackles  &UR; Todd
 &UR; Steussie and  &UR; Korey Stringer, all of whom helped the Vikings finish
15-1 last season, the best regular season mark in the league. &QL; 
Set him free &QL; 
Don't be surprised if the Rams release safety  &UR; Toby Wright, the
Mesa Dobson High School graduate who has been bothered by knee and
hamstring problems for much of the past three seasons.
</P>
<P>
   ``The waiting game is treacherous,'' Wright said.
</P>
<P>
   He thinks he's going to be cut after June 1, and one team he is
interested in joining is the Cardinals.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been in the league long enough to see the writing's on
the wall,'' Wright said. ``It's pretty obvious.''
</P>
<P>
   Wright is expendable because the Rams signed free agent safety
 &UR; Devin Bush from Atlanta in the off-season for $7.2 million over
four years.
</P>
<P>
   ``You bring in a safety, and you pay him like a starter, that's
your man,'' Wright said. `Politically, you've got to go with
him.'' &QL; 
Short shots &QL; 
Kansas City Chiefs Coach  &UR; Gunther Cunningham, on rookie free agent
running back  &UR; Brian Shay, who set an NCAA record 6,958 yards at
NCAA Division II Emporia (Kan.) State last season: ``I don't care
what level he gained those yards at. If it was Pop Warner, I don't
care. He accelerated a couple of times, and I was in awe.''
</P>
<P>
   The Pittsburgh Steelers signed  &UR; Kordell Stewart to a three-year,
$27 million contract extension because they think he's better than
the Cardinals'  &UR; Jake Plummer.
</P>
<P>
   Happy 100th birthday to  &UR; Marguerite Lambeau, the wife of former
Packers founder and Coach  &UR; Curley Lambeau, who also coached the
Cardinals in 1950 and '51.
</P>
<P>
   Jets rookie guard  &UR; David Loverne, on playing with a torn
pectoral muscle in the East-West Shrine All-Star Game: ``Anything
other than death is a minor injury.'' &QL; 
