<HEADLINE>
OHIO HIGH SCHOOL GETS INTO LUXURY ACT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By LES POLK  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   When you think of luxury suites, club seats and seat licenses,
it's only natural to think of wealthy professional sports teams and
their corporate clients.
</P>
<P>
   Think again. Not only do suites help finance pro sports
buildings, but they've permeated the college scene, and now an Ohio
high school is building a football stadium by selling seat
licenses.
</P>
<P>
   Ravenna High School is building a $5 million
athletic/recreational facility with a 5,000-seat football/soccer
stadium funded by personal seat licenses and community
fund-raising. No bond elections, no taxes, no stadium districts,
just an old-fashioned community effort with a newfangled twist.
</P>
<P>
   And the effort has attracted attention from school districts
across the nation, Ravenna Superintendent Phil Warner said.
</P>
<P>
   The blue-collar town of about 25,000, just east of Akron,
decided a few years ago to replace the football stadium, part of
which had to be closed off last year because it was falling apart.
</P>
<P>
   Rather than ask voters for an athletic bond issue, the school
board decided to try something different.
</P>
<P>
   ``We decided to explore private funding, thinking the community
might like it because we also need a bond election to build a new
high school,'' Warner said.
</P>
<P>
   Up-front funding was provided by a bank in a lease-purchase
agreement, and ground broke on the stadium in March. The board must
make payments over 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   An alumni campaign, school employees campaign, corporate
donations and the seat licenses have helped the board raise more
than $800,000 this year.
</P>
<P>
   About 1,200 seats in the stadium carry seat licenses ranging
from $1,000 to $1,500. More than $200,000 has been raised via
licenses, which give the holders first rights to tickets.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an opportunity to rally the community to support
itself and its kids,'' Warner said.
</P>
<P>
   The complex will include an outdoor education area, baseball and
softball diamonds and a cross country trail.
</P>
<P>
   Supporters can contribute to everything from engraved bricks at
the stadium entry walkway for $500 to a baseball backstop for
$20,000 to $100 for benches in the outdoor recreation area.
</P>
<P>
   ``The way we're doing this gives people a choice,'' Warner said.
``If they support athletics, great. If they don't, they don't pay
anything.''
</P>
<P>
   The stadium opens Aug. 27 for the football team's first game.
</P>
<P>
   But the campaign won't end there.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a long way to go,'' Warner said. ``It's a struggle, no
different than a bond election. But I really do feel that overall,
the community is behind it.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
