<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TORNADO-RELIEF-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON PROMISES AID FOR OKLAHOMA VICTIMS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JACK DOUGLAS Jr. 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DEL CITY, Okla. _ Standing outside their demolished homes
Saturday, hundreds of tornado victims greeted President Clinton and
were told that $12 million more in federal aid will be available to
help them rebuild their homes _ and their lives.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton called the view ``frightening'' as he flew over the
swath of destruction left by the killer tornadoes that cut through
11 Oklahoma counties Monday.
</P>
<P>
   In the suburban community of Del City, where five people died,
Clinton told survivors: ``This is the most devastating tornado I
have ever seen ... I'm sorry. Our hearts are with you. We will be
with you throughout the rebuilding.
</P>
<P>
   ``I came into this neighborhood today and I saw all these
American flags sticking up, all the people rooting around in the
rubble of their houses, looking for those family photos and the
marriage licenses and the other records of family life ... It was
profoundly moving to me.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton pledged $12 million from the U.S. Department of Labor,
which he said will be used to hire 3,500 people left jobless by the
storms.
</P>
<P>
   That pleased many in the crowd, including some who had said they
were not happy that they had to stop cleanup efforts so that Secret
Service agents could sweep the neighborhood before the president's
visit.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't really looking for relief, but I found some,'' said
Randy Reed, whose family lost their home in Del City. ``I think
people found more hope for tomorrow than they had before he came,''
Reed said.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton also encouraged victims to include a heavily fortified
space known as a ``safe room'' or ``safe closet'' when they rebuild
their homes, so they will have a place to go in the event of
another tornado. Government assistance will be available to defray
the costs for the indoor shelters, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The crowd applauded when Clinton said his proposed budget
includes several million dollars to work on improving the Doppler
radar warning system for dangerous weather.
</P>
<P>
   He also said he supports the creation of a National Weather
Center at the University of Oklahoma to work on improving warning
systems and to find scientific ways to weaken a potentially
dangerous tornado before it hits the ground.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll put Oklahoma at the center of that'' research, Clinton
said.
</P>
<P>
   As the president spoke, authorities continued to search for
people who have been unaccounted for since the tornadoes struck.
The list of the missing grew by one name Saturday when the Oklahoma
Medical Examiner's Office said a man identified as Mark Edward
Nelson, 40, was mistakenly taken off the list last week.
</P>
<P>
   Nelson was last seen Monday night in a 1997 Chevrolet Lumina,
traveling in the path of a tornado in Midwest City, the medical
examiner's office said.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities also continued to look for John and Barbara Potton,
a British couple traveling in a motor home, and Tram Bui, a
23-year-old woman who was trying to take cover under a bridge on
Interstate 35 when the storm hit.
</P>
<P>
   Neither the Pottons, who are believed to be in their 60s, nor
Bui have been heard from since the tornadoes.
</P>
<P>
   The death toll yesterday remained at 41 people, including two
infants and a 6-year-old girl.
</P>
<P>
   As he flew over the path of the tornadoes, Clinton said it is a
miracle that more people did not die.
</P>
<P>
   Some questioned the president's sincerity, and said his
appearance was an inconvenience in a time of urgency.
</P>
<P>
   ``His coming into our neighborhood is just slowing us up in
getting our stuff out,'' said Tom Holder, a Del City resident who
lost everything. ``I think it's a photo op,'' Holder said of
Clinton's visit.
</P>
<P>
   But Tammy Clymer, another resident whose home was destroyed,
said Clinton's appearance will help.
</P>
<P>
   ``As long as he's here, more people will know about it and that
will bring more help for all of us who need it,'' Clymer said.
</P>
<P>
   As she waited under the hot sun for the president, Toni
Maldonado said she is skeptical of the president because of his
highly publicized extramarital affair with a former White House
intern.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he wants to redeem himself, he should get down and work and
get his hands dirty,'' Maldonado said. She added, ``I think Hillary
(Rodham Clinton) should be here, really.''
</P>
<P>
   Later, however, Maldonado said she liked what the president had
to say.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
