<HEADLINE>
NEW DEPUTY SETS PRIORITIES IN PLACE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BARRY BURKHART  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - Steve Ferrell, a 20-year employee of the Arizona Game
and Fish Department, has been named to the second-highest position
in the department by Director Duane Shroufe.
</P>
<P>
   As deputy director, Ferrell will basically address problem areas
and run the day-to-day operation of the department.
</P>
<P>
   He replaced veteran Tom Spalding, who retired last fall.
Spalding will be a tough act to follow. He was both tough at times
but also fair. He served the department well.
</P>
<P>
   Ferrell is well-grounded in administration. He was assistant
director in charge of field operations before being promoted. In
that position, he was the chief administrator for all of Arizona's
regional offices. Before that, he was regional supervisor in the
Kingman area.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if I'm running day-to-day operations,'' he said.
``But I do have some areas that I want to work with.''
</P>
<P>
   Here are some of them:
</P>
<P>
   For wildlife particularly, there are diverse customers, some
with competing interests. The challenge, he said, is to try to meet
all their needs, if possible.
</P>
<P>
   Conflict resolution. Ferrell said Game and Fish already is doing
a good job of that but wants it to be even better.
</P>
<P>
   Better marketing. The agency is beginning to address that issue,
he said. The public needs to know what the agency is doing and what
it is.
</P>
<P>
   Ferrell, who has been a leader in developing quality management
practices for both the public and employees of the agency, said
that practice must continue.
</P>
<P>
   Funding must be produced to do all these things, he said.
``We've had no license fee increase in 10 years,'' he said. ``The
cost of business is continually rising.''
</P>
<P>
   Income has become stagnant, particularly because big-game permit
numbers have gone down, a result of the decrease in animals because
of drought conditions.
</P>
<P>
   That problem was eased week before last, when both the state
Senate and House approved a bill that allows the agency to raise
license fees by 30 percent. Shroufe said new fees won't come at
once.
</P>
<P>
   Salaries for veteran professionals is embarrassingly low.
Because of state hiring practices, some new employees come in
making more than veterans.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to get that problem solved,'' Ferrell said.
</P>
<P>
   He also wants to tweak the department's off-highway vehicle
program. He believes the agency must increase education and
information efforts in that area and better integrate the law
enforcement aspects into day-to-day field operations.
</P>
<P>
   It appears the new deputy director is a ball of fire. Here's
hoping he doesn't flame out. &QL; 
Try the Net &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Copies of hunting regulations for 1999-2000 will be delivered to
vendors sometime this week.
</P>
<P>
   But if you want an early peek, you can find the regulations on
the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Game and Fish is trying to streamline the process of giving the
public a quicker look at the seasons. After new hunting seasons
were approved by Game and Fish commissioners in April, the
department had them on the Net not too long after.
</P>
<P>
   That allows hunters to survey the seasons and start applying
whenever they wish.
</P>
<P>
   The new application form is on the department's home page. Old
hunt forms should be tossed. This year's form requires (by new
state law) that Social Security numbers be listed on all forms for
governmental agencies.
</P>
<P>
   For early application, call up the home page at
www.gf.state.az.us and remember it also can be obtained by fax at
(602) 530-2210. &QL; 
Barry Burkhart can be reached at (602) 444-8454 or at
barry.burkhart(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
