<SLUG> BC-BBN-DBACKS-NOTEBOOK-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
D-BACKS SEND ANDERSON TO TRIPLE-A TUCSON 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By PEDRO GOMEZ  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - Pitcher  &UR; Brian Anderson, the first player selected in
the November 1997 expansion draft, was sent to Triple-A Tucson on
Saturday morning.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson's demotion opened up a roster spot for reliever  &UR; Amaury
 &UR; Telemaco, whose 30-day rehabilitation assignment ended Friday
night. Because Telemaco is out of options, he needed to be placed
on the big-league roster or the club would have faced losing him
via waivers.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson, who has struggled in his role as a reliever, will
start three games for Tucson and then return to the major league
roster, Manager  &UR; Buck Showalter said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Brian is going down to pitch so that he can get back to where
he needs to be so he can come back here and help the major league
club,'' Showalter said. ``This is nothing he has created.''
</P>
<P>
   Anderson had just 10 innings pitched in eight appearances while
being used primarily in mop-up situations when a game is usually
out of hand. It's the first time in his career he has been used
exclusively as a reliever and it seemed Anderson, who relies
heavily on his change-up, never could make the adjustment to the
bullpen.
</P>
<P>
   ``As much as I didn't want to believe it, I almost saw this
coming,'' said Anderson, who is scheduled to start the Sidewinders
game Monday at Iowa. ``I'm in a role I've never been in. Basically,
I'm insurance right now in case there's a doubleheader, a spot
start is needed or there's an injury.''
</P>
<P>
   By stretching Anderson out _ he is scheduled to go from about 45
pitches Monday to 70 on May 15 and 90 on May 20 _ the left-hander
who won 12 games in 32 starts last season, might also be part of a
bigger plan.
</P>
<P>
   Two major league general managers believe the Diamondbacks may
be making this move in order to make a trade. Anderson's trade
value as a reliever is basically negligible. However, another
scenario might have another trade being made and Anderson slipping
back into the rotation.
</P>
<P>
   One possibility could include dealing  &UR; Andy Benes, whose name at
least one National League general manager has heard come up in the
form of a trade. Benes, however, would have to approve any trade
since he has a complete no-trade clause in his contract.
</P>
<P>
   ``Buck said he couldn't guarantee what I'd be doing when I
return,'' Anderson said. ``I might be coming back in the same
role.'' &QL; 
Snake bites &QL; 
Outfielder  &UR; Luis Gonzalez extended his hitting streak to 21 games,
but not before going hitless in his first three plate appearances.
Gonzalez lined a soft single to right field in the bottom of the
ninth.
</P>
<P>
   Reliever  &UR; Byung-Hyun Kim, who has caught the attention of most
everyone in the organization, is scheduled to be promoted from
Double-A El Paso to Tucson today. Kim entered Saturday's action
with a 2.08 ERA in 17 innings. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
