<SLUG> BC-BBO-NOTEBOOK-GOMEZ-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IF IT AIN'T BROKE . . .  
 RETALIATION SHOULD BE LEFT IN THE GAME 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By PEDRO GOMEZ  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   At what point exactly did baseball decide to put restraints on
its players and no longer allow them to play the game the way it
has been played for decades?
</P>
<P>
   Last week's incident between the Atlanta Braves and St. Louis
Cardinals demonstrates how baseball's umpires, possibly at the
urging of the commissioner's office, are taking a step backward
rather than forward.
</P>
<P>
   This is a touchy subject to most casual baseball fans because
they believe any form of violence is wrong. So when Braves starter
 &UR; Greg
 &UR; Maddux drilled St. Louis'  &UR; Ray Lankford two pitches after Mark
McGwire hit a grand slam, the Cardinals rightly took exception.
</P>
<P>
   But when home plate umpire  &UR; Larry Poncino warned Cardinals
pitcher
 &UR; Kent Mercker before the start of the next inning not to throw at
any Braves players, he basically took away the one way St. Louis
could retaliate, which is to have its pitcher plunk a Braves player
and square things.
</P>
<P>
   It may sound barbaric, but it's the way the game has been played
since the start of the century _ you hit one of our guys on
purpose, we're going to do the same to one of yours.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's not one of the problems baseball has,'' said Cincinnati
Manager  &UR; Jack McKeon, who has been involved in major league ball as
a player, coach, manager or general manager for 50 years. ``To me,
that's the way you play the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``The one thing now is that hitters don't think a pitcher can
come inside at all. They get an inside pitch, and they're ready to
charge the mound. I'd love to see one of these guys charge someone
like  &UR; Bob
 &UR; Gibson,  &UR; Sal Maglie or  &UR; Don Drysdale. Those pitchers would kill
these hitters. But today, there's a different breed of player.''
</P>
<P>
   It's just the way the game is played. The one time players
should take exception to being hit is when a ball comes in toward
the head, where serious damage can occur. But pitchers such as
Drysdale would drill a hitter in the ribs _ a spot that would hurt
for weeks, causing that hitter to curse Drysdale for weeks.
Drysdale hit 154 batters during his career.
</P>
<P>
   Retaliation should never be taken away in the game of baseball.
But now it has gotten to the point where the first club to strike
gets away with it because they simply plead innocence. In fact,
rarely are such instances innocent.
</P>
<P>
   They'll never admit it, but every single major league manager
has ordered one of his pitchers to hit an opposing batter at some
point in his career. It's truly an inside part of the game of
baseball. &QL; 
Trivial question &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Who holds the club record for home runs by an Atlanta Braves
player? &QL; 
Rocket fuel &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Toronto assistant general manager  &UR; Dave Stewart, one of the
fiercest competitors of the last quarter-century and one of the
most stand-up men in the game, is still quarreling with former Blue
Jays pitcher  &UR; Roger Clemens, who basically demanded to be traded
away from Toronto because he didn't deem the Blue Jays capable of
competing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our club as a whole feels we're a better club without Roger,''
Stewart said. ``I don't believe Roger is conducive to winning. He's
more of a guy that's good at accomplishing individual goals, but I
don't believe he's capable of bringing a team to a championship.
The proof is in the pudding.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's not done it in Boston. He came to Toronto, and he didn't
do it there. The situation in New York _ it's not that he would
bring a championship there, but he'd be riding the coattails of a
club that can do it without him.''
</P>
<P>
   It should be noted that Clemens signed with Toronto two winters
ago after the Blue Jays made the highest offer for his services
and, at the time, he said he was there to help bring back glory to
the franchise.
</P>
<P>
   It should also be noted that in 10 career meetings between
Clemens and Stewart (which includes the playoffs), Clemens never
once beat Stewart, who was 7-0 in those match-ups against Clemens.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the Blue Jays do not appear to be the dregs of the
league, which is how some interpreted Clemens' painting of the
club. &QL; 
Credit where it's due &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Just how good are the Cleveland Indians, owners of the best
record in baseball entering this weekend's series? Consider who
they have let go as a barometer of where they are at.
</P>
<P>
   Since the middle of the 1996 season, the Indians have seen
several top players leave either via trade or free agency, yet they
remain perched near the top of the 30 clubs in baseball.
</P>
<P>
   Here's a list of former Indians and where they are:  &UR; Albert
Belle, Baltimore's cleanup hitter;  &UR; Matt Williams, Arizona's
cleanup hitter;
 &UR; Jeromy Burnitz, Milwaukee's cleanup hitter;  &UR; Jeff Kent, San
Francisco's cleanup hitter;  &UR; Brian Giles, Pittsburgh's No. 3
hitter;  &UR; Sean Casey, Cincinnati's No. 3 hitter; and  &UR; Marquis
Grissom, Milwaukee's No. 7 hitter.
</P>
<P>
   When it comes to pitching, the list is also somewhat impressive.
It includes  &UR; Gregg Olson, Arizona's closer;  &UR; Jose Mesa, Seattle's
closer;
 &UR; Danny Graves, Cincinnati's closer; and  &UR; Chad Ogea, Philadelphia's
No. 3 starter.
</P>
<P>
   What did the Indians receive in exchange? Three players on their
current roster: third baseman  &UR; Travis Fryman and pitchers  &UR; Dave
Burba and  &UR; Steve Reed.
</P>
<P>
   Reliever  &UR; Ricky Rincon (he no longer wishes to be called
Ricardo) was also acquired in a trade, but he remains on the
disabled list.
</P>
<P>
   All of these moves are courtesy of General Manager  &UR; John Hart.
Say whatever you want about him or his ego, but Hart remains one of
the very best at his craft. &QL; 
Bleacher creatures &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Chicago Cubs management is promising a strict crackdown after
fans in the most famous bleachers in baseball inundated Wrigley
Field with half-filled beer cups, glass flasks of booze and full
cans of soda. The protests came about after a bad umpire's call
last Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are reviewing all of our options, including more security,
stationing personnel in different places, alcohol limits and other
opportunities available to us,'' said  &UR; Mark McGuire, the team's
executive vice president. ``I would suspect we will do some things
differently.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Cubs officials are caught in a tough spot because
they do not want to ruin the Wrigley Field bleachers for what they
are _ a great place to watch a ballgame. Yet, they realize they
must maintain some form of control.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's arguably the highest-demand seat in baseball,'' McGuire
said. ``We're caught trying to figure out the right way to do it.
Unfortunately, some of (the littering) is becoming part of the
tradition or culture of Wrigley Field, and it's one we would like
to lose quickly.''
</P>
<P>
   Cubs reliever  &UR; Rod Beck, known for indulging from time to time,
offered this opinion:
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm all for having a good time myself and having a few pops,
but not for wasting beer by throwing it onto the field. I'd rather
drink it than throw it.
</P>
<P>
   ``(But) they were throwing bottles and full pop cans and
baseballs. You're talking a guy's livelihood. What happens if
someone gets an eye put out?'' &QL; 
Trivial answer &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Before you jump to the presumably obvious, think about how the
questions was phrased. It asked the Atlanta Braves player with the
most home runs.
</P>
<P>
   The answer is  &UR; Dale Murphy, who had 371 career home runs in an
Atlanta uniform.  &UR; Hank Aaron hit 335 for Atlanta but is the
all-time Braves franchise leader with 733 home runs. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   THE HIT LIST &QL; 
 &UR; Canning his emotions: Detroit's  &UR; Bobby Higginson was so frustrated
after a game last weekend that he took his bat and whacked the
toilet repeatededly. The next day, he hit two doubles and a single
in his first three at-bats.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; The newest member of the Jack Lord Fan Club: Pittsburgh catcher
 &UR; Jason Kendall became only the seventh player since 1970 (as far
back as they can check) to have a box score line of 5-0-5-0. He had
five hits in five at-bats and nothing else.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Flashback: Mackey Sasser.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; And now, your Montreal EEEEEEEEEEEEEEEExpos!: Teammates, and
brothers,  &UR; Vladimir and  &UR; Wilton Guerrero have combined for 16
errors this season, nine by right fielder Vladimir.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Milestone week for managers: Three managers reached significant
victories in the past week. Los Angeles'  &UR; Davey Johnson got victory
No. 1,000, Cincinnati's  &UR; Jack McKeon notched No. 600 and Anaheim's
 &UR; Terry Collins got No. 400. &QL; 
EXTRA BASES &QL; 
Giants second baseman  &UR; Jeff Kent became just the second player ever
to hit for the cycle (single, double, triple and home run in the
same game) at Pittsburgh's Three Rivers Stadium last week. The
other was  &UR; Joe Torre, who accomplished the feat in 1973 as a member
of the St. Louis Cardinals.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Rafael Palmeiro of the Texas Rangers is at opposite ends of the
spectrum when it comes to batting against left-handers and
right-handers, entering the weekend series. His .441 (30 for 68)
average against right-handers is the best in the American League.
Conversely, his .083 (2 for 24) average against left-handers is the
worst.
</P>
<P>
   It's pretty early for such projections, but Atlanta's  &UR; Bret
Boone, who has five home runs and 18 RBIs, is on pace to become the
first Braves second baseman ever to have 30 home runs and 100 RBIs
in a season.
</P>
<P>
   The experiment in Pittsburgh is over, and catcher
 &UR; Jason Kendall has returned to the middle of the lineup. After
becoming one of the few catchers ever to lead off, Kendall was
dropped to fifth in the order. While in the top spot, though,
Kendall distinguished himself, batting .274 with seven stolen bases
in eight attempts. His .366 on-base percentage wasn't bad, either.
 &UR; Al Martin is the new leadoff hitter.
</P>
<P>
   The two pitchers tied for the most complete games in the
National League with two come from the Diamondbacks and Phillies.
As expected,  &UR; Randy Johnson is the name from Arizona. The one from
Philadelphia, however, might be surprising since it is  &UR; Carlton
Loewer, not  &UR; Curt Shilling, who mopped up in the category last
season with 15.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta's  &UR; John Smoltz, who is 5-0 with a 1.69 ERA, won the
second Pitcher of the Month award of his career. Coincidentally,
the other time he won was also in April. The year was 1996, when he
won the league's Cy Young Award. &QL; 
THE RUMOR MILL &QL; 
Minnesota closer  &UR; Rick Aguilera continues to be closely monitored
by Atlanta scouts. Word is that Aguilera will waive his no-trade
clause if a deal is stuck with Atlanta. Giving more credence to
this is the fact that a Twins scout spent all of last weekend
checking out Braves games.
</P>
<P>
   Cleveland teammates appear to be growing a bit weary of  &UR; David
Justice's minor injuries. Justice has gone into Manager  &UR; Mike
 &UR; Hargrove's office moments before games and asked out of the lineup.
Justice, who is signed through 2002, has three home runs and eight
RBIs. He has played left field in 27 of the 188 games since the
start of last season.
</P>
<P>
   Former World Series hero and rumored Diamondbacks expansion pick
draftee  &UR; Craig Counsell is being shopped by the Florida Marlins. He
has been completely buried by the Marlins, who are committed to
starting  &UR; Luis Castillo at second base.
</P>
<P>
   In what is probably a precursor to a move in 2000, San Francisco
called up  &UR; Dave Righetti to assume the role of pitching coach when
 &UR; Ron Perranoski was forced to leave the club to attend to his
ailing mother. Several people within the organization are very high
on Righetti.
</P>
<P>
   Cleveland's Gold Glove shortstop,  &UR; Omar Vizquel, is nursing a
pulled quadriceps that he hurt on April 10. The club refuses to
place him on the disabled list, even though his uncharacteristic
six errors (one more than all of last year) have been directly
related to the injury.
</P>
<P>
   Expect Chicago Cubs Manager  &UR; Jim Riggleman to be a part of
 &UR; Bruce Bochy's All-Star Game coaching staff. Bochy, a member of
Riggleman's staff when he managed in San Diego, wound up replacing
Riggleman. The two remain close friends. &QL; 
THE RANKINGS &QL; 
 &UR; TOP OF THE ORDER &QL; 
 &QL; 
1. Cleveland &QL; 28-5 in games delayed by rain since
the start of 1996. &QL; 
 &QL; 
2. NY Yankees &QL; The record is not an indication of several problems
on this club. &QL; 
 &QL; 
3. Atlanta &QL; Does not appear to missing  &UR; Andres Galarraga's bat at
all. &QL; 
 &QL; 
4. NY Mets &QL; Have the best bullpen in the game, which tends to lead
to contending. &QL; 
 &QL; 
5. Houston &QL; Astros are talking about moving  &UR; Scott Elarton into the
rotation. &QL; 
 &QL; 
6. Los Angeles &QL; Dodgers are only 3-3 in games  &UR; Kevin Brown starts. &QL; 
 &QL; 
7. St. Louis &QL;  &UR; Fernando Tatis is looking mahvelous. Simply
mahvelous. &QL; 
 &QL; 
8. San Francisco &QL; Barely clinging to first place as the weekend
series started. &QL; 
 &QL; 
9. Texas &QL; May miss President  &UR; Tom Schieffer more than they want to
lead on. &QL; 
 &UR; BOTTOM OF THE ORDER &QL; 
 &QL; 
30. Florida &QL; Had two smallest home crowds ever last
week. &QL; 
 &QL; 
29. Montreal &QL; Does anyone really follow this club? Even in
Quebec? &QL; 
 &QL; 
28. Minnesota &QL; Wake us when all this stadium garbage finally gets
resolved. &QL; 
 &QL; 
27. Baltimore &QL; A little winning streak is a start, but problems
persist here. &QL; 
 &QL; 
26. Kansas City &QL; Royals are hoping pitcher  &UR; Jose Rosado only misses
one start. &QL; 
 &QL; 
25. San Diego &QL; Will the Padres go from first to worst to first to
worst? &QL; 
 &QL; 
24. Cincinnati &QL; Has won two in a row three times, but never three
in a row. &QL; 
 &QL; 
23. Boston &QL; That 6-1 start seems like it took place years ago. &QL; 
 &QL; 
22. Anaheim &QL;  &UR; Tim Belcher has not survived the fifth inning in five
of six starts. &QL; 
ON THE RISE &QL; 
 &UR; Oakland Athletics: Manager  &UR; Art Howe has these young A's playing
like they're ready to make a nuisance of themselves in the AL West,
a division where they were supposed to clearly be the underbelly.
But a little more than a month into the season, Oakland is looking
the part of a club with some interesting parts. Offensively, this
club can stack up with the best of them in the AL. The middle of
the lineup, which features  &UR; Jason Giambi,  &UR; Matt Stairs and
surprising  &UR; Olmedo Saenz, is more than respectable. Shortstop
 &UR; Miguel Tejada is showing the ability that led many in the
organization to compare him to a young
 &UR; Barry Larkin, and it may not be long until minor league pitching
sensation  &UR; Mark Mulder arrives in the Bay area. This is one of the
hottest clubs in baseball. &QL; 
GOING SOUTH &QL; 
 &UR; Toronto Blue Jays: The Blue Jays lost at home last Tuesday, their
first loss at SkyDome in 10 games. They then lost again Wednesday
and Thursday, being swept by Oakland. All the good feelings that
were with this club in the middle of April seem to be disappearing.
Injured starter  &UR; Joey Hamilton is not expected to return before May
20, and the offense, which produced big scores during the past two
weeks, is getting little help from a pitching staff that is having
trouble keepng opponents under 10 runs. &QL; 
OVERHEARD &QL; 
Cincinnati, ahem, outfielder  &UR; Dmitri Young crashed into the
outfield wall at Turner Field last weekend while chasing a deep fly
hit by Atlanta's  &UR; John Smoltz. Young missed the next four games
because of soreness in his left side. Young said after that
particular game: ``I fought the wall and the wall won. Tomorrow,
I'm going to the &UR; Andruw Jones School of Wall-Climbing.'' &QL; 
OUT OF LEFT FIELD &QL; 
Texas Rangers reliever  &UR; Jeff Zimmerman can put to rest any tags
about being a castoff from the independent Northern League, the
same place that produced Atlanta's  &UR; Kerry Ligtenberg. Zimmerman
entered the weekend series at Toronto with a 0.93 ERA in 19
innings. In 10 games he has walked two and struck out 14. Texas
Manager  &UR; Johnny Oates is calling on Zimmerman in the toughest of
situations. Opponents are batting only .109 against the
hard-throwing right-hander, a figure that drops to .091 when
runners are on base. Not bad for a kid who was trying to latch on
to whatever Northern League club would take a look at him two years
ago. &QL; 
Includes information from other media sources. Pedro Gomez can be
reached at (602) 444-2364 or at pedro.gomez(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
