<DOCNO> NYT19990508.0252 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-08 22:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9819 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PUMP-AZR &LR;      05-08 2536
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PUMP-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THERAPY FOR CEREBAL PALSY A LITTLE KNOWN OPTION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By MAUREEN WEST  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Sometimes Sherry Steiner runs her fingers lightly over her
15-year-old stepson's face, just in case he has an itch that he
can't tell her about. She provides his daily care.
</P>
<P>
   Her stepson, Jeffrey Steiner Jr., who suffers from severe
cerebral palsy, is wracked by nearly continuous muscle spasms that
send his body into painful contortions. He is doing the equivalent
of a continuous high-energy, and very involuntary workout. He can't
stop, though the 65-pound teenager who lives in central Phoenix is
chronically exhausted.
</P>
<P>
   A medical device is available that might offer him a precious
fragment of a more typical life _ an implant called the Baclofen
pump, which delivers medication. Getting that pump, for which they
finally received authorization last week, had been the focus of his
parents' lives.
</P>
<P>
   While Jeffrey's parents want it for him to make him more
comfortable, other parents of children with cerebral palsy or with
head and spinal injuries see it as a way for their child to sit up,
bathe, dress and feed themselves. Or perhaps to talk or walk.
</P>
<P>
   But the pump is a well-kept secret in Arizona, medical
professionals say. Even though thousands use it across the country,
only four children use it in the Valley out of an estimated 2,000
possible cerebral palsy patients and many others with spinal
injuries.
</P>
<P>
   That's because many doctors don't offer the pump as an option,
pushing instead extensive and permanent surgeries, doctors say.
</P>
<P>
   And it's because getting funding for the pump, estimated to cost
$15,000 to $20,000 the first year, can mean treading the medical
insurance slippery slope.
</P>
<P>
   The state-funded Children's Rehabilitative Services doesn't
offer it to patients because they are still evaluating it, though
the FDA gave the approval for cerebral palsy patients in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Their concerns include stories of pump failures and infections.
Others have expressed concerns about the use of the pump in
children younger than 8. The size of the pump, comparable to a
hockey puck, is a problem for smaller bodies, even a smaller model
designed specifically for them.
</P>
<P>
   ``Children's bodies are still growing _ putting something into
an adult is different than putting something into a child,'' said
Dr. Theodore Tarby of CRS.
</P>
<P>
   Doctors who advocate the pump say it may not be the solution for
every child with cerebral palsy or brain damage. But it should at
least be considered one of the options.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, there have been problems with it, but all surgical
procedures have potential complications, including those that are
commonly used for children with cerebral palsy,'' said Dr. David
Hirsch, who treats a 16-year-old patient who for two years has been
successfully using the pump. &QL; 
`AN EXCITING OPTION'
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Linda Krach of Gillette Children's Specialty Health Care in
St. Paul, Minn., treats 150 children who have the pump. About 100
of those have cerebral palsy. One teenager who once needed help to
even get into his wheelchair can now dress herself, and is planning
the day when she will live on her own.
</P>
<P>
   ```We have others who now have more endurance for walking, can
dial a phone or feed themselves,'' Krach said.
</P>
<P>
   She acknowledged that the pump has caused infections, and some
have experienced tube malfunctions. But most choose to correct the
complications and keep the pump.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is an exciting option not without risks, but I hope it
becomes more available for children,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Only four children in the Valley have the pump. Jeffrey will be
the fifth. Three other families have approached their insurance
companies asking for them to pay for an evaluation to see whether
they would be candidates.
</P>
<P>
   The conventional treatment in Arizona for severely spastic
patients like Jeffrey include orally administered muscle relaxants,
expensive physical therapy, and periodic surgeries to cut and
reattach muscles and tendons, reducing their tension.
</P>
<P>
   Another surgery commonly done and of comparable expense as
having a Baclofen pump involves selectively cutting nerves as they
exit the spinal cord. It is helpful to many children, but those
cuts are permanent.
</P>
<P>
   If there are problems with the pump, you can just take it out,
doctors say. &QL; 
HOW IT WORKS
</P>
<P>
   The Baclofen pump chemically relaxes the muscles without surgery
and without many of the side effects of oral medication. Because
the pump places the medicine directly along the spine, the entire
body and brain do not have to be flooded with relaxants. The disk
is implanted in the abdomen where it pumps tiny amounts of Baclofen
around the spinal cord. It is refilled four or five times a year by
needle injection into the pump.
</P>
<P>
   In most cases, parents are not told about it unless they happen
across information on the Internet or in health magazines,
according to several parents in the Valley.
</P>
<P>
   Jeffrey, who was born prematurely at 31 weeks, weighing 2{
pounds, has severe cerebral palsy. He isn't able to talk or express
emotions in a way visitors can understand, but his parents know his
language of grunts and ``ah''s. When a phone call arrives from
out-of-state relatives, excitement fights its way, muscle by
muscle, to his face.
</P>
<P>
   ``Judging by his responses, there is a lot going on in his
mind,'' Sherry Steiner says. Someday she and Jeffrey's father,
Jeffrey Sr., hope to discover more of what's locked inside him.
</P>
<P>
   On April 12, he responded favorably to trial doses of Baclofen,
injected into his spinal fluid. That positive test meant that an
implanted Baclofen pump would likely work for him.
</P>
<P>
   But then the Steiners had to get the implant surgery authorized
by their insurance company, which came through last week. The pump
has been around for eight years and has been approved by the FDA
for cerebral palsy treatment since 1996. Many believe it isn't more
expensive that the present routine of pills, muscle surgeries, and
painful recoveries and therapy, and that, ultimately, it may
decrease other medical costs such as surgeries.
</P>
<P>
   The Baclofen pump, according to its manufacturer, Medtronics,
could work for about two-thirds of cerebral palsy patients
suffering severe spasticity. Other health experts say 10 to 50
percent is a better estimate. It also is useful for patients with
spasticity caused by other disorders, such as spinal cord and brain
injuries, multiple sclerosis, and transverse myelitis.
</P>
<P>
   The implanted pump costs about $15,000 to $20,000 for the first
year, including the $9,000 pump and surgery to install it.
Recharging the pump with fresh supplies of Baclofen costs about
$1,000 to $1,500 a year and then there is physical therapy. The
pump itself lasts five to seven years. Pumps lasting 10 years are
in development. &QL; 
MORE SHOULD BE TOLD
</P>
<P>
   Dr. John Porter, a Valley rehabilitation specialist, and Dr.
Martin Burnett, a Valley anesthesiologist who has done the Baclofen
pump implant surgeries on the four Valley patients who have them,
say more Arizona cerebral palsy patients should be told about the
pump. They are trying to spread the word.
</P>
<P>
   Other advocates are Guy Collison, executive director of United
Cerebral Palsy in the Valley, and William Timmons, CEO of Los Nin
os Hospital in Phoenix, which treats children with cerebral palsy,
head and spinal cord injuries.
</P>
<P>
   The same kind of implanted pump, filled with morphine instead of
Baclofen, is now used routinely for terminal cancer patients to
eliminate or reduce pain.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not allowing younger people to have them is like sentencing
them to 60 years in bed,'' Burnett said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Acupuncture took 4,000 years to prove itself. I hope we don't
have to wait that long for this procedure,'' Porter added.
</P>
<P>
   Children's Rehabilitative Services, which is under contract with
AHCCCS (the state's medical insurance system for lower income
families and some disabled), sees most of Arizona's cerebral palsy
patients. CRS does not endorse the pump nor do doctors there
educate the clients about its availability.
</P>
<P>
   They are evaluating it and discussing informing patients about
it, said Dr. Theodore Tarby, medical director for CRS. The CRS
medical board has discussed the pump at three of the four most
recent meetings.
</P>
<P>
   While he has visited clinics in other states that use the pump,
there is no formal study under way by CRS, nor has a time line for
a decision been set.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will continue to evaluate it on a quarterly basis until we
either accept it as an alternative or eliminate it completely,'' he
said. But he suspects the board will likely add the pump as an
option.
</P>
<P>
   Tarby is also concerned that once patients turn 21, and they
leave CRS care, there is no guarantee from an agency or insurance
company to continue maintaining the pumps. &QL; 
CAUGHT IN RED TAPE
</P>
<P>
   Some suspicious parents, including Sherry Charlot, believe that
the doctors who make a living doing surgery to relieve muscle
tension have a financial incentive to discourage the new
technology. She has filed a grievance to get a Baclofen evaluation
for her 9-year-old daughter, Kara, who has a moderate case of
cerebral palsy. She is not asking for a new pump but to see if her
daughter could likely benefit from one.
</P>
<P>
   Charlot and others say they are being caught between CRS and
their insurance companies because neither will pay for the
evaluations.
</P>
<P>
   Charlot said CRS told her that it was her insurance company's
responsibility. But her insurance company told her it was CRS's.
</P>
<P>
   For legal advice, she went to Ed Myers, assisted technology
lawyer for the Center for Law and Disabilities. He is disturbed by
CRS's position toward the pump, considering what he has read about
the research and anecdotes that are showing how it helps children
with cerebral palsy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why kids in this state aren't getting the evaluations is
beyond me,'' Myers said. ``If they are good candidates they should
be getting this kind of treatment. When it comes to assisted
technology, two things are common: one is lack of knowledge and the
other is the fear of cost.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fear is that everyone will come running to AHCCCS asking
for this. That's not true because not all kids will be good
candidates for this.''
</P>
<P>
   Tarby, of CRS, called invalid the claim that doctors are holding
back the pump because it would hurt their practices. Most want to
find anything that would help their patients, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Of the five children in the Valley known to have at one time
received Baclofen pumps, one had the pump removed because the
child's body rejected it.
</P>
<P>
   But there are success stories. Car accident victim Sara Smith,
now 10, suffered painful spasms that stiffened her body, according
to her mother. She had to stay in bed most of the time. She
couldn't even be put into a wheelchair. Since receiving the pump,
Sara now uses a wheelchair, has re-learned how to speak and is back
in school.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. David Hirsch, Jeffrey's pediatrician, has another young
patient with a pump, a 16-year-old-boy who is doing very well with
it after two years. His spasticity is the result of an accident and
subsequent brain damage.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would like to see it done more,'' Hirsch said. ``But it is
important for people to be carefully evaluated first.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like it because it is another alternative in terms of
therapy and to improve function and quality of life. Ultimately it
may decrease other medical costs if it reduces other
complications'' such as surgeries and medications.
</P>
<P>
   Jeffrey's parents were delighted that their insurance company
approved the evaluation and trial. During the past three weeks, the
Steiners and their doctors made many long phone calls to Cigna
HealthCare of Arizona, their insurance company, to explain the
medical benefits and how money would be saved in the long run. On
Friday, Cigna authorized the pump for Jeffrey.
</P>
<P>
   Timmons, CEO of Los Ninos, was delighted: ``I would hope that
other health care plans will follow Cigna's lead, and that more
children are evaluated for the Baclofen therapy,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Jeffrey could receive the pump within a couple of weeks, but not
until the family weighs whether there are other medical risks to
the boy. &QL; 
MEDICINE VS. INSURERS
</P>
<P>
   The Baclofen pump is one example of a new technology aggravating
the relationships between insurers, doctors and patients, according
to health care experts. Sales of new medical devices in the United
States rose 30 percent over the past five years, outpacing the 22
percent general rise in health care spending, according to a recent
``New York Times'' story. Insurance companies balk at paying the
initial high costs for the pump and other new devices, even though
they may save money in the long run.
</P>
<P>
   Porter and Myers both commented that they believe any changes in
policy involving new technologies will have to be consumer-driven.
If insurance companies, CRS or AHCCCS hear from 100 or more upset
parents who can't get their children evaluated, that in itself
could help change the policy, Myers said.
</P>
<P>
   Krach says that generally insurance companies approve it, after
she makes the case that it isn't experimental and that it is FDA
approved.
</P>
<P>
   Being frustrated and persistent helped Alice Wilson of Kingman
get help for her daughter, Danah, 24. She only wishes her daughter,
who has had cerebral palsy since birth, had received the implanted
pump when she was younger. After two years and a mountain of
paperwork, her daughter underwent implant surgery in December.
</P>
<P>
   ``She is communicating and enjoying life more,'' Wilson said.
Danah then spoke for herself, agreeing that she now feels much
better. So much better, in fact, that a previously scheduled back
surgery has been canceled.
</P>
<P>
   Six months ago Danah couldn't speak in a way that strangers
could understand. She was taking three different muscle relaxants,
and was undermedicated or overmedicated at various times.
</P>
<P>
   Danah tells her mother she hopes to live on her own someday. Her
mother prays she is able to do that. They believe in good breaks
now. &QL; 
PUMP RAISES HOPES
</P>
<P>
   Jeffrey Steiner Jr. was able to get a temporary break in life on
April 12, as the drug Baclofen was injected into his spinal canal
and his muscles relaxed. But it was temporary; eight hours later
the effects of the medicine wore off.
</P>
<P>
   With the Baclofen pump, there is hope that, once his muscles
relax, he might be able to breathe normally and not require his
oxygen bottle. He might be able to swallow, or eat solid foods.
</P>
<P>
   Could he walk and talk again? His parents don't dream for that
right now. Most say that will probably never happen in his case.
But for Sara Smith, it's a possibility.
</P>
<P>
   A more realistic dream for Jeffrey is that he be spared the
torture of his constant involuntary workout and the total
dependence it causes.
</P>
<P>
   At age 3, Jeffrey's parents were told it might be better to
institutionalize him and then move on with their own lives. That's
a necessary choice for many. But Jeffrey Sr. couldn't do that,
believing it would have been like signing a death sentence for his
son.
</P>
<P>
   Things are looking up now, he believes. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
