<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-MARINERS-375&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EL DUQUE FINDS THAT LIFE IN BIG CITY CAN BE BRUTAL 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By JACK CURRY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Orlando Hernandez ambled toward the dugout after his
miserable day had ended Saturday, resembling a wayward tourist lost
in Central Park. He pulled off his New York Yankee cap, rubbed his
bald head and looked as if he did not belong. When the fans gave
the bruised Hernandez a rousing ovation, the scene seemed even more
incongruous.
</P>
<P>
   Give Hideki Irabu a reprieve following Friday night's
masterpiece. But what about El Duque? What is wrong with El Duque?
The usually cool pitcher could not last beyond a disaster of a
fifth inning and was pummeled during an ugly 14-5 loss to the
Seattle Mariners at Yankee Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   As the Yankees have won 12 of their last 17 games and rumbled
along in first place, their winning has often obscured some
problems. One problem that has evolved is Hernandez, who has
allowed 26 earned runs in his last 28 2/3 innings to fatten his
earned run average from a puny 2.51 to a portly 6.28. Saturday was
no mirage because El Duque has pitched poorly in three of five
starts since opening up 2-0.
</P>
<P>
   Even though the Yankees insisted that Hernandez simply lost his
rhythm and did not throw crisp breaking pitches in a six-run fifth
inning, the pitcher was so upset that he bolted the clubhouse
without addressing reporters. Hernandez's locker was barren, but
the first-base coach Jose Cardenal, the pitcher's interpreter, sat
in front of the empty locker and playfully asked and answered
questions by himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``El Duque, they want to know why you left,'' Cardenal said.
</P>
<P>
   Then Cardenal made his voice deeper and explained that Hernandez
was perturbed with himself.
</P>
<P>
   That was obvious. Usually, Hernandez is engaging and it was very
surprising that he was unavailable. Perhaps he did not want to
recapitulate the details of the fifth, an inning in which the
Mariners scored all six runs with two out. Hernandez was torched
for seven runs and 10 hits in four and two-thirds innings, the
third time this season he has allowed seven runs in a start.
</P>
<P>
   ``Apparently, he was disgusted with the way the game went,''
said Mel Stottlemyre, the pitching coach. ``I didn't talk to him
after the game. I can't tell you any more than that. I have to wait
until tomorrow to talk to him myself.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   On a lazy, gray afternoon on which umbrellas were almost always
poised, Hernandez sputtered while Freddy Garcia survived. Garcia, a
22-year-old right-hander who was sent to Seattle last year as part
of the Randy Johnson trade with Houston, left with a 9-1 cushion in
the sixth after Chili Davis hit a line drive off his right
shoulder. The rookie was charged with three runs in five and
two-thirds innings, which is ordinary, yet Garcia was the most
impressive pitcher of the day.
</P>
<P>
   Hernandez was close to duplicating's Garcia performance as the
Yankees trailed by only 1-0 in the the fifth.
</P>
<P>
   But with two outs and no one on base, Hernandez allowed Brian
Hunter's single, and that started a frustrating procession of six
straight Mariners reaching base against him. All six scored as
David Bell, Ken Griffey Jr. and David Segui singled in runs, John
Mabry had a run-scoring double and Tom Lampkin looped a two-run
double off Tony Fossas. It was 7-0. It was not a pretty sight,
especially for Hernandez.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he had a good rhythm for a while, and then he lost it
and got disgusted and didn't regroup,'' Stottlemyre said. ``He had
good stuff. I think he let things bother him and things got out of
control.''
</P>
<P>
   Very out of control. But the Yankees, who have watched Hernandez
baffle teams with his array of pitches and his high leg kick and
funky delivery, refused to concede that anything is wrong.
</P>
<P>
   They said that Saturday was a bad day, ignoring the fact that it
has been a bad three weeks for Hernandez.
</P>
<P>
   ``They hit some of his breaking stuff,'' said Don Zimmer, the
interim manager. ``I'm not going to worry about that. The next time
he's liable to pitch a shutout.''
</P>
<P>
   After Hernandez departed, the game disintegrated into a display
of pathetic middle relief. The Yankees sliced their deficit to 9-4
with three runs in the sixth, but Jay Tessmer, who was blitzed for
six runs in two innings, could not stop the Mariners, and the game
took almost four hours to complete. By then, Hernandez was
showered, dressed and had his car keys ready. He knew his way to
the parking lot.
</P>
<P>
   ``He looked pretty disappointed,'' David Cone said. ``He wasn't
happy about it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
