<SLUG> BC-BKN-LAKERS-NOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TONE DEAF? LAKERS WILL HEAR O'NEAL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   INGLEWOOD _ It won't take long for the Lakers to gauge their
chances in today's opener of their first-round playoff series. Just
look to the big fella.
</P>
<P>
   Shaquille O'Neal is at his best, his most focused, his meanest
when the playoffs arrive. You can usually see it in his face, and
in his scoring totals. O'Neal's intensity was noticeably ratched up
two weeks ago against Portland, and with the Lakers following his
lead, they routed the Blazers to start a four-game winning streak.
</P>
<P>
   ``Shaq sets that tone,'' Derek Fisher said. ``If he comes out
with an aggressive mentality on both ends, then he sets the tone
for everybody.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think you can look at games over the years that we've lost
and look at Shaquille's play and how he starts a game, you can kind
of determine how we play from there. He's gonna score 30 with his
eyes closed, but if he scores 30 and he's blocking shots and he's
rebounding and he's being a presence in the middle, then that's the
Shaquille we can win with.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Shaquille that just averages 30 points just because he has
that ability doesn't do us a lot of good. We need the dominant
Shaquille, the one that plays defense, blocks shots, helps us
rotate on defense and is basically captain of the ship.''
</P>
<P>
   Coach Kurt Rambis said it's O'Neal's responsibility to set the
tone.
</P>
<P>
   ``I still firmly believe that as he goes, our team goes,''
Rambis said. ``We put a lot of pressure on him as the leader of
this ballclub, and the hub of this team to deliver for us at both
ends of the court. That's what superstars do, they step it up in
the playoffs because they know they have to. I think those last few
ballgames we played are an indication, he's ready to go and he's
ready to play.''
</P>
<P>
   Daily dose of Chuck: From the mouth of the NBA's reigning
talker, Houston's Charles Barkley, came these highlights Saturday:
</P>
<P>
   On the presumption he has little time left to win a
championship: ``I wish everybody would quit telling me what I think
and I feel. I would love to win the championship, but you can be
rest assured, I'm not gonna kill myself if I don't win.''
</P>
<P>
   On the early hype surrounding the Lakers: ``I didn't think they
were the favorites, they're not the favorites.... They obviously
felt they were overrated if they made all those changes.... The
team they started the season with, you all were swinging on their
vines like you L.A. people have a tendency to do. They've got a lot
of talent, but they weren't the best team in the West.''
</P>
<P>
   On the trade that brought Glen Rice to L.A.: ``I think they
really do miss Elden Campbell and Eddie Jones. I think they've
proven that. We knew they were gonna miss Elden Campbell. I think
they missed him all season.''
</P>
<P>
   Jewelry challenged: O'Neal isn't concerned that the Rockets'
Scottie Pippen has six championship rings and Hakeem Olajuwon two.
</P>
<P>
   ``But,'' the ring-less O'Neal said, ``I'm on the same page with
Barkley.''
</P>
<P>
   No Dionne Warwick: Rambis bristled when a reporter asked if
Houston's recent 22-point victory over the Lakers would give the
Rockets an edge in confidence.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ask them, I've got no idea what they're thinking,'' he said.
``If I could know what people are thinking, I'd be in Vegas right
now.''
</P>
<P>
   Ouch report: Both teams enter today's game without significant
injuries.
</P>
<P>
   Fisher said his left shoulder, wrenched in practice on Friday,
felt fine and he was able to practice without limitations, making
him probable for today's game.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's better. I got some treatment (Friday), iced it a couple
times, took some anti-inflammatories, it felt a lot better,'' he
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
