<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-08 23:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9825 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-SUNS-CASSTEVENS-A     05-08 0718
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-SUNS-CASSTEVENS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SABONIS BECOMES BIG OBSTACLE FOR SUNS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID CASSTEVENS  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PORTLAND - If he yelled the instruction once he yelled it a
half-dozen times. Danny Ainge shouted, ``Thumb up Sabonis!''
</P>
<P>
   I'm not sure what that means, but I wouldn't do it.
</P>
<P>
   Why make the big guy mad?
</P>
<P>
   Arvydas Sabonis is a huge man. He is not to be trifled with. If
the Portland center appears on TV to be bigger than other players
you should see him in person and Luc Longley and the Suns got a
close-up look at the Portland's aging giant.
</P>
<P>
   There he was, big as Eastern Europe, loping ponderously up and
down the court.
</P>
<P>
   The man with the bad haircut and soft hands dropped a baby hook
gently into the net. He moved outside and swished a jumper. More
than once he deftly flipped the ball off to a teammate with a quick
no-look Globetrotter pass.
</P>
<P>
   When the Trail Blazers' 7-foot-3, 300- pound post man pinned a
Suns' missed shot against the glass and seized the ball with one
hand, as if picking grapefruit, the Rose Garden crowd ooooooohhhhed
and aaaaahed and celebrated the impressive feat with an
oh-my-goodness grin.
</P>
<P>
   Big man.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's as big as Shaq,'' said Joe Kleine.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, bigger,'' Ainge said.
</P>
<P>
   And the visitors who haven't beaten the Blazers in four tries
had no answer for him. The Suns hired Longley to match up with
other teams' big men but he didn't in Game 1 of the first-round
playoff series, which the Trail Blazers won, 95-85, after a late
scoring run, led by Isaiah Rider.
</P>
<P>
   Sabonis scored 12 points and grabbed eight rebounds. He posted
career-playoffs highs in assists (8) and steals (3). He blocked
three shots.
</P>
<P>
   Longley took six shots, made one and scored two points. The Suns
finally gave up on him in the fourth quarter when they went to a
smaller lineup.
</P>
<P>
   Sabonis is an interesting story. He was born Dec. 19-20-21, 1964
in Lithuania. The son of a tailor, Arvydas divided his time as a
youth learning five languages and growing. Some days he did both at
once.
</P>
<P>
   Sabonis became one of the biggest names in international
basketball. He was the best player in Europe in the mid-1980s. The
Trail Blazers drafted Sabonis in 1986 but it wasn't until four
years ago, when he was past his prime, that he joined the team as a
31-year-old NBA rookie.
</P>
<P>
   Blazer fans always will wonder what if. What if Sabonis had been
the center when Portland reached the NBA finals in 1990 and 1992.
The Blazers lost both series with center Kevin Duckworth, which
produced the philosophical question that sounds like a Groucho Marx
joke.
</P>
<P>
   What's a Duckworth? Answer: not much.
</P>
<P>
   Sabonis isn't comfortable in the limelight. He hid in the
training room after the game, leaving his teammates to put their
spin on a game the Suns had a chance to win even though they didn't
shoot well (Rex Chapman 3-for-12) and were playing in an arena
where the Blazers lost only three times this year.
</P>
<P>
   The Suns were right there. They led by one with 7{ minutes left.
Then Rider went to work, leading Portland on a 13-2 run. The
Blazers fed off the energy of their temperamental star. Unable to
answer, the Suns had to sense it was over when Sabonis put up a
hook shot. The ball rolled lazily off the rim, but Brian Grant's
tip-in increased the lead to 10.
</P>
<P>
   Portland presents a big problem. The Trail Blazers are young and
athletic and have what seems to be an inexhaustable supply of
players. If it's not Sabonis it's Rider. If not Rider it's Grant or
Rasheed Wallace or Walt Williams or Jim Jackson who scored a 12
points as a reserve, 10 in the fourth quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Is there no end? Where do they keep coming from? The bench? The
stands?
</P>
<P>
   Before tipoff, Ainge looked around the arena. When his eyes fell
on a fellow sitting in a section behind the Suns bench, Danny
grinned.
</P>
<P>
   He was a Blazers fan, but he looked like a refugee from the Age
of Aquarius _ long beard, shoulder-length hair, headband, tie-dyed
T-shirt.
</P>
<P>
   Ainge didn't think the guy would get into the game but he looked
so familiar, so much like a former Blazer did years ago, he had to
ask.
</P>
<P>
   ``Is that Bill Walton?'' &QL; 
David Casstevens can be reached at (602) 444-8635 or at
david.casstevens(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
