<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-DONATE-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHINA PROBE FOCUSES ON CASH FOR VISAS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY KAMMER  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Johnny Chung, the Chinese-American at the center of a Democratic
fund-raising scandal, has told congressional investigators that a
former U.S. Embassy official in Beijing received a bag of cash from
a Chinese beer company executive.
</P>
<P>
   Chung is expected to tell a House committee Tuesday that he saw
an executive of the Haomen Group Co. hand the money to Charles
Parish, who ran the embassy's visa section from 1994 to 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Chung's testimony before the House Committee on Government
Reform and Oversight is expected to center on Chinese attempts to
funnel money to the 1996 Clinton-Gore campaign.
</P>
<P>
   A source close to the investigation said that Chung's
information about Parish, as well as other revelations about Parish
in ``The Arizona Republic,'' have triggered a separate
investigation into the former State Department officer.
</P>
<P>
   ``The State Department has received a subpoena for materials
relating to Mr. Parish,'' said the source, who spoke on condition
of anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Republic'' reported in March that Parish, who served at
the embassy from 1994 to 1996, repeatedly violated State Department
rules by accepting favors from the Chinese-government-owned
corporation that owns the COFCO Chinese Cultural Center in Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   Parish acknowledged that he accepted free lodging at corporate
apartments in Las Vegas and Norwalk, Calif., during the time he was
providing visa assistance to COFCO executive Elizabeth Mann.
</P>
<P>
   Mann, a Chinese-born American citizen, is the top executive in
Phoenix for COFCO, a corporate giant that is based in Beijing and
is directed by the Chinese Ministry of Foreign Trade.
</P>
<P>
   A 1997 ``Los Angeles Times'' story about Chung's emergence as
one of the biggest contributors to the Democratic Party quoted
Parish as saying he was ``a good friend of Johnny's.''
</P>
<P>
   Between 1994 and 1996, Chung visited the White House at least 49
times, often leading groups of Chinese businessmen. He also
contributed $366,000 to the Democratic National Committee, which
helped him arrange the visits.
</P>
<P>
   Now congressional investigators suspect that Parish accepted
cash in return for his influence in issuing visas to Chinese
businessmen allied to Chung.
</P>
<P>
   ``The committee views with great concern the ease with which
Johnny Chung was able to manipulate the system to obtain visas for
foreign nationals,'' the House Committee reported last year. The
report did not mention Parish.
</P>
<P>
   ``In 1995 and 1996 Chung formed seven companies in Los Angeles
with seven Chinese nationals,'' the report says. ``All of them
attended DNC and Clinton/Gore fund-raisers with Chung at which the
president made appearances. Most of them sent Chung large sums of
money.''
</P>
<P>
   Chung has informed investigators that Parish attended a 1995
fund-raiser in California as Chung's guest.
</P>
<P>
   Parish's father, speaking Friday from his Las Vegas home, said
his son is traveling on the East Coast and could not be reached for
comment.
</P>
<P>
   Parish, 52, who attended Arizona State University from 1968 to
1974 and earned a degree from Chapman College in Orange, Calif.,
insisted in March that the favors he received from Mann did not
affect his visa decisions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Did I ever abuse my position? No,'' said Parish, who retired
last year from the State Department. ``I'm very emphatic about
that. I'm very clear about that.''
</P>
<P>
   Chung has been cooperating with federal investigators under a
plea agreement. He has admitted making $30,000 in illegal
contributions to Democrats, including $20,000 to the Clinton-Gore
re-election campaign.
</P>
<P>
   He has also told federal investigators that he received $300,000
from China's chief military intelligence officer to give to the
Democratic Party for the Clinton re-election campaign. But Chung
said he gave only $35,000 of the money to the DNC and put the rest
into a bank account.
</P>
<P>
   Congressional and Justice Department investigators are trying to
determine whether the Chinese government secretly funneled campaign
contributions to the United States as part of an effort to gain
political influence.
</P>
<P>
   The House committee has reported that Chung escorted Haomen
executives Shi Zeng Chen and Yei Jun He to a 1994 White House
reception and that the executives had their photographs taken with
President Clinton and first lady Hillary Rodham Clinton. Haomen is
China's second-largest beer producer.
</P>
<P>
   According to the ``Washington Post,'' Chung has told Senate
investigators that one of the photos was used in an ad to sell
Haomen beer in China and that the publicity generated by that ad
gave Chung ``a formidable reputation in China as being
well-connected in U.S. political circles.''
</P>
<P>
   The Haomen Group wired $150,000 to Chung from a Bank of China
account in March 1995, three days before Chung wrote a $50,000
check to the DNC. Two days after that, he went to the White House
and presented the check to Hillary Clinton's chief of staff,
Margaret Williams. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
