<SLUG> BC-BBN-METS-DIAMONDBACKS-400&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YOSHII'S MOVE HAS METS BACK ON TRACK 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By JASON DIAMOS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX _ Seventeen inches may not sound like much. But it has
made all the difference in Masato Yoshii's season.
</P>
<P>
   Yoshii has been near perfect almost from the moment he moved
that far on the pitching rubber two starts ago, throwing 12 innings
without surrendering a run. But even though Yoshii tossed six
scoreless innings Saturday, the New York Mets still needed Armando
Benitez to relieve John Franco in the ninth inning before they
could close out a 4-2 victory over the Arizona Diamondbacks.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I was the manager, I would have brought him in today,
too,'' said Franco, who waited on the mound to literally _ and
perhaps symbolically _ hand the ball over to Benitez in what could
be a precursor to an eventual shift in roles.
</P>
<P>
   Benitez recorded the final two outs _ both on hard-hit fly balls
_ to strand the tying runs on first and second for his first save
with the Mets. And then Franco, who had allowed a two-run home run
to Jay Bell in the ninth in a nonsave situation, said that Benitez
told him, ``You pick me up, I pick you up.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the biggest pickup of the day, however, was provided by
Yoshii, considering that the Mets (18-12) had lost three straight
games, including a 14-7 setback here Friday night.
</P>
<P>
   Under the retractable Bank One Ballpark dome, Yoshii (2-3)
extended his scoreless string to 12 innings _ all coinciding with
his move on the rubber _ while allowing only two singles Saturday
before he left the game with a cracked nail on his right middle
finger.
</P>
<P>
   Gone was the wildness that Yoshii had experienced before he
changed the starting position of his motion from the first-base
side of the rubber to the third-base side. Of his 77 pitches
Saturday, 53 went for strikes. And Yoshii left in style, retiring
the last 12 batters he faced, quashing _ for now _ talk of his
being replaced in the rotation any time soon.
</P>
<P>
   In his last two starts, Yoshii has lowered his earned run
average from 7.52 to 4.73. He said he could not explain the rapid
turnaround. Catcher Mike Piazza said that Yoshii was just being
more aggressive.
</P>
<P>
   But ever since Yoshii shifted on the rubber, he has become a
different pitcher.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know it makes a big difference in the angle of his
pitches,'' said Manager Bobby Valentine, who had asked Yoshii to
move to the first-base side in spring training.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Valentine noticed that Yoshii's position on the rubber might
have been causing his shuto _ the Japanese word for a shooting
fastball _ to sail out of the strike zone, and asked him to move
back to the third-base side 10 days ago. Since then, the
34-year-old Japanese right-hander has been almost unhittable.
</P>
<P>
   In Yoshii's previous outing _ with his spot in the rotation in
jeopardy _ he allowed three hits and two walks in six scoreless
innings. Saturday Yoshii was even more precise. The only walk he
allowed was to Bell in the first inning.
</P>
<P>
   The only runner to advance past first against Yoshii was Damian
Miller, who was sacrificed to second by pitcher Andy Benes after he
singled to lead off the third.
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately for Yoshii, Roger Cedeno was in right field
Saturday, not the limping Bobby Bonilla, because Miller was held at
second thanks to a tremendous diving, tumbling catch by Cedeno in
short right-center field on a ball hit by Tony Womack.
</P>
<P>
   The catch preserved the 1-0 lead that John Olerud had given
Yoshii in the first with his sixth homer of the season. The Mets
added an unearned run in the fifth, and Matt Franco drilled his
first homer of the year in the sixth to give Yoshii a 3-0 lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``When he was pitching at home with the guillotines sharpened,
Masato came up big,'' Valentine said, referring to Yoshii's last
start. ``And today we had lost three in a row and were going up
against a team that had banged out a thousand hits the night
before, and he gave up two hits. He's a pretty good pitcher. And,
yes, I think the move has made a big difference.''
</P>
<P>
   Even if it could be measured with a ruler.
</P>
</TEXT>
