u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-CHINA-2NDLD-WR     05-08 0771
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-CHINA-2NDLD-WRITETHRU-725(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANGRY PROTESTS IN SEVERAL CHINESE CITIES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (SUBS to update; 3rd graf is new.) (lh) 
 By ELISABETH ROSENTHAL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIJING _ Large, angry protests erupted around U.S. government
offices in several cities on Saturday as Chinese learned that NATO
bombs had hit their embassy in Belgrade, killing at least three
people sleeping inside.
</P>
<P>
   In Beijing, thousands of well-organized university students,
cheered on by other Beijing residents, held tense noisy protests on
the streets surrounding the U.S. Embassy, as police looked on. But
the initially peaceful march quickly turned violent, as small
groups of students and residents threw rocks through embassy
windows, pummeled cars belonging to embassy employees and burned
American flags.
</P>
<P>
   By dawn Sunday, the streets, guarded by thousands of police
officers, were quiet. But by 9 a.m., students by the tens of
thousands were streaming toward the U.S. Embassy, by bus, by subway
and on foot, to resume their impassioned march.
</P>
<P>
   It was the by far the largest anti-American demonstration in
China since well before President Nixon's historic visit to China
in 1972 and the largest political protest since the student rallies
in Tiananmen Square 10 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now we hate America,'' said Ma Zhang Lu, a 20-year-old male
student with shoulder-length dyed hair, who had just hurled a rock
at the embassy. ``China has been especially friendly to the
American people. But we have been rebuffed, and now the Americans
have broken international law.''
</P>
<P>
   The protests marked an extraordinary moment in a controlled
country where such outbursts are normally forbidden and almost
never occur, though Saturday's demonstrations clearly had some
measure of government approval.
</P>
<P>
   The protests also comes just two weeks after Buddhist Law, a
spiritual group seeking official recognition, held another huge
rally in the city center.
</P>
<P>
   In Shanghai, a large, chanting crowd threw rocks and bottles at
the U.S. Consulate. Similar demonstrations were reported in
Guangzhou. And in the southern city of Chengdu, protesters set a
fire at the U.S. consulate early Sunday, but it was put out. A
Chinese guard was reported hurt.
</P>
<P>
   In Beijing after nightfall on Saturday, large unruly throngs
roamed the embassy district, defying police requests to go home.
Several times crowds pushed against lines of police officers,
linked arm in arm, who held them away from the U.S. and British
embassies.
</P>
<P>
   At one point, a group of 50 demonstrators burst through police
lines, only to be stopped by a row of police five deep about 50
yards from the U.S. Embassy compound. The police, who did not carry
weapons, made no arrests.
</P>
<P>
   Late on Saturday afternoon, the U.S. Embassy ``strongly
protested'' inadequate police protection, after students were
allowed to press up against the embassy's street-side gates and
throw rocks through windows of an office building still holding 15
to 20 embassy staff members, including James Sasser, the U.S.
ambassador.
</P>
<P>
   Virtually all protesters said they thought the bombing was
intentional.
</P>
<P>
   The protests began early Saturday afternoon when angry people
started gathering on the tree-lined streets in front of the embassy
in Beijing. Around 4 p.m., they were joined by thousands of angry,
chanting students, not die hard Communist Party cadres but
thoroughly Westernized youths, wearing baseball caps and Nike sweat
pants.
</P>
<P>
   The Beijing students marched in groups of several hundred behind
their university banners carrying hand-painted signs, some in
English, like ``USA Nazi Killers'' and chanting slogans like ``The
blood of Chinese must be repaid.''
</P>
<P>
   Each group paused in front of the iron gate at the embassy, just
15 feet from its front door, to chant, sing patriotic songs and
deliver a variety of petitions.
</P>
<P>
   At first, an officer from the embassy's political section came
out solemnly to accept the papers. But the protests quickly turned
violent, as students from several universities pelted the embassy
with rocks and water bottles. Each broken light and window was
greeted with thunderous cheers.
</P>
<P>
   Although most students returned to their campuses around
nightfall, many remained in the embassy district, and by 9 p.m.
raucous students and other demonstrators had regrouped near the
embassy, smashing cars with U.S. Embassy plates, identifiable by
the red character for embassy, followed by the number 224. An
American flag was burned outside Sasser's residence.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Although police presence was heavy, the officers, generally
equipped at most with cell phones, at first did little to stop the
rock throwing. The Embassy warned Americans living in Beijing to
increase personal security and to avoid any protests.
</P>
<P>
   As the fever pitch increased, reinforcements were brought in and
made some serious efforts, though often with little effect. Police
stood by as hundreds of protesters burned an American flag.
</P>
<P>
   The well-planned afternoon march was clearly condoned by the
government. Official student organizations arranged for buses, and
students said that the Beijing Municipal government had approved
the protest.
</P>
<P>
   Foreign reporters, who are generally shooed away by public
security officers from even minor car accidents, were given freedom
to interview and photograph protesters on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   But the anger was deep and genuine both from the students and
the thousands of Beijing residents who apparently gathered
spontaneously, many with children, after they had found out about
the protest from friends or on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a young Chinese I've always felt a very friendly attitude
toward the U.S. and its people,'' said Wang Bin, an interpreter,
who decided early Saturday afternoon to stand peacefully outside
the embassy in protest. ``But now I feel a deep internal disgust
and anger.''
</P>
<P>
   Chinese public opinion has been violently opposed to the NATO
war over Kosovo since the start of the bombing, in some part
because the government-controlled press did not report on the
Serbian purge of Kosovo Albanians.
</P>
<P>
   But most also agree with their government that Kovoso's internal
ethnic conflicts should not be solved by ``a foreign bully''
wielding bombs. Thanks to the bombing, they now regard President
Slobodan Milosevic of Yugoslavia as a hero for standing up to NATO
and the Serbs as an oppressed people.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd always thought that Kosovo should be considered an
internal affair and that NATO shouldn't be there,'' said Guo
Qionghu, a student at the National Minorities University. ``But
today this issue has fallen directly on the heads of the Chinese
people, and that's why our emotions are so aroused.''
</P>
<P>
   The evening television news carried China's official
condemnations of the attack as ``barbarian'' and a ``gross
violation of China's sovereignty'' and featured the students'
demonstrations.
</P>
<P>
   The three known Chinese killed in the Belgrade attack were
identified as Shao Yunhuan, a 40-year-old woman who was a reporter
for the New China News Agency; Xu Xinghu, the resident
correspondent in Belgrade for the newspaper Guangming Daily, and
Xu's wife, Zhu Yin, an employee in the advertising section of the
newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   In a bitter interview on national television, the chief of the
New China News Agency praised Ms. Shao as a ``good comrade and
outstanding reporter.'' The editor of the Guangming Daily said the
dead couple had only been married a year and that Xu's final report
had appeared in Saturday's newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   Before being trapped in the embassy compound, Sasser had been
called in to the Chinese Foreign Ministry to receive its strong
protest.
</P>
<P>
   In a country where there is often a huge divide between official
pronouncements and public opinion, China now appeared to react as
one.
</P>
<P>
   ``They did it on purpose,'' said Yu He, a bank employee in
Shanghai, adding. ``Of course I'm angry now they're attacking us
too.''
</P>
<P>
   Even before the protests, a Chinese Internet chat room about
Kosovo that has been popular in recent weeks was deluged with
vituperative messages, including ``Tonight, let's lay siege to the
U.S. Embassy.''
</P>
<P>
   Liberal Chinese who have supported engagement with the United
States called reporters with a deep sense of disbelief and
betrayal, looking for explanations. Students at the Beijing
demonstration, some of whom had welcomed President Clinton to China
a year ago, said they also felt betrayed.
</P>
<P>
   Kicking off the protest, student delegations from China's most
prominent universities _ Beijing University, Qinghua University and
People's University _ marched in lines, waving red flags and
banners, chanting slogans like ``Down with Imperialism'' and
singing patriotic songs.
</P>
<P>
   Some students carried hand-painted signs condemning NATO or the
United States and wore targets like those worn in protest by
civilians in Serbia.
</P>
<P>
   The crowd turned violent when the group of 200 students from
Beijing Polytechnic turned onto the road that bisects the two
grassy office compounds of the U.S. Embassy. Piles of rocks and
cement squares lined the sidewalks, which are being re-laid as part
of the campaign to dress up Beijing for the 50th anniversary this
fall.
</P>
<P>
   The building material along the narrow street provided ample
weaponry for the students in the dense crowd, who hurled the rocks
through the windows of the U.S. Embassy's visa office and an
administrative building just behind the fence.
</P>
<P>
   The embassy is a hodgepodge of older buildings in three
different sites, all within 15 to 20 feet of the road. The street
that divides the two main office sites, home to the day's protests,
has been closed to nonembassy automotive traffic since the bombings
in Africa last summer.
</P>
<P>
   Police had clearly been girding since early in the day, when
they closed a nearby popular outdoor market, Silk Alley, where
tourists flock to buy Beanie Babies, Chinese qipao dresses and fake
Prada bags.
</P>
<P>
   But they were certainly unprepared for the outpouring of anger
that gathered throughout the day and into the late evening, when
thousands of angry protesters moved from the U.S. Embassy to the
nearby British Embassy and on to the U.S. Ambassador's house.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
