<HEADLINE>
RANGERS' RELIEVER ZIMMERMAN STIFLES TORONTO
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHNNY PAUL 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   TORONTO _ Toronto's Jim Fregosi did not attempt to feign
disinterest when the discussion shifted to Rangers right-hander
Jeff Zimmerman.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, the Blue Jays manager fulfilled his obligation to
the Canadian media and their local-boy-makes-good slant after he
was informed that Zimmerman hails from Kelowna, British Columbia.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, and he plays hockey? Well, the way he pitched today,''
Fregosi said, ``I wished the hell he'd go play hockey.''
</P>
<P>
   Zimmerman, the Canadian-turned-Rangers' savior, once again stood
on his head, to use hockey vernacular, in a 4-3 victory yesterday
at SkyDome.
</P>
<P>
   He protected the Rangers' one-run lead _ built on Rafael
Palmeiro's seventh-inning, run-scoring double _ with two scoreless
innings before manager Johnny Oates summoned closer John Wetteland
to record his 10th save.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Ziminator,'' as Rangers right-hander Tim Crabtree refers
to the former TCU pitcher, greeted the media afterward with an 0.84
earned-run average.
</P>
<P>
   ``There can't be anyone in baseball pitching more quality
innings in crunch time than he has this year,'' said Oates, who
appears willing to stitch the letter ``S'' on Zimmerman's chest and
hang a blue cape from the reliever's shoulders.
</P>
<P>
   Why not?
</P>
<P>
   American League batters are hitting .114 (8-for-70) with 16
strikeouts through 21 1/3 innings against Zimmerman.
</P>
<P>
   Oates demonstrated his faith by letting Zimmerman pitch to three
left-handed hitters _ Shawn Green, Carlos Delgado and Willie Greene
_ in the eighth inning, while left-hander Mike Munoz continued to
warm in the bullpen.
</P>
<P>
   ``I ain't taking any chances,'' Oates said. ``He hasn't done
anything to deserve to be taken out of that game. I don't know how
any manager could have any more confidence in anyone right now.''
</P>
<P>
   Zimmerman induced an infield popup from Green before issuing a
two-out walk to Delgado on a 3-2 pitch.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's poise,'' Crabtree said of the walk. ``He knew he didn't
want to let Delgado beat him there. That's my protege. He's
everything I wanted to be.''
</P>
<P>
   Delgado advanced 90 feet and moved into scoring position when
Mark Dalesandro's weak ground ball rolled into right field for a
seeing-eye single, but Zimmerman retired Greene on strikes to
``Ziminate'' the threat.
</P>
<P>
   Eight Canadian media reporters waited almost an hour after the
contest to speak with Zimmerman, who went for his postgame workout
almost immediately after the final pitch.
</P>
<P>
   ``I appreciate you guys waiting around for me,'' Zimmerman said.
``I'm sorry I kept you waiting.''
</P>
<P>
   One of Zimmerman's first response's revealed his level-headed
approach to his early success.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every day I pinch myself and thank the Lord for giving me this
opportunity,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Zimmerman, too, wondered whether Oates would let him face the
Blue Jays' left-handed hitters in the crucial eighth.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was definitely on my mind, but I wanted to stay in there,''
Zimmerman admitted. ``I knew I could get them out.''
</P>
<P>
   Zimmerman's performance overshadowed right-hander Mike Morgan's
six-inning start, the defensive play of reserve Jon Shave at
shortstop and the three runs batted in by left fielder Rusty Greer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think there are enough adequate words,'' Oates said,
``to describe what Jeff has done for our club this year.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
