<SLUG> BC-FBN-TUINEI-MEMORIAL-TEX </SLUG>
 
Tuinei remembered for big heart, smile (For use by NYTimes News
Service clients) 
By CLARENCE E. HILL JR. 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
ADDISON, Texas _ According to his closest friends, former Cowboys
offensive tackle Mark Tuinei lived a life full of smiles and
laughter.
<TEXT>
<P>
   And that's how he was remembered at a 11/2-hour private memorial
service yesterday at Trinity Christian Academy attended by about
450 former teammates, coaches, friends and family members.
</P>
<P>
   Tuinei, 39, was found dead early Thursday in his car outside his
Plano home. The cause of death is unknown.
</P>
<P>
   His life was celebrated by four former teammates: Cowboys
quarterback Jason Garrett, Cowboys fullback Daryl Johnston, Cowboys
deep snapper Dale Hellestrae and Dolphins guard Kevin Gogan.
Cowboys team chaplain John Webber gave the eulogy.
</P>
<P>
   Interspersed by tears, the players shared jokes and stories
about Tuinei, at times filling the auditorium with laughter. The
unifying theme was that the heart of the 6-foot-5, 320-pound Tuinei
was as big as his body.
</P>
<P>
   ``You couldn't have found a better friend,'' Johnston said. ``He
was always there for you. You think of the big man, the big heart,
the big head, the big smile and the big laugh. This is a void that
is not going to be filled. He is irreplaceable. But we got our
memories.''
</P>
<P>
   Garrett said Tuinei, known as the team's chief practical
jokester, was special because he related to all teammates.
Free-agent rookies, all-pro players, blacks, whites, coaches,
trainers and equipment managers were touched by Tuinei's friendship
and pranks, Garrett said.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one crammed more life than Tuinei in 39 years,'' Garrett
said. ``Thank God for letting me cross paths with the guy.''
</P>
<P>
   Gogan, who played alongside Tuinei from 1987 through 1993, said:
``It's not how Tuinei died but how he lived. I'm privileged that my
children knew him. But I feel cheated that they didn't know him
longer.''
</P>
<P>
   Among the Cowboys players at the service were Troy Aikman,
Emmitt Smith, Kevin Smith, Eric Bjornson and Leon Lett, as well as
owner Jerry Jones. Among the former Cowboys attending were Everson
Walls, Drew Pearson, John Dutton, Tom Rafferty, Nate Newton and
Tony Tolbert, and former coach Barry Switzer.
</P>
<P>
   Pictures of Tuinei with a variety of friends and former
teammates were displayed in the foyer. Four framed items surrounded
the casket inside the auditorium, including one of his Cowboys
jerseys.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Pulemau Tuinei was born March 31, 1960, in Oceanside,
Calif., to Ane and Tumuauatasi Tuinei Sr. Mark Tuinei grew up in
Hawaii on Oahu, where he starred in football, basketball and track
at Punahou High School. He was selected Hawaii prep lineman of the
year and was the state's shot put champion as a senior.
</P>
<P>
   Tuinei played his first two college seasons at UCLA before
transferring to the University of Hawaii. He married Ponolani
Pavich on Feb. 19, 1984. They did not have children.
</P>
<P>
   Tuinei joined the Cowboys in 1983 as a rookie free agent. After
playing various positions on offense and defense for much of his
first four seasons, Tuinei settled at left tackle midway through
the 1986 season. He was a mainstay at left tackle for 11 seasons,
which included Super Bowl titles in 1992, 1993 and 1995.
</P>
<P>
   His career came to an end after the 1997 season as a result of
chronic knee problems. He was released by the Cowboys in April
1998.
</P>
<P>
   Tuinei, however, was a frequent visitor to Valley Ranch and
remained friends with several players.
</P>
<P>
   He is survived by his wife; his mother and father; four sisters,
Louise, Frances, Katherine and Julia; one brother, Tom; and 26
nieces and nephews.
</P>
<P>
   Collin County medical examiner William Rohr is awaiting results
of toxicology tests, which could be done by tomorrow, on the cause
of death.
</P>
<P>
   The family plans to take Tuinei's body to Hawaii for burial next
week.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
