<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-LANDRY-LEUKEMIA-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FORMER COWBOYS COACH LANDRY HOSPITALIZED WITH LEUKEMIA
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MICHAEL WEISSENSTEIN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Legendary Cowboys coach Tom Landry has been hospitalized and is
undergoing chemotherapy after he was found to have leukemia,
friends said yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   Landry, 74, who led the team to a record 20 consecutive winning
seasons in his 29 years as head coach, recently had suffered from
fatigue and a bout with pneumonia, former Cowboys players and staff
said.
</P>
<P>
   Blood tests revealed leukemia, a cancer that affects blood and
bone-marrow cells, and Landry was admitted to a Dallas-area
hospital on Tuesday, friends said.
</P>
<P>
   Former Cowboys quarterback Roger Staubach said he learned Monday
night from Landry's wife, Alicia, that his former coach had been
found to have the disease.
</P>
<P>
   ``He had been feeling tired lately. Now they have it diagnosed
early, and they're real positive about it,'' Staubach said
yesterday. ``He's getting treatment right now.''
</P>
<P>
   Former Cowboys president and general manager Tex Schramm learned
of Landry's illness yesterday at his home in Key West, Fla., he
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a terrible thing, but he's a tough guy, he'll fight it
out,'' Schramm said.
</P>
<P>
   Leukemia strikes about 29,000 people each year. The cancer
causes blood cells to reproduce uncontrollably and accumulate in
the bone marrow, preventing a sufficient number of normal blood
cells from being produced.
</P>
<P>
   Leukemia is typically treated with chemotherapy, and 47 percent
of patients survive five years after a diagnosis.
</P>
<P>
   The prognosis for Landry is good, Staubach said. He said the
former coach is expected to leave the hospital ``soon,'' but
declined to specify when Landry might be released.
</P>
<P>
   There are four major types of leukemia, but friends did not say
which type was affecting Landry. Older adults make up the highest
proportion of leukemia patients, with more than half of all cases
occurring in people over 60.
</P>
<P>
   Symptoms include fatigue, frequent infections, weakness and
shortness of breath resulting from anemia.
</P>
<P>
   Landry, third all-time in NFL victories, began as the Cowboys
head coach with the franchise's initial season in 1960 and
continued through 1988. He ended his career with a 270-178-6
record, including playoffs, and led his team to a record 20
consecutive winning seasons from 1966 through 1985. Under Landry,
the Cowboys went to the Super Bowl five times, winning Super Bowl
VI and XII.
</P>
<P>
   Landry was inducted into the Pro Football Hall of Fame in 1990
and was included in the Cowboys' Ring of Honor in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   Since being fired by Cowboys owner Jerry Jones, Landry has
devoted his time to speaking engagements, appearances on behalf of
the Fellowship of Christian Athletes and evangelist Billy Graham,
and business interests with his son.
</P>
<P>
   Schramm, who hired Landry as coach, called the news shocking.
</P>
<P>
   ``But in a way, I knew that something was wrong,'' he said. ``I
saw Tom two weeks ago at his golf tournament and, in fact, I
introduced him at a dinner, and he didn't look good.''
</P>
<P>
   Landry played college football at the University of Texas, where
he met his wife. They had three children, Tom Jr., Kitty Landry
Phillips and the late Lisa Landry Childress. \Ntagtop:Michael
Weissenstein, (817) 390-7386
\Ntagbottom:weissenm\Nstar-telegram.com \Ntagtop:Staff writer
Clarence E. Hill Jr. contributed to this report.
</P>
<P>
   LEUKEMIA Leukemia, a cancer that affects the bone marrow and
blood cells, strikes approximately 29,000 people in the United
States each year. The malignant disease causes a patient's blood
cells to reproduce uncontrollably. Immature, useless cells
accumulate in the marrow, which cannot produce a sufficient number
of normal red and white blood cells and platelets.
</P>
<P>
   The cancerous cells can also invade the liver, spleen, lymph
nodes, kidneys and brain.
</P>
<P>
   The disease affects men, women and children of all ages. But
older adults make up the highest proportion of leukemia patients,
with more than half of all cases occurring in people over 60.
</P>
<P>
   It is typically treated with chemotherapy.
</P>
<P>
   There are about 140,000 leukemia patients in the United States.
Approximately 21,600 Americans die from the disease each year.
</P>
<P>
   Signs and symptoms include easy bleeding or bruising, paleness,
fatigue, frequent minor infections and poor healing of minor
scrapes and cuts.
</P>
<P>
   Anyone displaying these symptoms warrant medical examination,
including blood tests to diagnose leukemia.
</P>
<P>
   The causes of the disease are unknown.
</P>
<P>
   Sources: Leukemia Society of America, Merck Manual of Medical
Information
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
