<HEADLINE>
IN NEW ORLEANS, DEVELOPERS RUSH TO ADD HOTELS 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By SHAWN G. KENNEDY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW ORLEANS _ The enduring allure of the French Quarter coupled
with the city's role as host to such spirited street parties as
Mardi Gras and the annual New Orleans Jazz and Heritage Festival
have secured its place as a top vacation spot. But increasingly
travelers are in town on business _ at least for part of their
stay.
</P>
<P>
   The result has been a strong demand for hotel rooms by travelers
to conventions and trade shows. To meet that demand, 13 hotel
projects are in various stages of construction, 10 of them new
hotels and the rest expansions of existing hotels. Half a dozen
additional projects are in the preconstruction development phase.
All this activity follows the opening of a dozen new hotels over
the last three years.
</P>
<P>
   The New Orleans Metropolitan Convention and Visitors Bureau puts
the annual average occupancy rate at 75 percent, compared with 73
percent five years ago. In that time, 7,000 hotel rooms have been
added for a total of 28,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``People think of New Orleans as a tourist town,'' said John
Keeling, a hotel specialist in the Houston office of PKF
Consulting, a real estate consulting company. ``But now, first and
foremost, it is a convention town.''
</P>
<P>
   The new hotels include the independently owned and operated
International House and the St. James Hotel and franchise
operations _ Holiday Inn, Sheraton, Marriott, and Promus Hotel
Corp., whose brands in New Orleans are Hampton Inn and Embassy
Suites.
</P>
<P>
   A major catalyst for the sustained growth, hotel operators and
developers say, has been the 360,000-square-foot expansion of the
city's riverfront convention center. The third phase of the Ernest
N. Morial Convention Center, completed earlier this year, brought
its space to 1.1 million square feet. Built on the riverfront more
than 15 years ago as the Lousiana State Pavilion for the 1984
World's Fair, which rose in what is now the Warehouse District, the
center has been host to more than one million out-of-town people
each year.
</P>
<P>
   As an event the World's Fair did not draw as many visitors as
the city had hoped, said William Langkopp, executive vice president
of the Louisiana Hotel and Motel Association. But it did open up
the riverfront and drew people into the warehouse area, which had
never been considered for hotels, restaurants and shops.
</P>
<P>
   The recent hotel development trend here has been different from
development in other prominent convention destinations, such as Las
Vegas or Orlando, Fla. With few exceptions, the new hotels are
opening in the central business district or in the warehouse area.
Both neighborhoods are within walking distance of the French
Quarter and the riverfront.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, a majority of the new hotels are small to mid-sized
projects _ 150 to 350 rooms. Statistics gathered by the New Orleans
Metropolitan Visitors and Convention Bureau show that over the next
two years about 2,350 rooms will be added to the present inventory.
</P>
<P>
   The lodgings are usually five to 15 stories high, a modest scale
dictated almost entirely by city policies that have simultaneously
limited the number of available sites for new construction and
spurred the redevelopment of underutilized properties that the city
has deemed worth saving.
</P>
<P>
   ``The city realized that there were many neighborhoods and
buildings worth preserving beyond those in our traditional historic
areas like the French Quarter and the Garden District,'' said John
Williams, an architect who has been involved in the designs of
several gut-renovation projects, including the Ritz-Carlton Hotel.
``So you have projects like the Queen &AMP; Crescent hotel, which
preserves the city's first high rise and gives the business
district a new hotel.''
</P>
<P>
   The City Council reviews every demolition petition in historic
districts, which now include most of the warehouse and central
business districts. Most buildings 50 years or older qualify for
protection. But to encourage development in these areas, the city
provides a restoration tax abatement that freezes the assessment to
the predevelopment level for at least five years.
</P>
<P>
   Potentially of even more value to developers taking on gut
renovations of these properties is the federal historic
rehabilitation tax credit, which allows developers of qualified
properties to recover up to 20 percent of the redevelopment costs.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Marriott International's recent expansion in New Orleans
illustrates some aspects of the current hotel development trend.
Until 1997 the only hotel in the central part of the city operated
by Marriott was the 54-story, 1,290-room Marriott New Orleans, a
convention hotel on Canal Street. But changes in the city's guest
profile encouraged Marriott to expand its presence here.
</P>
<P>
   With New Orleans-based TVG Group, whose partners are Steve
Manshel and Henry O'Connor, serving as the builder and owner,
Marriott has opened two Courtyards in the last two years. A
Residence Inn by Marriott, an extended-stay hotel, opened in 1997
and a Marriott Renaissance, a moderate-rate hotel, is scheduled to
open in the middle of 2001.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our Courtyard product has been a successful suburban hotel
concept,'' said Craig E. Lambert, senior vice president for
moderate and economy brands for Marriott Corp., based in Bethesda,
Md. ``But we discovered that in New Orleans people wanted the
Courtyard brand in the urban area where there are exciting and fun
things going on.''
</P>
<P>
   The Marriott Courtyard that opened last December went into a
building that included the gut renovation of a molasses factory and
a newly built section. The new 202-room Courtyard is on Julia
Street in the heart of the Warehouse District.
</P>
<P>
   Lambert said that it was usually difficult to justify the cost
of a newly built Courtyard in urban areas. The tax incentives offer
a way of doing it in New Orleans at the price point people will
pay, he said.
</P>
<P>
   In New Orleans Marriott Courtyard nightly room rates range from
$100 to $150 depending on the season, which is well below the rate
range for the company's full-service hotel on Canal Street where
rooms range between $180 and $225.
</P>
<P>
   By far the largest and most ambitious of the gut-renovation
projects is on Canal Street, where the landmarked Maison Blanche
department store is being transformed into a Ritz-Carlton hotel.
The $200-million project, which will include the renovation of the
adjacent Kress building and Maison Blanche annex, is being
developed by White House LLC, based in Baton Rouge, which owns the
buildings. The development partnership includes Bernard Mason,
William Hindman and Stewart Juneau, who is the managing partner.
</P>
<P>
   In recent years the 530,000-square-foot building has been less
and less profitable as a department store. But Juneau was convinced
of its potential as a luxury hotel because of its location on the
western boundary of the French Quarter and because of the city's
strong hotel market.
</P>
<P>
   ``Occupancy is improving, and room rates are rising,'' said
Juneau. But historic rehabilitation tax credits were an essential
component of this project.
</P>
<P>
   The hotel, scheduled to open next fall, will have 452 rooms,
25,000 square feet of meeting space, including a 10,000-square-foot
column free ballroom; a mezzanine level spa and street level
shopping arcade. Room rates will range from $305 to $335, said
Mason, one of the developers.
</P>
<P>
   The project will also include an all-suite hotel, to be known as
the Quarter Suites, also managed by the Ritz-Carlton. Room rates
have yet to be set.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the pace of hotel development, industry analysts do not
see a potential glut of rooms in the foreseeable future. The main
reason is a shortage of available sites or redevelopable buildings
in the areas where hotel operators need to be.
</P>
<P>
   While the national chains have entered the New Orleans market,
there are limits, Keeling believes, to their willingness to expand.
``This will help bring about an equilibrium,'' he said. ``And the
shortage of rooms may continue for an extended period.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
