<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-08 23:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9843 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BORDER-COMMUNITIES-RE     05-08 0979
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BORDER-COMMUNITIES-REAL-3TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHOOSING THE HOUSE OVER THE ZIP CODE 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By LISA PREVOST   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Brently L. Frey made the usual Westchester and Connecticut
stop-offs when he began looking for a home with a feeling of
history two years ago. He toured houses in Danbury, Ridgefield,
Yorktown Heights and Bronxville, but nothing fit his criteria.
</P>
<P>
   Frey, a marketing consultant who works at home, wanted a
property that was truly distinct. And while he could have spent
well over $400,000, the house had to be priced low enough to give
him the option of renovating the interior in his own style.
</P>
<P>
   Flipping through real estate magazines, he noticed a number of
interesting homes for sale in a place he hadn't previously
considered _ Mount Vernon, the city separating the Bronx from
Bronxville. More urban melting pot than sheltered suburbia, what
Mount Vernon lacked in exclusivity it made up for in proximity to
the city (25 minutes by train) and competitive housing prices.
</P>
<P>
   It was in the city's Fleetwood section, a neighborhood of
closely spaced houses and tree-lined streets butting up against the
border of high-priced Bronxville, that Frey found his home _ a
1920s brick colonial with a grand center hall, French doors,
Palladian windows and a tiled solarium with the original wall
fountain. He closed on the house last May at a price that he said
was ``between $350,000 and $400,000.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Like many old gems, this one needed to be dusted off,'' said
the 35-year-old Frey. ``It's like a diamond in the rough. For me,
where I live is not an issue of prestige. It's an issue of my
house, and I want my house to be what I want.''
</P>
<P>
   While so many home buyers studiously heed the cardinal rule of
real estate and elevate location above all other considerations,
Frey represents a different breed of buyer, one for whom house
matters much more than address.
</P>
<P>
   These are the people who are either unwilling or unable to pay
the price for their ideal house in the most sought-after ZIP codes.
So they happily drift across the borders of prime neighborhoods to
lay claim to similar properties in less lofty surroundings. Some
purposely seek out these border communities because they tend to
offer more diversity.
</P>
<P>
   As home prices have soared in the last few years, these buyers
have become all the more evident as they fuel demand in less
prestigious neighborhoods bordering communities where similar homes
carry significantly higher price tags. Some examples of such
communities in Westchester are Fleetwood and the Armour Villa,
Lawrence Park West, Beech Hill, Cedar Knolls and Park Hill
neighborhoods of Yonkers.
</P>
<P>
   In Connecticut, the Black Rock and Brooklawn neighborhoods of
Bridgeport, bordering Fairfield, offer good value for prime
properties. In Norwalk, price differentials still exist in the
Cranbury and Wolfpit neighborhoods of the city along the Westport
border, but the price gap between Norwalk and surrounding towns has
closed considerably, brokers say.
</P>
<P>
   The same is also true on the North Shore of Long Island, where
one-time factory towns like Glen Cove used to offer waterfront
properties at prices much lower than the more exclusive areas, said
Lee E. Koppelman, executive director of the Center for Regional
Policy Studies at the State University of New York at Stony Brook.
The tight real estate market has narrowed price differentials in
Nassau County considerably as ``the areas that would have served as
a contrast have been gentrified,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In New Jersey, South Orange, adjacent to Short Hills, offers
some ``wonderful old housing stock,'' as does the Sleepy Hollow
section of Plainfield, bordering Edison Township, according to
James Hughes, dean of the Rutgers University School of Planning and
Public Policy. In addition, the Montclair Heights neighborhood of
Clifton is an increasingly popular alternative for buyers attracted
to higher-priced Montclair, said Ken Hauser, a sales associate with
Weichert Realtors in Clifton.
</P>
<P>
   In many of these areas, historic or architecturally detailed
homes can cost hundreds of thousands less than their counterparts
just blocks away across community borders. And property taxes, too,
can be thousands of dollars lower. The trade-off for a smaller
mortgage and lower property taxes, however, is often a school
district that compares unfavorably with adjoining towns and perhaps
a higher crime rate.
</P>
<P>
   One factor motivating some of the more venturesome buyers in
these areas, said Dr. Hughes, may be that thanks to the stock
market runup of recent years, the role of the house as the dominant
investment has diminished for more families. ``Their stock holdings
could potentially dwarf their house,'' he said. ``These areas may
appeal to people who aren't so housing-dependent for their nest
egg.''
</P>
<P>
   And it's possible that once the real-estate market slows again,
some who invested heavily in improving homes in secondary areas may
find it difficult to get their money out, noted Julie Garton-Good,
a real estate lecturer and author of ``The Frugal Homeowner's Guide
to Buying, Selling and Improving Your Home'' (Dearborn, 1999).
``There's nothing wrong with people going in and losing money on a
house,'' she said. ``But they need to be aware of it ahead of
time.''
</P>
<P>
   Then again, observed John Clapp, a professor of finance and real
estate at the University of Connecticut's Center for Real Estate in
Storrs, a less predictable degree of risk can also lead to a higher
return. Over the last five years in Norwalk, for example,
condominium prices appreciated an average of 9.2 percent annually,
while condominium prices in Stamford, a lower-risk market than
Norwalk by Clapp's measurements, appreciated an average 3.5 percent
annually, he said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Even if buyers consider their house less of an investment than
simply a home, they should still sit down and weigh other
considerations before they begin looking, advises Martin Shenkman,
a New York City real estate lawyer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Private or public schools, commute time _ whatever the most
important amenities _ all those things have to be thought
through,'' Shenkman said. ``People have to sit down and rank their
priorities before they fall all over a house. Then whatever they
decide is fine, once they've made that personal choice.''
</P>
<P>
   Frey has long since stopped worrying about how much money he's
spending on his house. He is having his prominent corner lot
landscaped, a project that includes adding a garden off the
solarium. He has also paid for installation of a central
air-conditioning system, restoration of some of the French doors,
interior repainting and refinishing of the oak floors.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have a lot of friends who are real estate agents and, in the
beginning when I was making renovations, I was always asking them,
`Am I spending too much?''' he said. ``And they would say, `You
can't put a dollar value on it. It's not a dollar value, it's a
love value.'''
</P>
<P>
   The average sale price of a house in the Fleetwood area last
year was about one-third of that in Bronxville, said Elizabeth
Lindsey, owner of Lindsey Real Estate in Mount Vernon. For many
buyers who wind up in Fleetwood the cost of renovating a house
there still puts them ahead of what their neighbors in Bronxville
are paying.
</P>
<P>
   ``But you can stand in one of our houses, and it looks the same,
the air smells the same,'' she said. ``And the termites don't stop
at the Bronxville border.''
</P>
<P>
   Sabina Grochowski, 39, and her husband Peter Wyrwinski, 37, both
physicians, scouted out Bronxville, Mamaroneck, Scarsdale,
Larchmont and New Rochelle before friends convinced them to look in
Mount Vernon. Ready to move out of their co-op in Woodmere on Long
Island, they wanted an impressive historic home in good repair with
high ceilings and at least four bedrooms.
</P>
<P>
   They came close to buying a $699,000 Tudor on a tiny lot in
Larchmont. But last December, they found a 1913 Mediterranean-style
home on an acre on Gramatan Avenue in Fleetwood with such lavish
details as stained-glass windows, relief ceilings, mahogany
paneling and an elaborately carved central staircase. They snatched
it up for $648,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think Mount Vernon is one of the few underrated spots in
Westchester,'' Grochowski said.
</P>
<P>
   At about $18,000 a year, the taxes on the property are about the
same as those on other houses they considered, Grochowski said. But
the price is considerably better, she added, even after figuring in
the $40,000 they spent on renovations before moving in last month.
And since the couple have no children, schools were not a
consideration, she said.
</P>
<P>
   As a rule, lower housing prices are partly a reflection of the
perceived quality of the community's schools. Several economic
studies have tried to measure just how much a good school is worth
on the real estate market.
</P>
<P>
   In a summary of those studies published last fall in a report
titled, ``House Prices and the Quality of Public Schools,'' in
Business Review, a Federal Reserve publication, Theodore Crone,
head of the regional economics section of the Federal Reserve Bank
of Philadelphia, noted that because housing prices were affected by
so many other neighborhood characteristics, it's difficult to
separate out the absolute value of a school district. But such a
``school premium'' clearly exists, Crone said, and is often linked
to districts with higher per-pupil expenditures and higher test
scores.
</P>
<P>
   In a 1997 study titled ``Do Better Schools Matter?'' Sandra E.
Black, an economist with the Federal Reserve Bank of New York,
found that even when parents were already paying for a better
school district in the Boston suburbs, they would pay an additional
2.5 percent for a house linked to an elementary school that had
test scores just 5 percent above the others in that district.
</P>
<P>
   Parents who can afford to pay this housing premium, but choose
not to do so, generally make the choice quite consciously. ``A
number of people don't even ask about schools anymore because
they've done the research and they know what they're doing with
their kids,'' said Jane McAfee, a Yonkers sales agent for
Prudential Ragette.
</P>
<P>
   In Yonkers, residents may choose from a variety of magnet
schools in the public school system, or send their children to one
of the many nearby parochial and private schools. Some even pay to
have their children attend public schools in Pelham or Ardsley. The
Beech Hill neighborhood near Scarsdale and the Armour Villa and
Lawrence Park neighborhoods bordering Bronxville have long been
popular with buyers wanting large homes at lower prices. And they
both offer the added bonus of a Scarsdale or Bronxville ZIP code.
</P>
<P>
   ``The people I deal with certainly have looked around and they
know the prices of houses in Scarsdale,'' said Kathleen Kuhnel, an
associate broker at Cardinal Realty in Ardsley. ``Some of them have
kids in private schools anyway, so they figure, `Why pay those
taxes?'''
</P>
<P>
   The differences can be dramatic: A five-bedroom colonial in the
Beech Hill neighborhood with a Scarsdale ZIP code was recently
listed at $385,000 with taxes of $7,700 while in Scarsdale a
colonial of the same size and age was priced at $675,000 with taxes
of almost $14,000.
</P>
<P>
   Prices are even higher in Bronxville, where a 50-year-old,
four-bedroom colonial was recently listed at $699,000 with taxes of
more than $17,000. Just over the border in the Cedar Knolls
neighborhood of Yonkers a similar colonial was listed at $399,000
with taxes of $6,100.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The Yonkers neighborhood of Park Hill, though not on the border
of Bronxville or Scarsdale, has also caught on in the last few
years. One of the first planned residential suburbs around New
York, Park Hill is a mix of about 200 19th- and early 20th-century
homes on a 300-foot plateau overlooking the Hudson River.
</P>
<P>
   Though the neighborhood has long been popular with artists and
entertainers, its proximity to blighted areas had previously made
it a hard sell with less venturesome spirits. Now, Ms. McAfee has a
list of 25 buyers waiting for houses in Park Hill, where homeowners
say they are united in their determination to restore the
neighborhood to its former glory.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was invited to a party by a neighbor before I even moved
in,'' said Mary Jerome, 54, chairwoman of the English as a second
language program for international students at Columbia University.
``People have asked me over to dinner. I've been asked to join the
Park Hill Conservancy. It's really a nice mix of people _ kind
people.''
</P>
<P>
   In January, Ms. Jerome moved into a 100-year-old,
7,000-square-foot Georgian with a view of the Hudson and space for
a garden, exactly the kind of magnificent home she had long dreamed
of owning. Having lived in Manhattan for 27 years, she knew little
about Westchester and nothing of Park Hill when she began looking
at houses. She estimates that the $780,000 sale price on the house
would undoubtedly have been double in Hastings-on-Hudson or
Bronxville, the other communities she had looked into.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never even considered whether I'd be able to get my money
out because I knew this was it,'' she said. ``My daughter's grown,
and this is where I'll stay. Just this morning I went outside and
looked at all the stupid little things I planted, which are just
pathetic. But I love having the green space.''
</P>
<P>
   Empty-nesters are, of course, among the buyers most likely to
trade off a prime address for lower taxes and a better deal. In
Connecticut, for example, Wendy Tremaglio and her husband, Ralph, a
golf pro, opted for Norwalk about two years ago as a money-wise
alternative to Westport, where they raised their daughter. As they
shopped around for a house, their biggest priority was one-level
living to make it easier for their two aging bichon frises to get
around.
</P>
<P>
   By crossing the Westport border into Norwalk's quiet Cranbury
neighborhood the couple were able to get a large two-bedroom ranch
with an attached garage on a third of an acre for just under
$190,000. Taxes are $3,400 a year. They spent about $30,000 on
renovations, including redoing the kitchen.
</P>
<P>
   ``But this house in Westport would have probably been about
$400,000 or $500,000,'' said Mrs. Tremaglio, 44. And it's still
only minutes away from her two places of employment _ her family's
store, Dining In, in Norwalk and Riverside-Shavell Realty in
Westport.
</P>
<P>
   More up-and-coming is the Black Rock neighborhood of Bridgeport,
a waterfront community along Black Rock Harbor. ``I've heard of
three or four instances now where people have sold their homes in
Westport and moved to Black Rock,'' said Ken Scala, owner of
Century 21 Scala and Clark in Bridgeport. ``This is a trend now,
it's really happening.''
</P>
<P>
   While Black Rock has most of Bridgeport's highest-priced homes,
prices are still significantly less than the beach neighborhoods of
Fairfield and Westport. For example, a four-bedroom, 1920s Cape Cod
with a view of Long Island Sound recently sold in Black Rock for
$211,500, with estimated taxes of $3,478. A similar-sized 1920's
colonial on a slightly smaller lot in the beach area of Fairfield
recently sold for $400,000, with estimated taxes of $3,500.
</P>
<P>
   Last summer, Nikita and Maiko Cheremeteff moved to Black Rock
after 23 years in Westport. Cheremeteff, 66, had just retired as
vice president for manufacturing at Loctite Corp. in Hartford, a
chemical company, and the couple's four children were all living on
their own. So the Cheremeteffs settled into a five-bedroom 1920s
colonial in Black Rock on a hill overlooking the Sound. They paid
$370,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wanted to move to a cheaper house, but a better house, a
nicer house,'' Cheremeteff said. ``And we wanted to be on the
Metro-North line, so the children could come visit easily. We still
do all of our shopping in Westport _ it's only seven minutes away.
There are a lot of people around us who have moved here from
Westport, basically for the same reason.
</P>
<P>
   ``Twenty years ago, we would have stayed in Westport because the
school system is much better. But now, school is no longer a
problem.''
</P>
<P>
   Buyer interest in Black Rock is such that prices have
appreciated more there in the last 12 months than in any other area
of Bridgeport, said Scala, the brokerage owner. ``There's a real
sense of community there,'' he said. ``Neighbors gather at the
Harbor View Market _ it's kind of the local meeting place.''
</P>
<P>
   To a great extent, the empty-nesters moving downmarket are
encouraged to to so by a strong market and a seemingly endless
supply of another breed of buyers, those willing to pay top dollar
for the most desirable addresses. Indeed, it was a developer who
bought the Cheremeteffs' 1970s split-level on two acres in
Westport. He promptly razed the house to make way for a $2.6
million mansion.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
